WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.880
Blind Sight by Peter Watts, narrated by Zachary Reid. For Lisa, if we're not in

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:15.080
pain, we're not alive. This is what fascinates me most in existence, the

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:22.160
peculiar necessity of imagining what is, in fact, real. Philip Gurovich, you will

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:29.960
die like a dog for no good reason, Ernest Hemingway. Prologue. Try to touch

00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:37.040
the past. Try to deal with the past. It's not real. It's just a dream. Ted Bundy.

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:43.720
It didn't start out here. Not with the scramblers or roar shock, not with Big

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:47.920
Ban or Theesius or the vampires. Most people would say it started with the

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:53.120
fireflies, but they'd be wrong. It ended with all those things. For me, it began

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:58.480
with Robert Pagliano. At the age of eight, he was my best and only friend. We were

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:04.200
fellow outcasts bound by complimentary misfortune. Mine was developmental. His

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:07.960
was genetic, an uncontrolled genotype that left him predisposed to

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:13.360
nearsightedness, acne, and, as it later turned out, a susceptibility to narcotics.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:18.920
His parents had never had him optimized. Those few twin-sen relics who still

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:22.720
believed in God also held that one shouldn't try to improve upon his

00:01:22.720 --> 00:01:27.280
handiwork. So although both of us could have been repaired, only one of us had

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:32.160
been. I arrived at the playground to find Pagliano at the center of attention for

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:36.640
some half-dozen kids, those lucky few in front punching him in the head, the

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:43.320
others making do with taunts of mongrel and Polly awaiting their turn. I watched

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:48.360
him raise his arms, almost hesitantly, to ward off the worst the blows. I could

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:51.720
see into his head better than I could see into my own. He was scared that his

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:55.600
attackers might think those hands were coming up to hit back, that they'd read

00:01:55.680 --> 00:02:00.160
it as an act of defiance and hurt back even more. Even then, at the tender age of

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:05.280
eight and with half my mind gone, I was becoming a superlative observer. But I

00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:09.800
didn't know what to do. I hadn't seen much of Pagliano lately. I was pretty sure

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:13.520
he'd been avoiding me. Still, when you're best friends in trouble, you help out,

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:17.680
right? Even if the odds are impossible, and how many eight-year-olds would go up

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:21.680
against six bigger kids for a sandbox buddy, at least you call for backup,

00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:29.120
flag a sentry, something. I just stood there. I didn't even especially want to

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:34.200
help him. That didn't make sense. Even if he hadn't been my best friend, I should

00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:38.080
have at least empathized. I'd suffered less than Pag in the way of overt

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:42.120
violence. My seizures tended to keep the other kids at a distance, scared them

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:47.920
even as they incapacitated me. Still, I was no stranger to the taunts and insults,

00:02:47.920 --> 00:02:52.360
or the foot that appears from nowhere to trip you, on-route from A to B. I knew how

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:57.360
that felt, or I had once. But that part of me even cut out along with the bad

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:01.480
wiring. I was still working up the algorithms to get it back, still learning

00:03:01.480 --> 00:03:07.080
by observation. Pag animals always tear apart the weaklings in their midst. Every

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:11.360
child knows that much instinctively. Maybe I should just let that process

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:15.840
unfold. Maybe I shouldn't try to mess with nature. Then again, Pag's parents

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:19.600
hadn't messed with nature, and look what it got them. A son curled up in the dirt

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:24.280
while a bunch of engineered superboys kicked in his ribs. In the end, propaganda

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:29.000
work were empathy failed. Back then, I didn't so much as think as observe. Didn't

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.080
adduce so much as remember. And what I remembered was a thousand inspirational

00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:37.960
stories, louding anyone who ever stuck up for the underdog. So I picked up a rock

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:41.880
the size of my fist, and hit two of Pag's assailants across the backs of their

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:46.680
heads before anyone even knew I was in the game. A third, turning to face the new

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:50.040
threat, took a blow to the face that audibly crunched the bones of his cheek.

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:54.520
I remember wondering why I didn't take any satisfaction from that sound, and why

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:57.720
it meant nothing beyond the fact that I had one less opponent to worry about.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:02.160
The rest of them ran at the sight of blood. One of the braver promised me I

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:06.480
was dead, shouting, fucking zombie over his shoulder as he disappeared around the

00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:13.360
corner. Three decades it took to see the irony in that remark. Two of the enemy

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:17.040
twitched at my feet. I kicked one in the head until it stopped moving, turned to

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:21.240
the other. Something grabbed my arm and I swung without thinking, without looking

00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:27.600
until Pag yelped and ducked out of reach. Oh, I said. Sorry. One thing lay

00:04:27.600 --> 00:04:32.680
motionless. The other moaned and held its head and curled up in a ball. Oh shit,

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:38.760
Pag panted. Blood cursed unheeded from his nose and splattered down his shirt. His

00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:43.800
cheek was turning blue and yellow. Oh shit, oh shit, oh shit, oh shit. I thought

00:04:43.800 --> 00:04:49.920
of something to say. You alright? Oh shit, you, I mean you never... he wiped his mouth.

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:56.080
Blood smeared the back of his hand. Oh man, are we in trouble? They started it. Yeah,

00:04:56.080 --> 00:05:01.160
but you, I mean look at them. The moaning thing was crawling away on all fours. I

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:06.000
wondered how long it would be before it found reinforcements. I wondered if I

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:11.600
should kill it before then. You'd have never done that before, Pag said. Before

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:17.680
the operation, he meant. I actually did feel something then. Faint, distant, but

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:24.560
unmistakable. I felt angry. They started Pag backed away, eyes wide. What are you

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:31.360
doing? Put that down! I raised my fists. I didn't remember doing that. I hand

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:40.760
clenched them. It took a while. It took a while. I had to look at my hands very

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:45.960
hard for a long, long time. The rock dropped to the ground, bloodstained and

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:51.280
glistening. I was trying to help. I didn't understand why he couldn't see that.

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:56.240
You're not the same, Pag said from a safe distance. You're not even

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:03.320
serious anymore. I am too. Don't be a fuckwad. They cut out your brain. Only half

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:08.200
for the ep- I know for the epilepsy. You think I don't know? But you were in that

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:12.800
half or like part of you was. He struggled with the words, with the concept

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:16.880
behind them. And now you're different. It's like your mom and dad murdered you.

00:06:17.400 --> 00:06:22.840
My mom and dad, I said, suddenly quiet. Saved my life. I would have died.

00:06:22.840 --> 00:06:29.360
I think you did die, said my best and only friend. I think Ciri died. They scooped

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:32.840
him out and threw him away and you've got some whole other kid that just just

00:06:32.840 --> 00:06:37.360
grew back out of what was left. You're not the same. Ever since, you're not the

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:42.920
same. I still don't know if Pag really knew what he was saying. Maybe his mother

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:46.860
just pulled the plug in whatever game he'd been wired into for the previous 18

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:51.660
hours, forced him outside for some fresh air. Maybe after fighting pod people in

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:56.340
game space, he couldn't help but see them everywhere. Maybe. But you could make a

00:06:56.340 --> 00:07:02.400
case for what he said. I remember Helen telling me, and telling me, how difficult

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:07.140
it was to adjust. Like you had a whole new personality, she said. And why not?

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:12.580
There's a reason they call it radical, hemiospherectomy. Half the brain thrown

00:07:12.580 --> 00:07:17.440
out with yesterday's krill, the remaining half press ganged into double duty. Think

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:20.740
of all the rewiring that one lonely hemisphere must have struggled with as

00:07:20.740 --> 00:07:25.340
it tried to take up the slack. It turned out okay, obviously. The brain's a very

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:32.020
flexible piece of meat. It took some doing, but it adapted. I adapted. Still, think

00:07:32.020 --> 00:07:35.800
of all that must have been squeezed out, deformed, reshaped by the time the

00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:39.660
renovations are through. You could argue that I'm a different person than the one

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:44.000
who used to occupy this body. The grown-up showed up eventually, of course.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:49.280
Medicine was besowed, ambulance is called. Parents were outraged, diplomatic

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:52.980
volleys exchanged, but it's tough to draw up neighborhood outrage on behalf of

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:56.340
your injured baby when playground surveillance in three angles shows

00:07:56.340 --> 00:08:00.580
little darling and five of his buddies kicking in the ribs of a disabled boy.

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:05.260
My mother, for her part, recycled the usual complaints about problem children

00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:09.940
and absentee fathers. Dad was off again in some other hemisphere, but the dust

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:13.900
settled pretty quickly. Pag and I even stayed friends after the short hiatus

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:17.460
that reminded us both of the limited social prospects open to schoolyard

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:21.780
rejects who don't stick together. So I survived that and a million other

00:08:21.780 --> 00:08:26.980
childhood experiences. I grew up and got along. I learned to fit in. I observed,

00:08:26.980 --> 00:08:31.260
recorded, derived the algorithms and mimicked appropriate behaviors. Not

00:08:31.260 --> 00:08:35.940
much of it was, heartfelt, I guess the word is. I had friends and enemies like

00:08:35.940 --> 00:08:39.860
everyone else. I chose them by running through checklists of behaviors and

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:44.740
circumstances compiled from years of observation. I may have grown up distant,

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:50.100
but I grew up objective and I have Robert Pagliano to thank for that. His

00:08:50.100 --> 00:08:55.140
seminal observation was set everything in motion. It led me into synthesis,

00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:59.420
faded me to our disastrous encounter with the scramblers, spared me the worst

00:08:59.540 --> 00:09:03.700
fate of falling earth or the better one I suppose depending on your point of

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:10.220
view point of view matters. I see that now blind talking to myself trapped in a

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:14.740
coffin falling past the edge of the solar system. I see it for the first time

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:18.460
since some beaten bloody friend on a childhood battlefield convinced me to

00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:24.460
throw my own point of view away. He may have been wrong. I may have been, but

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:30.100
that that distance, a chronic sense of being an alien among your own kind. It's

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:34.340
not entirely a bad thing. It came in especially handy when the real aliens

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:35.060
came calling.

00:09:39.540 --> 00:09:48.780
Theseus. Blood makes noise. Suzanne Vega. Imagine you are Siri Keaton. You

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:53.140
awaken an agony of resurrection grasping after a record shattering bout of sleep

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:58.780
and a shrapnel. You can feel your blood and syrupy with dobutamine and

00:09:58.780 --> 00:10:03.860
Lone and Kephalin forcing its way through artery shriveled by months on standby.

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:09.620
The body inflates in painful increments. Blood vessels dilate. Flesh peels apart

00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:15.180
from flesh. Ribs crack in your ears with sudden, unaccustomed flexion. Your joints

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:19.700
have seized up through disuse. You're a stick man frozen in some perverse rear

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:25.140
vitae. You'd scream if you had the breath. Vampires did this all the time, you

00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:29.260
remember. It was normal for them. It was their own unique take on resource

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:33.780
conservation. They could have taught your kind a few things about restraint if that

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:37.620
absurd aversion to right angles hadn't done them in at the dawn of civilization.

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:43.100
Maybe they still can. They're back now after all, raised from the grave with the

00:10:43.100 --> 00:10:47.100
voodoo of paleogenetics, stitched together from junk genes and fossil

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:50.740
marrow, steeped in the blood of sociopaths and high functioning autistics.

00:10:51.540 --> 00:10:55.860
One of them commands this very mission. A handful of his genes live on in your

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:59.180
own body so it too can rise from the dead here at the edge of interstellar

00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:03.260
space. Nobody gets past Jupiter without becoming part vampire.

00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:09.300
The pain begins just slightly to recede. You fire up your inlays and access

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:13.460
your own vitals. It'll be long minutes before your body responds fully to

00:11:13.460 --> 00:11:18.260
motor commands, hours before it stops hurting. The pain is an unavoidable

00:11:18.260 --> 00:11:22.380
side effect. That's just what happens when you splice vampire subroutines into

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:26.740
human code. You asked about pain killers once, but nerve blocks of any kind

00:11:26.740 --> 00:11:33.260
compromise metabolic reactivation. Suck it up, soldier. You wonder if this was how

00:11:33.260 --> 00:11:38.260
it felt for Chelsea before the end. But that evokes a whole other kind of pain,

00:11:38.260 --> 00:11:41.980
so you block it out and concentrate on the life pushing its way back into your

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:48.180
extremities. Suffering in silence, you check the logs for fresh telemetry. You

00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:53.260
think that can't be right? Because if it is, you're in the wrong part of the

00:11:53.260 --> 00:11:57.700
universe. You're not in the Kuiper Belt where you belong. You're high above the

00:11:57.700 --> 00:12:02.700
ecliptic and deep into the oar. The realm of long period comets that only grace

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:07.660
the sun every million years or so. You've gone interstellar, which means you

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:14.340
bring up the system clock. You've been undead for 1800 days. You've overslept by

00:12:14.340 --> 00:12:20.620
almost five years. Lid on your coffin slides away. Your own cadaverous body

00:12:20.620 --> 00:12:24.860
reflects from the mirrored bulkhead opposite, a desiccated lungfish waiting

00:12:24.860 --> 00:12:29.260
for the rains. Ladders of isotonic saline cling to its limbs like

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:33.900
engorged anti-parasites, like the opposite of leeches. You remember the

00:12:33.900 --> 00:12:37.380
needles going in just before you shut down way back when your veins were more

00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:42.700
than dry twisted filaments of beef jerky. Spindle's reflection stares back from

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:46.860
his own pod to your immediate right. His face is as bloodless and skeletal as

00:12:46.860 --> 00:12:51.540
yours. His wide, sunken eyes jiggle in their sockets as he reacquires his own

00:12:51.540 --> 00:12:55.740
links. Sensory interface is so massive that your own off-the-shelf inlay is

00:12:55.740 --> 00:13:00.220
amount to shadow puppetry in comparison. You hear coughing and the rustling of

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:04.140
limbs just past line of sight catch glimpses of reflected motion where the

00:13:04.180 --> 00:13:08.420
others stir at the edge of vision. What? Your voice is barely more than a

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:14.020
horse whisper. How? Spindle works his jaw. Bone cracks audibly.

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:20.700
Suckered! He hisses. You haven't even met the aliens yet and they're already

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:26.940
running rings around you. So we dragged ourselves back from the dead. Five

00:13:26.940 --> 00:13:32.860
part-time cadavers, naked, emaciated, barely able to move even in zero G. We

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:36.980
merged them our coffins like premature moths from their cocoons. Still half

00:13:36.980 --> 00:13:41.340
grub. We were alone and off course and utterly helpless and it took a conscious

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:45.100
effort to remember they would never have risked our lives if we hadn't been

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:50.820
essential. Morning, Commissar! Isaac Spindle reached one trembling in since

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:56.060
eight hand for the feedback gloves at the base of his pod. Just past him, Susan

00:13:56.060 --> 00:13:59.580
James was curled into a loose a loose fetal ball murmuring to

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:04.700
herself. Only Amanda Bates, half dressed and cycling through a sequence of

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:10.140
bone cracking isometrics possessed anything approaching mobility. Every

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:14.260
now and then she tried bouncing a rubber ball off the bulkhead but not even

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:19.660
she was up to catching it on the rebound yet. The journey had melted us down to a

00:14:19.660 --> 00:14:24.780
common archetype. James's round cheeks and hips, Spindle's high forehead and

00:14:24.820 --> 00:14:30.180
lumpy, lanky chasses, even the enhanced carb platinum brick shithouse that Bates

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:35.020
used for a body all had shriveled to the same desiccated collection of sticks and

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:41.860
bones. Even our hair seemed to have become strangely discolored during the

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:45.860
voyage although I knew that was impossible. More likely it was just

00:14:45.860 --> 00:14:51.100
filtering the pallor of the skin beneath. Still, the pre-dead James had been dirty

00:14:51.100 --> 00:14:55.300
blonde, Spindle's hair had been almost dark enough to call black, but the stuff

00:14:55.300 --> 00:15:00.020
floating from their scalps looked the same dull kelpy brown to me now. Bates

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:03.420
kept her head shaved, believing her eyebrows weren't as rusty as I remembered

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:10.140
them. We'd revert to our old skills soon enough, just add water. For now though the

00:15:10.140 --> 00:15:14.740
old slur was freshly relevant. The undead really did look all the same if you

00:15:14.740 --> 00:15:20.100
didn't know how to look. If you did of course, if you forgot appearance and

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:25.180
watched for motion, ignored meat and studied topology, you'd never mistake one

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:30.500
for another. Every facial tick was a data point. Every conversational pause spoke

00:15:30.500 --> 00:15:35.180
volumes more than the words to either side. I could see James's personae

00:15:35.180 --> 00:15:39.780
shatter and coalesce in the flutter of an eyelash. Spindle's unspoken distrust of

00:15:39.780 --> 00:15:44.060
a man to Bates shouted from the corner of his smile. Every twitch of the

00:15:44.060 --> 00:15:49.140
phenotype cried aloud to anyone who knew the language. Where's James croached,

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:54.900
croaked, coughed, waved one Spindle arm at Sarastee's empty coffin gaping at the

00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:59.980
end of the row. Spindle's lips cracked in a small rictus. Gone back to fab, eh?

00:15:59.980 --> 00:16:04.860
Getting the ship to build some dirt to lie on. Probably communing with the

00:16:04.860 --> 00:16:09.260
captain. Bates breathed louder than she spoke. A dry rustle from pipes still

00:16:09.260 --> 00:16:14.140
getting reacquainted with the idea of respiration. James again, could do that

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:20.180
up here. Could take a dump up here too, eh? Spindle rasped. Some things you do by

00:16:20.180 --> 00:16:25.860
yourself. And some things you kept to yourself. Not many baselines felt

00:16:25.860 --> 00:16:31.060
comfortable locking stairs to the vampire. Sarastee, ever courteous, tended to

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:35.380
avoid eye contact for exactly that reason. But there were other surfaces to his

00:16:35.420 --> 00:16:39.980
apology. Just as mammalian and just as readable. If he had withdrawn from public

00:16:39.980 --> 00:16:45.900
view, maybe I was the reason. Maybe he was keeping secrets. After all, these is

00:16:45.900 --> 00:16:51.820
damn well was. She'd taken us a good 15 AU's towards our destination before

00:16:51.820 --> 00:16:55.780
something scared her off course. Then she'd skidded north like a startled cat

00:16:55.780 --> 00:17:01.780
and started climbing. A wild, high, 3G burn off the ecliptic. 1300 tons of

00:17:01.780 --> 00:17:07.100
momentum buckling against Newton's first. She'd emptied her pen tanks, bled dry her

00:17:07.100 --> 00:17:12.740
substrate mass, squandered 140 days of fuel in hours. Then a long, cold coast

00:17:12.740 --> 00:17:16.500
through the abyss, years of stingy accounting, the thrust of every anti-

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:20.500
proton weighed against the drag of seething it from the void. Teleportation

00:17:20.500 --> 00:17:24.500
isn't magic. The Icarus stream couldn't send us the actual antimatter it made,

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:28.700
only the quantum specs. The easiest had to filter feed the raw material from

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:34.340
space one ion at a time. For long, dark years, she'd made do on pure inertia,

00:17:34.340 --> 00:17:39.940
hoarding every swallowed atom. Then flip, ionizing lasers strafing the space ahead,

00:17:39.940 --> 00:17:44.140
a ram scoop thrown wide in a heartbreak. The weight of a trillion, trillion

00:17:44.140 --> 00:17:47.780
protons slowed her down and refilled her gut and flattened us all over again.

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:51.940
Beasius had burned relentless until almost the moment of our resurrection.

00:17:51.940 --> 00:17:56.740
It was easy enough to retrace those steps. Our course was there in consensus

00:17:56.780 --> 00:18:01.060
for anyone to see. Exactly why the ship had blazed the trail was another matter.

00:18:01.060 --> 00:18:07.500
Doubtless it would come all out during the post-Raz briefing. We were hardly the

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:11.500
first vessel to travel under the cloak of sealed orders, and if there'd been a

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:16.300
pressing need to know by now, we've known by now. Still, I wondered who had locked

00:18:16.300 --> 00:18:22.380
out the comm logs, mission control maybe, or Sarasti, or Theesius herself for that

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:27.700
matter. It was easy to forget the quantical AI at the heart of the ship. It stayed so

00:18:27.700 --> 00:18:32.060
discreetly in the background, nurtured and carried us to permeate our existence

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:36.060
like an unintrusive god. But like god, it never took your calls.

00:18:36.060 --> 00:18:40.940
Sarasti was the official intermediary. When the ship did speak, it spoke to him,

00:18:40.940 --> 00:18:48.420
and Sarasti called it captain. So did we all. He'd given us four hours to come back.

00:18:48.460 --> 00:18:55.020
It took more than three just to get me out of the crypt. By then, my brain was at least firing on most of its synapses,

00:18:55.020 --> 00:18:59.540
although my body, still sucking fluids like a thirsty sponge, continued to ache

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:03.980
with every movement. I swapped out drained electrolyte bags or fresh ones and headed

00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:10.180
aft. Fifteen minutes to spin up. Fifty to the post-Raz briefing. Just enough time

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:13.500
for those who preferred gravity bow and sleep to haul their personal effects

00:19:13.620 --> 00:19:17.740
into the drum and stake out their allotted 4.4 square meters of floor space.

00:19:17.740 --> 00:19:24.340
Gravity, or any centripetal facsimile thereof, did not appeal to me. I set up my

00:19:24.340 --> 00:19:28.700
own tent in zero G in as far as Stern as possible, nuzzling the forward wall of the

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:33.780
starboard shuttle tube. The tent inflated like an abscess on Theesius's spine, a

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:37.620
little climate-controlled bubble of atmosphere in the dark cavernous vacuum

00:19:37.620 --> 00:19:42.380
beneath the ship's carapace. My own effects were minimal. It took all of 30

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:45.580
seconds to stick them to the wall and another 30 to program the tent's

00:19:45.580 --> 00:19:50.740
environment. Afterwards, I went for a hike. After five years, I needed the

00:19:50.740 --> 00:19:55.780
exercise. Stern was closest, so I started there, at the shielding that separated

00:19:55.780 --> 00:20:00.140
payload from propulsion. A single sealed hatch blistered the aft bulkhead dead

00:20:00.140 --> 00:20:04.340
center. Behind it, a service tunnel warmed back through the machinery best left

00:20:04.340 --> 00:20:08.580
untouched by human hands. The fat, superconducting torus of the ram scoop

00:20:08.620 --> 00:20:12.860
ring. The antennae fan behind it unwound now into an indestructible soap bubble

00:20:12.860 --> 00:20:16.660
big enough to shroud a city. Its face turned sunward to catch the faint

00:20:16.660 --> 00:20:21.100
quantum sparkle of the aqueous antimatter stream. More shielding behind

00:20:21.100 --> 00:20:25.300
that than the telematter reactor, where raw hydrogen and refined information

00:20:25.300 --> 00:20:30.940
conjured fire 300 times hotter than the sun's. I knew the incantations, of

00:20:30.940 --> 00:20:34.660
course, antimatter cracking and deconstruction, the teleportation of

00:20:34.700 --> 00:20:39.060
quantum serial numbers, but it was still magic to me how we'd come so far so

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:46.100
fast. It would have been magic to anyone, except Sarasti, maybe. Around me, the same

00:20:46.100 --> 00:20:50.580
magic worked at cooler temperatures and to less volatile ends. A small riot of

00:20:50.580 --> 00:20:54.940
shoots and dispensers crowded the bulkhead on all sides. A few of those

00:20:54.940 --> 00:20:59.380
openings would choke on my fist. One or two could swallow me whole. The easiest

00:20:59.380 --> 00:21:03.700
fabrication plant could build everything from cutlery to cockpits, give it a big

00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:07.260
enough matter stockpile and it could even have built another thesias, albeit in

00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:11.940
many small pieces and over a very long time. Some wondered if it could build

00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:16.420
another crew as well, although we'd been assured that was impossible. Not even

00:21:16.420 --> 00:21:20.660
these machines had fine enough fingers to reconstruct a few trillion SNAT synapses

00:21:20.660 --> 00:21:27.020
in the space of the human skull. Not yet, anyway. I believed it. They would never

00:21:27.020 --> 00:21:30.980
have shipped us out fully assembled if there had been a cheaper alternative. I

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:35.180
faced forward. Putting the back of my head against that sealed hatch, I could see

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:40.060
almost a thesias' bow, an uninterrupted line of sight extending to a tiny dark

00:21:40.060 --> 00:21:44.580
bullseye 30 meters ahead. It was like staring at a great textured target in

00:21:44.580 --> 00:21:48.020
shades of white and gray, concentric circles, hatches centered within

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:52.340
bulkheads one behind another, perfectly aligned. Every once stood open in

00:21:52.340 --> 00:21:56.700
non-schlot defiance of a previous generation's safety codes. We could keep

00:21:56.700 --> 00:22:00.940
them closed if we wanted to, if it made us feel safer. That was all it would do

00:22:00.940 --> 00:22:05.380
though. It wouldn't improve our Imperial odds one bit. In the event of trouble,

00:22:05.380 --> 00:22:09.140
those hatches would slam shut milliseconds before human senses could even make

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:14.020
sense of an alarm. They weren't even computer controlled. The easiest body

00:22:14.020 --> 00:22:19.220
parts had reflexes. I pushed off against the stern plating, wincing at the tug

00:22:19.220 --> 00:22:23.820
and stretch of disused tendons, and coasted forward, leaving the fab behind.

00:22:23.820 --> 00:22:28.780
The shuttle-axis hatches to Silla and Caribdis briefly constricted my passage

00:22:28.820 --> 00:22:33.260
to either side. Past them, the spine widened into a corrugated extensible

00:22:33.260 --> 00:22:39.100
cylinder two meters across and, at the moment, maybe 15 long. A pair of ladders

00:22:39.100 --> 00:22:43.340
ran opposite each other along its length. Raised portholes the size of manhole covers

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:47.420
stippled the bulkhead to either side. Most of those just looked into the hold.

00:22:47.420 --> 00:22:51.020
A couple served as general-purpose airlocks should anyone want to take a

00:22:51.020 --> 00:22:55.700
stroll beneath the Caribbas. One opened into my tent. Another, four meters

00:22:55.740 --> 00:23:00.740
further forward, opened to debates. From a third, just short of the forward

00:23:00.740 --> 00:23:06.100
bulkhead, Yucca Sardosti climbed into view like a long white spider. If he'd

00:23:06.100 --> 00:23:09.940
been human, I'd have known instantly what I saw there. I'd have smelled murderer

00:23:09.940 --> 00:23:14.060
all over his topology. And I wouldn't have been able to even guess at the number

00:23:14.060 --> 00:23:18.460
of his victims because his affect was so utterly without remorse. The killing of

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:26.100
100 was so... ah, start over. The killing of 100 would leave no more stain on

00:23:26.100 --> 00:23:30.460
Sardosti's services and the swatting of an insect. Gilt beat it and rolled off

00:23:30.460 --> 00:23:35.780
its creature like water on wax. But Sardosti wasn't human. Sardosti was a

00:23:35.780 --> 00:23:39.300
whole different animal and coming from him all those homicidal refractions

00:23:39.300 --> 00:23:43.340
meant nothing more than predator. He had the inclination. He had the

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:48.180
inclination. Was born to it. Whether he had ever acted on it was between him and

00:23:48.220 --> 00:23:53.500
mission control. Maybe they cut you some slack, I didn't say to him. Maybe it's

00:23:53.500 --> 00:23:57.220
just the cost of doing business. Your mission critical after all. For all I

00:23:57.220 --> 00:24:01.580
know they cut you a deal. You're so very smart. You know we wouldn't have brought

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:05.780
you back in the first place if we hadn't needed you. From the day they cracked

00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:10.740
that vat you knew you had leverage. Isn't that how it works, Yucca? You save

00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:15.420
the world and the folks who hold your leash agree to look the other way. As a

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:18.780
child I'd read tales about jungle predators transfixing their prey with a

00:24:18.780 --> 00:24:23.980
stare. Only after I'd met Yucca Sardosti did I know how it felt. But he wasn't

00:24:23.980 --> 00:24:28.020
looking at me now. He was focused on installing his own tent and even if he

00:24:28.020 --> 00:24:30.860
had looked me in the eye there'd have been nothing to see with the dark wrap

00:24:30.860 --> 00:24:35.740
around visor. He wore indeference to human skittishness. He ignored me as I

00:24:35.740 --> 00:24:42.780
grabbed a nearby rung and squeezed past. I could have sworn I smelled raw meat

00:24:42.780 --> 00:24:48.060
on his breath. Into the drum. Drums, technically. The biomed hoop at the back

00:24:48.060 --> 00:24:52.620
spawning its own bearings. I flew through the center of a cylinder 16 meters

00:24:52.620 --> 00:24:57.780
across. Theseus spinal nerves ran along its axis. The exposed plexi and piping

00:24:57.780 --> 00:25:02.180
bundled against the ladders on either side. Past them spindles and James

00:25:02.180 --> 00:25:06.380
freshly erected tents rose from nooks on opposite sides of the world. Spindle

00:25:06.380 --> 00:25:10.460
himself loaded off my shoulders. Still naked but for his gloves. I could tell

00:25:10.540 --> 00:25:14.500
from the way his fingers moved that his favorite color was green. He anchored

00:25:14.500 --> 00:25:18.380
himself to one of the three stairways to nowhere arranged around the drum.

00:25:18.380 --> 00:25:22.700
Steep narrow steps rising five vertical meters from the deck into empty air.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:27.820
The next hatch gave dead center of the drum's forward wall. Pipes and

00:25:27.820 --> 00:25:31.900
conduits plunged into the bulkhead on either side. I grabbed a convenient

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:36.140
rung to slow myself, biting down once more on the pain, and floated through.

00:25:36.540 --> 00:25:41.340
T-junction. The spinal corridor continued forward. A small diverticulum

00:25:41.340 --> 00:25:45.740
branched off to an EVA cubby in the forward airlock. I stayed the course and

00:25:45.740 --> 00:25:49.100
found myself back in the crypt, mirror bright and less than two meters deep.

00:25:49.660 --> 00:25:54.780
Empty pods gaped to the left, sealed ones to the right. We were so irreplaceable we'd come with

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:59.420
replacements. They slept on, oblivious. I'd met three of them back in training.

00:25:59.420 --> 00:26:04.140
Hopefully none of us would be getting reacquainted anytime soon. Only four pods

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:10.460
to starboard though. No backup for Svarasti. Another hatchway, smaller this time.

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:15.900
I squeezed through into the bridge. Dim light there. A silent, shifting mosaic of icons and

00:26:15.900 --> 00:26:21.420
alphanumerics iterating across dark glassy surfaces. Not so much bridge as cockpit and a

00:26:21.420 --> 00:26:26.860
cramped one at that. I'd emerged between two acceleration couches, each surrounded by a horseshoe

00:26:26.860 --> 00:26:32.940
array of controls and readouts. Nobody expected to ever use this compartment. Thesias was perfectly

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:39.500
capable of running herself. And if she weren't, we were capable of running her from our inlays.

00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:44.620
And if we weren't, odds were overwhelming we were all dead anyway. Still, against that

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:49.500
astronomically off-the-wall chance, this was where one or two intrepid survivors could pilot

00:26:49.500 --> 00:26:54.700
the ship home after everything else had failed. Between the footwells, the engineers had crammed

00:26:54.700 --> 00:27:00.620
one last hatch and one last passageway to the observation blister on Thesias' prow. I hunched

00:27:00.620 --> 00:27:08.140
my shoulders, tendons cracked and complained, and pushed through into darkness. Clam shell shielding

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:13.340
covered the outside of the dome like a pair of eyelids squeezed tight. A single icon glowed

00:27:13.340 --> 00:27:18.060
softly from a touchpad to my left. A faint stray light followed me through from the spine,

00:27:18.620 --> 00:27:24.220
brushed in fingers across the concave enclosure. The dome resolved in faint shades of blue and

00:27:24.220 --> 00:27:29.820
gray as my eyes adjusted. A stale draft stirred the webbing floating up from the rear bulkhead,

00:27:29.900 --> 00:27:35.020
mixed oil and machinery at the back of my throat. Buckles clicked faintly in the breeze like

00:27:35.020 --> 00:27:40.860
impoverished wind chimes. I reached out and touched the crystal. The innermost layer of two,

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:46.620
warm air piped through the gap between to cut the cold. Not completely, though. My fingertips

00:27:46.620 --> 00:27:53.900
chilled instantly. Space out there. Perhaps en route to our original destination, Thesias had seen

00:27:53.900 --> 00:27:58.940
something that scared her clear out of the solar system. More likely she hadn't been running away

00:27:58.940 --> 00:28:03.500
from anything but to something else, something that hadn't been discovered until we'd already

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:10.140
died and gone to heaven. In which case, I reached back and tapped the touchpad. I half expected

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:15.500
nothing to happen. Thesias windows could be as easily locked as their com logs. But the dome

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:21.500
split instantly before me. A crack, then a crescent, then a wide-eyed, lidless stare as the shielding

00:28:21.500 --> 00:28:27.580
slid smoothly back into the hull. My fingers clenched reflexively into a fistful of webbing.

00:28:27.580 --> 00:28:32.220
The sudden void stretched empty and unforgiving in all directions, and there was nothing to cling

00:28:32.220 --> 00:28:39.340
to but a metal disk barely four meters across. Stars everywhere. So many stars that I could not

00:28:39.340 --> 00:28:47.740
for the life of me understand how the sky could contain them yet all be so black. Stars and nothing

00:28:47.740 --> 00:28:53.820
else. What did you expect, I chided myself. An alien mothership hanging off the starboard bow?

00:28:54.540 --> 00:29:00.380
Well, why not? We were out here for something. The others were anyway. They'd be essential no

00:29:00.380 --> 00:29:06.700
matter where we ended up. My own situation was different, I realized. My usefulness degraded

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:13.340
with distance, and we were over half a light year from home. When it is dark enough, you can see the

00:29:13.340 --> 00:29:21.500
stars. Emerson. Where was I when the lights came down? I was emerging from the gates of heaven,

00:29:21.500 --> 00:29:27.340
mourning a father who was, to his own mind at least, still alive. It had been scarcely two months

00:29:27.340 --> 00:29:32.540
since Helen had disappeared under the cowl. Two months by hour reckoning at least. From her

00:29:32.540 --> 00:29:37.180
perspective it could have been a day or a decade, the virtually omnipotent set their subjective

00:29:37.180 --> 00:29:42.940
clocks along with everything else. She wasn't coming back. She would only deign to see her husband

00:29:42.940 --> 00:29:48.700
under conditions that amounted to a slap in the face. He didn't complain. He visited as often as

00:29:48.700 --> 00:29:55.820
she would allow. Twice a week, then once, then every two. Their marriage decayed with the exponential

00:29:55.820 --> 00:30:00.940
determinism of a radioactive isotope, and he still sought her out, except for her conditions.

00:30:02.140 --> 00:30:07.260
On the day the lights came down, I had joined him at my mother's side. It was a special occasion,

00:30:07.260 --> 00:30:12.380
the last time we would ever see her in the flesh. For two months her body had lain in a state along

00:30:12.380 --> 00:30:18.620
with 500 other new ascendants on the ward, open for viewing by the next of kin. The interface was

00:30:18.620 --> 00:30:23.100
no more real than it would ever be, of course. The body could not talk to us, but at least it was there.

00:30:23.660 --> 00:30:29.260
Its flesh warm, the sheets clean and straight, Helen's lower face still visible below the cowl,

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:35.740
though eyes and ears were helmeted. We could touch her. My father often did. Perhaps some distant

00:30:35.740 --> 00:30:42.300
part of her still felt it. But eventually someone has to close the casket and dispose of the remains.

00:30:42.300 --> 00:30:46.940
Room must be made for new arrivals, so we came to this last day at my mother's side.

00:30:47.740 --> 00:30:52.620
Jim took her hand one more time. She would still be available in her world on her terms,

00:30:52.620 --> 00:30:57.100
but later this day the body would be packed into storage facilities crowded far too efficiently

00:30:57.100 --> 00:31:02.300
for flesh and blood visitors. We had been assured that the body would remain intact.

00:31:02.300 --> 00:31:07.340
The muscles electrically exercised, the body flexed and fed, the corpus kept ready to return

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:11.580
to active duty should have an experience on inconceivable and catastrophic meltdown.

00:31:12.380 --> 00:31:17.740
Everything was reversible, we were told. And yet, there were so many who had ascended,

00:31:17.740 --> 00:31:22.860
and not even the deepest catacombs go on forever. There were rumors of dismemberment,

00:31:22.860 --> 00:31:28.220
of non-essential body parts hewn away over time according to some optimum packing algorithm.

00:31:28.940 --> 00:31:33.100
Perhaps Helen would be a torso this time next year, and is somebody to head the year after.

00:31:33.660 --> 00:31:37.580
Perhaps chassis would be stripped down to the brain before we'd even left the building,

00:31:37.660 --> 00:31:42.460
awaiting only that final technological breakthrough that would herald the arrival of the great digital

00:31:42.460 --> 00:31:48.700
upload. Rumors, as I say, I personally didn't know of anyone who'd come back after ascending,

00:31:48.700 --> 00:31:53.180
but then why would anyone want to? Not even Lucifer left heaven until he was pushed.

00:31:55.340 --> 00:31:59.660
Dad might have known for sure. Dad knew more than most people about the things that people

00:31:59.660 --> 00:32:06.460
weren't supposed to know, but he never told tales out of turn. Whatever he knew, he'd obviously

00:32:06.460 --> 00:32:11.180
decided its disclosure wouldn't have changed Helen's mind. That would have been enough for him.

00:32:12.140 --> 00:32:16.780
We'd on the hoods that served as day passes for the unwired, and we met my mother in the Spartan

00:32:16.780 --> 00:32:22.220
visiting room she imagined for these visits. She'd built no windows into the world she occupied,

00:32:22.220 --> 00:32:28.140
no hint of whatever utopian environment she'd constructed for herself. She hadn't even opted

00:32:28.140 --> 00:32:32.540
for one of the prefab visiting environments designed to minimize dissonance among visitors.

00:32:33.260 --> 00:32:38.860
We found ourselves in a featureless bay sphere five meters across. There was nothing in there

00:32:38.860 --> 00:32:46.380
but her. Maybe not so far removed from her version of utopia after all, I thought. My father smiled.

00:32:46.380 --> 00:32:53.340
Helen. Jim! She was twenty years younger than the thing on the bed, but still she made my skin crawl.

00:32:53.340 --> 00:32:58.860
Siri, you came! She always used my name. I don't think she ever called me son.

00:32:59.820 --> 00:33:01.900
You're still happy here? My father asked.

00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:04.780
Wonderful! I do wish you could join us.

00:33:05.660 --> 00:33:08.300
Jim smiled. Someone asked to keep the lights on.

00:33:09.180 --> 00:33:13.100
Now you know this isn't goodbye, she said. You can visit whenever you like.

00:33:14.140 --> 00:33:20.060
Only if you do something about the scenery. Not just a joke, but a lie. Jim would have come at

00:33:20.060 --> 00:33:26.140
her call even if the gauntlet involved bare feet and broken glass. And Chelsea too, Helen continued.

00:33:26.140 --> 00:33:29.820
It would be so nice to finally meet her after all this time.

00:33:30.860 --> 00:33:37.180
Chelsea's gone, Helen, I said. Oh yes, but I know you stay in touch. I know she was special to you.

00:33:37.180 --> 00:33:41.900
Just because you're not together anymore doesn't mean she can't. You know she...

00:33:42.700 --> 00:33:47.580
A startling possibility stopped me in mid-sentence. Maybe I hadn't actually told them.

00:33:48.540 --> 00:33:52.220
Son, Jim said quietly. Maybe you could give us a moment.

00:33:52.700 --> 00:33:58.700
I would have given them a fucking lifetime. I unplugged myself back to the ward, looked from

00:33:58.700 --> 00:34:03.500
the corpse on the bed to my blind and catatonic father on his couch, murmuring sweet nothings

00:34:03.500 --> 00:34:09.340
into the data stream. Let them perform for each other. Let them formalize and finalize their so

00:34:09.340 --> 00:34:14.780
called relationship in whatever way they saw fit. Maybe just once they could even bring themselves

00:34:14.780 --> 00:34:18.940
to be honest, there in that other world where everything else was a lie. Maybe.

00:34:19.900 --> 00:34:25.420
I felt no desire to bear witness either way. But of course I had to go back in for my own

00:34:25.420 --> 00:34:31.580
formalities. I adopted my role and the familial set piece one last time, partook of the usual lies.

00:34:32.140 --> 00:34:36.380
We all agreed that this wasn't going to change anything and nobody deviated enough from the

00:34:36.380 --> 00:34:42.620
script to call anyone else liar on their account. And finally, careful to say until next time rather

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:48.620
than goodbye, we took our leave of my mother. I even suppressed my gag reflex long enough to

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:56.700
give her a hug. Jim had his inhaler in hand as we emerged from the darkness. I hoped, without much

00:34:56.700 --> 00:35:01.740
hope, that he'd throw it in the garbage receptacles we passed through the lobby. But he'd raised it

00:35:01.740 --> 00:35:08.540
to his mouth and took another hit of vasopressin that he would never be tempted. Fidelity in an

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:15.580
aerosol. You don't need that anymore, I said. Probably not, he agreed. It won't work anyway.

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:20.060
You can't just imprint on someone who isn't even there, no matter how many hormones you snored.

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:26.060
It just... Jim said nothing. We passed beneath the muzzles of centuries panning for infiltrating

00:35:26.060 --> 00:35:32.380
realists. She's gone, I blurted. She doesn't care if you find someone else. She'd be happy if you did.

00:35:33.260 --> 00:35:37.820
It would let her pretend the books had been balanced. She's my wife, he told me.

00:35:38.700 --> 00:35:44.380
That doesn't mean what it used to. It never did. He smiled a bit at that. It's my life, son.

00:35:44.380 --> 00:35:50.220
I'm comfortable with it. Dad, I don't blame her, he said, and neither should you.

00:35:51.660 --> 00:35:56.540
Easy for him to say. Easy even to accept the hurt he'd inflicted on him all these years.

00:35:57.180 --> 00:36:02.540
This cheerful facade here at the end, hardly made up for the endless bitter complaints my father had

00:36:02.540 --> 00:36:07.180
endured throughout living memory. Do you think it's easy when you disappear for a month on end?

00:36:07.740 --> 00:36:11.820
Do you think it's easy always wondering who you're with and what you're doing and even if you're alive?

00:36:12.780 --> 00:36:15.580
Do you think it's easy raising a child like that on your own?

00:36:16.540 --> 00:36:21.180
She'd blamed him for everything, but he bore it gracefully because he knew it was all a lie.

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:27.340
He knew he was only the pretense. She wasn't leaving because he was AWOL or unfaithful.

00:36:27.340 --> 00:36:33.900
Her departure had nothing to do with him at all. It was me. Helen left the world because she couldn't

00:36:33.900 --> 00:36:39.900
stand to look at the thing who replaced her son. I would have pursued it, would have tried yet again

00:36:39.900 --> 00:36:44.940
to make my father see, but by now we'd left the gates of heaven for the streets of Purgatory,

00:36:44.940 --> 00:36:49.820
where pedestrian's and all sides murmured an astonishment and stared open mouth at the sky.

00:36:50.700 --> 00:36:55.660
I followed their gaze to a strip of raw twilight between the towers and gasped.

00:36:56.460 --> 00:37:02.700
The stars were falling. The zodiac had rearranged itself into a precise grid of bright points with

00:37:02.700 --> 00:37:07.900
luminous tails. It was as though the whole planet had been caught in some great closing net, the

00:37:07.980 --> 00:37:13.740
knots of its mesh aglow with St. Elmo's fire. It was beautiful. It was terrifying.

00:37:14.700 --> 00:37:19.660
I looked away to recalibrate my distance vision to give this ill-behaved hallucination a chance

00:37:19.660 --> 00:37:25.660
to vanish gracefully before I set my empirical gaze to high beam. I saw a vampire in that moment,

00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:31.420
a female, walking among us like the archetypal wolf in sheep's clothing. Vampires were uncommon

00:37:31.420 --> 00:37:37.020
creatures on street level. I'd never seen one in the flesh before. She had just stepped onto the

00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:41.660
street from the building across the way. She stood ahead taller than the rest of us, her eyes

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:47.820
shining yellow and bright as a cat in the deep, deepening dark. She realized as I watched that

00:37:47.820 --> 00:37:53.660
something was amiss. She looked around, glanced at the sky, and continued on her way, totally

00:37:53.660 --> 00:37:57.820
indifferent to the cattle on all sides, to the heavenly portent that had transfixed them.

00:37:58.940 --> 00:38:02.140
Totally indifferent to the fact that the world had just turned inside out.

00:38:03.100 --> 00:38:08.060
It was 1035 Greenwich Mean Time, February 13th, 2082.

00:38:12.060 --> 00:38:17.340
They clenched around the world like a fist. Each black as the inside of an event horizon until

00:38:17.340 --> 00:38:23.420
those last bright moments when they all burned together. They screamed as they died. Every radio

00:38:23.420 --> 00:38:30.140
up to geostat, groaned in unison. Every infrared telescope went briefly snow-blind. Ashes stained

00:38:30.220 --> 00:38:35.660
the sky for weeks afterwards. Mesophheric clouds high above the jet stream turned to glowing rust

00:38:35.660 --> 00:38:49.020
with every sunrise. The objects apparently consisted largely of iron. Nobody ever knew

00:38:49.020 --> 00:38:55.340
what to make of that. But for perhaps the first time in history the world knew before being told,

00:38:55.900 --> 00:39:01.260
if you'd seen the sky, you had the scoop. The usual arbiters of newsworthiness stripped of the

00:39:01.260 --> 00:39:07.100
accustomed role in filtering reality had to be content with merely labeling it. It took them

00:39:07.100 --> 00:39:13.580
90 minutes to agree on fireflies. A half hour after that, the first Fourier transforms had

00:39:13.580 --> 00:39:18.540
appeared in the news sphere. To no one's great surprise, the fireflies had not wasted their

00:39:18.540 --> 00:39:24.140
dying breaths on static. There was pattern embedded in that terminal chorus, some cryptic

00:39:24.140 --> 00:39:31.180
intelligence that resisted all earthly analysis. The experts, rigorously empirical, refused to

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:36.700
speculate. They only admitted that the fireflies had said something. They didn't know what.

00:39:37.740 --> 00:39:45.980
Everyone else did. How else would you explain 65,536 probes evenly dispersed along a latitude

00:39:45.980 --> 00:39:52.140
longitude grid that barely left any square meter of planetary surface unexposed? Obviously,

00:39:52.140 --> 00:39:57.100
the flies had taken our picture. The whole world had been caught with its pants down in panoramic

00:39:57.100 --> 00:40:03.180
composite freeze frame. We'd been surveyed. Whether as a prelude to formal introductions or outright

00:40:03.180 --> 00:40:10.140
invasion was anyone's guess. My father might have known someone who might have known. But by then he'd

00:40:10.140 --> 00:40:16.380
long since disappeared, as he always did during times of hemispheric crisis. Whatever he knew or

00:40:16.380 --> 00:40:21.660
didn't, he'd left me to find my own answers with everyone else. There was no shortage of

00:40:21.660 --> 00:40:27.100
perspectives. The news sphere seethed with scenarios ranging from utopian to apocalyptic.

00:40:27.660 --> 00:40:33.180
The fireflies had seated lethal germs throughout the jet stream. The fireflies had been on nature

00:40:33.180 --> 00:40:38.460
safari. The Icarus Array was being retooled to power a doomsday weapon against the aliens.

00:40:39.100 --> 00:40:44.140
The Icarus Array had already been destroyed. We had decades to react. Anything from another

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:47.500
solar system would have to obey the light speed limit just like everything else.

00:40:48.220 --> 00:40:53.260
We had days to live. Organic warships had just crossed the asteroid belt and would be fumigating

00:40:53.260 --> 00:40:59.820
the planet within a week. Like everyone else, I bore witness to lurid speculations and talking

00:40:59.820 --> 00:41:05.260
heads. I visited blather nodes, soaked myself in other people's opinions. That was nothing new

00:41:05.260 --> 00:41:10.460
as far as it went. I'd spent my whole life as a sort of alien ethologist in my own right,

00:41:10.460 --> 00:41:14.940
watching the world behave, gleaning patterns and protocols, learning the rules that allowed

00:41:14.940 --> 00:41:23.260
me to infiltrate human society. It had always worked before. Somehow, though, the presence of

00:41:23.260 --> 00:41:28.620
real aliens had changed the dynamics of the equation. Mirror observation didn't satisfy

00:41:28.620 --> 00:41:33.260
anymore. It was as though the presence of this new outgroup had forced me back into the clade

00:41:33.260 --> 00:41:38.460
whether I liked it or not. The distance between myself and the world suddenly seemed forced and

00:41:38.460 --> 00:41:43.100
faintly ridiculous. Yet I couldn't for the life of me figure out how to let it go.

00:41:44.460 --> 00:41:48.540
Chelsea had always said that telepresence emptied the humanity from human interaction.

00:41:49.100 --> 00:41:53.820
They say it's indistinguishable, she told me once. Just like having your family right there,

00:41:53.820 --> 00:41:58.460
snuggled up so you can see them and feel them and smell them next to you. But it's not. It's just

00:41:58.460 --> 00:42:03.100
shadows on the cave wall. I mean, sure, the shadows come in 3D color with force feedback,

00:42:03.100 --> 00:42:07.660
tactile interactivity. They're good enough to fool the civilized brain, but your gut knows

00:42:07.660 --> 00:42:13.420
those aren't people, even if it can't put its finger on how it knows. They just don't feel real.

00:42:13.420 --> 00:42:18.940
Know what I mean? I didn't. Back then I'd had no clue what she was talking about.

00:42:19.500 --> 00:42:23.660
But now we were all cavemen again, huddling beneath some overhang while lightning split

00:42:23.660 --> 00:42:29.500
the heavens and vast formless monsters barely glimpsed in bright strobe-frozen instance roared

00:42:29.500 --> 00:42:35.580
and clashed in darkness on all sides. There was no comfort in solitude. You couldn't get it from

00:42:35.580 --> 00:42:41.500
interactive shadows. You needed someone real at your side, someone to hold on to, someone to share

00:42:41.500 --> 00:42:46.700
your airspace along with your fear and hope and uncertainty. I imagine the presence of

00:42:46.700 --> 00:42:52.060
companions who wouldn't vanish the moment I unplugged, but Chelsea was gone and Pag in her wake.

00:42:52.780 --> 00:42:57.980
The few others I could have called, peers and former clients with whom I impersonations of rapport

00:42:57.980 --> 00:43:03.500
had been especially convincing, didn't seem worth the effort. Flesh and blood had its own

00:43:03.500 --> 00:43:09.580
relationship to reality, necessary but not sufficient. Watching the world from a distance

00:43:09.580 --> 00:43:14.700
that occurred to me at last, I knew exactly what Chelsea had meant with her lead-out ramblings about

00:43:14.700 --> 00:43:21.420
desaturated humanity and the colorless interactions of virtual space. I'd known all along. I'd just

00:43:21.420 --> 00:43:23.980
never been able to see how it was any different from real life.

00:43:24.940 --> 00:43:33.820
Imagine you are a machine. Yes, I know, but imagine you're a different kind of machine,

00:43:33.820 --> 00:43:38.860
one built from metal and plastic and designed not by blind haphazard natural selection by

00:43:38.860 --> 00:43:45.100
engineers and astrophysicists with their eyes fixed firmly on specific goals. Imagine that your

00:43:45.100 --> 00:43:51.100
purpose is not to replicate or even to survive but to gather information. I can imagine that easily.

00:43:51.660 --> 00:43:56.060
It is in fact a much simpler impersonation than the kind I'm usually called on to perform.

00:43:57.340 --> 00:44:02.940
I coast through the abyss on the colder side of Neptune's orbit. Most of the time I exist only as

00:44:02.940 --> 00:44:09.020
an absence to any observer on the visible spectrum, a moving asymmetrical silhouette blocking the stars.

00:44:09.820 --> 00:44:14.780
But occasionally during my slow endless spin, I glint with dim hints of reflected starlight.

00:44:15.420 --> 00:44:18.780
If you catch me in those moments, you might infer something of my true nature,

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:24.540
a segmented creature with foil skin bristling with joints and dishes and spindly antennae.

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:30.140
Here and there a whisper of accumulated frost clings to a joint or seam, some frozen

00:44:30.140 --> 00:44:35.820
wisp of gas encountered in Jupiter space perhaps. Elsewhere I carry the microscopic corpses of

00:44:35.820 --> 00:44:40.860
earthly bacteria who thrived with carefree abandon on the skins of space stations or the benign lunar

00:44:40.860 --> 00:44:47.340
surface, but who had gone to crystal at only half present distance from the Sun. Now a breath away

00:44:47.340 --> 00:44:53.740
from absolute zero they might shatter to Photon's touch. My heart is warm at least. A tiny nuclear

00:44:53.740 --> 00:44:59.340
fire burns in my thorax, leaves me indifferent to the cold outside. It won't go out for a thousand

00:44:59.340 --> 00:45:04.380
years barring some catastrophic accident. For a thousand years I will listen for faint voices

00:45:04.380 --> 00:45:10.300
from mission control and do everything they tell me to do. So far they have told me to study comets.

00:45:11.100 --> 00:45:16.140
Every instruction I have received has been a precise and unambiguous elaboration on that one

00:45:16.140 --> 00:45:22.380
overriding reason for my existence. Which is why these latest instructions are so puzzling,

00:45:22.380 --> 00:45:28.380
for they make no sense at all. The frequency is wrong. The signal strength is wrong. I cannot

00:45:28.380 --> 00:45:34.860
even understand the handshaking protocols. I request clarification. The response arrives

00:45:34.860 --> 00:45:39.900
almost a thousand minutes later and it is an unprecedented mix of orders and requests for

00:45:39.900 --> 00:45:46.700
information. My answer is best I can. Yes, this is the bearing at which signal strength was greatest.

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:53.260
No, it is not the usual bearing for mission control. Yes, I can retransmit. Here it is all over again.

00:45:53.820 --> 00:46:00.620
Yes, I will go into standby mode. I await further instructions. They arrive 839 minutes later and

00:46:00.620 --> 00:46:06.140
they tell me to stop studying comets immediately. I am to commence a controlled, possessive tumble

00:46:06.140 --> 00:46:10.860
that sweeps my antenna through a consecutive 5 degree arc increments along all three axes

00:46:10.860 --> 00:46:16.300
with a period of 94 seconds. Upon encountering any transmission resembling the one which confused

00:46:16.300 --> 00:46:21.820
me, I am to fix upon the bearing of maximal signal strength and arise a series of parameter values.

00:46:22.620 --> 00:46:25.820
I am also instructed to retransmit the signal to mission control.

00:46:27.260 --> 00:46:33.500
I do as I am told. For a long time I hear nothing, but I am infinitely patient and incapable of boredom.

00:46:34.380 --> 00:46:40.140
Eventually, a fleeting familiar signal brushes against my afferent array. I reacquire and track

00:46:40.140 --> 00:46:46.220
it to source, which I am well equipped to describe, a trans-Neptunian comet in the Kuiper Belt,

00:46:46.220 --> 00:46:52.460
approximately 200 kilometers in diameter. It is sweeping a 21 centimeter tight beam radio wave

00:46:52.460 --> 00:46:58.620
across the heavens with a periodicity of 4.57 seconds. This beam does not intersect mission

00:46:58.620 --> 00:47:03.420
control's coordinates at any point. It appears to be directed at a different target entirely.

00:47:04.380 --> 00:47:08.780
It takes much longer than usual for mission control to respond to this information.

00:47:09.580 --> 00:47:15.100
When it does, it tells me to change course. Mission control informs me that henceforth

00:47:15.100 --> 00:47:21.900
my new destination is to be referred to as Burns Callfield. Given current fuel and inertial constraints,

00:47:21.900 --> 00:47:27.260
I will not reach it in less than 39 years. I am to watch nothing else in the meantime.

00:47:28.620 --> 00:47:36.620
I had been liaising for a team at the Kurzweil Institute, a fractured group of cutting-edge

00:47:36.620 --> 00:47:40.780
savants convinced they were on the verge of solving the quantum glial paradox,

00:47:40.780 --> 00:47:46.540
that particular logjam installed AI for decades. Once broken, the expert promised we'd be 18 months

00:47:46.540 --> 00:47:51.660
away from the first personality upload and only two years from reliable human consciousness emulation

00:47:51.660 --> 00:47:57.660
in a software environment. It would spell the end of corporeal history, usher in a singularity that

00:47:57.740 --> 00:48:03.580
had been wading in the wings impatiently for nigh on 50 years. Two months after firefall,

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:09.100
the institute cancelled my contract. I was actually surprised it had taken them so long.

00:48:09.100 --> 00:48:14.620
It had cost us so much, this overnight inversion of global priorities, these breakneck measures

00:48:14.620 --> 00:48:20.620
making up for lost initiative. Not even our shiny, new post-scarcity economy could withstand such a

00:48:20.620 --> 00:48:26.300
seismic shift without lurching towards bankruptcy. Installations in deep space, long-sense imagines

00:48:26.300 --> 00:48:31.020
secure by virtue of their remoteness, were suddenly vulnerable for exactly the same reason.

00:48:31.580 --> 00:48:36.860
The Grange habitats had to be refitted for defense against an unknown enemy. Commercial ships on

00:48:36.860 --> 00:48:41.660
the Martian loop were conscripted, weaponized, and reassigned. Some secured to the high ground

00:48:41.660 --> 00:48:47.660
over Mars while others fell sunward to guard the Icarus Array. It didn't matter that the fireflies

00:48:47.660 --> 00:48:53.180
hadn't fired a shot at any of these targets. We certainly couldn't afford the risk. We were all

00:48:53.260 --> 00:48:58.220
in it together, of course, desperate to regain some hypothetical upper hand by any means necessary.

00:48:58.940 --> 00:49:03.820
Kings and corporations scribbled IOUs on the backs of napkins and promised to sort everything out

00:49:03.820 --> 00:49:08.780
once the heat was off. In the meantime, the prospect of utopia in two years took a back seat

00:49:08.780 --> 00:49:13.900
to the shadow of Armageddon reaching back from next Tuesday. The Kurzweil Institute, like everyone

00:49:13.900 --> 00:49:20.140
else, suddenly had other things to worry about. So I returned to my apartment, split a bulb of

00:49:20.140 --> 00:49:26.620
Genfiddich, and arrayed virtual windows like daisy petals in my head. Everyone icons debated on all

00:49:26.620 --> 00:49:32.540
sides, serving up leftovers two weeks past their expiry date. This graceful breakdown of global

00:49:32.540 --> 00:49:40.060
security. No harm done. Calm sats annihilated, thousands dead. Random collisions, accidental deaths.

00:49:40.060 --> 00:49:46.540
Who sent them? We should have seen them coming. Why didn't we? Deep space, inverse square, do the math.

00:49:47.180 --> 00:49:52.940
They were stealthed. What do they want? We were raped. Jesus Christ, they just took our picture.

00:49:53.660 --> 00:50:00.700
Why the silence? Moon's fine. Mars is fine. Where are they? Why haven't they made contact?

00:50:01.340 --> 00:50:06.460
Nothing's touched the O'Neill's. Technology implies belligerence. Are they coming back?

00:50:07.180 --> 00:50:14.860
Nothing attacked us. Yet. Nothing invaded. So far. But where are they? Are they coming back?

00:50:15.420 --> 00:50:24.380
Anyone? Jim Moore voice only encrypted. Except? The text blossomed directly in my line of sight,

00:50:24.380 --> 00:50:30.060
eclipsing the debate. I read it twice. I tried to remember the last time he'd called from the field,

00:50:30.060 --> 00:50:37.980
and couldn't. I muted the other windows. Dad? Son, he replied after a moment. Are you well?

00:50:39.100 --> 00:50:43.500
Like everyone else, still wondering whether we should be celebrating or crapping our pants.

00:50:44.460 --> 00:50:49.020
He didn't answer immediately. It's a big question, all right? He said it last.

00:50:49.820 --> 00:50:53.660
I don't suppose you could give me any advice. They're not telling us anything at ground level.

00:50:54.540 --> 00:50:58.780
It was a rhetorical request. His silence was hardly necessary to make the point.

00:51:00.060 --> 00:51:05.580
I know I added after a moment. Sorry, it's just they're saying the Icarus of Wittoray went down,

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:12.940
and you know I can't. Oh, my father paused. That's ridiculous. Icarus is fine. It is?

00:51:13.820 --> 00:51:17.900
He seemed to be weighing his words. The fireflies probably didn't even notice it.

00:51:17.900 --> 00:51:22.140
There's no particle trail as long as it stays off stream, and it would be buried in solar glare

00:51:22.140 --> 00:51:28.140
unless someone knew where to search. It was my turn to fall silent. This conversation felt suddenly

00:51:28.140 --> 00:51:34.060
wrong. Because when my father went on the job, he went dark. He never called his family.

00:51:35.420 --> 00:51:41.180
Because even when my father came off the job, he never talked about it. It wouldn't matter

00:51:41.180 --> 00:51:45.020
whether the Icarus Array was still online or whether it had been shredded and thrown into the

00:51:45.020 --> 00:51:49.900
sun like a thousand kilometers of torn origami. He wouldn't tell either tale unless an official

00:51:49.900 --> 00:51:55.500
announcement had been made. Which, I refreshed and indexed when Doge has to be sure. It hadn't.

00:51:56.540 --> 00:52:02.220
Because while my father was a man of few words, he was not a man of frequent indecisive pauses,

00:52:02.860 --> 00:52:06.860
and he had hesitated before each and every line he'd spoken in this exchange.

00:52:07.820 --> 00:52:13.900
I tugged ever so gently on the line. But they've sent ships, and started counting.

00:52:14.620 --> 00:52:20.940
One one thousand, two one thousand, just a precaution. Icarus was overdue for a visit anyway.

00:52:20.940 --> 00:52:24.300
You don't want to swap out your whole grid without at least dropping in and kicking the

00:52:24.300 --> 00:52:28.220
new tires first. Nearly three seconds to respond.

00:52:29.180 --> 00:52:33.500
You're on the moon, I said. Pause. Close enough.

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:38.700
What are you, dad? Why are you telling me this? Isn't this a security breach?

00:52:39.580 --> 00:52:46.540
You're going to get a call, he told me. From who? Why? They're assembling a team, the kind of

00:52:46.540 --> 00:52:51.660
people you deal with. My father was too rational to dispute the contributions of the

00:52:51.660 --> 00:52:55.900
reconz and hybrids in our midst, but he'd never been able to hide his mistrust of them.

00:52:56.700 --> 00:52:58.540
They need a synthesis, he said.

00:52:59.900 --> 00:53:05.340
Isn't it lucky you've got one in the family? Radio bounced back and forth.

00:53:05.340 --> 00:53:09.740
This isn't nephysism, Ciri. I've wanted very much for them to pick someone else.

00:53:10.780 --> 00:53:15.260
Thanks for the vote of Kant, but he'd seen it coming, and preempted me before my words could

00:53:15.260 --> 00:53:19.740
cross the distance. It's not a slap at your abilities and you know it. You're simply the

00:53:19.740 --> 00:53:25.420
most qualified and the work is vital. So why, I began and stopped. He wouldn't want to keep

00:53:25.420 --> 00:53:30.060
me away from some theoretical gig at a West Ham lab. What's this about, dad?

00:53:30.860 --> 00:53:33.100
The fireflies. They found something.

00:53:33.900 --> 00:53:38.780
What? A radio signal from the Kuiper. We traced the bearing.

00:53:39.420 --> 00:53:40.140
They're talking?

00:53:41.340 --> 00:53:46.940
Not to us, he cleared his throat. It was something of a fluke that we even intercepted the transmission.

00:53:47.660 --> 00:53:53.900
Who were they talking to? We don't know. Friendly, hostile, sun, we don't know.

00:53:54.780 --> 00:54:00.780
The encryption seems similar, but we can't even be sure of that. All we have is the location.

00:54:01.820 --> 00:54:07.500
So you're sending a team. You're sending me. We'd never gone to the Kuiper before.

00:54:08.060 --> 00:54:13.260
It had been decades since we'd even sent robots. Not that we lacked capacity. We just hadn't

00:54:13.260 --> 00:54:18.620
bothered. Everything we needed was so much closer to home. The interplanetary age had stagnated at

00:54:18.620 --> 00:54:23.820
the asteroids. But now something lurked at the furthest edge of our backyard, calling into the

00:54:23.820 --> 00:54:29.980
void. Maybe it was talking to some other solar system. Maybe it was talking to something closer.

00:54:29.980 --> 00:54:35.820
Something en route. It's not the kind of situation we can safely ignore, my father said.

00:54:37.420 --> 00:54:42.140
What about probes? Of course, but we can't wait for them to report back. The follow-ups

00:54:42.220 --> 00:54:48.380
then fast-tracked. Updates can be sent en route. He gave me a few extra seconds to digest that.

00:54:48.940 --> 00:54:54.940
When I still didn't speak, he said, You have to understand. Our only edge is that as far as we

00:54:54.940 --> 00:55:00.220
know Burns Callfield doesn't know we're onto it. We have to get as much as we can in whatever window

00:55:00.220 --> 00:55:07.340
of opportunity that grants us. But Burns Callfield hidden itself. Burns Callfield might not welcome

00:55:07.340 --> 00:55:15.340
a forced introduction. What if I refuse? The time lag seemed to say Mars. I know you son,

00:55:15.900 --> 00:55:20.940
you won't. But if I did, if I'm the best qualified, if the job's so vital,

00:55:21.900 --> 00:55:28.060
he didn't have to answer. I didn't have to ask. At these kind of stakes, mission critical elements

00:55:28.060 --> 00:55:33.260
didn't get the luxury of choice. I wouldn't even have the child's satisfaction of holding my breath

00:55:33.340 --> 00:55:37.980
and refusing to play. The will to resist is no less mechanical than the urge to breathe.

00:55:38.700 --> 00:55:41.420
Both can be subverted but the right neurochemical keys.

00:55:42.460 --> 00:55:47.660
You killed my Kurzweil contract, I realized. That's the least of what we did.

00:55:49.020 --> 00:55:51.500
We let the vacuum between us speak for a while.

00:55:53.100 --> 00:55:59.100
If I could go back and undo the thing that made you what you are, Dad said after a while,

00:55:59.820 --> 00:56:07.100
I wouldn't in a second. Yeah. I have to go. I just wanted to give you the heads up.

00:56:08.060 --> 00:56:13.980
Yeah, thanks. I love you son. Where are you? Are you coming back?

00:56:15.340 --> 00:56:18.220
Thanks, I said again. That's good to know.

00:56:20.140 --> 00:56:23.820
This is what my father could not un-make. This is what I am.

00:56:24.060 --> 00:56:28.060
I am the bridge between the bleeding edge and the dead center.

00:56:28.780 --> 00:56:34.060
I stand between the Wizard of Oz and the man behind the curtain. I am the curtain.

00:56:35.180 --> 00:56:39.660
I am not an entirely new breed. My roots reach back to the dawn of civilization,

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:43.100
but those precursors served a different function, a less honorable one.

00:56:43.820 --> 00:56:48.860
They only greased the wheels of social stability. They would sugarcoat unpleasant truths or

00:56:48.860 --> 00:56:54.380
inflate imaginary bogeymen for political expedience. They were vital enough in their own way.

00:56:54.380 --> 00:56:59.420
Not even the most heavily armed police state can exert brute force on all its citizens all the time.

00:57:00.300 --> 00:57:05.660
Meme management is so much subtler. The rose-tinted refraction of perceived reality,

00:57:05.660 --> 00:57:10.300
the contagious fear of threatening alternatives. There have always been those tasked with the

00:57:10.300 --> 00:57:14.940
rotation of informational topologies, but throughout most of history they had little to do with

00:57:14.940 --> 00:57:21.820
increasing its clarity. The new millennium changed all that. We've surpassed ourselves now. We're

00:57:21.820 --> 00:57:26.940
exploring terrain beyond the limits of merely human understanding. Sometimes it contours,

00:57:26.940 --> 00:57:30.860
even in conventional space, are just too intricate for our brains to track.

00:57:32.700 --> 00:57:37.500
Other times its very axes extend into dimensions inconceivable to minds built to

00:57:37.500 --> 00:57:43.660
fucking fight on some prehistoric grassland. So many things constrain us from so many directions.

00:57:44.380 --> 00:57:49.500
The most altruistic and sustainable philosophies fail before the brute brainstem imperative of

00:57:49.500 --> 00:57:54.780
self-interest. Subtle and elegant equations predict the behaviour of the quantum world,

00:57:54.780 --> 00:58:00.700
but none can explain it. After 4,000 years we can't even prove that reality exists beyond the

00:58:00.700 --> 00:58:06.940
mind of the first person dreamer. We have such need of intellects greater than our own. But we're

00:58:06.940 --> 00:58:12.460
not very good at building them. The forced matings of minds and electrons succeed and fail with

00:58:12.460 --> 00:58:19.020
equal spectacle. Our hybrids become as brilliant as savants and as autistic. We graft people to

00:58:19.020 --> 00:58:24.220
prosthetics, making their overloaded motor strips jiggle meat and machinery and shake our heads when

00:58:24.220 --> 00:58:29.100
their fingers twitch and their tongues stutter. Computers bootstrap their own offspring, grow

00:58:29.100 --> 00:58:34.380
so wise and incomprehensible to their communiques assume the hallmarks of dementia, unfocused and

00:58:34.380 --> 00:58:39.660
irrelevant to the barely intelligent creatures left behind. And when your surpassing creations

00:58:39.740 --> 00:58:44.780
find the answers you asked for, you can't understand their analysis and you can't verify their answers.

00:58:45.340 --> 00:58:51.900
You have to take their word on faith. Or you use information theory to flatten it for you,

00:58:51.900 --> 00:58:57.260
to squash the Tesseract into two dimensions and the Klein bottle into three, to simplify reality

00:58:57.260 --> 00:59:01.660
and pray to whatever gods survive the millennium but your honourable twisting of the truth hasn't

00:59:01.660 --> 00:59:07.580
ruptured off any of its load-bearing pylons. You hire people like me, the cross-bred progeny of

00:59:07.580 --> 00:59:13.180
profilers and proof assistants and information theorists. In formal settings you'd call me a

00:59:13.180 --> 00:59:19.180
synthesis. On the street you'd call me jargonaut or poppy. If you're one of those savants whose hard

00:59:19.180 --> 00:59:23.980
one truths are being bastardized and lobotomized or powerful no-nothings interested only in market

00:59:23.980 --> 00:59:30.940
share you might call me a mole or a chaperone. If your eyes expindle you'd call me commisar

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:36.300
and when the jive would be a friendly one it would also be more than that. I've never convinced myself

00:59:36.300 --> 00:59:41.660
that we made the right choice. I can cite the usual justifications in my sleep, talk endlessly

00:59:41.660 --> 00:59:46.540
about the rotational topology of information and the irrelevance of semantic comprehension.

00:59:47.340 --> 00:59:53.180
But after all the words I'm still not sure. I don't know if anyone else is either. Maybe it's just

00:59:53.180 --> 00:59:59.340
some grand consensual con. Marks and players all in league. We won't admit that our creations are

00:59:59.340 --> 01:00:04.700
beyond us. They may speak in tongues but our priests can read those signs. Gods leave their

01:00:04.700 --> 01:00:10.380
algorithms carved into the mountain side but it's just little old me bringing the tablets down to

01:00:10.380 --> 01:00:16.860
the masses and I don't threaten anyone. Maybe the singularity happened years ago. We just don't want

01:00:16.860 --> 01:00:28.140
to admit we were left behind. All kinds of animals living here. Occasional demons too. Ian Anderson,

01:00:28.220 --> 01:00:36.380
catfish rising. The third wave they called us. All in the same boat, driving into the long,

01:00:36.380 --> 01:00:41.420
dark courtesy of a bleeding edge prototype, crash graduated from the simulators full 18 months

01:00:41.420 --> 01:00:46.700
ahead of schedule. In a less fearful economy such violence to the timetable would have bankrupted

01:00:46.700 --> 01:00:52.540
four countries and 15 multi-corps. The first two waves came out of the gate and even more of a hurry.

01:00:52.540 --> 01:00:55.980
I didn't find out what happened to them until 30 minutes before the briefing.

01:00:56.620 --> 01:01:03.900
When Sodosti released the telemetry into consensus. Then I opened wide. Experience flooded up my

01:01:03.900 --> 01:01:09.660
inlays and spilled across my parietal cortex in glorious high density fast forward. Even now I

01:01:09.660 --> 01:01:17.740
can bring those data back fresh as the day they were recorded. I'm there. I'm them. I am unmanned.

01:01:18.380 --> 01:01:24.140
I am disposable. I am souped up and stripped down. A telematter drive with a couple of cameras bolted

01:01:24.220 --> 01:01:30.220
to the front end pushing G's that would turn meat to jelly. I sprint joyously toward the darkness.

01:01:30.220 --> 01:01:36.060
My twin brother hysterioscopic hundred clicks to starboard. Dual streams of backspat pions boosting

01:01:36.060 --> 01:01:42.060
us to relativity before poor old theseus had even crawled past Mars. But now six billion kilometers

01:01:42.060 --> 01:01:47.900
to stern mission control turns off the tap and leaves us coasting. The comet swells in our sights.

01:01:47.900 --> 01:01:53.660
A frozen enigma sweeping its signal across the sky like a lighthouse beam. We bring rudimentary

01:01:53.660 --> 01:01:59.500
senses to bear and stare it down a thousand wavelengths. We've lived for this moment.

01:02:00.620 --> 01:02:06.780
We see an erratic wobble that speaks of recent collisions. We see scars smooth icy expanses

01:02:06.780 --> 01:02:12.220
where once acne skin is liquefied and refrozen far too recently for the insignificant sun at our

01:02:12.220 --> 01:02:19.500
backs to be of any kind of suspect. We see an astronomical impossibility. A comet with a heart

01:02:19.500 --> 01:02:28.220
of refined iron burns call field sings as we glide past. Not to us. It ignores our passage as it

01:02:28.220 --> 01:02:33.820
ignored our approach. It sings to someone else entirely. Perhaps we'll meet that audience someday.

01:02:34.380 --> 01:02:39.340
Perhaps they're waiting in the desolate wastelands ahead of us. Mission control flips us onto our

01:02:39.340 --> 01:02:44.940
backs. Keep us fixed on our target past any realistic hope of acquisition. They send last

01:02:45.100 --> 01:02:48.860
ditch instructions. Squeeze our fading signals for every last bit among the static.

01:02:51.180 --> 01:02:56.700
I can sense their frustration. Their reluctance to let us go. Once or twice we're even asked if

01:02:56.700 --> 01:03:02.300
some judicious mix of thrust and gravity might let us linger here a bit longer. But deceleration is

01:03:02.300 --> 01:03:11.420
for pansies. We are headed for the stars. Bye, Burnsy. Bye, Mission Control. Bye, Sol. See you at heat death.

01:03:11.740 --> 01:03:19.900
Wherely we close on target. There are three of us in the second wave. Slower than our predecessors,

01:03:19.900 --> 01:03:25.740
yes, but still so much faster than anything flash constrained. We are weighed down by payloads which

01:03:25.740 --> 01:03:31.740
make us virtually omniscient. We see on every wavelength from radio to string. Our autonomous

01:03:31.740 --> 01:03:37.980
microbes measure everything our masters anticipated. Tiny onboard assembly lines that can build tools

01:03:37.980 --> 01:03:43.500
from the atoms up to assess the things they did not. Atoms scavenged from where we are,

01:03:43.500 --> 01:03:48.380
joined with ions beamed from where we were, thrust and material accumulate in our bellies.

01:03:49.740 --> 01:03:54.140
This extra mass has slowed us, but midpoint breaking maneuvers have slowed us even more.

01:03:54.700 --> 01:03:58.700
The last half of this journey has been a constant fight against momentum from the first.

01:03:59.420 --> 01:04:04.860
It is not an efficient way to travel. In lesser times we would have been built early to some

01:04:04.860 --> 01:04:10.540
optimal speed, perhaps slung around a convenient planet for a little extra oomph, coasted most of

01:04:10.540 --> 01:04:16.460
the way. But time is pressing, so we burn at both ends. We must reach our destination. We cannot

01:04:16.460 --> 01:04:23.020
afford to pass it. Cannot afford to kamikaze exuberance of the first wave. They merely glimpse

01:04:23.020 --> 01:04:28.540
the lay of the land. We must map it down to the moats. We must be more responsible.

01:04:28.700 --> 01:04:35.820
Now, slowing towards orbit, we see everything they saw and more. We see the scabs, the possible iron

01:04:35.820 --> 01:04:41.900
core, we hear the singing. And there, just beneath the comet's frozen surface, we see the structure,

01:04:41.900 --> 01:04:48.060
an infiltration of architecture into geology. We are not yet close enough to squint, and radar

01:04:48.060 --> 01:04:52.860
is too long in the tooth for fine detail. But we are smart, and there are three of us,

01:04:52.860 --> 01:04:58.700
widely separated in space. The wavelengths of three radar sources can be calibrated to interfere

01:04:58.700 --> 01:05:03.740
at some predetermined point of convergence, and those tripartite echoes, hologrammically

01:05:03.740 --> 01:05:10.860
remixed, will increase resolution by a factor of 27. Burns' call field stops singing the moment we

01:05:10.860 --> 01:05:19.180
put our planet to action. In the next instant, I go blind. It's a temporary aberration. A reflex

01:05:19.180 --> 01:05:25.500
amping off filters to compensate for the overload. My arrays are back online in seconds, diagnostics

01:05:25.500 --> 01:05:30.620
green and within and without. I reach out to the others, confirm identical experiences, identical

01:05:30.620 --> 01:05:35.900
recoveries. We are still fully functional unless the sudden increase in ambient ion density is

01:05:35.900 --> 01:05:41.100
some kind of sensory artifact. We are ready to continue investigation of Burns' call field.

01:05:42.300 --> 01:05:46.460
The only real problem is that Burns' call field seems to have disappeared.

01:05:49.420 --> 01:05:59.180
Theseus carried no regular crew. No navigators or engineers, no one to swab the decks, no meat

01:05:59.180 --> 01:06:03.980
wasted on tasks that machinery orders of mag smaller can perform orders of mag better.

01:06:04.860 --> 01:06:09.340
Let superfluous deck hands weigh down other ships, if the non-ascended hordes needed to

01:06:09.340 --> 01:06:14.940
attack some pre-tensive usefulness to their lives. Let them infest vessels driven only by commercial

01:06:14.940 --> 01:06:20.140
priorities. The only reason we were here was because nobody had yet optimized software for

01:06:20.140 --> 01:06:26.380
first contact. Bound past the edge of the solar system, already freighted with the fate of the

01:06:26.380 --> 01:06:32.940
world, Theseus wasted no mass on self-esteem. So here we were, rehydrated and squeaky clean.

01:06:33.580 --> 01:06:39.660
Isaac Spindle to study the aliens, the gang of four, Susan James and her secondary persona to

01:06:39.660 --> 01:06:46.780
talk to them. Major Amanda Bates was here to fight, if necessary, and Yuka Sodosti to command us all,

01:06:46.780 --> 01:06:51.580
to move us like chess pieces on some multi-dimensional game board that only vampires could see.

01:06:52.940 --> 01:06:56.940
He'd arrayed us around a conference table that warped gently through the commons,

01:06:56.940 --> 01:07:01.900
keeping a discreet and constant distance from the curved deck beneath. The whole drum was furnished

01:07:01.900 --> 01:07:06.700
in early concave, tricked unwary and hung over brains into thinking they were looking at the

01:07:06.700 --> 01:07:12.300
world through fisheye lenses. In deference to the greakiness of the Nevoa undead, it spun in a

01:07:12.300 --> 01:07:17.740
mere fifth of a G, but it was just warming up. We'd be at half-grave in six hours, stuck there for

01:07:17.740 --> 01:07:23.260
the 18 out of every 24 until the ship decided we were fully recovered. For the next few days,

01:07:23.260 --> 01:07:30.460
freefall would be a rare and blessed thing. Light sculptures appeared on the tabletop. Sodosti

01:07:30.460 --> 01:07:34.300
could have fed the information directly into our inlays. The whole briefing could have gone

01:07:34.300 --> 01:07:38.700
through consensus without the need to assemble physically in the same place, but if you want

01:07:38.700 --> 01:07:44.220
to make sure everyone's paying attention, you bring them together. Spin the lead in conspiratorily

01:07:44.220 --> 01:07:49.420
at my side. Or maybe the bloodsucker just gets off seeing all this meat in close quarters, eh?

01:07:50.620 --> 01:07:56.060
If Sodosti heard he didn't show it, not even to me, he pointed it to the dark heart at the

01:07:56.060 --> 01:08:02.140
center of the display, his eyes lost behind the black glass. A wasa object, infrared emitter,

01:08:02.140 --> 01:08:09.180
methane glass. On the display was nothing. Our apparent destination was a black disc,

01:08:09.180 --> 01:08:15.260
a round absence of stars. In real life, it weighed in at over 10 Jupiters and measured 20%

01:08:15.260 --> 01:08:20.700
wider at the belly. It was directly in our path, too small to burn, too remote for the reflection

01:08:20.700 --> 01:08:26.860
of distant sunlight, too heavy for a gas giant, too light for a brown dwarf. When did that show up?

01:08:27.660 --> 01:08:30.620
Bates squeezed her rubber ball in one hand, the knuckles whitening.

01:08:31.660 --> 01:08:36.780
X-Race bike appears during the 76th microwave survey, six years before firefall.

01:08:41.340 --> 01:08:46.460
Never confirmed, never reacquired, like a torsion flare from an L-class dwarf,

01:08:46.460 --> 01:08:50.060
but we should see anything big enough to generate that kind of effect in the sky's

01:08:50.060 --> 01:08:56.300
dark on that bearing. IAU calls it a statistical artifact. Spindle's eyes drew together like

01:08:56.380 --> 01:09:01.980
courting caterpillars. What changed? Sotosti smiled faintly, keeping his mouth closed.

01:09:02.860 --> 01:09:08.460
The meta-base gets crowded after firefall. Everyone skittish, looking for clues.

01:09:09.020 --> 01:09:14.060
After Burns' call field explodes, he clicked at the back of his throat. Turns out the spike

01:09:14.060 --> 01:09:17.900
might arise from a sub-dwarf object after all, if the magnetosphere is torqued enough.

01:09:18.940 --> 01:09:21.900
Bates, torqued by what? Don't know.

01:09:21.900 --> 01:09:24.220
No.

01:09:24.220 --> 01:09:29.020
Layers of statistical interference piled up on the table while Sotosti's sketched background.

01:09:29.020 --> 01:09:33.020
Even with a solid bearing and half the world's attention, the object had hidden from all but

01:09:33.020 --> 01:09:38.380
the most intensive search. A thousand telescopic snapshots had been stacked one on another and

01:09:38.380 --> 01:09:43.500
squeezed through a dozen filters before something emerged from the static, just below the 3-meter

01:09:43.500 --> 01:09:48.220
band on the threshold of certainty. For the longest time, it hadn't even been real,

01:09:48.220 --> 01:09:52.140
just a probabilistic ghost until Thesias got close enough to collapse the waveform.

01:09:52.700 --> 01:09:58.780
A quantum particle, heavy as 10 Jupiters. Earthbound cartographers were calling it Big Ben.

01:09:59.580 --> 01:10:03.020
Thesias had barely passed Saturn's orbit when it showed up in the residuals.

01:10:03.660 --> 01:10:07.900
That discovery would have been moot for anyone else. No other ship caught on route could have

01:10:07.900 --> 01:10:13.740
packed enough fuel for anything but the long dejected loop back home. But Thesias' thin,

01:10:13.820 --> 01:10:18.780
infinitely attenuate fuel line reached all the way back to the Sun. She could turn on the proverbial

01:10:18.780 --> 01:10:25.100
dime. We changed course in our sleep and the Icarus stream tracked our moves like a cat after

01:10:25.100 --> 01:10:31.100
prey, feeding us at light speed. And here we were. Talk about long shots, spindle grumbled.

01:10:32.060 --> 01:10:37.900
Across the table, baits flicked her wrist. Her ball sailed over my head. I heard it bounce off the deck.

01:10:38.540 --> 01:10:41.340
Not the deck, something in me amended. Handrail.

01:10:42.300 --> 01:10:44.940
We're assuming the comet was a deliberate decoy then.

01:10:45.660 --> 01:10:50.940
Sardosti nodded. The ball ricocheted back into my line of sight, high overhead, and disappeared

01:10:50.940 --> 01:10:55.820
briefly behind the spinal bundle, looping through some eccentric, counter-intuitive parabola in the

01:10:55.820 --> 01:11:03.580
drum's feeble grav. So they want to be left alone. Sardosti steepled his fingers and turned his face

01:11:03.580 --> 01:11:10.780
in her direction. That your recommendation? She wished it was. No, sir. I'm just saying that

01:11:10.780 --> 01:11:16.220
Burns Caulfield took a lot of resources and effort to set up. Whoever built it obviously values

01:11:16.220 --> 01:11:22.380
their anonymity and has the technology to protect it. The ball bounced one last time and wobbled

01:11:22.380 --> 01:11:28.540
back towards the commons. Baits half hopped from her seat. She floated briefly, barely catching

01:11:28.620 --> 01:11:34.300
it on its way past. There remained a newborn animal awkwardness to her movements, half choreolous,

01:11:34.300 --> 01:11:40.140
half residual rigor. Still, a big improvement in four hours. The rest of the humans were barely

01:11:40.140 --> 01:11:45.660
past the walking stage. Maybe it wasn't much trouble for them at all, eh? Spindle amusing.

01:11:46.300 --> 01:11:52.060
Maybe it was dead easy. In which case they might or might not be as xenophobic, but they're even

01:11:52.060 --> 01:11:57.580
more advanced. We don't want to rush into this. Sardosti turned back to the simmering graphics.

01:11:58.220 --> 01:12:05.980
So. Baits needed the recovered ball with her fingertips. The second mouse gets the cheese.

01:12:05.980 --> 01:12:10.460
We may have blown our top of the line recon in the Kuiper, but we don't have to go in blind.

01:12:10.460 --> 01:12:14.940
Send in our own drones along separate vectors. Hold off on a close up approach until we at least

01:12:14.940 --> 01:12:21.340
know whether we're dealing with friendlies or hostels. James shook her head. If they were hostile,

01:12:21.340 --> 01:12:26.140
they could have packed the fireflies with antimatter, or sent one big object instead of 60,000

01:12:26.220 --> 01:12:32.780
little ones. Let the impact take us out. The fireflies only imply an initial curiosity, Baits said.

01:12:33.340 --> 01:12:39.180
Who knows if they like what they saw. What if this whole diversion theory is just so much shit?

01:12:40.620 --> 01:12:45.740
I turn briefly startled. James' mouth had made the words. Sasha had spoken them.

01:12:46.620 --> 01:12:51.020
You want to stay hidden. You don't light up the sky with fucking fireworks, she continued.

01:12:51.020 --> 01:12:55.740
You don't need a diversion if nobody's looking for you, and nobody's looking for you if you lie low.

01:12:55.740 --> 01:12:58.540
If they were so curious, they could have just snuck in a spy cam.

01:12:59.500 --> 01:13:04.620
Risk detection, the vampire said mildly. Hate to break at Yuka, but the fireflies

01:13:04.620 --> 01:13:09.420
didn't exactly slip under the ra- Sadasti opened his mouth, closed it again,

01:13:10.060 --> 01:13:13.340
filed teeth, briefly visible, clicked audibly behind his face.

01:13:14.060 --> 01:13:19.180
Tabletop graphics reflected off his visor, a band of writhing polychrome distortions where eyes

01:13:20.140 --> 01:13:21.500
should be. Sasha shut up.

01:13:22.540 --> 01:13:28.060
Sadasti continued. They traded stealth for speed. By the time you react, they already have what

01:13:28.060 --> 01:13:35.260
they want. He spoke quietly, patiently, a well-fed predator explaining the rules of the game to pray

01:13:35.260 --> 01:13:40.380
that really should know better. The longer it takes me to track you down, the more hope you have of

01:13:40.380 --> 01:13:47.260
escaping. But Sasha had already fled. Her service is it's scattered like a flock of panicked starlings,

01:13:47.340 --> 01:13:52.060
and the next time James's mouth, Susan James's mouth, opened it was Susan James who spoke through

01:13:52.060 --> 01:13:57.740
it. Sasha's aware of the current paradigm Yuka. She's simply more worried that it might be wrong.

01:13:59.100 --> 01:14:03.980
Got another way we could trade it in on? Spindle wondered. More options, longer warranty?

01:14:04.940 --> 01:14:11.180
I don't know, James sighed. I guess not. It's just odd that they'd want to actively mislead us.

01:14:11.900 --> 01:14:18.540
I'd hope that they were merely, well, she spread her hands. Probably no big deal. I'm sure they'll

01:14:18.540 --> 01:14:23.340
still be willing to talk if we handle the introductions right. We just need to be a little bit more

01:14:23.340 --> 01:14:31.180
cautious, perhaps. Sadasti unfolded himself from his chair and loomed over us. We go in. What we

01:14:31.180 --> 01:14:38.700
know weighs against further delay. Bates frown and pitched her ball back into orbit. Sir, all we know

01:14:38.700 --> 01:14:43.340
is that an Owasa emitters in our path. We don't even know if there's anyone there.

01:14:44.140 --> 01:14:51.740
There is, Sadasti said. They expect us. Nobody spoke for a few seconds. Someone's joint

01:14:51.740 --> 01:14:58.540
cracked in silence. Uh, Spindle began. Without looking, Sadasti flicked out his arm and snatched

01:14:58.540 --> 01:15:04.220
Bates' returning ball from the air. Later our ping's thesy is four hours forty eight minutes ago.

01:15:04.300 --> 01:15:10.300
We respond with an identical signal. Nothing. Probe launches half hour before we wake up.

01:15:10.300 --> 01:15:16.140
We don't go in blind, but we don't wait. They see us already. Longer we wait, greater risk of

01:15:16.140 --> 01:15:21.980
countermeasures. I looked at the dark, featureless placeholder on the table, bigger than Jupiter

01:15:21.980 --> 01:15:27.340
and we couldn't even see it yet. Something in the shadow of that mass had just reached out

01:15:27.340 --> 01:15:32.300
with a casual, unimaginable precision and tapped us on the nose with a laser beam.

01:15:33.260 --> 01:15:40.060
This was not going to be an even match. Spindle spoke for all of us. You knew that all along?

01:15:40.060 --> 01:15:47.420
You're telling us now? This time Sadasti's smile was wide and toothy. It was though a gash

01:15:47.420 --> 01:15:53.420
had opened in the lower half of his face. Maybe it was a predator thing. He just couldn't help

01:15:53.420 --> 01:16:02.140
playing with his food. It wasn't so much the way they looked. The elongate limbs, the pale skin,

01:16:02.140 --> 01:16:08.220
the canines and the extended mandible. Noticable, yes, even alien, but not disturbing, not frightening.

01:16:08.220 --> 01:16:12.780
Not even the eyes, really. The eyes of dogs and cats shine in the darkness. We don't shiver at the

01:16:12.780 --> 01:16:20.300
sight. Not the way they looked. The way they moved. Something in the reflexes, maybe. The way they

01:16:20.300 --> 01:16:25.420
held their limbs, like mantis limbs, long, jointed things you just knew could reach out and snatch

01:16:25.420 --> 01:16:31.580
you from right across the room anytime they felt like it. When Sadasti looked at me, really looked,

01:16:31.580 --> 01:16:38.300
naked-eyed, unfiltered by the visor. A half million years just melted away. The fact that he was

01:16:38.300 --> 01:16:43.660
extinct meant nothing. The fact that we'd come so far, grown strong enough to resurrect our own

01:16:43.660 --> 01:16:50.780
nightmares to serve us, meant nothing. The genes aren't fooled. They know what to fear. Of course,

01:16:50.780 --> 01:16:57.020
you had to experience it in person. Robert Pagliani knew the story of vampires down to molecules,

01:16:57.100 --> 01:17:00.700
but even with all those technical specs in his head, he never really got it.

01:17:01.820 --> 01:17:06.780
He called me before we left. I hadn't been expecting it, ever since the roster had been

01:17:06.780 --> 01:17:11.900
announced. Our watches had blocked Hall so many would not explicitly contact listed. I'd forgot

01:17:11.900 --> 01:17:16.860
that Pag had been. We hadn't spoken since Chelsea. I'd given up on ever hearing from him again.

01:17:17.500 --> 01:17:21.980
But there he was. Podman? He smiled, a tentative overture.

01:17:22.620 --> 01:17:26.620
It's good to see you, I said, because that's what people said in similar situations.

01:17:27.980 --> 01:17:32.060
Yeah, well, I saw your name on the noose. You've made it big for a baseline.

01:17:32.780 --> 01:17:33.500
Not so big.

01:17:34.380 --> 01:17:40.300
Crap, you're the vanguard of the human race. You're our first, last, and only hope against the unknown.

01:17:40.860 --> 01:17:45.580
Man, you showed them. He held up his fist and shook it, vicariously triumphant.

01:17:46.140 --> 01:17:51.820
Showing them had become a cornerstone of Robert Pagliano's life. He'd really made it work for him,

01:17:51.820 --> 01:17:57.020
too, overcome the handicap of a natural birth with retrofits and enhancements and sheer bloody

01:17:57.020 --> 01:18:02.220
mindedness. In a world in which humanity had become redundant and unprecedented numbers,

01:18:02.220 --> 01:18:06.140
we'd both retain the status of another age, working professional.

01:18:07.100 --> 01:18:11.500
So you're taking orders from a vamp, he said now, talk about fighting fire with fire.

01:18:12.460 --> 01:18:15.180
I guess it's practice until we run up against the real thing.

01:18:16.060 --> 01:18:21.900
He laughed. I couldn't imagine why, but I smiled back anyway. It was good to see him.

01:18:22.780 --> 01:18:28.220
So what do they like? Pag asked. Vampires? I don't know, just met my first one yesterday.

01:18:28.700 --> 01:18:33.980
And? Hard to read. Didn't even seem to be aware of his surrounding sometimes. He seemed to be

01:18:34.620 --> 01:18:39.820
often his own little world. He's aware, all right. Those things are so fast, it's scary.

01:18:39.980 --> 01:18:44.700
You know they can hold both aspects of the necker cube in their heads at the same time?

01:18:45.340 --> 01:18:50.700
The term rang a bell. I subtitled and saw the wire, the thumbnail of a familiar wireframe box.

01:18:51.740 --> 01:18:57.180
Now I remembered. Classic ambiguous illusion. Sometimes the shaded panel seemed to be in front,

01:18:57.180 --> 01:19:01.500
sometimes behind. The perspective flipped back and forth as you watched.

01:19:03.420 --> 01:19:06.380
You or I, we can only see it one way or the other, Pag was saying.

01:19:07.100 --> 01:19:11.900
Vamp's see it both ways at once. Do you have any idea what kind of an edge that gives him?

01:19:12.620 --> 01:19:19.180
Not enough of one. Touche. Hey, not their, not their fault. Neural traits get fixed in small

01:19:19.180 --> 01:19:25.740
populations. I don't know if I'd call the crucifix glitch neutral. It was at first.

01:19:25.740 --> 01:19:31.180
How many intersecting right angles do you see in nature? He waved one dismissive hand. Anyway,

01:19:31.180 --> 01:19:35.500
that's not the point. The point is they can do something that's neurologically impossible for

01:19:35.500 --> 01:19:42.220
us humans. They can hold simultaneous multiple worldviews, podman. They just see things we have

01:19:42.220 --> 01:19:47.580
to work out step by step. They don't have to think about it. You know, there isn't a single baseline

01:19:47.580 --> 01:19:51.900
human who could just tell you just off the top of their heads every prime number between one and

01:19:51.900 --> 01:19:58.300
a billion. In the old days, only a few autistics could do shit like that. He never uses the past

01:19:59.260 --> 01:20:05.660
tense, I murmured. Huh? Oh, that, Pag nodded. They never experienced the past tense. It's just another

01:20:05.660 --> 01:20:11.660
thread to them. They don't remember stuff. They relive it. What, like a post-traumatic flashback?

01:20:12.300 --> 01:20:18.700
Not so traumatic, he grimaced. Not for them, at least. So this is obviously your current

01:20:18.700 --> 01:20:26.380
hotspot, vampires. Vampires are the capital hot spot for anyone with a neuro in their CV.

01:20:26.380 --> 01:20:31.980
I'm just doing a couple of histology papers. Pattern matching receptors, Mexican hat arrays,

01:20:31.980 --> 01:20:38.140
reward irrelevance filters, the eyes basically. Right, I hesitated. Those kind of throw you.

01:20:38.780 --> 01:20:46.700
No shit, Pag nodded knowingly. That tap lucid under theirs, that shine, scary. He shook his head,

01:20:46.700 --> 01:20:50.780
impressed all over at the recollection. You've never met one, I surmised.

01:20:51.420 --> 01:20:57.660
What, in the flesh? I'd give my left ball. Why? It's not the shine, it's... I groped for another word

01:20:57.660 --> 01:21:05.180
that fit. The attitude, maybe. Yeah, he said after a bit. I guess sometimes you just gotta be there,

01:21:05.180 --> 01:21:12.140
huh? Which is why I envy you, podman. You shouldn't. I shouldn't. Even if you've never met who sent

01:21:12.140 --> 01:21:18.780
the flies, you're in for one Christly research opportunity with that... Sarasti, is it? Wasted

01:21:19.020 --> 01:21:25.340
on me, the only neuro in my files under medical history. He laughed. Anyway, like I said, I just

01:21:25.340 --> 01:21:29.260
saw your name in the headlines and figured, hey, the man's leaving in a couple months. I should

01:21:29.260 --> 01:21:36.060
probably stop waiting around for him to call. It had been over two years. I didn't think I'd get through.

01:21:36.780 --> 01:21:42.620
I thought you shiftlisted me. No, never. He looked down though and fell silent.

01:21:43.500 --> 01:21:49.420
But you should've called her, he said at last. I know. She was dying. You should've...

01:21:50.060 --> 01:21:57.820
There wasn't time. He let the lie sit for a while. Anyway, he said at last. I just wanted to wish you

01:21:57.820 --> 01:22:05.660
luck. Which wasn't exactly true either. Thanks, I appreciate that. Kick their alien asses. If

01:22:05.660 --> 01:22:11.820
aliens have asses. There's five of us, Pag. Nine if you count the backups. We're not exactly an army.

01:22:12.620 --> 01:22:17.420
Just an expression, fellow mammal. Bury the hatchet, damn the torpedoes, soothe the serpent.

01:22:18.300 --> 01:22:22.700
Raise the white flag, I thought. I guess you're busy, he said. I'll...

01:22:23.740 --> 01:22:27.660
Look, you want to get together in airspace? I haven't been to cubits in a while.

01:22:28.300 --> 01:22:32.300
Love to, Pod. Unfortunately, I'm in Mancoya, splice and dice workshop.

01:22:33.100 --> 01:22:36.780
What, you mean physically? Cutting edge research. Old school habits.

01:22:37.740 --> 01:22:40.940
Too bad. Anyway, I'll let you go. I just wanted, you know...

01:22:41.580 --> 01:22:49.740
Thanks, I said again. So, you know, bye. Robert Pagliano told me. Which was, when you get down

01:22:49.740 --> 01:22:53.980
to it, the reason he called. He wasn't expecting another chance.

01:22:56.860 --> 01:23:03.260
Pag blamed me for the way it ended with Chelsea. Fair enough. I blamed him for the way it began.

01:23:04.220 --> 01:23:08.780
He'd gone into neuroeconomics, at least partly because his childhood buddy had turned into a

01:23:08.780 --> 01:23:14.540
pod person before his eyes. I'd ended up in synthesis for roughly the same reason. Our paths

01:23:14.540 --> 01:23:19.820
had diverged, and we didn't see each other in the flesh all that often. But two decades after

01:23:19.820 --> 01:23:24.940
I'd brutalized a handful of children on his behalf, Robert Pagliano was still my best and only friend.

01:23:25.820 --> 01:23:30.940
You seriously need to thaw out, he told me. And I know just the lady to handle the oven mitts.

01:23:31.020 --> 01:23:36.700
That is perhaps the worst use of metaphor in the history of human language, I said.

01:23:37.420 --> 01:23:42.700
Seriously, Pod, she'll be good for you. A counterbalance. Easy a bit on the comfy mean, you know?

01:23:43.580 --> 01:23:46.860
No, Pag, I don't. What is she, another neuroeconomist?

01:23:47.580 --> 01:23:51.260
Neuro-Aesthetist, he said. There's still a market for those?

01:23:52.060 --> 01:23:56.780
I couldn't imagine how. Why pay to tweak your compatibility with some significant other when

01:23:56.780 --> 01:24:02.060
significant others themselves were so out of fashion. Not much of one, Pag admitted.

01:24:02.700 --> 01:24:07.660
Fact is, she's pretty much retired, but she still got the tools, my man. Very thigmotatic.

01:24:08.300 --> 01:24:10.940
Likes all her relationships face to face and in the flesh.

01:24:11.820 --> 01:24:16.940
I don't know, Pag. Sounds like work. Not like your work. She's gotta be easier than the

01:24:16.940 --> 01:24:22.700
bleeding composites you front for. She's smart, she's sexy, and she's nicely inside the standard

01:24:23.020 --> 01:24:28.540
except for the personal contact thing, which is not so much outright perversion as charming fetish.

01:24:28.540 --> 01:24:33.820
In your case, it could even be therapeutic. If I wanted therapy, I'd see a therapist.

01:24:34.540 --> 01:24:41.740
She does a bit of that too, actually. Yeah, and then despite myself. Any good? He looked me up and

01:24:41.740 --> 01:24:47.580
down. No one's that good. That's not what this is. I just figured you two would click. Chelsea is

01:24:47.580 --> 01:24:53.580
one of the few who might not be completely put off by your intimacy issues. Everyone's got into

01:24:53.580 --> 01:24:58.700
me as intimacy issues these days in case you hadn't noticed. He must have. The population

01:24:58.700 --> 01:25:03.980
have been dropping for decades. I was being euphemistic. I mean, you're aversion to general

01:25:03.980 --> 01:25:11.100
human contact. Making it euphemistic to call you human? He grinned. Different deal. We got history.

01:25:11.740 --> 01:25:17.580
No thanks. Too late, she's already on route to the appointed place. A point you're an asshole,

01:25:17.580 --> 01:25:24.940
Pag. The tightest. Which was how I found myself intrusively face to face in an airspace lounge

01:25:24.940 --> 01:25:29.580
south of Beth and Bear. The lighting was low and indirect, creeping from under seats and at the

01:25:29.580 --> 01:25:35.500
edges of tables. The chromatics, this afternoon at least, were defiantly long wave. It was a place

01:25:35.500 --> 01:25:41.500
where baselines could pretend to see an infrared. So I pretended for a moment, assessing the woman

01:25:41.500 --> 01:25:47.900
in the corner booth, gangly and glorious, half a dozen ethnicities coexisting peacefully with no

01:25:47.900 --> 01:25:53.500
single voice dominant. Something glowed on her cheek, a faint emerald staccato against the ambient

01:25:53.500 --> 01:25:59.900
redshift. Her hair floated in a diffuse, ebony cloud above her head. As I neared, I caught occasional

01:25:59.900 --> 01:26:04.460
glints of metal within that nimbus, the threads of a static generator, pervading the illusion of

01:26:04.460 --> 01:26:09.900
weightlessness. In normal light, her blood red skin would doubtless shift down to the fashionable

01:26:09.900 --> 01:26:15.820
but water scotch of an unrepentant mongrel. She was attractive, but so was everyone in this kind

01:26:15.820 --> 01:26:20.860
of light. The longer the wavelength, the softer the focus. There's a reason fuck cubbies don't come

01:26:20.860 --> 01:26:28.860
with fluorescent lights. You will not fall for this, I told myself. Chelsea, she said. Her little

01:26:28.860 --> 01:26:34.700
finger rested on one of the tables, inset trickle chargers. Former neuroesthetist, presently a

01:26:34.700 --> 01:26:41.100
parasite on the body economic thanks to genes and the machines on the cutting edge. I glow, the glow

01:26:41.100 --> 01:26:48.940
on her cheek flapped bright and lazy wings. A tattoo, a bioluminescent butterfly. Siri, I said.

01:26:48.940 --> 01:26:53.740
Freelance synthesis indentured servant to the genes and machines that turned you into a parasite.

01:26:54.700 --> 01:27:00.460
She waved at the empty seat. I took it, assessing the system before me, sizing up the best approach

01:27:00.460 --> 01:27:06.460
for a fast, yet diplomatic disconnect. The set of her shoulders told me she enjoyed lightscapes and

01:27:06.460 --> 01:27:11.900
was embarrassed to admit it. Monahan was her favorite artist. She thought herself a natural girl

01:27:11.900 --> 01:27:16.460
because she'd stayed on chemical libidinals all these years, even though a synaptic edit would

01:27:16.460 --> 01:27:22.060
have been simpler. She reveled in her own inconsistency, a woman whose professional machinery edited

01:27:22.060 --> 01:27:28.140
thought itself, yet mistrustful of the dehumanizing impact of telephones. Inanately affectionate

01:27:28.140 --> 01:27:32.860
and innately afraid of unreturned affection and indomitably unwilling to let any of that stop her.

01:27:33.660 --> 01:27:37.820
She liked what she saw when she looked at me. She was a little afraid of that too.

01:27:39.180 --> 01:27:44.140
Chelsea gestured at my side of the table. The touch pads there glowed soft, dissonant sapphire

01:27:44.140 --> 01:27:49.260
in the bloody light, like a set of splayed fingerprints. Good dope here. Extra hydroxyl

01:27:49.260 --> 01:27:55.260
on the ring or something. Assemblyline Neurofarm doesn't do much for me. It's optimized for people

01:27:55.260 --> 01:28:00.060
with more meat in their heads. I fingered one of the pads for appearances and barely felt the tangle.

01:28:01.260 --> 01:28:08.460
So, a synthesis, explaining the incomprehensible to the indifferent. I smiled on cue, more like

01:28:08.460 --> 01:28:12.540
bridging the gap between the people who make the breakthroughs and the people who take the credit for

01:28:12.540 --> 01:28:18.780
them. She smiled back. So how do you do it? All those optimized frontal lobes and refits?

01:28:18.780 --> 01:28:21.340
I mean, if they're incomprehensible, how do you comprehend them?

01:28:22.860 --> 01:28:27.740
It helps to find pretty much everyone else incomprehensible too, provides experience.

01:28:28.460 --> 01:28:30.940
There, that should force a bit of difference.

01:28:32.140 --> 01:28:37.180
It didn't. She thought I was joking. I could see her lining up to push for more details,

01:28:37.180 --> 01:28:41.980
to ask questions about what I did. Which would lead to questions about me? Which would lead?

01:28:42.620 --> 01:28:46.700
Tell me what it's like, I said smoothly, rewiring people's heads for a living.

01:28:47.660 --> 01:28:52.540
Chelsea grimaced. The butterfly on her cheek fluttered nervously at the motion, wings brightening.

01:28:53.340 --> 01:28:56.940
God, you make it sound like we turn them into zombies or something. They're just tweaks,

01:28:56.940 --> 01:29:01.900
mainly. Changing taste in music or cuisine, optimizing make-impedibility. It's completely

01:29:01.900 --> 01:29:09.340
reversible. There aren't drugs for that? Nah, too much developmental variation between brains.

01:29:09.340 --> 01:29:14.780
Our targeting is really fine scale. But it's not all microsurgery and fried synapses, you know?

01:29:14.860 --> 01:29:19.340
You'd be surprised how much rewiring could be done noninvasively. You can start all sorts of

01:29:19.340 --> 01:29:23.580
cascades just by playing certain sounds in the right order or showing images with the right

01:29:23.580 --> 01:29:30.620
balance of geometry and emotion. I assume those are new techniques. Not really. Rhythm and music

01:29:30.620 --> 01:29:35.820
hang their hats in the same basic principle. We just turned art into science. Yeah, but when?

01:29:36.460 --> 01:29:39.980
The recent past, certainly. Sometime within the last 20 years or so.

01:29:40.940 --> 01:29:46.700
Her voice grew suddenly quiet. Robert told me about your operation. Some kind of viral epilepsy,

01:29:46.700 --> 01:29:52.460
right? Back when you were just a tyke? I'd never explicitly asked him to keep it a secret. What

01:29:52.460 --> 01:29:57.740
was the difference anyway? I'd made a full recovery. Besides, Peg still thought that had happened to

01:29:57.740 --> 01:30:03.820
someone else. I don't know your specifics, Chelsea continued gently. But from the sound of it,

01:30:03.820 --> 01:30:07.740
noninvasive techniques wouldn't have helped. I'm sure they only did what they had to.

01:30:07.980 --> 01:30:12.860
I tried to suppress the thought and couldn't. I like this woman.

01:30:14.220 --> 01:30:19.340
I felt something then. A strange unfamiliar sensation that somehow loosened my vertebrae.

01:30:19.900 --> 01:30:23.660
The chair felt subtly, indefinably more comfortable at my back.

01:30:24.700 --> 01:30:29.900
Anyway, my silence had thrown her off stride. Haven't done much since the bottom dropped out of the

01:30:29.900 --> 01:30:34.460
market. But it did leave me with a fondness for face-to-face encounters, if you know what I mean.

01:30:35.420 --> 01:30:39.340
Yeah, Peg said you took your sex in the first person. She nodded.

01:30:39.900 --> 01:30:42.060
I'm very old school. You okay with that?

01:30:43.260 --> 01:30:48.140
I wasn't certain. I was a virgin in the real world, one of the few things I still had in

01:30:48.140 --> 01:30:54.300
common with the rest of civilized society. In principle, I guess, it just seems a lot of effort

01:30:54.300 --> 01:31:01.260
for not as much payoff, you know? Don't I, she smiled. Real fuck buddies aren't airbrushed,

01:31:01.260 --> 01:31:06.460
got all those needs and demands that you can't edit out. How can you blame anyone for saying no

01:31:06.460 --> 01:31:10.940
thanks to all that? Now there's a choice. You gotta wonder how our parents ever stayed together

01:31:10.940 --> 01:31:17.020
sometimes. You gotta wonder why they did. I felt myself sinking deeper into the chair,

01:31:17.020 --> 01:31:22.380
wondered again at this strange new sensation. Chelsea had said the dopamine was tweaked.

01:31:22.380 --> 01:31:28.780
That was probably it. She leaned forward, not koi, not kuketish, not breaking eye contact for an

01:31:28.780 --> 01:31:33.820
instant in the long wave gloom. I could smell the lemony tang of pheromones and synthetics

01:31:33.820 --> 01:31:40.300
mingling on her skin. But there are advantages too once you learn the moves, she said. The body's

01:31:40.300 --> 01:31:45.340
got a long memory. And you do realize there's no trickler under your left finger there, don't you,

01:31:45.340 --> 01:31:51.980
Siri? I looked. My left arm was slightly extended, index finger touching one of the trickle pads.

01:31:52.540 --> 01:31:56.940
And my right hand mirrored the motion while I wasn't watching, its own finger tapping

01:31:56.940 --> 01:32:03.660
uselessly on a blank tabletop. I pulled it back. Bit of a bilateral twitch, I admitted.

01:32:03.660 --> 01:32:09.580
The body creeps into symmetrical poses when I'm not looking. I waited for a joke, at least a raised

01:32:09.580 --> 01:32:15.020
eyebrow. Chelsea just nodded and resumed her thread. So have your game for this, so am I.

01:32:15.020 --> 01:32:20.140
I've never been entangled with a synthesis before. Jargonaut's fine. I'm not proud.

01:32:21.020 --> 01:32:25.980
Don't you always know just exactly what to say? She cocked her head at me.

01:32:26.700 --> 01:32:32.060
So your name, what's it mean? Relaxed. That was it. I felt relaxed.

01:32:32.940 --> 01:32:37.740
I don't know, it's just a name. Well it's not good enough. If you're going to be swapping spit

01:32:37.740 --> 01:32:43.100
for any length of time, you gotta get a name that means something. And we were, I realized.

01:32:43.100 --> 01:32:47.100
Chelsea had decided while I wasn't looking. I could have stopped her right there, told her what

01:32:47.100 --> 01:32:53.260
a bad idea this was, apologized for any misunderstanding. But then there'd be wounded looks and hurt

01:32:53.260 --> 01:32:57.900
feelings and guilt because after all, if I wasn't interested, why the hell had I even shown up?

01:32:58.700 --> 01:33:06.060
She seemed nice. I didn't want to hurt her. Just for a while, I told myself. It'll be an experience.

01:33:07.100 --> 01:33:14.380
I think I'll call you Cygnus, Chelsea said. The swan, I said. A bit preta- a bit precious,

01:33:14.380 --> 01:33:19.820
but it could have been worse. She shook her head. Black hole. Cygnus X1.

01:33:20.860 --> 01:33:26.300
I furrowed my brow at her, but I knew exactly what it meant. A dark, dense object that sucks

01:33:26.300 --> 01:33:33.500
up the light and destroys everything in its path. Thanks a whole fucking lot. Why? I'm not sure.

01:33:33.500 --> 01:33:39.980
Something dark about you. She shrugged and gave me a great toothy grin. But it's not unattractive.

01:33:39.980 --> 01:33:42.940
And let me give you a tweak or two. I bet you'd grow right out of it.

01:33:44.540 --> 01:33:49.180
Pag admitted afterward a bit sheepishly that maybe I should have read that as a warning sign.

01:33:50.140 --> 01:33:50.780
Live and learn.

01:33:54.220 --> 01:34:00.300
Leaders are visionaries with a poorly developed sense of fear and no concept of the odds against

01:34:00.300 --> 01:34:09.900
them. Robert Jarvik. Our scout fell towards orbit watching Ben. We fell days behind watching

01:34:09.980 --> 01:34:15.100
the scout. And that was all we did. Sitting Thesias belly while the system's stream telemetry

01:34:15.100 --> 01:34:21.260
were inlays. Essential, irreplaceable, mission critical. We might as well have been ballast

01:34:21.260 --> 01:34:27.020
during the first approach. We passed Ben's Raleigh limit. Thesias squinted at a meagre

01:34:27.020 --> 01:34:32.860
mission spectrum and saw a rogue halo element from Canid's major. A dismembered remnant of some

01:34:32.860 --> 01:34:38.300
long lost galaxy that had drifted into ours and ended up as Roadkill, uncounted billions of years ago.

01:34:39.100 --> 01:34:41.820
We were closing on something from outside the Milky Way.

01:34:42.940 --> 01:34:48.380
The probe had arced down and in, drew close enough for false color enhance. Ben surfaced

01:34:48.380 --> 01:34:53.100
brightened to a seething parfait of high contrast bands against a diamond-hard starscape.

01:34:53.820 --> 01:34:57.340
Something twinkled there. Faint sparkles on endless overcast.

01:34:58.060 --> 01:35:01.180
Lightning, James wondered. Spindle shook his head.

01:35:01.740 --> 01:35:04.220
Media writes, must be a lot of rock in the neighborhood.

01:35:05.100 --> 01:35:10.700
Wrong color, Sir Oste said. He was not physically among us. He was back in his tent hard-lined

01:35:10.700 --> 01:35:16.700
into the captain, but consensus put him anywhere on board he wanted to be. Morphometrics scrolled

01:35:16.700 --> 01:35:23.100
across my inlays. Mass, diameter, mean density. Ben's day lasted seven hours, 12 minutes.

01:35:23.100 --> 01:35:27.500
Diffused with massive accretion belts circling the equator, more torus than ring,

01:35:27.500 --> 01:35:32.620
extending almost a half million kilometers from cloud tops. The pulverized corpses of moons,

01:35:32.620 --> 01:35:37.980
perhaps, ground down to leftovers. Media writes, Spindle grinned. Dolja.

01:35:39.180 --> 01:35:44.060
He seemed to be right. Increasing proximity speared many of those pinpoint sparkles into

01:35:44.060 --> 01:35:50.940
bright ephemeral hyphens, scratching the atmosphere. Closer to the poles, cloud banks flickered with

01:35:50.940 --> 01:35:57.820
dim, intermittent flashes of electricity. Weak radio emission peaks at 31 and 400 meters,

01:35:57.820 --> 01:36:02.940
outer atmosphere heavy with methane and ammonia, lithium, water, carbon monoxide and abundance.

01:36:03.660 --> 01:36:08.700
Ammonia hydrogen sulfide, alky halide mixing locally in those torn, swirling clouds,

01:36:08.700 --> 01:36:13.820
neutral alkalis in the upper layers. By now, even thesius could pick those things out from a distance,

01:36:13.820 --> 01:36:19.580
but our scout was close enough to see the filigree. It was no longer a disk. It gazed down at a dark

01:36:19.580 --> 01:36:25.180
convex wall and seething layers of red and brown, soft faint stains of anthracine and pyrene.

01:36:25.260 --> 01:36:32.060
One of the myriad meteorite contrails scorched Ben's face directly ahead. For a moment, I thought I

01:36:32.060 --> 01:36:37.340
could even see a tiny dark speck at its core, but sudden static scratched the feet. Baits

01:36:37.340 --> 01:36:42.620
cursed softly. The image blurred, then steadied as the probe pitched its voice higher up the spectrum.

01:36:43.260 --> 01:36:47.580
Unable to make itself heard, among the long wave din, it now spoke down a laser.

01:36:48.460 --> 01:36:53.260
And still, it stuttered. Keeping it aligned across a million fluctuating kilometers should

01:36:53.340 --> 01:36:57.820
have posed no problem at all. Our respective trajectories were known parabolas,

01:36:57.820 --> 01:37:03.660
our relative positions infinitely predictable at any time t. But the meteorite's contrail jumped

01:37:03.660 --> 01:37:08.220
and skittered on the feet as if the beam were being repeatedly, infinitesimally knocked out of

01:37:08.220 --> 01:37:13.900
alignment. Incandescent gas blurred its details. I doubted that even a rock-steady image would

01:37:13.900 --> 01:37:19.900
have offered any sharp edges for a human eye to hold onto. Still, there was something wrong about

01:37:19.980 --> 01:37:24.700
it somehow. Something about the tiny black dot at the core of that fading brightness.

01:37:25.260 --> 01:37:29.100
Something that some primitive part of my mind refused to accept as natural.

01:37:29.900 --> 01:37:32.940
The image lurched again and flashed to black and didn't return.

01:37:33.980 --> 01:37:39.180
Probes fried, Baits reported, spiked there at the end, like it hit a Parker spiral but with a

01:37:39.180 --> 01:37:45.740
really tight wind. I didn't need to call it the subtitles. It was obvious in the set of her face

01:37:45.820 --> 01:37:50.060
the sudden creases between her eyebrows. She was talking about a magnetic field.

01:37:50.780 --> 01:37:54.540
It's... she began and stopped as a number popped up in consensus.

01:37:55.340 --> 01:38:01.020
11.2 Tesla. Holy shit, spindle whispered. Is that right?

01:38:02.300 --> 01:38:06.620
Sonosti clicked from the back of his throat in the back of the ship. A moment later he

01:38:06.620 --> 01:38:11.020
served up an instant replay. Those last few seconds of telemetry zoomed in and smoothed in

01:38:11.020 --> 01:38:17.100
contrast and handsome visible light deep down to infrared. There was that same dark shard called

01:38:17.100 --> 01:38:22.300
in flame. There was the contrail burning in its wake. Now it dimmed as the objects skipped off

01:38:22.300 --> 01:38:27.820
the denser atmosphere beneath and regained altitude. Within moments the heat trace had faded

01:38:27.820 --> 01:38:34.220
entirely. The thing that burned at its center rose back into space a fading ember. A great conic

01:38:34.220 --> 01:38:39.340
scoop at its front end agaped like a mouth. Stubby fins disfigured an ovoid abdomen.

01:38:40.140 --> 01:38:41.900
Ben lurched and went out all over again.

01:38:42.940 --> 01:38:49.500
Meteorites, bait said dryly. The thing had left me with no sense of scale. It could have been an

01:38:49.500 --> 01:38:55.820
insect or an asteroid. How big, I whispered a split second before the answer appeared on my inlays.

01:38:56.700 --> 01:39:05.100
400 meters along the major axis. Ben was safely distanced in our sights once more. A dark, dim

01:39:05.100 --> 01:39:10.700
disc centered in Theesius forward viewfinder. But I remembered to close up a twinkling orb of

01:39:10.700 --> 01:39:17.500
black-hearted fires, a face gashed and pockmarked, endlessly wounded, endlessly healing. There'd

01:39:17.500 --> 01:39:25.100
been thousands of the things. Theesius shivered along her length. It was just a pulse of decelerating

01:39:25.100 --> 01:39:29.020
thrust, but for that one moment I imagined I knew how she felt.

01:39:29.420 --> 01:39:39.180
We headed in and hedged our bets. Theesius weaned herself with the 98 second burn, edged us into

01:39:39.180 --> 01:39:44.860
some vast arc that might with little effort turn into an orbit, or into a quick, discrete flyby if

01:39:44.860 --> 01:39:49.980
the neighborhood turned out to be a little too rough. The Icarus stream fell invisibly to port,

01:39:49.980 --> 01:39:57.100
its unwavering energy lost to spacetime. Our city-sized molecule-thick parasol wound down

01:39:57.180 --> 01:40:02.460
and packed itself away until the next time the ship got thirsty. Anti-matter stockpiles began

01:40:02.460 --> 01:40:07.980
dropping immediately. This time we were alive to watch it happen. The dip was infinitesimal,

01:40:07.980 --> 01:40:12.460
but there was something disquieting about the sudden appearance of that minus sign on the display.

01:40:13.420 --> 01:40:18.380
You could have retained the apron strings, left a buoy behind in the telematter stream to bounce

01:40:18.380 --> 01:40:22.460
energy down the well after us. Susan James wondered why we hadn't.

01:40:23.340 --> 01:40:29.100
Too risky, Sadasti said without elaboration. Spindle leaned in James' direction.

01:40:29.740 --> 01:40:36.140
Why give him something else to shoot at, eh? We sent more probes ahead, though, spat them out hard

01:40:36.140 --> 01:40:41.260
and fast and too fuel constrained for anything but flyby and self-destruct. They couldn't take

01:40:41.260 --> 01:40:47.260
their eyes off the machine swinging around big bend. Theesius stared her own unblinking stare,

01:40:47.260 --> 01:40:51.900
more distant, though more acute. But if those high divers even knew we were out there,

01:40:51.900 --> 01:40:56.220
they ignored us completely. We tracked them across the closing distance,

01:40:56.220 --> 01:40:59.660
watched them swoop and loop through a million parabolas at a million angles.

01:41:00.220 --> 01:41:04.620
We never saw them collide, not with each other, not with the cauldron of rock tumbling around

01:41:04.620 --> 01:41:10.860
Ben's equator. Every perigee dipped briefly into atmosphere. There they burned and slowed and

01:41:10.860 --> 01:41:15.420
accelerated back into space, their anterior scoops glowing with residual heat.

01:41:16.380 --> 01:41:22.140
Bates grabbed a consensus image, drew highlights and a conclusion around the front end. Scramjet.

01:41:23.340 --> 01:41:29.020
We tracked nearly 400,000 in less than two days. That appeared to be most of them.

01:41:29.020 --> 01:41:33.820
New sightings leveled off afterwards. The cumulative curve flattening towards some

01:41:33.820 --> 01:41:39.580
theoretical asymptote. Most of the orbits were close and fast, but Sadasti projected a frequency

01:41:39.580 --> 01:41:44.700
distribution extending almost back to Pluto. We might stay out here for years and still catch

01:41:44.700 --> 01:41:48.540
the occasional new shovel nose returning from its extended foray into the void.

01:41:49.420 --> 01:41:54.140
The faster ones are pulling over 50 Gs on the hairpin turn, Spindle pointed out.

01:41:54.140 --> 01:41:56.220
Meat couldn't handle that. I say they're unmanned.

01:41:57.020 --> 01:42:02.700
Meat's reinforceable, Sadasti said. If it's got that much scaffolding, you might as well

01:42:02.700 --> 01:42:08.940
stop splitting hairs and call it a machine anyway. Surface morphometrics were absolutely uniform.

01:42:08.940 --> 01:42:14.460
400,000 divers, everyone identical. If there was an alpha male calling the shots

01:42:14.460 --> 01:42:19.740
among the herd, it couldn't be distinguished on sight. One night, as such things are measured on

01:42:19.740 --> 01:42:24.620
board, I followed a soft squeal of tortured electronics up to the observation blister.

01:42:25.260 --> 01:42:29.260
Spindle floated there watching the skimmers. He'd closed the clam shells,

01:42:29.260 --> 01:42:32.460
blocked off the stars, and built a little analytical nest in their place.

01:42:33.420 --> 01:42:38.140
Graphs and windows spilled across the inside of the dome as though the virtual space in Spindle's

01:42:38.140 --> 01:42:43.100
head was insufficient to contain them. Tactical graphics lit him from all sides, turned his

01:42:43.100 --> 01:42:47.420
body into a bright patchwork of flickering tattoos. The illustrated man.

01:42:48.460 --> 01:42:53.500
Mind if I come in? I asked. He grunted. Yeah, but not enough to push it.

01:42:54.540 --> 01:42:58.860
Inside the dome, the sound of heavy rainfall hissed and spat behind the screeching that had

01:42:58.860 --> 01:43:05.180
led me there. What is that? Ben's magnetosphere. He didn't look back. Nice, eh?

01:43:06.060 --> 01:43:11.420
Synthesis didn't have opinions on the job. It keeps observers, observer effects to a minimum.

01:43:12.220 --> 01:43:17.100
This time, I permitted myself a small breach. The static's nice. I could do without the screeching.

01:43:17.660 --> 01:43:21.980
Are you kidding me? That's the music of the sphere, his connoisseur. It's beautiful. Like

01:43:21.980 --> 01:43:28.620
old jazz. I never got the hang of that, either. He shrugged and squelched the upper register,

01:43:28.620 --> 01:43:33.820
letting the rain pattering around us. His jiggling eyes fixed on some arcane graphic.

01:43:34.460 --> 01:43:38.220
Want a scoop for your notes? Sure. There you go.

01:43:38.700 --> 01:43:44.700
Light reflective office feedback glove, iridescing like the wing of a dragonfly as he pointed.

01:43:45.260 --> 01:43:51.340
An absorption spectrum, a looped time series. Bright peaks surged and subsided, surged and

01:43:51.340 --> 01:43:57.180
subsided across a 15 second time frame. Subtitles only gave me wavelengths and angstroms.

01:43:57.980 --> 01:44:03.420
What is it? Diver farts. Those bastards are dumping complex organics into the atmosphere.

01:44:04.300 --> 01:44:11.180
How complex. Hard to tell so far. Faint traces and they dissipate like that. But sugars and

01:44:11.180 --> 01:44:20.060
aminos at least. Maybe proteins. Maybe more. Maybe life. Microbes. An alien terraforming project.

01:44:20.940 --> 01:44:27.580
Depends how you define life, eh? Spindle said. Not even Dianocus would last long down there,

01:44:27.580 --> 01:44:31.980
but it's a big atmosphere. They better not be in any hurry if they're reworking the whole thing by

01:44:32.060 --> 01:44:38.140
direct inoculation. If they were, the job would go a lot faster with self-replicating inoculates.

01:44:39.020 --> 01:44:45.660
Sounds like life to me. Sounds like agricultural aerosols is what it sounds like. Those fuckers

01:44:45.660 --> 01:44:50.940
are turning the whole damn gas ball into a rice paddy bigger than Jupiter. He gave me a scary grin.

01:44:51.660 --> 01:44:57.820
Something's got a big appetite, hm? You gotta wonder if we aren't gonna be a teeny bit outnumbered.

01:45:02.380 --> 01:45:09.100
Spindle's findings were front and center at our next get-together. The vampire summed it up for us.

01:45:09.100 --> 01:45:15.500
Visual aids dancing on the table. Vaughn Newman's self-replicating R-selector. Seed washes up and

01:45:15.500 --> 01:45:20.620
sprouts skimmers. Skimmers harvest raw materials from the accretion belt. Some perturbations in

01:45:20.620 --> 01:45:27.020
those orbits. Belt still unsettled. Haven't seen any of the herd giving birth, Spindle remarked.

01:45:27.100 --> 01:45:33.900
Any sign of a factory? Sardasty shook his head. Discarded, maybe. Decompiled. Or the herd stopped

01:45:33.900 --> 01:45:40.380
breeding at optimal end. These are only the bulldozers, Bates pointed out. There'll be tenets.

01:45:41.180 --> 01:45:45.020
A lot of them, eh? Spindle added. Outnumber us by orders of Meg.

01:45:46.220 --> 01:45:53.180
James. But they might not show up for centuries. Sardasty clicked. Do these skimmers build

01:45:53.180 --> 01:46:00.060
fireflies? Burns Caulfield? It was a rhetorical question. Spindle answered anyway. Don't see how.

01:46:00.860 --> 01:46:03.260
Something else does, then. Something already local.

01:46:05.020 --> 01:46:10.860
Nobody spoke for a moment. James' topology shifted and shuffled in the silence. When she opened her

01:46:10.860 --> 01:46:17.100
mouth again, someone indefinably younger was on top. Their habitat isn't anything like ours,

01:46:17.180 --> 01:46:25.020
if they're building a home way out here. That's hopeful. Michelle. The Synthesite. Proteins. Sardasty's

01:46:25.020 --> 01:46:30.220
eyes were unreadable behind the visor. Comparable biochemistries. They might eat us.

01:46:31.260 --> 01:46:37.420
Whatever these beings are, they don't even live in sunlight. No territorial overlap. No resource

01:46:37.420 --> 01:46:41.740
overlap. No basis for conflict. There's no reason we shouldn't get along just fine.

01:46:42.140 --> 01:46:47.420
On the other hand, Spindle said, technology implies belligerence.

01:46:48.700 --> 01:46:55.340
Michelle storted stoffly. According to a coterie of theoretical historians who've never actually

01:46:55.340 --> 01:47:01.980
met an alien, yes. Maybe now we get to prove them wrong. And in the next instance, she was just gone.

01:47:01.980 --> 01:47:06.780
Her affect scattered like leaves in a dust devil. And Susan James was back in her place saying,

01:47:07.420 --> 01:47:14.700
why don't we just ask them? Ask, Bates said. There are 400,000 machines out there. How do we

01:47:14.700 --> 01:47:20.780
know they can't talk? We'd have heard, Spindle said. They're drones. Can't hurt to ping them just

01:47:20.780 --> 01:47:27.260
to make sure. There's no reason they should talk even if they are smart. Language and intelligence

01:47:27.260 --> 01:47:32.940
aren't all that strongly correlated. Eat them on Earth. James rolled her eyes. Why not try at least?

01:47:33.020 --> 01:47:36.620
It's what we're here for. It's what I'm here for. Just send a bloody signal.

01:47:37.420 --> 01:47:43.980
After a moment, Bates picked up the ball. Bad game theory, Sue's. Game theory. She made it sound

01:47:43.980 --> 01:47:49.820
like a curse. Tit for tat's the best strategy. They pinged us. We pinged back. Ball's in their

01:47:49.820 --> 01:47:55.820
court now. We send another signal. We may give away too much. I know the rules, Amanda. They say if

01:47:55.820 --> 01:47:59.740
the other party never takes the initiative again, we ignore each other for the rest of the mission

01:47:59.820 --> 01:48:05.260
because game theory says you don't want to look needy. The rule only applies when you're going

01:48:05.260 --> 01:48:10.140
up against an unknown player, the Major explained. We'll have more options the more we will learn.

01:48:11.260 --> 01:48:16.940
James sighed. It's just you all seem to be going into this assuming they'll be hostile,

01:48:17.660 --> 01:48:20.780
as if a simple hailing signal was going to bring them down on us.

01:48:21.900 --> 01:48:27.580
Bates shrugged. It only makes sense to be cautious. I may be a jarhead, but I'm not eager to piss off

01:48:27.580 --> 01:48:32.780
anything that hops between stars and terraform super Jovians for a living. I don't have to remind

01:48:32.780 --> 01:48:40.700
anyone here that Theseus is no worship. She'd said anyone she'd meant Sarashti, and Sarashti

01:48:40.700 --> 01:48:46.220
focused on his own horizon didn't answer. Not out loud at least, but his surface spoke in a

01:48:46.220 --> 01:48:55.980
different tongue entirely. Not yet, they said. Bates was right, by the way. Theseus was officially

01:48:55.980 --> 01:49:01.100
tricked out for exploration, not combat. No doubt our masters would have preferred to load

01:49:01.100 --> 01:49:06.300
her up with nukes and particle cannons as well as her scientific payload, but not even a telemattered

01:49:06.300 --> 01:49:11.260
fuel stream can change the laws of inertia. A weaponized prototype would have taken longer to

01:49:11.260 --> 01:49:16.140
build, a more massive one laden with heavy artillery would have taken longer to accelerate.

01:49:17.180 --> 01:49:22.780
Time, our masters decided, was of greater essence than armament. In a pinch, our fabrication

01:49:22.780 --> 01:49:27.420
facilities could build almost anything we needed given time. It might take a while to build a

01:49:27.420 --> 01:49:31.500
particle beam cannon from scratch, and we might have to scavenge a local asteroid for the raw

01:49:31.500 --> 01:49:37.500
material, but we could do it. Assuming our enemies would be willing to wait in the interests of fair

01:49:37.500 --> 01:49:42.380
play. What were the odds that even our best weapons would prove effective against the

01:49:42.380 --> 01:49:47.500
intelligence that had pulled off the firefall? If the unknown was hostile, we would probably

01:49:47.500 --> 01:49:53.340
do them no matter what they did. The unknown was technologically advanced, and there were some

01:49:53.340 --> 01:49:59.180
who claimed that that made them hostile by definition. Technology implies belligerence, they said.

01:50:00.380 --> 01:50:05.420
I suppose I should explain that now that it's completely irrelevant. You've probably forgotten

01:50:05.420 --> 01:50:12.620
after all this time. Once there were three tribes. The optimists, whose patron saints were Drake and

01:50:12.620 --> 01:50:17.580
Sagan, believed in a universe crawling with gentle intelligence. Spiritual breath were

01:50:17.580 --> 01:50:22.460
in vaster and more enlightened than we, a great galactic siblinghood into whose ranks we would

01:50:22.460 --> 01:50:28.540
someday ascend. Surely, said the optimists, space travel implies enlightenment, for it requires

01:50:28.540 --> 01:50:33.900
the control of great destructive energies. Any race which can't rise above its own brutal instincts

01:50:33.900 --> 01:50:39.580
will wipe itself out long before it learns to bridge the interstellar gulf. Of cross from the

01:50:39.580 --> 01:50:45.580
optimists sat the pessimists, who genuflected before graven images of Saint Fermi and a host of

01:50:45.580 --> 01:50:51.980
lesser lightweights. The pessimists envisioned a lonely universe full of dead rocks and prokaryotic

01:50:51.980 --> 01:50:57.660
slime. The odds are just too low, they insisted. Too many rogues, too much radiation, too much

01:50:57.660 --> 01:51:03.260
eccentricity, and too many orbits. It's a surpassing miracle that even one earth exists,

01:51:03.260 --> 01:51:09.500
to hope for many is to abandon reason and embrace religious mania. After all, the universe is 14

01:51:09.500 --> 01:51:13.900
billion years old. If the galaxy were alive with intelligence, wouldn't it be here by now?

01:51:14.940 --> 01:51:20.140
Equidistant to the other two tribes, sat the historians. They didn't have too many thoughts

01:51:20.140 --> 01:51:25.340
on the probable prevalence of intelligent spacefaring extraterrestrials. But if there are any,

01:51:25.340 --> 01:51:29.820
they said, they're not just going to be smart, they're going to be mean.

01:51:32.060 --> 01:51:37.980
It might almost seem too obvious a conclusion. What is human history if not an ongoing succession

01:51:38.060 --> 01:51:42.940
of greater technologies grinding lesser ones beneath their boots? But the subject wasn't

01:51:42.940 --> 01:51:50.220
merely human history, or the unfair advantage the tools give to any given side. The oppressed

01:51:50.220 --> 01:51:55.260
snatch up advanced weaponry as readily as the oppressor, given half a chance. No, the real

01:51:55.260 --> 01:52:00.140
issue was how those tools got there in the first place. The real issue was what tools are for.

01:52:01.500 --> 01:52:06.860
To historians, tools existed for only one reason, to force the universe into unnatural shapes.

01:52:07.500 --> 01:52:12.300
They treated nature as an enemy, thereby definition or rebellion against the way things were.

01:52:13.020 --> 01:52:18.860
Technology is a stunted thing in benign environments. It never thrived in any culture,

01:52:18.860 --> 01:52:23.820
gripped by belief in natural harmony. Why invent fusion reactors if your climate is comfortable,

01:52:23.820 --> 01:52:29.580
if your food is abundant? Why build fortresses if you have no enemies? Why force change upon a

01:52:29.580 --> 01:52:36.540
world which poses no threat? Human civilization had a lot of branches not so long ago. Even into

01:52:36.540 --> 01:52:42.540
the 21st century, a few isolated tribes had barely developed stone tools. Some settled down with

01:52:42.540 --> 01:52:47.820
agriculture, others weren't content that they had endured nature itself, still others until they

01:52:47.820 --> 01:52:54.380
built cities in space. We all rested eventually though. Each new technology trampled lesser ones,

01:52:54.380 --> 01:52:59.900
climbed to some complacent asymptote and stopped. Until my own mother packed herself away like a

01:52:59.900 --> 01:53:04.780
larva in a honeycomb softened by machinery, robbed of incentive by her own contentment.

01:53:05.740 --> 01:53:10.940
But history never said that everyone had to stop where we did. It only suggested that those who

01:53:10.940 --> 01:53:16.220
had stopped no longer struggled for existence. There could be other more hellish worlds where

01:53:16.220 --> 01:53:20.940
the best human technology would crumble, where the environment was still the enemy, where the only

01:53:20.940 --> 01:53:26.780
survivors were those who fought back with sharper tools and stronger empires. The threats contained

01:53:26.780 --> 01:53:31.980
in those environments would not be simple ones. Harsh weather and natural disasters either kill

01:53:32.060 --> 01:53:38.460
you or they don't, and once conquered or adapted to, they lose their relevance. No, the only environmental

01:53:38.460 --> 01:53:43.340
factors that continued to matter were those that fought back. They countered new strategies with

01:53:43.340 --> 01:53:49.100
newer ones that forced their enemies to scale ever greater heights just to stay alive. Ultimately,

01:53:49.100 --> 01:53:54.620
the only enemy that mattered was an intelligent one. And if the best toys do end up in the hands

01:53:54.620 --> 01:53:59.420
who've never forgotten that life itself is an act of war against intelligent opponents,

01:53:59.420 --> 01:54:02.700
what does that say about a race whose machines travel between the stars?

01:54:03.580 --> 01:54:08.300
The argument was straightforward enough. It might have even been enough to carry the historians to

01:54:08.300 --> 01:54:14.700
victory if such debates were ever settled on the basic of logic, and if a poor population hadn't

01:54:14.700 --> 01:54:20.460
already awarded the game to Fermi on points. But the historian paradigm was just too ugly,

01:54:20.460 --> 01:54:26.060
too Darwinian for most people, and besides, no one really cared anymore. Not even the

01:54:26.060 --> 01:54:31.500
Cassidy surveys late breaking discoveries changed much. So what if some dirt ball at

01:54:31.500 --> 01:54:37.660
Ursa Majoris Aridani had an oxygen atmosphere? It was 43 light years away and it wasn't talking.

01:54:38.220 --> 01:54:43.020
If you wanted flying chandeliers and alien messiahs, you could build them to order in heaven.

01:54:43.740 --> 01:54:48.460
If you wanted testosterone and target practice, you could choose an afterlife chock full of nasty

01:54:48.460 --> 01:54:53.660
alien monsters with really bad aim. If the mere thought of an alien intelligence threatened your

01:54:53.660 --> 01:54:58.860
worldview, you could explore a virtual galaxy of empty real estate, ripe and awaiting for any

01:54:58.860 --> 01:55:04.780
godfearing earthly pilgrims who chanced by. It was all there, just on the other side of a 15-minute

01:55:04.780 --> 01:55:10.860
splice job in a cervical socket. Why endure the cramped and smelly confines of real-life space

01:55:10.860 --> 01:55:17.820
travel to go visit Pondskum on Europa? And so, inevitably, a fourth tribe arose, a heavenly

01:55:17.820 --> 01:55:23.500
host that triumphed over all, the tribe that just didn't give a shit. They didn't know what to do

01:55:23.500 --> 01:55:30.300
and the fireflies showed up. So they sent us, in honor of the belated historian Mantra. They sent

01:55:30.300 --> 01:55:35.580
along a warrior just in case. It was doubtful in the extreme that any child of Earth would be a

01:55:35.580 --> 01:55:41.580
match for a race with interstellar technology, should they prove unfriendly. Still, I could

01:55:41.580 --> 01:55:46.780
tell that Bates' presence was a comfort to the human members of the crew, at least. If you go up

01:55:46.780 --> 01:55:53.260
unarmed against an angry T-Rex with a four-digit IQ, it can't hurt to have a trained combat specialist

01:55:53.340 --> 01:55:59.180
on your side. At the very least, she might be able to fashion a pointy stick from the branch of some

01:55:59.180 --> 01:56:00.060
convenient tree.

01:56:06.700 --> 01:56:11.660
I swear, if the aliens end up eating the lot of us, we'll have the Church of Game Theory to thank

01:56:11.660 --> 01:56:18.620
for it, Sasha said. She was grabbing a brick of couscous from the galley. I was there for the caffeine.

01:56:18.620 --> 01:56:22.140
We were more or less alone. The rest of the crew was strewn from dome to fab.

01:56:23.020 --> 01:56:28.300
Linguists don't use it. I knew some that did. We don't. And the others are hacks.

01:56:28.860 --> 01:56:33.340
Thing about Game Theory is, it assumes rational self-interest among the players,

01:56:33.340 --> 01:56:39.820
and people just aren't rational. It used to assume that, I allowed. These days, they factor in social

01:56:39.820 --> 01:56:46.700
neurology. Human social neurology. She bit off a corner of her brick, spoke about around a mouthful

01:56:46.780 --> 01:56:52.860
of semolina. That's what Game Theory is good for. Rational players or human ones. And let me take a

01:56:52.860 --> 01:56:58.540
wild stab here and wonder if either of those is going to apply to that. She waved her hand at some

01:56:58.540 --> 01:57:04.620
archetypal alien lurking past the bulkhead. It's got its limitations, I admitted. I guess you use

01:57:04.620 --> 01:57:10.860
the tools you can lay hands on. Sasha snorted. So if you couldn't get your hands on a proper set of

01:57:10.860 --> 01:57:18.140
blueprints, you'd base your dream home on a book of dirty limericks. Maybe not. And then a bit

01:57:18.140 --> 01:57:23.660
defensive in spite of myself, I added, I found it useful, though, in areas you might not expect it

01:57:23.660 --> 01:57:33.500
to be. Yeah, name one. Birthdays, I said, and I immediately wished I hadn't. Sasha stopped chewing.

01:57:33.500 --> 01:57:38.300
Something behind her eyes flickered, almost strobed, as if her other selves were pricking up their

01:57:39.260 --> 01:57:44.940
ears. Go on, she said, and I could feel the whole gang listening in. It's nothing really, just an

01:57:44.940 --> 01:57:52.700
example. So tell us. Sasha Cock James' head at me. I shrugged, no point in making a big thing out of

01:57:52.700 --> 01:57:58.780
it. Well, according to Game Theory, you should never tell anyone when your birthday is. I don't

01:57:58.780 --> 01:58:05.180
follow. It's a lose-lose proposition. There's no winning strategy. What do you mean strategy? It's

01:58:05.180 --> 01:58:12.700
a birthday. Chelsea had said the exact same thing when I tried to explain it to her. Look, I'd said,

01:58:12.700 --> 01:58:16.620
say you tell everyone when it is and nothing happens. It's kind of a slap in the face.

01:58:17.420 --> 01:58:22.700
Or say, suppose they throw you a party, Chelsea, it replied. Then you don't know whether they're

01:58:22.700 --> 01:58:28.300
doing it sincerely, or if your earlier interaction just guilted them into observing an occasion

01:58:28.300 --> 01:58:32.700
they'd rather have ignored. But if you don't tell anyone and nobody commemorates the event,

01:58:32.700 --> 01:58:37.980
there's no reason to feel badly because after all, nobody knew. And if someone does buy you a drink,

01:58:37.980 --> 01:58:41.820
then you know it's sincere because nobody would go to all the trouble of finding out when your

01:58:41.820 --> 01:58:48.220
birthday is and then celebrating it if they honestly didn't like you. Of course, the gang was more

01:58:48.220 --> 01:58:53.260
up to speed on such things. I didn't have to explain it verbally. I could just grab a piece of consensus

01:58:53.260 --> 01:58:58.380
and plot out the payoff matrix. Tell, don't tell, along the columns, celebrated, not celebrated,

01:58:58.380 --> 01:59:03.660
along the rows, the unassailable black and white logic of cost and benefit in the squares themselves.

01:59:04.380 --> 01:59:10.460
The math was irrefutable. The one winning strategy was concealment. Only fools revealed their birthdays.

01:59:11.580 --> 01:59:18.620
Sasha looked at me. You ever show this to anyone else? Sure, my girlfriend. Her eyebrows lifted.

01:59:19.180 --> 01:59:25.740
You had a girlfriend, a real one? I nodded once. I mean, after you showed this to her.

01:59:26.300 --> 01:59:34.060
Well, yes. Uh-huh. Her eyes wandered back to the payoff matrix. Just curious, Ciri, how did she react?

01:59:34.940 --> 01:59:43.100
She didn't really. Not at first. Then, well, she laughed. Better woman than me, Sasha shook her head.

01:59:43.100 --> 01:59:44.380
I'd have dumped you on the spot.

01:59:50.300 --> 01:59:55.420
My nightly constitutional up the spine, glorious dreamy flight along a single degree of freedom,

01:59:56.140 --> 02:00:00.780
I sailed through hatches and corridors through my arms wide and spun in the gentle cyclonic

02:00:00.780 --> 02:00:05.980
breeze of the drum. Bates ran circles around me, bounced, bouncing her ball against bins and

02:00:05.980 --> 02:00:11.500
bulkheads, stretching the field to curving rebound and torque pseudograph. The toy ricocheted off a

02:00:11.500 --> 02:00:16.300
stairwell and out of reach as I passed. The major's curses followed me through the needle's eye from

02:00:16.300 --> 02:00:21.420
Crip to Bridge. I break to just short of the dome, stopped by the sound of quiet voices on the head.

02:00:22.140 --> 02:00:24.940
Of course they're beautiful, spindle murmured, they're stars.

02:00:25.740 --> 02:00:29.660
And I'm guessing I'm not your first choice to share the view, James said.

02:00:30.540 --> 02:00:36.300
You're a close second, but I've got a date with Mish. She never mentioned it. She doesn't tell you

02:00:36.300 --> 02:00:43.020
everything, ask her. Hey, this body's taking its antelibs, even if yours isn't. Mind out of the

02:00:43.020 --> 02:00:49.580
gutters, Seuss. Eros is only one kind of love, eh? Ancient Greeks recognized for. Right.

02:00:50.460 --> 02:00:55.260
Definitely not Susan, not anymore. Figures you take your lead from a bunch of sodomites.

02:00:56.140 --> 02:01:00.780
Fuck, Sasha, all I'm asking is a few minutes alone with Mish before the whip starts cracking again.

02:01:01.580 --> 02:01:07.740
My body too, Ike? You want to pull your eyes over my wool? I just want to talk, eh? Alone?

02:01:07.740 --> 02:01:13.660
That too much to ask? I heard Sasha take a breath. I heard Michelle let it out.

02:01:14.620 --> 02:01:20.620
Sorry, kid. You know the gang. Thank God. It's like some group inspection whenever I come looking

02:01:20.620 --> 02:01:26.540
for FaceTime. I guess you're lucky they like you then. I still say you ought to stage a coup.

02:01:27.100 --> 02:01:31.580
You could always move in with us. I heard the rustle of bodies and gentle contact.

02:01:32.220 --> 02:01:38.060
How are you, spindle-last? You okay? Pretty good. I think I'm finally used to being alive again. You?

02:01:38.780 --> 02:01:42.700
Hey, I'm a spaz no matter how long I've been dead. You get the job done.

02:01:43.260 --> 02:01:50.220
Why, merci. I try. A small silence. Thiesi has hummed quietly to herself.

02:01:51.180 --> 02:01:57.180
Mom was right, Michelle said. They are beautiful. What do you see when you look at them, and then

02:01:57.180 --> 02:02:04.620
catching himself? I mean, they're prickly, Michelle told him. When I turn my head, it's like the bands

02:02:04.620 --> 02:02:10.220
of very fine needles rolling across my skin and waves. But it doesn't hurt at all. It's almost

02:02:10.220 --> 02:02:17.420
electric. It just tingles. It's nice. Wish I could feel that way. You've got the interface. Just patch

02:02:17.420 --> 02:02:22.860
a camera into your parietal lobe instead of your visual cortex. That just tell me how a machine

02:02:22.860 --> 02:02:31.340
feels vision, eh? Still wouldn't know how you do. Isaac, spindle. You're romantic. Nah. You don't want

02:02:31.340 --> 02:02:37.100
to know. You want to keep it mysterious. Already got more than enough mystery to deal with out here

02:02:37.100 --> 02:02:43.180
in case you hadn't noticed. Yeah, but we can't do anything about that. That'll change. We'll be

02:02:43.180 --> 02:02:50.060
working our asses off in no time. You think? Count on it, spindle said. So far we've just been

02:02:50.060 --> 02:02:54.220
peaking from a distance, eh? Bet all kinds of interesting stuff happens when we get in there

02:02:54.220 --> 02:02:59.260
and start poking it with a stick. Maybe for you, there's got to be a biological somewhere in the

02:02:59.260 --> 02:03:03.980
mix with all those organics. Damn right, and you'll be talking to them while I'm giving them their

02:03:03.980 --> 02:03:09.820
physicals. Maybe not. I mean, mom would never admit it in a million years, but you had a point

02:03:09.820 --> 02:03:14.940
about language. When you get right down to it, it's a workaround. Like trying to describe dreams

02:03:14.940 --> 02:03:20.540
with smoke signals. It's noble. It's maybe the most noble thing a body can do, but you can't turn a

02:03:20.540 --> 02:03:25.420
sunset into a string of grunts without losing something. It's limiting. Maybe whatever's out

02:03:25.420 --> 02:03:31.020
here doesn't even use it. Bet they do, though. Since when? You're the one who's always pointing

02:03:31.020 --> 02:03:36.700
out how inefficient language is. Only when I'm trying to get under your skin. Your pants,

02:03:36.700 --> 02:03:41.980
a whole other thing. He laughed at his own joke. Seriously, what are they going to use instead,

02:03:41.980 --> 02:03:47.020
telepathy? I say you'll be up to your elbows in hieroglyphics before you know it. And what's more,

02:03:47.020 --> 02:03:53.340
you'll decode them in no time. You're sweet, but I wonder. Half the time I can't even decode Yuka.

02:03:54.300 --> 02:04:01.340
Michelle fell silent. He actually kind of throws me sometimes. You and seven billion others.

02:04:01.980 --> 02:04:07.020
Yeah, I know it's silly, but when he's not around, there's a part of me that can't stop wondering

02:04:07.020 --> 02:04:11.580
where he's hiding. And when he's right there in front of me, I feel like I should be hiding.

02:04:12.540 --> 02:04:18.140
Not his fault he creeps us out. I know, but it's hardly a big morale booster.

02:04:18.140 --> 02:04:22.780
What genius came up with the idea of putting a vampire in charge. Where else are you going to

02:04:22.860 --> 02:04:28.300
put him a you want to be the one getting orders to him? And it's not just the way he moves. It's

02:04:28.300 --> 02:04:34.620
the way he talks. It's just wrong. You know, he I'm not talking about the present tense thing or

02:04:34.620 --> 02:04:41.420
about all the glottals. He Well, you know how he talks, he's terse. It's efficient. It's artificial,

02:04:41.420 --> 02:04:46.220
Isaac. He's smarter than all of us put together. But sometimes he talks like he's got a 50 word

02:04:46.220 --> 02:04:52.140
vocabulary, a soft snort. It's not like I'd kill him to use an adverb once in a while.

02:04:53.740 --> 02:04:57.900
Ah, but you say that because you're a linguist and you can't see why anyone wouldn't want to

02:04:57.900 --> 02:05:03.820
wallow in the sheer beauty of language. Spindle harromped with mock pomposity. Now me, I'm a

02:05:03.820 --> 02:05:10.140
biologist, so it makes perfect sense. Really? Then explain it to me. Oh, why is an powerful

02:05:10.140 --> 02:05:17.100
mutilator of frogs? Simple. Bloodsuckers are transient, not a resident. What are Oh, those

02:05:17.100 --> 02:05:23.100
are killer whales, right? Whistle dialects. I said forget the language. Think about the lifestyle.

02:05:24.060 --> 02:05:29.100
Residents are fish eaters, eh? They hang out in big groups. Don't move around much talk all the time.

02:05:29.980 --> 02:05:34.780
I heard a whisper of motion. Imagine spindle laying in and laying a hand on Michelle's arm.

02:05:35.500 --> 02:05:41.820
I imagine the sensors in his gloves telling him what she felt like. Transients now. They eat mammals.

02:05:41.820 --> 02:05:46.620
Seals, sea lions, smart prey, smart enough to take cover when they hear a fluke slap or a click

02:05:46.620 --> 02:05:52.220
train. So transients are sneaky, eh? Hunt in small groups, range all over the place,

02:05:52.220 --> 02:05:56.700
keep their mouths shut so nobody hears him coming. And yuka's a transient.

02:05:57.740 --> 02:06:03.020
Man's instinct tell him to keep quiet around prey. Every time he opens his mouth, every time he lets

02:06:03.020 --> 02:06:08.220
us see him, he's fighting his own brainstem. Maybe we shouldn't be too harsh on the old guy just

02:06:08.220 --> 02:06:13.020
because he's not the world's best motivational speaker, eh? He's fighting the urge to eat us

02:06:13.020 --> 02:06:18.860
every time we have a briefing. That's reassuring. Spindle chuckled. It's probably not that bad.

02:06:18.860 --> 02:06:23.340
I guess even killer whales let their guard down after making a kill. Why sneak around in a full

02:06:23.340 --> 02:06:30.380
snum, eh? So he's not fighting his brainstem. He just isn't hungry. Probably a little of both.

02:06:30.380 --> 02:06:35.580
Brainstem never really goes away, you know. But I'll tell you one thing. Some of the playfulness

02:06:35.580 --> 02:06:41.580
ebbed from spindle's voice. I've got no problem if Sudosti wants to run the occasional briefing

02:06:41.580 --> 02:06:47.100
from his quarters. But the moment we stop seeing him altogether, that's when you start watching your back.

02:06:51.180 --> 02:06:51.980
End of part two.

02:06:55.580 --> 02:06:59.500
Looking back, I can finally admit it. I envied spindle his way with the ladies.

02:07:00.060 --> 02:07:04.380
Spliced in dice to gangly massive ticks and jitters that could barely feel his own skin.

02:07:04.380 --> 02:07:08.940
Somehow he managed to be... charming. That's the word. Charming.

02:07:10.220 --> 02:07:14.780
As a social necessity, it was all but obsolete, fading into irrelevance along with two-party

02:07:14.780 --> 02:07:20.300
non-virtual sex pairing. But even I'd tried one of those, and it would have been nice to have

02:07:20.300 --> 02:07:26.140
spindle's self-deprecating skill set to call on. Especially when everything with Chelsea started

02:07:26.140 --> 02:07:31.660
falling apart. I had my own style, of course. I tried to be charming in my own peculiar way.

02:07:32.380 --> 02:07:37.100
Once, after one too many fights about honesty and emotional manipulation,

02:07:37.100 --> 02:07:42.060
I started to think maybe a touch of whimsy might smooth things over. I'd come to suspect that

02:07:42.060 --> 02:07:47.660
Chelsea just didn't understand sexual politics. Sure, she edited brains for a living, and maybe

02:07:47.660 --> 02:07:51.500
she just memorized all that circuitry without giving any thought to how it had arisen in the

02:07:51.500 --> 02:07:57.420
first place. To the ultimate rules of natural selection that had shaped it. Maybe she honestly

02:07:57.420 --> 02:08:01.580
didn't know that we were evolutionary enemies, that all relationships were doomed to failure.

02:08:02.380 --> 02:08:07.180
If I could slip that insight into her head, if I could charm my way past her defenses,

02:08:07.740 --> 02:08:11.900
maybe we'd be able to hold things together. So I thought about it, and came up with the

02:08:11.900 --> 02:08:18.140
perfect way to raise her awareness. I wrote her a bedtime story, a disarming blend of humor and

02:08:18.140 --> 02:08:25.180
affection, and I called it The Book of Oogenesis. In the beginning there were gemmets, and though

02:08:25.180 --> 02:08:31.660
there was sex, low there was no gender, and life was in balance. And God said, let there be sperm,

02:08:31.660 --> 02:08:35.900
and some seeds did shrivel in size and grow cheap to make, and they did flood the market.

02:08:36.620 --> 02:08:42.220
And God said, let there be eggs, and other seeds were afflicted by a plague of sperm,

02:08:42.220 --> 02:08:46.860
and yay, few of them bore full fruit, for sperm brought no food for the zygote,

02:08:46.860 --> 02:08:51.580
and only the largest eggs could make up for the shortfall, and these grew yet larger in the fullness

02:08:51.580 --> 02:08:56.860
of time. And God put the eggs into the womb, and said, wait here, for thy bulk has made the

02:08:56.860 --> 02:09:02.140
unwieldy, and sperm must seek thee out in thy chambers. Henceforth shout thou be fertilized

02:09:02.140 --> 02:09:08.940
internally, and it was so. And God said to the gemmets, the fruit of thy fusion may abide in

02:09:08.940 --> 02:09:14.940
any place, and take any shape. It may breathe air, or water, or the sulfurous muck of hydrothermal

02:09:14.940 --> 02:09:19.820
vents. But do not forget my one commandment unto you, which has not changed from the beginning of

02:09:19.820 --> 02:09:26.300
time. Spread thy genes. And thus did sperm and egg go into the world, and sperm said,

02:09:26.860 --> 02:09:31.900
I am cheap and plentiful, and if I so debundantly I will surely fulfill God's plan,

02:09:32.460 --> 02:09:36.780
I shall forever seek out new mates, and then abandon them when they are with child,

02:09:36.780 --> 02:09:42.460
for there are many wombs and little time. But egg said, low, the burden of procreation weighs

02:09:42.460 --> 02:09:48.220
heavily upon me. I must carry flesh that is but half mine, gestate and feed it even when it leaves

02:09:48.220 --> 02:09:55.420
my chamber, for by now many of eggs bodies were of warm, furry, warm blood and furry besides.

02:09:56.380 --> 02:10:01.500
I can have but few children, and must devote myself to those, and protect them at every turn,

02:10:01.500 --> 02:10:06.380
and I will make sperm help me, for he got me into this. And he doth struggle at my side,

02:10:06.380 --> 02:10:12.300
I shall not let him strain, or lie with my competitors. And sperm liked this knot. And

02:10:12.300 --> 02:10:16.220
God smiled, for its commandment had put sperm and egg at war with each other,

02:10:16.220 --> 02:10:23.340
even until the day they made themselves obsolete. I brought her flowers one dusky Tuesday evening

02:10:23.340 --> 02:10:27.900
when the light was perfect. I pointed out the irony of that old romantic tradition,

02:10:27.900 --> 02:10:32.540
the sever genitalia of another species offered as a pre-copulatory bribe,

02:10:33.260 --> 02:10:39.260
and then recited my story just as we were about to fuck. To this day I still don't know what went wrong.

02:10:39.580 --> 02:10:46.460
The glass ceiling is in you. The glass ceiling is conscience.

02:10:47.820 --> 02:10:50.140
Jacob Holtzbrink, the keys to the planet.

02:10:52.060 --> 02:10:57.180
There were stories before we left earth of a fourth wave, a fleet of deep-space dreadknots

02:10:57.180 --> 02:11:01.500
running silent on our wake, should the cannon fodder up front run into something nasty.

02:11:02.060 --> 02:11:07.100
Or if the aliens were friendly, an ambassadorial frigate full of politicians and CEOs ready to

02:11:07.100 --> 02:11:12.620
elbow their way to the front of the line. Never mind that earth had no deep-space dreadknots or

02:11:12.620 --> 02:11:18.860
ambassadorial spaceships. Easy as hadn't existed either before firefall. Nobody had told us of

02:11:18.860 --> 02:11:23.980
any such contingent, but you never show the big picture to your front line. The less they know,

02:11:23.980 --> 02:11:29.740
the less they can betray. I still don't know if the fourth wave ever existed. I never saw any

02:11:29.740 --> 02:11:35.180
evidence of one, for whatever that's worth. We might have left them floundering back at Burns

02:11:35.260 --> 02:11:40.060
Caulfield, or maybe they followed us all the way to Big Ben, crept just close enough to see what

02:11:40.060 --> 02:11:46.140
we were up against and turn tail before things got ugly. I wonder if that's what happened. I wonder

02:11:46.140 --> 02:11:56.300
if they made it back home. I look back now and hope not. A giant marshmallow kicked theseus in the

02:11:56.300 --> 02:12:02.620
side, down and swung like a pendulum. Across the drum spindle, yelped as if scalded, in the galley,

02:12:02.620 --> 02:12:08.940
a cracking a bulb of hot coffee. I nearly was. This is it, I thought. We got too close. They're

02:12:08.940 --> 02:12:13.900
hitting back. What the... A flicker on the party line as baits linked from the bridge.

02:12:14.460 --> 02:12:16.620
Main drive just kicked in. We're changing course.

02:12:17.420 --> 02:12:22.780
To what? Where? Whose orders? Mine, Sudasti said, appearing above us.

02:12:23.660 --> 02:12:28.060
Nobody spoke, drifting into the drum through the stern hatchway, the sound of something grinding.

02:12:28.780 --> 02:12:34.220
I pinged Theseus' resource allocation stack. Fabrication was retooling itself for the mass

02:12:34.220 --> 02:12:39.500
production of doped ceramics. Radiation shielding. Solid stuff, bulky and primitive,

02:12:39.500 --> 02:12:45.100
not the controlled magnetic fields we usually relied on. The game emerged, sleepy-eye from their

02:12:45.100 --> 02:12:52.380
tent, Sasha grumbling. What the fuck? Watch. Sudasti took hold of consensus and shook it.

02:12:53.340 --> 02:12:57.980
It was a blizzard, not a briefing. Gravity wells and orbital trajectories,

02:12:57.980 --> 02:13:02.620
sheer stress simulations in thunderheads of ammonium and hydrogen, stereoscopic

02:13:02.620 --> 02:13:07.740
planetscapes buried under filters ranging from gamma to radio. I saw breakpoints and

02:13:07.740 --> 02:13:13.180
saddle points and unstable equilibria. I saw fold catastrophes plotted in five dimensions.

02:13:13.740 --> 02:13:18.380
My augments strained to rotate the information. My meaty half-brain struggled to understand

02:13:18.380 --> 02:13:25.500
the bottom line. Something was hiding down there, in plain sight. Ben's accretion belt wasn't

02:13:25.500 --> 02:13:30.860
misbehaving. Its delinquency wasn't obvious, Sudasti hadn't had to plot every pebble and

02:13:30.860 --> 02:13:36.140
mountain and planetesimal to find the pattern, but he'd come close. And neither he nor the

02:13:36.140 --> 02:13:40.700
conjoined intelligence he shared with the captain had been able to explain those trajectories as

02:13:40.700 --> 02:13:46.780
the mere aftermath of some past disturbance. The dust wasn't just settling, some of it marched

02:13:46.780 --> 02:13:51.100
down hill to the beat of something that even now reached out from the cloud tops and pulled debris

02:13:51.100 --> 02:13:57.740
from orbit. Not all that debris seemed to hit. Ben's equatorial regions flickered constantly

02:13:57.740 --> 02:14:02.620
with the light of meteorite impacts, much fainter than the bright wakes of the skimmers and gone in

02:14:02.620 --> 02:14:07.580
the wink of an eye, but those frequency distributions didn't quite account for all the rocks that had

02:14:07.580 --> 02:14:13.820
fallen. He was almost as though every now and then some piece of incoming detris simply vanished

02:14:13.820 --> 02:14:20.140
into a parallel universe, or got caught by something in this one. Something that circled Ben's equator

02:14:20.140 --> 02:14:25.100
every 40 hours, almost low enough to graze the atmosphere. Something that didn't show up in

02:14:25.100 --> 02:14:31.020
visible light or infrared or radar. Something that might have remained pure hypothesis if a skimmer

02:14:31.020 --> 02:14:35.820
hadn't burned an incandescent trail across the atmosphere behind it when the easiest it happened

02:14:35.820 --> 02:14:42.940
to be watching. Sudasti threw that one dead center, a bright contrail streaking diagonally across Ben's

02:14:42.940 --> 02:14:48.140
perpetual nightscape, stuttering partway a degree or two to the left, stuttering back just

02:14:48.140 --> 02:14:53.980
before it passed from sight. Freeze frame showed a beam of light frozen solid, a segment snapped

02:14:53.980 --> 02:14:59.820
from its midsection and jiggled just a hair out of alignment. A segment nine kilometers long.

02:15:00.860 --> 02:15:07.660
It's cloaked, Sasha said, impressed. Not very well. Bates emerged from the forward hatch and

02:15:07.820 --> 02:15:13.260
stailed spinward. Pretty obvious refactory artifact. She caught stairs halfway to the deck,

02:15:13.260 --> 02:15:17.020
used the torque of spin against spam to flip upright and plant her feet on the steps.

02:15:17.660 --> 02:15:23.420
Why didn't we catch that before? No backlight, spindle suggested. It's not just the contrail,

02:15:23.420 --> 02:15:28.460
look at the clouds. Sure enough, Ben's cloudy backdrop showed the same subtle dislocation.

02:15:29.260 --> 02:15:33.820
Bates stepped onto the deck and headed for the conference table. We should have seen this earlier.

02:15:34.780 --> 02:15:41.580
The other probes see no such artifact, Sudasti said. This probe approaches from a wider angle,

02:15:41.580 --> 02:15:49.340
27 degrees. Wider angle to what? Sasha said. To the line, Bates murmured, between us and them.

02:15:50.940 --> 02:15:55.740
It was all there on tactical. The easiest fell inwards along an obvious arc, but the probes

02:15:55.740 --> 02:16:01.340
weren't, we dispatched, hadn't dicked around with the Hohmann transfers. They'd burnt straight down,

02:16:01.340 --> 02:16:05.900
their courses barely bending, all within a few degrees of the theoretical line connecting Ben

02:16:05.900 --> 02:16:13.180
Dethesius. Except this one. This one had come in wide and seen a trickery. The further our bearing,

02:16:13.180 --> 02:16:18.700
the more obvious the discontinuity, Sudasti intoned. I think it's clearly visible on any

02:16:18.700 --> 02:16:24.540
approach perpendicular to ours. So we're in a blind spot. We see it if we change course.

02:16:25.100 --> 02:16:30.300
Bates shook her head. The blind spot's moving, Sasha. It's... tracking us.

02:16:30.940 --> 02:16:39.020
Sasha sucked breath between her teeth. Motherfucker! Spindle twitched. So what is it, our skimmer factory?

02:16:40.460 --> 02:16:45.500
The freeze frame's pixels began to crawl. Something emerged, granular and indistinct,

02:16:45.500 --> 02:16:51.180
from the turbulent swirls and curlicues of Ben's atmosphere. There were curves and spikes and no

02:16:51.180 --> 02:16:55.900
smooth edges. I couldn't tell how much of the shape was real and how much of fractal intrusion

02:16:55.900 --> 02:17:01.660
of underlying cloudscape. But the overall outline was that of a torus, or perhaps a collection of

02:17:01.660 --> 02:17:07.580
smaller jagged things piled together in a rough ring and it was big. Those nine clicks of displaced

02:17:07.580 --> 02:17:13.500
contrail had merely grazed the perimeter, cut across an arc of 40 or 50 degrees. The thing

02:17:13.500 --> 02:17:17.660
hiding in the shadow of 10 Jupiters was almost 30 kilometers from side to side.

02:17:18.620 --> 02:17:24.700
Sometime during Sadasti's executive summary we'd stopped accelerating. Down was back where it

02:17:24.700 --> 02:17:31.420
belonged. We weren't, though. Our hesitant maybe-maybe-not approach was a thing of the past. We vectored

02:17:31.420 --> 02:17:33.420
straight in now and damned the torpedoes.

02:17:34.460 --> 02:17:39.900
Uh, that's 30 clicks across, Sasha pointed out. And it's invisible. Shouldn't we maybe be a little

02:17:39.900 --> 02:17:46.300
more cautious now? Spindle shrugged. We could second-guess vampires. We wouldn't need vampires,

02:17:46.380 --> 02:17:52.380
eh? A new facet bloomed of the feed. Frequency histograms and a harmonic spectra erupted into

02:17:52.380 --> 02:17:56.220
flatline into shifting mountain scapes. A chorus of visible light.

02:17:57.020 --> 02:18:03.020
Modulated laser, Bates reported. Spindle looked up. From that? Bates nodded.

02:18:03.580 --> 02:18:06.220
Right after we blow its cover. Interesting timing.

02:18:06.860 --> 02:18:12.700
Scary timing, Spindle said. How'd it know? We changed course. We're heading right for it.

02:18:13.580 --> 02:18:15.980
The lightscape played on, knocking at the window.

02:18:16.860 --> 02:18:20.060
Whatever it is, Bates said. It's talking to us.

02:18:21.180 --> 02:18:27.660
Well then, remarked a welcome voice. By all means, let's say hello. Susan James was back in the

02:18:27.660 --> 02:18:35.660
driver's seat. I was the only peer spectator. They all performed what duties they couldn't.

02:18:35.660 --> 02:18:39.500
Spindle ran Sadasti's sketchy silhouette through a series of filters,

02:18:39.500 --> 02:18:44.620
perchance to squeeze a bit of biology from engineering. Bates compared morphometrics between

02:18:44.620 --> 02:18:49.820
the cloaked artifact and the skimmers. Sadasti watched us all from overhead and thought vampire

02:18:49.820 --> 02:18:54.940
thoughts deeper than anything we could aspire to. But it was all just make work. The gang of four

02:18:54.940 --> 02:19:01.340
was on center stage, under the capable direction of Susan James. She grabbed the nearest chair,

02:19:01.340 --> 02:19:07.180
sat, raised her hands as if queuing an orchestra. Her fingers trembled in midair as she played

02:19:07.180 --> 02:19:13.580
virtual icons. Her lips and jaw twitched with subvocal commands. I tapped her feet and saw a text

02:19:13.580 --> 02:19:21.260
decreting around the alien signal. Rorschach to vessel approaching 116 degrees azimuth,

02:19:21.260 --> 02:19:27.820
negative 20 degrees declination relative. Hello, Thezius. Rorschach to vessel approaching 116

02:19:27.820 --> 02:19:34.300
degrees azimuth, negative 23 degrees declination relative. Hello, Thezius. Rorschach to vessel

02:19:34.300 --> 02:19:39.820
approaching 116 degrees azimuth, she decoded the damn thing already. She was even answering it.

02:19:40.700 --> 02:19:47.100
Thezius to Rorschach. Hello, Rorschach. Hello, Thezius. Welcome to the neighborhood.

02:19:48.220 --> 02:19:52.540
She'd had less than three minutes, or rather they'd had less than three minutes,

02:19:52.540 --> 02:19:57.820
four fully conscious hub personalities and a few dozen unconscious semiotic modules all working in

02:19:57.820 --> 02:20:03.580
parallel all exquisitely carved from the same lump of gray matter. I could almost see why someone

02:20:03.580 --> 02:20:07.820
would do such deliberate violence to their own minds if it resulted in this kind of performance.

02:20:08.780 --> 02:20:13.180
Up until now I had never convinced myself that even survival was sufficient cause.

02:20:14.140 --> 02:20:20.300
Request permission to approach, the gang sent. Simple and straightforward, just facts and data

02:20:20.300 --> 02:20:25.500
thank you with as little room as possible for ambiguity and misunderstanding. Fancy sentiments

02:20:25.500 --> 02:20:31.740
like we come in peace could wait. A handshake was not the time for cultural exchange. You should

02:20:31.740 --> 02:20:39.260
stay away. Seriously. This place is dangerous. That got some attention. Bates and Spindle

02:20:39.260 --> 02:20:46.380
hesitated momentarily in their own head spaces and glanced into James. Request information on danger,

02:20:46.380 --> 02:20:52.860
the gang sent back. Still keeping it concrete. Too close and dangerous to you. Low orbit

02:20:52.860 --> 02:21:01.580
complications. Request information on low orbit complications. Lethal environment. Rocks and

02:21:01.580 --> 02:21:09.340
rads. You're welcome. I can take it but we're like that. We are aware of the rocks in low orbit.

02:21:09.340 --> 02:21:16.060
We are equipped to deal with radiation. Request information on other hazards. I dug under the

02:21:16.060 --> 02:21:21.100
transcript to the channel if fed from. Theseus had turned part of the incoming beam into a sound

02:21:21.100 --> 02:21:28.300
wave according to the color code. Vocal communication then. They spoke. Waiting behind that icon where

02:21:28.300 --> 02:21:35.660
the raw sounds of an alien language. Of course I couldn't resist. Anytime between friends right?

02:21:35.660 --> 02:21:43.260
Are you here for the celebration? English. The voice was human. Male. Old.

02:21:44.460 --> 02:21:51.500
We're here to explore. Replied the gang. Although their voice was pure athesias. Request dialogue

02:21:51.500 --> 02:21:57.900
with agents who sent objects into near solar space. First contact. Sounds like something to

02:21:57.900 --> 02:22:05.100
celebrate. I double check the source. No this wasn't a translation. This was the actual unprocessed

02:22:05.100 --> 02:22:11.340
signal coming from Rorschach. It had called itself. Part of the signal anyway. There were

02:22:11.340 --> 02:22:18.140
other elements. Nonacoustic ones encoding in the beam. I browsed them while James said. Request

02:22:18.140 --> 02:22:25.020
information about your celebration. Standard ship to ship hand taking protocols. You're interested.

02:22:25.820 --> 02:22:34.700
The voice was stronger now. Younger. Yes. You are? Yes. The gang repeated patiently. You are?

02:22:35.740 --> 02:22:43.420
The slightest hesitation. This athesias. I know that baseline. In Mandarin now. Who are you?

02:22:44.780 --> 02:22:49.820
No obvious change in the harmonics. Somehow though the voice seemed to have acquired an edge.

02:22:50.620 --> 02:22:56.700
This is Susan James. I am a... You wouldn't be happy here Susan. Fetishistic religious beliefs

02:22:56.700 --> 02:23:03.420
involved. There are dangerous observances. James chewed her lip. Request clarification.

02:23:03.420 --> 02:23:10.540
Are we in danger from these observances? You certainly could be. Request clarification.

02:23:10.540 --> 02:23:16.300
Is it the observances that are dangerous or the low orbit environment? The environment of the

02:23:16.300 --> 02:23:22.380
disturbances. You should pay attention Susan. Inattention connotes indifference, Rorschach said.

02:23:23.420 --> 02:23:26.620
Or disrespect. It added after a moment.

02:23:30.540 --> 02:23:37.020
We had four hours before Ben got in the way. Four hours of uninterrupted nonstop communication made

02:23:37.020 --> 02:23:43.500
vastly easier than anyone had expected. It spoke our language after all. Repeatedly it expressed

02:23:43.500 --> 02:23:49.260
polite concern for our welfare. And yet for all its facility with human speech it told us very little.

02:23:50.060 --> 02:23:54.540
For four hours it managed to avoid giving a straight answer on any subject beyond the

02:23:54.540 --> 02:24:00.220
extreme inadvisability of closer contact. And by the time it fell into eclipse we still didn't know why.

02:24:01.740 --> 02:24:06.060
Sadasti dropped onto the deck halfway through the exchange, his feet never touching the stairs.

02:24:06.780 --> 02:24:11.740
He reached out and grabbed a railing to steady himself on landing and staggered only briefly.

02:24:11.820 --> 02:24:16.060
If I tried that I'd have ended up bouncing along the deck like a pebble in a cement mixer.

02:24:19.980 --> 02:24:22.780
He stood still as stone for the rest of the session,

02:24:22.780 --> 02:24:28.540
face motionless, eyes hidden behind his onyx visor. When Rorschach's signal faded in mid-sentence

02:24:28.540 --> 02:24:30.940
he assembled us around the commons table with a gesture.

02:24:32.140 --> 02:24:39.260
It talks, he said. James nodded. It doesn't say much except for asking us to keep our distance.

02:24:39.340 --> 02:24:44.060
So far the voice has manifested as an adult male although the apparent age changed a few times.

02:24:44.860 --> 02:24:51.340
He'd heard all that. Structure? The ship-to-ship protocols are perfect. Its vocabulary is far

02:24:51.340 --> 02:24:55.340
greater than you could derive from standard nav chatter between a few ships so they've been

02:24:55.340 --> 02:25:00.540
listening to all our in-system traffic I'd say for several years at least. On the other hand the

02:25:00.540 --> 02:25:05.500
vocabulary doesn't have anywhere near the range you'd get by monitoring entertainment multimed so

02:25:05.500 --> 02:25:11.260
they probably arrived after the broadcast age. How well do they use the vocabulary they have?

02:25:12.220 --> 02:25:15.900
They're using phase structure grammar, long distance dependencies,

02:25:15.900 --> 02:25:20.620
FLN recursion, at least four levels deep and I see no reason why won't go deeper with continued

02:25:20.620 --> 02:25:28.140
contact. They're not parrots, Yuka. They know the rules. That name for instance. Rorschach,

02:25:28.140 --> 02:25:32.780
Bates murmured, Knuckles cracking as she squeezed her pet ball. Interesting choice.

02:25:33.100 --> 02:25:39.340
I checked the registry. There's an I-CAN freighter called Rorschach on the Martian loop. Whoever

02:25:39.340 --> 02:25:43.660
we're talking to must regard their own platform the way we regard a ship and pick one of our names

02:25:43.660 --> 02:25:50.460
to fit. Spinzel dropped into the chair beside me fresh from a galley run. A bulb of coffee glistened

02:25:50.460 --> 02:25:56.140
like jelly in his hand. That name out of all ships in the intersist seems way too symbolic for random

02:25:56.140 --> 02:26:02.620
choice. I don't think it was random. Unusual ship names promote Comet. Rorschach's pilot goes

02:26:02.620 --> 02:26:07.900
ship to ship with some other vessel. The other vessel comes back with, oh grandma what an unusual

02:26:07.900 --> 02:26:13.900
name you have. Rorschach replies with some off the cuff comment about non-clam- nominclature

02:26:13.900 --> 02:26:19.340
origins and it all goes out in the e.m. Someone listening to all that chatter not only figures

02:26:19.340 --> 02:26:23.740
out the name and the thing it applies to but can get some sense of meaning from the context.

02:26:24.380 --> 02:26:28.940
Our alien friends probably easily dropped on half the registry and deduced that Rorschach

02:26:28.940 --> 02:26:36.620
could be a better tag for someone unfamiliar than say the SS Jamie Matthews. Territorial and smart,

02:26:36.620 --> 02:26:42.620
Spindle grimaced, conjuring a mug from beneath his chair. Wonderful. Bates shrugged.

02:26:48.140 --> 02:26:53.500
Territorial maybe. Not necessarily aggressive. In fact I wonder if they could even hurt us if they

02:26:53.500 --> 02:27:01.580
wanted to. I don't, Spindle said. Those skimmers. The major wave to dismissive hand. Big ships turn

02:27:01.580 --> 02:27:07.020
slowly. If they were setting up to snooker us we'd see it well in advance. She looked around the table.

02:27:07.020 --> 02:27:12.220
Look am I the only one who finds this odd an interstellar technology that redecorates super

02:27:12.220 --> 02:27:19.500
Jovians and lines up meteoroids like elephants on parade and they were hiding from us? Unless there's

02:27:19.500 --> 02:27:26.140
someone else out here, James suggested uneasily. Bates shook her head. The cloak was directional.

02:27:26.140 --> 02:27:33.020
It was aimed at us and no one else. And even we saw through it, Spindle added. Exactly. So they go to

02:27:33.020 --> 02:27:38.140
Plan B which so far amounts to nothing but bluster and vague warnings. I'm just saying they're not

02:27:38.140 --> 02:27:44.300
acting like giants. Rorschach's behavior feels improvised. I don't think they expected us.

02:27:45.020 --> 02:27:49.020
Of course not. Burns Caulfield was, I don't think they expected us yet.

02:27:50.140 --> 02:27:56.060
Um, Spindle said, digesting it. The major ran one hand over her naked scalp.

02:27:56.780 --> 02:28:01.100
Why would they expect us to just give up after we learned we'd been sniped? Of course we'd look

02:28:01.100 --> 02:28:06.300
elsewhere. Burns Caulfield could only have intended as a delaying action. If I was them,

02:28:06.300 --> 02:28:11.420
I'd plan on us getting out here eventually. But I think they miscalculated somehow. We got out here

02:28:11.420 --> 02:28:15.980
sooner than they expected and caught them with their pants down. Spindle split the bowl but

02:28:15.980 --> 02:28:22.540
emptied it into his mug. Pretty large miscalculation for something so smart, eh? A hologram bloomed on

02:28:22.540 --> 02:28:26.940
contact with the steaming liquid, glowing in soft commemoration of the gods of glasslands.

02:28:27.660 --> 02:28:32.620
The scent of plasticized coffee flooded the commons. Especially after they surveilled us

02:28:32.620 --> 02:28:39.740
down to the square meter, he added. And what did they see? Icans. Solar sails. Ships that take

02:28:39.740 --> 02:28:44.620
years to reach the Kuiper and don't have the reserves to go anywhere else afterwards. Telematter

02:28:44.620 --> 02:28:50.060
didn't exist beyond bowing simulators and half a dozen prototypes back then. Easy to miss. They

02:28:50.060 --> 02:28:55.420
must have figured one decoy would buy them all the time they needed. To do what, James wondered.

02:28:56.300 --> 02:29:03.340
Whatever it is, Bates said, we're ringside. Spindle raised his mug with an infirm hand and sift.

02:29:03.900 --> 02:29:08.060
The coffee trembled in its prison, the surface wobbling and blobbing in the drums half-hearted

02:29:08.060 --> 02:29:14.300
gravity. James pursed her lips in faint disapproval. Open top containers for liquids were technically

02:29:14.300 --> 02:29:19.100
verboten in variable gravity environments, even for people without spindle's dexterity issues.

02:29:20.060 --> 02:29:26.140
So they're bluffing, Spindle said at last. Bates nodded. That's my guess. Rorschach's still under

02:29:26.140 --> 02:29:31.260
construction. We could be dealing with an automated system of some kind. So we can ignore the keep

02:29:31.260 --> 02:29:36.940
off the grass signs, eh? Walk right in. We can afford to bite our time. We can afford to not push it.

02:29:37.580 --> 02:29:42.140
Ah, so even though you could maybe handle it now, you want to wait until it graduates from

02:29:42.140 --> 02:29:47.580
covert to invulnerable. Spindle shuddered, set down his coffee. Where'd you get your military

02:29:47.580 --> 02:29:53.500
training again, Sporting Chance Academy? Bates ignored the jibe. The fact that Rorschach's

02:29:53.500 --> 02:29:59.020
still growing may be the best reason to leave it alone for a while. We don't have any idea what the

02:29:59.020 --> 02:30:04.940
mature, I guess, what the mature form of this artifact might be. Sure, it hid. Lots of animals

02:30:04.940 --> 02:30:10.940
take cover from predators without being predators, especially young ones. Sure, it's evasive. Doesn't

02:30:10.940 --> 02:30:16.060
give us the answers we want. But maybe it doesn't know them. Did you consider that? How much luck

02:30:16.060 --> 02:30:21.500
would you have interrogating a human embryo? Adult could be a whole different animal. Adult could

02:30:21.500 --> 02:30:27.660
put our asses through a meat grinder. So could the embryo, for all we know. Bates rolled her eyes.

02:30:27.660 --> 02:30:32.380
Jesus, Isaac, you're the biologist. I shouldn't have to tell you how many shy, reclusive critters

02:30:32.380 --> 02:30:36.460
pack a punch when they're cornered. Porcupine doesn't want any trouble, but he'll still give you a

02:30:36.460 --> 02:30:44.220
faceful of quills if you ignore the warning. Spindle said nothing. He slid his coffee sideways

02:30:44.220 --> 02:30:49.100
along the concave tabletop to the very limit of his reach. The liquid sat there in the mug,

02:30:49.100 --> 02:30:54.140
a dark circle perfectly parallel to the rim, but canted slightly towards us. I thought I could

02:30:54.140 --> 02:30:59.980
make out even the merest convexivity in the surface itself. Spindle smiled faintly at the effect.

02:31:00.940 --> 02:31:06.060
James cleared her throat. Not to downplay your concerns, Isaac, but we've hardly exhausted

02:31:06.060 --> 02:31:11.500
the diplomatic route. At least it's willing to talk, even if it's not as forthcoming as we'd like.

02:31:12.140 --> 02:31:18.940
Sure it talks, Spindle said. Eyes still leaning on the mug. Not like us. Well, no, there's some...

02:31:22.300 --> 02:31:27.580
It's not just slippery. It's downright dyslexic sometimes, you noticed, and it mixes up its

02:31:27.580 --> 02:31:33.500
pronouns. Given that it picked up the language entirely via passive eavesdropping, it's remarkably

02:31:33.500 --> 02:31:37.820
fluent. In fact, from what I can tell, they're more efficient at processing speech than we are.

02:31:38.700 --> 02:31:41.820
Gotta be efficient at the language if you're gonna be so evasive in it, eh?

02:31:42.540 --> 02:31:47.420
If they were human, I might agree with you, James replied. But what appears to us as evasion or

02:31:47.420 --> 02:31:51.740
deceit could just as easily be explained by reliance on smaller conceptual units.

02:31:52.540 --> 02:31:58.460
Conceptual units? Bates, I was beginning to realize, never pulled up a subtitle if she could help it.

02:31:59.340 --> 02:32:05.420
James nodded. Like processing a line of text word by word instead of looking at complete phrases,

02:32:05.420 --> 02:32:09.980
the smaller the units, the faster they can be reconfigured. It gives you very fast semantic

02:32:09.980 --> 02:32:15.420
reflexes. The downside is that it's difficult to maintain the same level of logical consistency

02:32:15.420 --> 02:32:18.620
since the patterns within the larger structure are more likely to get shuffled.

02:32:19.580 --> 02:32:24.700
Whoa. Spindle straightened, all thoughts of liquids and centipital force forgotten.

02:32:25.660 --> 02:32:29.900
All I'm saying is we aren't necessarily dealing with deliberate deception here.

02:32:29.900 --> 02:32:35.180
An entity who parses information at one scale might not be aware of inconsistencies at another.

02:32:35.180 --> 02:32:40.860
It might not even have a conscious access to that level. That's not all you're saying. Isaac,

02:32:40.860 --> 02:32:46.780
you can't apply human norms to a- I wondered what you were up to. Spindle drove into the

02:32:46.860 --> 02:32:53.340
transcripts. A moment later he dredged up an excerpt. Request information on environments you

02:32:53.340 --> 02:32:59.180
consider lethal. Request information on your response to the prospect of imminent exposure

02:32:59.180 --> 02:33:05.260
to lethal environments. Glad to comply, but your lethal is different from us. There are many

02:33:05.260 --> 02:33:11.900
migrating circumstances. You were testing it, Spindle crowed. He smacked his lips, his jaw ticked.

02:33:11.900 --> 02:33:16.940
You were looking for an emotional response. It was just a thought. It didn't prove anything.

02:33:17.660 --> 02:33:22.300
Was there a difference in the response time? James hesitated, then shook her head.

02:33:22.860 --> 02:33:27.820
But it was a stupid idea. There are so many variables. We have no idea how they- I mean,

02:33:27.820 --> 02:33:35.100
they're alien. The pathology is classic. What pathology? I asked. It doesn't mean anything

02:33:35.100 --> 02:33:40.140
except they're different from the human baseline, James insisted, which is not something anyone

02:33:40.140 --> 02:33:46.620
here can look down their nose about. I tried again. What pathology? James shook her head.

02:33:47.180 --> 02:33:52.220
Spindle filled me in. There's a syndrome you might have heard about, eh? Fast talkers, no

02:33:52.220 --> 02:33:58.140
conscience, tend to malopropism and self-contradiction, no emotional affect. We're not talking about

02:33:58.140 --> 02:34:04.860
human beings here, James said again softly. But if we were, Spindle added, we might call Rorschach

02:34:04.860 --> 02:34:11.500
a clinical sociopath. Sodosti had said nothing during the entire exchange. Now with the word

02:34:11.500 --> 02:34:14.220
hanging out in the open, I noticed that nobody else would look at him.

02:34:20.780 --> 02:34:25.980
We all knew that Yuka Sodosti was a sociopath, of course. Most of us just didn't mention it in

02:34:25.980 --> 02:34:31.580
polite company. Spindle was never that polite. Or maybe it was just that he seemed to almost

02:34:31.580 --> 02:34:36.460
understand Sodosti. He could look behind the monster and regard the organism, no less the

02:34:36.460 --> 02:34:40.300
product of natural selection for all the human flesh it had devoured in Eon's past.

02:34:41.340 --> 02:34:46.380
That perspective calmed him somehow. He could watch Sodosti watching him and not flinch.

02:34:47.180 --> 02:34:50.860
I feel sorry for the poor son of a bitch, he said once back in training.

02:34:51.820 --> 02:34:56.540
Some would have thought that absurd. This man so massively interfaced with machinery that his

02:34:56.540 --> 02:35:01.980
own motor skills had degraded for want of proper care and feeding. This man who heard x-rays and

02:35:01.980 --> 02:35:06.540
saw in shades of ultrasound, so corrupted by retrofits he could no longer even feel his own

02:35:06.540 --> 02:35:10.620
fingertips without assistance. This man could pity anyone else.

02:35:14.540 --> 02:35:19.100
Let alone an infra-eyed predator built to murder without the slightest twitch of remorse.

02:35:20.060 --> 02:35:23.020
Empathy for sociopaths isn't common, I remarked.

02:35:23.740 --> 02:35:28.380
Maybe it should be. We, at least. He waved an arm, some remote-length sensor cluster,

02:35:28.380 --> 02:35:33.900
crossed the simulator, whirred and torqued reflexively, chose the add-ons. Vampires had to

02:35:33.900 --> 02:35:38.780
be sociopaths. They're too much like their own prey. A lot of taxonomists don't even consider them

02:35:38.780 --> 02:35:43.420
a subspecies, you know that? Never diverged far enough for complete reproductive isolation.

02:35:44.220 --> 02:35:50.460
So maybe they're more syndrome than race. Just a bunch of obligate cannibals with a sense of

02:35:50.460 --> 02:35:57.660
consistent deformities. And how does that make... if the only thing that you can eat is your own kind,

02:35:57.660 --> 02:36:02.380
empathy is going to be the first thing that goes. Psychopathies no disorder in those shoes,

02:36:02.380 --> 02:36:06.940
eh? Just survival strategy. But they still make our skin crawl, so we chain them up.

02:36:07.740 --> 02:36:12.780
You think we should have repaired the crucifix glitch? Everyone knew why we hadn't. Only a

02:36:12.780 --> 02:36:18.220
fooled, resurrected monster without safeguards in place. Vampires came with theirs built in.

02:36:18.220 --> 02:36:23.180
Without his anti-euclidean, Serosti would go grand maul in the first thing he caught close sight

02:36:23.180 --> 02:36:29.340
of the four-panel window frame. But Spindle was shaking his head. We couldn't have fixed it,

02:36:29.340 --> 02:36:35.580
or we could have, he amended. But the glitch is in the visual cortex, eh? Linked to Omni-Savantism.

02:36:36.140 --> 02:36:39.660
You fix it, you disable their pattern-matching skills, and then what's even the point of

02:36:39.660 --> 02:36:45.980
bringing them back? I didn't know that. Well, that's the official story. He fell silent for a moment,

02:36:45.980 --> 02:36:50.140
cracked a crooked grin. Then again, we didn't have any trouble fixing the

02:36:50.700 --> 02:36:54.700
Proto-Cadiran pathways when it suited us. I subtitled.

02:36:55.260 --> 02:37:02.540
Context-sensitive consensus served up Proto-Cadiran-Y, the magical hominid brain protein that vampires

02:37:02.540 --> 02:37:07.340
had never been able to synthesize. The reason they hadn't just switched to zebras or warthogs

02:37:07.340 --> 02:37:11.980
once denied human prey. Why our discovery of the terrible secret of the right angle had

02:37:12.060 --> 02:37:18.460
spelled their doom. Anyway, I just think he's cut off. A nervous tick tugged at the corner of

02:37:18.460 --> 02:37:24.540
Spindle's mouth. Lone wolf, nothing but sheep for company. Wouldn't you feel lonely? They don't like

02:37:24.540 --> 02:37:29.500
company, I reminded him. You didn't put vampires of the same sex together, not unless you were

02:37:29.500 --> 02:37:35.580
taking bets on a bloodbath. They were solitary hunters and very territorial. With a minimum

02:37:35.580 --> 02:37:41.420
viable pred-prey ratio of one to ten, and human prey spread so sparsely across the Pliastocene

02:37:41.420 --> 02:37:45.340
landscape, the biggest threat to their survival had been competition from their own kind.

02:37:45.900 --> 02:37:48.780
Natural selection had never taught them to play nicely together.

02:37:49.580 --> 02:37:54.620
That didn't cut any ice with Spindle, though. Doesn't mean he can't be lonely, he insisted.

02:37:54.620 --> 02:37:55.900
Just means he can't fix it.

02:37:58.460 --> 02:38:03.180
They know the music, but not the words. Hair without conscience.

02:38:05.180 --> 02:38:10.620
We did it with mirrors. Great round parabolic things, each impossibly thin and three times as

02:38:10.620 --> 02:38:15.340
high as a man. Theseus rolled them up and bolted them to firecrackers, stuffed with precious

02:38:15.340 --> 02:38:20.700
antimatter from our dwindling stockpiles. With twelve hours to spare, she flung them like confetti

02:38:20.700 --> 02:38:25.980
along precise ballistic trajectories. And when they were safely distant, she set them alight.

02:38:27.900 --> 02:38:32.860
They pinwheeled off every which way, gamma-sleeting in their wake until they burned dry. Then they

02:38:32.860 --> 02:38:38.540
coasted, unfurling, mercurial insect wings across the void. In the greater distance,

02:38:38.620 --> 02:38:42.860
400,000 alien machines looped and burned and took no obvious notice.

02:38:43.980 --> 02:38:49.980
Rorschach fell around a bend barely 1500 kilometers from atmosphere, a fast, endless circle that took

02:38:49.980 --> 02:38:55.340
just under 40 hours to complete. By the time it didn't return to our sight, our mirrors were all

02:38:55.340 --> 02:39:00.700
outside the zone of total blindness. A close-up of Ben's equatorial edge floated in consensus.

02:39:01.260 --> 02:39:06.140
Mirror icons sparkled around it like an exploding schematic, like the disconnected facets of some

02:39:06.140 --> 02:39:12.140
great expanding compound eye. None had breaks. Whatever high ground the mirrors held, they

02:39:12.140 --> 02:39:18.940
wouldn't hold it for long. There, Bates said. A mirage wavered stage left, a tiny spot of swirling

02:39:18.940 --> 02:39:24.220
chaos, perhaps half the size of a fingernail, held an arm's length. It told us nothing. It was pure

02:39:24.220 --> 02:39:30.620
heat shimmer. But light bounced towards us some dozens of relayers. And while we each saw scarcely

02:39:30.620 --> 02:39:35.660
more than our last probe had, a patch of dark clouds set slightly awry by some invisible prism,

02:39:35.660 --> 02:39:40.780
each of these views refracted differently. The captain sieved flashes from the heavens and

02:39:40.780 --> 02:39:47.900
stitched them into a composite view. Details emerged. First, a faint sliver of shadow, a tiny dimple

02:39:47.900 --> 02:39:53.020
all but lost in the seething equatorial cloud bands. It had just barely rotated into view around

02:39:53.020 --> 02:39:57.660
the edge of the disk, a rock in the stream, perhaps, an invisible finger stuck in the clouds,

02:39:57.660 --> 02:40:03.740
turbulence and sheer stress shredding the boundary layers to either side. Spindle squinted. Plage

02:40:03.740 --> 02:40:08.940
effect. Subtitle said he was talking about a kind of sunspot, a knot in Ben's magnetic field.

02:40:09.660 --> 02:40:15.260
Higher, James said. Something floated above that dimple in the clouds, the way a ground effect

02:40:15.260 --> 02:40:20.940
ocean liner floats above the depression it pushes into the water's surface. I zoomed. Next to an

02:40:20.940 --> 02:40:27.580
oasis subdwarf with ten times the mass of Jupiter, Rorschach was tiny. Next to Thesias, it was a

02:40:27.580 --> 02:40:35.580
colossus. Not just a torus but a tangle, a city-sized chaos of spun glass, loops and bridges and

02:40:35.580 --> 02:40:40.860
a tenuette spires. The surface texture was pure artifice, of course. Consensus merely gift wrapped

02:40:40.860 --> 02:40:45.740
the enigma and refracted background. Still, in some dark haunting way it was almost beautiful.

02:40:46.460 --> 02:40:49.500
A nest of obsidian snakes and smoky crystalline spines.

02:40:50.220 --> 02:40:54.940
It's talking again, James reported. Talk back, Sodosti said, and abandoned us.

02:40:54.940 --> 02:41:01.020
So she did, and while the gang spoke with the artifact, the others spied upon it.

02:41:01.660 --> 02:41:06.060
Their vision failed over time, mirrors fell away along their respective vectors, lines of

02:41:06.060 --> 02:41:10.620
sight degraded with each passing second, but consensus filled with things learned in the meantime.

02:41:11.420 --> 02:41:17.340
Rorschach massed 1.8 times 10 to the 10th kilograms with a total volume of 2.3 times 10 to the 8th

02:41:17.340 --> 02:41:23.500
cubic meters. Its magnetic field, judging by radio squeals and its plage effect, was thousands of

02:41:23.580 --> 02:41:29.020
times stronger than the sun's. Astonishingly, parts of the composite image were clear enough to discern

02:41:29.020 --> 02:41:34.860
fine spiral grooves twined around the structure. Fibonacci sequence, Spindle reported. One jiggling

02:41:34.860 --> 02:41:40.540
eye fixing me for a moment. At least they're not completely alien. Spheroid protuberances

02:41:40.540 --> 02:41:45.980
disfigured the tips of at least three of Rorschach's innumerable spines. The grooves were more widely

02:41:45.980 --> 02:41:51.500
spaced in those areas, like skin grown tight and swollen with infection. Just before one vital

02:41:51.500 --> 02:41:55.820
mirror sailed out of range, it glimpsed another spine, split a third of the way along its length.

02:41:56.460 --> 02:41:59.180
Torn material floated flaccid and unmoving in the vacuum.

02:42:00.220 --> 02:42:03.900
Please, Bates said softly. Tell me that's not what it looks like.

02:42:04.780 --> 02:42:08.780
Spindle grinned. Sporangium? Seed pod? Why not?

02:42:10.060 --> 02:42:13.980
Rorschach may have been reproducing, but beyond a doubt it was growing,

02:42:13.980 --> 02:42:17.340
fed by a steady trickle of in-falling debris from Ben's accretion belt.

02:42:17.980 --> 02:42:20.780
We were close enough now to get a clear view of that procession.

02:42:21.420 --> 02:42:25.020
Rocks and mountains and pebbles fell like sediments swirling around a drain.

02:42:25.980 --> 02:42:31.740
Particles that collided with the artifact simply stuck. Rorschach engulfed prey like some vast

02:42:31.740 --> 02:42:37.580
metastic amoeba. The acquired mass was apparently processed internally and shunted to atypical

02:42:37.580 --> 02:42:47.180
growth zones. Judging by infinitesimal changes in the artifact's alimetry, it grew from the tips of

02:42:47.180 --> 02:42:54.780
its branches. The procession never stopped. Rorschach was insatiable. It was a strange

02:42:54.780 --> 02:42:59.660
attractor in the interstellar gulf, the paths along which the rocks fell were precisely and utterly

02:42:59.660 --> 02:43:08.300
chaotic. It was as though some Keplerian black belt had set up the whole system like an astronomical

02:43:08.300 --> 02:43:12.380
wind-up toy, kicked everything into motion, and let inertia do the rest.

02:43:13.100 --> 02:43:16.780
Didn't think that was possible, Bates said. Spindle shrugged.

02:43:16.780 --> 02:43:19.980
Hey, chaotic trajectories are just as deterministic as any other kind.

02:43:20.620 --> 02:43:24.060
That doesn't mean you can even predict them, let along set them up like that.

02:43:24.860 --> 02:43:29.980
Luminous intel reflected off the major's bald head. You have to know the starting conditions

02:43:29.980 --> 02:43:37.020
of a million different variables to ten decimal places, literally. Yep. Vampires can't do that.

02:43:37.100 --> 02:43:41.340
Quantical computers can't do that. Spindle shrugged like a marionette.

02:43:42.300 --> 02:43:46.940
All the while the gang had been slipping in and out of character, dancing with some unseen partner

02:43:46.940 --> 02:43:51.260
that, despite their best efforts, told us little beyond endless permutations of,

02:43:51.260 --> 02:43:57.100
you really wouldn't like it here. Any interrogative it answered with another, yet somehow it left

02:43:57.100 --> 02:44:01.900
the sense of questions answered. Did you send the fireflies? Sasha asked.

02:44:02.700 --> 02:44:07.660
We send many things many places, Rorschach replied. What did their specs show?

02:44:08.780 --> 02:44:12.940
We do not know their specifications. The fireflies burned up over Earth.

02:44:13.660 --> 02:44:17.180
Then shouldn't you be looking there? When our kids fly, they're on their own.

02:44:18.140 --> 02:44:23.260
Sasha muted the channel. You know who we're talking to? Jesus of fucking Nazareth, that's who.

02:44:23.980 --> 02:44:26.860
Spindle looked at Bates. Bates shrugged, palms up.

02:44:27.500 --> 02:44:33.100
You didn't get it? Sasha shook her head. That last exchange was the informational equivalent of

02:44:33.100 --> 02:44:38.460
should we render taxes unto Caesar. Beat for beat. Thanks for casting us at the Pharisees,

02:44:38.460 --> 02:44:42.460
Spindle grumbled. Hey, if the Jew fits, Spindle rolled his eyes.

02:44:43.660 --> 02:44:49.500
That was when I first noticed it. A tiny imperfection in Sasha's topology, a fly speck of doubt marring

02:44:49.500 --> 02:44:55.900
one of her facets. We're not getting anywhere, she said. Let's try a side door. She winked out.

02:44:55.900 --> 02:45:01.980
Michelle reopened the outgoing line. These is to Rorschach, open to requests for information.

02:45:02.620 --> 02:45:05.820
Cultural exchange, Rorschach said. That works for me.

02:45:07.020 --> 02:45:12.460
Bates' brow furrowed. Is that wise? If it's not inclined to give information, maybe it would

02:45:12.460 --> 02:45:18.620
rather get some. We could learn a great deal from the kind of question it asks. But tell us about

02:45:18.620 --> 02:45:25.660
home, Rorschach said. Sasha resurfaced just long enough to say, relax, major. Nobody said we had

02:45:25.740 --> 02:45:30.940
to give it the right answers. The stain on the gang's topology had flickered when Michelle took

02:45:30.940 --> 02:45:36.940
over, but it hadn't disappeared. It grew slightly as Michelle described some hypothetical hometown

02:45:36.940 --> 02:45:43.260
in careful terms that mentioned no object smaller than a meter across. Consensus confirmed, my guess,

02:45:43.260 --> 02:45:48.380
the hypothetical limit of firefly eyesight. When Cruncher took a rare turn at the helm.

02:45:49.180 --> 02:45:54.540
We don't all of us have parents or cousins. Some never did. Some come from vats.

02:45:55.500 --> 02:46:02.860
I see. That's sad. Vats sound so dehumanizing. The stain darkened and spread across his surface

02:46:02.860 --> 02:46:10.300
like an oil slick. Takes too much on faith, Susan said a moment later. By the time Sasha had

02:46:10.300 --> 02:46:15.740
cycled back into Michelle, it was more than doubt, stronger than suspicion. It had become an insight,

02:46:15.740 --> 02:46:20.860
a dark little meme infecting each of the body's minds in turn. The gang was on the trail of

02:46:20.860 --> 02:46:28.860
something. They still weren't sure what. I was. Tell me more about your cousins, Rorschach sent.

02:46:29.820 --> 02:46:36.620
Our cousins lie about the family tree, Sasha replied. With nieces and nephews and neanderthals,

02:46:36.620 --> 02:46:40.700
we do not like annoying cousins. We'd like to know more about this tree.

02:46:41.500 --> 02:46:45.500
Sasha muted the channel and gave us a look that said could it be any more obvious?

02:46:46.060 --> 02:46:50.460
It couldn't have parsed that. There were three linguistic ambiguities in there. It just ignored

02:46:50.460 --> 02:46:56.140
them. Well, it asked for clarification, Bates pointed out. It asked a follow-up question,

02:46:56.140 --> 02:47:01.100
different thing entirely. Bates was still out of the loop. Spindle was starting to get it, though.

02:47:02.300 --> 02:47:07.980
Subtle motion drew my eye. Sonosty was back, floating above the bright topography on the table.

02:47:07.980 --> 02:47:12.700
The light show squirmed across his visor as he moved his head. I could feel his eyes behind it.

02:47:13.580 --> 02:47:20.140
And something else behind him. I couldn't tell what it was. I could point to nothing but

02:47:20.140 --> 02:47:26.220
a vague sense of something out of place, somewhere in the background. Something over on the far side

02:47:26.220 --> 02:47:33.100
of the drum wasn't quite right. No, that wasn't it. Something nearer. Something amiss somewhere

02:47:33.100 --> 02:47:38.220
along the drum's axis. But there was nothing there, nothing I could see, just the naked pipes and

02:47:38.220 --> 02:47:44.460
conduits of the spinal bundle, threading through empty space and... and suddenly whatever had

02:47:44.460 --> 02:47:50.060
been wrong was right again. That was what finally locked my focus, the evaporation of some anomaly.

02:47:50.140 --> 02:47:53.660
A reversion to normalcy that caught my eye like a flicker of motion.

02:47:54.780 --> 02:47:59.340
I could see the exact spot along the bundle where the change had occurred. There was nothing out of

02:47:59.340 --> 02:48:07.180
place that I could see now, but there had been. It was in my head, barely subliminal, an itch so

02:48:07.180 --> 02:48:13.340
close to the surface that I knew I could bring it back if I just concentrated. Sasha was talking to

02:48:13.340 --> 02:48:18.940
some alien artifact at the end of a laser beam. She was going on about familial relationships,

02:48:18.940 --> 02:48:24.700
both evolutionary and domestic. Neanderthal and Cro Magnin and Mother's Cousins twice removed.

02:48:25.420 --> 02:48:30.060
She'd been doing it for hours now, and she had hours yet to go, but right now her chatter was

02:48:30.060 --> 02:48:35.500
distracting me. I tried to block her out and concentrate on the half-perceived image teasing

02:48:35.500 --> 02:48:42.300
my memory. I'd seen something there just a moment ago. One of the conduits had... yes,

02:48:42.300 --> 02:48:46.860
too many joints on one of the pipes. Something that should have been straight and smooth but

02:48:46.860 --> 02:48:54.060
was somehow articulated instead. But not one of the pipes, I remembered. An extra pipe. An extra

02:48:54.060 --> 02:49:00.940
something anyway. Something bony. That was crazy. There was nothing there. We were half a light

02:49:00.940 --> 02:49:05.900
year from home talking to unseen aliens about family reunions and my eyes were playing tricks on me.

02:49:06.620 --> 02:49:08.860
Have to talk to Spindle about that if it happened again.

02:49:09.260 --> 02:49:17.740
A lull in the background chatter brought me back. Spindle had... stopped talking.

02:49:18.940 --> 02:49:25.340
Darkened facets hung around her like a thunder cloud. I pulled the last thing she said. We usually

02:49:25.340 --> 02:49:32.300
found our nephews with telescopes. They are as hard as hoblinites. More calculated ambiguity,

02:49:32.860 --> 02:49:37.980
and hoblinites wasn't even a word. Imminent decisions reflected in her eyes.

02:49:38.780 --> 02:49:43.260
Sasha was poised at the edge of a precipice, gauging the depth of dark waters below.

02:49:44.140 --> 02:49:47.180
You haven't mentioned your father at all, Rorschach remarked.

02:49:47.820 --> 02:49:53.500
That's true, Rorschach. Sasha had admitted softly, taking a breath and stepping forward.

02:49:54.380 --> 02:49:56.860
So why don't you just suck my big fat hairy dick?

02:49:57.580 --> 02:50:03.260
The drum fell instantly silent. Bates and Spindle stared open mouth.

02:50:03.820 --> 02:50:07.660
Sasha killed the channel and turned to face us, grinning so widely I thought the top of her

02:50:07.660 --> 02:50:15.260
head would fall off. Sasha, Bates breathed. Are you crazy? So what if I am? Doesn't matter that

02:50:15.260 --> 02:50:20.540
thing. It doesn't have a clue what I'm saying. What? It doesn't even have a clue. What it's saying

02:50:20.540 --> 02:50:27.020
back, she added. Wait a minute, you said—Susan said they weren't parrots, they knew the rules.

02:50:27.740 --> 02:50:33.260
And there Susan was, melting to the fore. I did, and they do, but pattern matching doesn't equal

02:50:33.260 --> 02:50:39.820
comprehension. Bates shook her head. You said whatever we're talking to, it's not even intelligent?

02:50:39.820 --> 02:50:44.300
Oh, it could be intelligent, certainly, but we're not talking to it in any meaningful sense.

02:50:44.940 --> 02:50:46.220
So what is it, voicemail?

02:50:47.100 --> 02:50:53.740
Actually, Spindle said slowly, I think they call it a Chinese room. About bloody time, I thought.

02:50:55.180 --> 02:51:01.420
I knew all about Chinese rooms. I was one. I didn't even keep it a secret. I told anyone who was

02:51:01.420 --> 02:51:08.140
interested enough to ask. In hindsight, sometimes that was a mistake. How can you possibly tell the

02:51:08.140 --> 02:51:11.900
rest of us what you're bleeding edges up to if you don't understand it yourself?

02:51:11.900 --> 02:51:16.140
Chelsea demanded back when things were good between us, before she got to know me.

02:51:17.020 --> 02:51:21.820
I shrugged. It's not my job to understand them. If I could, they wouldn't be very bleeding edge

02:51:21.820 --> 02:51:27.500
in the first place. I'm just, you know, a conduit. Yeah, but how can you translate something if you

02:51:27.500 --> 02:51:33.660
don't understand it? A common cry outside the field. People simply can't accept that patterns

02:51:33.660 --> 02:51:38.220
carry their own intelligence, quite apart from the semantic content that clings to their services,

02:51:38.300 --> 02:51:42.860
if you manipulate the topology correctly, that content just comes along for the ride.

02:51:43.660 --> 02:51:50.300
You ever hear of the Chinese room? I asked. She shook her head. Only vaguely. Really all, right?

02:51:50.300 --> 02:51:54.380
Hundred years at least. It's a fallacy, really. It's an argument that supposedly puts the lie

02:51:54.380 --> 02:51:59.820
deterring tests. You stick some guy in a closed room, sheets with strange squiggles come in through

02:51:59.820 --> 02:52:04.620
a slot in the wall. You've got access to this huge database of squiggles just like it, and a bunch

02:52:04.620 --> 02:52:11.260
of rules to tell him how to put those squiggles together. Grammar, Chelsea said, syntax. I nodded.

02:52:11.260 --> 02:52:15.580
The point is, though, he doesn't have any idea what the squiggles are or what information they

02:52:15.580 --> 02:52:20.540
contain. He only knows that when he encounters squiggle delta, he's supposed to extract the

02:52:20.540 --> 02:52:25.420
fifth and sixth squiggles from the file theta and put them back together with another squiggle from

02:52:25.420 --> 02:52:30.300
gamma. So he builds this response string, puts it on the sheet, slides it back out the slot and

02:52:30.300 --> 02:52:35.180
takes a nap until the next iteration. Repeat until the remains of the horse are well and thoroughly

02:52:35.180 --> 02:52:41.420
beaten. So he's carrying on a conversation, Chelsea said. In Chinese, I assume, or they would have

02:52:41.420 --> 02:52:47.660
called it the Spanish Inquisition. Exactly. Point being, you can use basic pattern matching algorithms

02:52:47.660 --> 02:52:52.860
to participate in a conversation without having any idea what you're saying. Depending on how

02:52:52.860 --> 02:52:57.660
good the rules are, you can pass a Turing test. You can be a wit and wreck on tour in a language

02:52:57.740 --> 02:53:04.540
you don't even speak. That's synthesis? Only the part that involves downscaling semiotic protocols

02:53:04.540 --> 02:53:09.420
and only in principle. And I'm actually getting my input in Cantonese and replying in German,

02:53:09.420 --> 02:53:14.620
because I'm more of a conduit than a conversant, but you get the idea. How do you keep all the

02:53:14.620 --> 02:53:19.500
rules and protocols straight? There must be millions of them. It's like anything else,

02:53:19.500 --> 02:53:23.740
once you learn the rules, you do it unconsciously, like riding a bike or pinging the new sphere.

02:53:24.300 --> 02:53:28.860
You don't actively think about the protocols at all, you just imagine how your targets behave.

02:53:30.620 --> 02:53:35.740
A subtle half-smile played at the corner of her mouth. But the argument's not really a fallacy,

02:53:35.740 --> 02:53:39.660
then is it? It's spot on. You really don't understand Cantonese or German.

02:53:40.540 --> 02:53:46.060
The system understands. The whole room, with all its parts. The guy who does the scribbling is just

02:53:46.060 --> 02:53:50.540
one component. You wouldn't expect a single neuron in your head to understand English, would you?

02:53:51.340 --> 02:53:56.140
Sometimes one's all I can spare, Chelsea shook her head. She wasn't going to let it go.

02:53:56.780 --> 02:54:01.500
I could see her sorting questions in order of priority. I could see them getting increasingly

02:54:01.500 --> 02:54:07.260
personal. To get back to the matter at hand, I said, preempting them all. You were going to show

02:54:07.260 --> 02:54:12.460
me how to do that thing with the fingers. A wicked grin swiped or wiped the questions off her face.

02:54:13.100 --> 02:54:21.260
Oh, that's right. It's risky getting involved. Too many confounds. Every tool in the shed goes

02:54:21.260 --> 02:54:26.300
dull and rusty the moment you get entangled with the system you're observing. Still serviceable

02:54:26.300 --> 02:54:30.700
in the pinch, though.

02:54:32.060 --> 02:54:40.300
It hides now, Sadasti said. It's vulnerable now. Now we go in. It wasn't news so much as review.

02:54:40.300 --> 02:54:45.260
We've been straight-lining towards Ben for days now, but perhaps the Chinese room hypothesis

02:54:45.260 --> 02:54:49.980
had strengthened his resolve. At any rate, with war shock and eclipse once more, we were prepared

02:54:49.980 --> 02:54:56.220
to take intrusiveness to the next level. Theseus was perpetually gravid, a generic probe incubated

02:54:56.220 --> 02:55:00.540
in her fabrication plant. Its development arrested just short of the birth of anticipation of

02:55:00.540 --> 02:55:05.900
unforeseen mission requirements. Sometime between briefings, the captain had brought it to

02:55:05.900 --> 02:55:11.900
part tuition, customized for close contact and groundwork. It burned down the well at high G

02:55:11.900 --> 02:55:17.020
a good 10 hours before war shock's next scheduled appearance, inserted itself into the rock string,

02:55:17.020 --> 02:55:21.820
and went to sleep. If our calculations were in order, it would not be smashed by some errant

02:55:21.820 --> 02:55:26.940
piece of debris before it woke up again. If all went well, an intelligence that had precisely

02:55:26.940 --> 02:55:33.100
orchestrated a cast of millions would not notice one extra dancer on the floor. If we were just

02:55:33.100 --> 02:55:38.060
plain lucky, the myriad high divers that happened to be a line of sight at the time were not programmed

02:55:38.060 --> 02:55:44.060
as tattletales. Acceptable risks. If we hadn't been up for them, we might as well have stayed home.

02:55:45.020 --> 02:55:50.540
And so we waited. Four optimized hybrids somewhere past the threshold of mere humanity,

02:55:50.540 --> 02:55:53.900
one extinct predator who'd opted to command us instead of eating us alive.

02:55:54.620 --> 02:55:59.660
We waited for war shock to come back around the bend. The probes fell smoothly around the well,

02:55:59.660 --> 02:56:05.180
an ambassador to the unwilling. Or if the gang was right, maybe just a backdoor artist set to

02:56:05.180 --> 02:56:11.260
a B&E and empty condo. Spindle had named it Jack in a Box after some antique child's toy that

02:56:11.260 --> 02:56:16.620
didn't even rate a listing in consensus. We fell in its wake, nearly ballistic now. Momentum and

02:56:16.620 --> 02:56:20.940
inertia carefully pre-calculated to thread us through the chaotic minefield of Ben's accretion

02:56:20.940 --> 02:56:26.780
belt. Kepler couldn't do it all, though. Thesias grumbled briefly now and then, the intermittent

02:56:26.780 --> 02:56:31.260
firing of her attitude jets rumbling softly up the spine as the captain tweaked our descent into

02:56:31.260 --> 02:56:38.060
the maelstrom. No plan ever survives first contact with the enemy, I remembered. But I didn't know

02:56:38.060 --> 02:56:44.540
from where. Got it, Bates said. A speck appeared at Ben's edge. The display zoomed instantly to

02:56:44.540 --> 02:56:50.940
close up. Proximity boot. Roar shock remained invisible to Thesias, close as we were, close as

02:56:50.940 --> 02:56:55.980
we were to coming. But parallax stripped at least some of the scales in the probes' eyes.

02:56:55.980 --> 02:56:59.740
It woke to spikes and spirals of smoky glass flickering in and out of view.

02:57:00.540 --> 02:57:04.460
Ben's flat endless horizon sent me visible through the inter-reading translucent.

02:57:05.420 --> 02:57:08.700
The view trembled. Waveforms rippled across consensus.

02:57:09.420 --> 02:57:11.580
Quite the mechantic field, Spindle remarked.

02:57:12.140 --> 02:57:18.540
Breaking, Bates reported. Jack turned slowly retrograde and fired its torch. On tactical,

02:57:18.540 --> 02:57:22.940
Delta Veef swung to red. Sasha was driving the gang's body this shift.

02:57:23.500 --> 02:57:26.220
Incoming signal, she recorded. Same format.

02:57:26.220 --> 02:57:28.060
Sudosti clicked. Biped.

02:57:28.860 --> 02:57:30.380
Roar shocked Thesias.

02:57:30.380 --> 02:57:34.380
Hello again, Thesias. The voice was female this time and middle-aged.

02:57:35.020 --> 02:57:36.220
Sasha grinned.

02:57:36.220 --> 02:57:39.740
See? She's not offended at all. Big hairy dick, notwithstanding.

02:57:40.460 --> 02:57:42.380
Don't answer, Sudosti said.

02:57:43.260 --> 02:57:44.860
Burn complete, Bates supported.

02:57:45.500 --> 02:57:47.580
Coasting now, Jack sneezed.

02:57:48.140 --> 02:57:52.300
Silver chaff shot into the void towards the target. Millions of compass needles,

02:57:52.300 --> 02:57:57.820
brilliantly reflective, fast enough to make Thesias seem slow. They were gone in an instant.

02:57:57.820 --> 02:58:02.780
The probe watched them flee, swept laser eyes across every degree of arc, scanned its sky

02:58:02.780 --> 02:58:06.060
twice a second, and took careful note of each and every reflective flash.

02:58:07.100 --> 02:58:11.100
Only at first did those needles shoot anything along approaching a straight line.

02:58:11.100 --> 02:58:15.820
Then they swept abruptly into lorant spirals, twisting into sudden arcs and corkscrews,

02:58:15.820 --> 02:58:19.500
shot away along new and intricate trajectories bordering on the relativistic.

02:58:20.220 --> 02:58:23.900
The contours of Rorschach's magnetic field resolved in consensus,

02:58:23.900 --> 02:58:27.020
at first glance looking like nested layers of a glass onion.

02:58:27.740 --> 02:58:29.820
Sprawling, Spindle said.

02:58:31.180 --> 02:58:33.260
At second glance, the onion grew wormy.

02:58:34.140 --> 02:58:39.420
Invignations appeared, long snaking tunnels of energy proliferating fractally at every side.

02:58:40.060 --> 02:58:41.660
Roar shocked Thesias.

02:58:41.660 --> 02:58:43.020
Hello, Thesias. You there?

02:58:44.140 --> 02:58:49.260
A holographic inset beside the main display plotted the points of a triangle in flux.

02:58:49.260 --> 02:58:53.100
Thesias at the apex, Rorschach and Jack defining the narrow base.

02:58:53.980 --> 02:58:56.700
Rorschach to Thesias. I see you.

02:58:57.980 --> 02:59:00.460
She's got a more casual affect than he ever did.

02:59:01.100 --> 02:59:05.900
Sasha glanced up at Sotosti and did not add, you sure about this?

02:59:05.900 --> 02:59:07.580
She was starting to wonder herself, though.

02:59:08.220 --> 02:59:12.060
Starting to dwell on the potential consequences of being wrong now that we were committed.

02:59:12.860 --> 02:59:16.860
As far as sober second thought was concerned, it was too little, too late.

02:59:16.860 --> 02:59:18.540
But for Sasha, that was progress.

02:59:19.260 --> 02:59:21.340
Besides, it had been Sotosti's decision.

02:59:22.380 --> 02:59:25.340
Great hoops were resolving in Rorschach's magnetosphere.

02:59:25.900 --> 02:59:30.060
Invisible to human eyes, their outlines were vanishingly faint even on tactical.

02:59:30.060 --> 02:59:34.540
The chaff had scattered so thinly across the sky that even the captain was resorting to guesswork.

02:59:35.180 --> 02:59:40.380
The new macro structures hovered in the magnetosphere like the nested gimbals of some greater phantom gyroscope.

02:59:41.260 --> 02:59:44.220
I see you haven't changed your vector, Rorschach remarked.

02:59:44.780 --> 02:59:47.580
We really wouldn't advise continuing your approach.

02:59:47.580 --> 02:59:49.500
Seriously, for your own safety.

02:59:50.460 --> 02:59:51.500
Spindle shook his head.

02:59:52.140 --> 02:59:54.860
Hey, Mandy, Rorschach talking to Jack at all?

02:59:55.820 --> 02:59:57.500
If it is, I'm not seeing it.

02:59:57.500 --> 03:00:00.380
No incident lied, no direct DM of any kind.

03:00:00.380 --> 03:00:01.820
She smiled grimly.

03:00:01.820 --> 03:00:04.940
Seems to have snuck in under the radar and don't call me Mandy.

03:00:05.900 --> 03:00:07.420
Thesias groaned, twisting.

03:00:07.980 --> 03:00:11.180
I staggered in the low pseudograph, reaching out to steady myself.

03:00:11.740 --> 03:00:14.460
Course correction, baits replied, unplotted rock.

03:00:15.260 --> 03:00:17.660
Rorschach to Thesias, please respond.

03:00:17.660 --> 03:00:19.660
Your current heading is unacceptable.

03:00:19.660 --> 03:00:22.540
Repeat, your current heading is unacceptable.

03:00:22.540 --> 03:00:24.540
Strongly advise you change course.

03:00:25.900 --> 03:00:29.580
By now the probe coasted just a few kilometers off of Rorschach's leading edge.

03:00:30.140 --> 03:00:33.100
That close it served way more than magnetic fields.

03:00:33.100 --> 03:00:36.700
It presented Rorschach itself in bright tactical color codes.

03:00:36.700 --> 03:00:41.820
Invisible curves and spikes iridesced in consensus across any number of on-demand pigment schemes.

03:00:42.380 --> 03:00:47.420
Gravity, reflectivity, black body emissions, massive electrical bolts erupting from the

03:00:47.420 --> 03:00:50.220
tips of thorns rendered in lemon pastels.

03:00:50.220 --> 03:00:53.100
User-friendly graphics had turned Rorschach into a cartoon.

03:00:53.980 --> 03:00:56.220
Rorschach to Thesias, please respond.

03:00:57.260 --> 03:00:59.420
Thesias growled to stern fish-tailing.

03:00:59.420 --> 03:01:04.460
On tactical, another just-plotted piece of debris swept by a discreet 6000 meters to port.

03:01:05.100 --> 03:01:08.700
Rorschach to Thesias, if you are unable to respond, please...

03:01:08.700 --> 03:01:09.420
HOLY SHIT!

03:01:10.060 --> 03:01:12.700
The cartoon flickered and died.

03:01:13.820 --> 03:01:16.140
I'd seen what had happened in the last instant, though.

03:01:16.700 --> 03:01:19.340
Jack passing near one of those great phantom hoops.

03:01:19.340 --> 03:01:21.900
A tongue of energy flicking out, quick as a frog's.

03:01:21.900 --> 03:01:22.700
A dead feed.

03:01:23.420 --> 03:01:25.980
I see what you're up to now, you cocksuckers.

03:01:25.980 --> 03:01:27.820
Do you think we're fucking blind down here?

03:01:28.700 --> 03:01:30.380
Sasha clenched her teeth.

03:01:30.380 --> 03:01:32.540
We... no, Sotosti said.

03:01:33.180 --> 03:01:34.220
But it fit...

03:01:34.220 --> 03:01:37.500
Sotosti hissed from somewhere in the back of his throat.

03:01:38.060 --> 03:01:41.180
I had never heard a mammal make a noise quite like that before.

03:01:41.900 --> 03:01:43.500
Sasha fell immediately silent.

03:01:44.140 --> 03:01:46.220
Bates negotiated with her controls.

03:01:46.220 --> 03:01:47.980
I've still got... just a sec.

03:01:48.700 --> 03:01:51.820
You pull that thing back right fucking now, you hear us?

03:01:51.820 --> 03:01:52.860
Right fucking now!

03:01:53.580 --> 03:01:53.980
Got it.

03:01:54.540 --> 03:01:56.860
Bates gritted as the feed came back up.

03:01:56.860 --> 03:01:58.780
Just had to re-acquire the laser.

03:01:58.780 --> 03:02:01.100
The probe and bid kicked wildly off course,

03:02:01.100 --> 03:02:04.300
as if someone fording a river had been caught in sudden undertow

03:02:04.300 --> 03:02:05.820
and thrown over a waterfall.

03:02:05.900 --> 03:02:07.660
But it was still talking and still mobile.

03:02:08.540 --> 03:02:09.020
Barely.

03:02:09.660 --> 03:02:11.500
Bates struggled to stay the course.

03:02:12.060 --> 03:02:14.140
Jack staggered and wobbled uncontrollably

03:02:14.140 --> 03:02:16.860
through the tightly wound folds of Rorschach's magnetosphere.

03:02:17.420 --> 03:02:19.820
The artifact loomed huge in its view.

03:02:19.820 --> 03:02:20.860
The feeds strobed.

03:02:21.580 --> 03:02:24.060
Maintain approach, Sotosti said calmly.

03:02:24.620 --> 03:02:26.860
Love to, Bates gritted, trying.

03:02:27.900 --> 03:02:30.220
Thiesi is skitted again, corkscrewing.

03:02:30.220 --> 03:02:33.900
I could have sworn I heard the bearings in the drum grind for a moment.

03:02:33.900 --> 03:02:35.900
Another rock sailed past on tactical.

03:02:36.860 --> 03:02:40.220
I thought you'd plotted those things, spindle grumbled.

03:02:40.220 --> 03:02:42.060
You want to start a war, Thiesius?

03:02:42.060 --> 03:02:43.180
Is that what you're trying to do?

03:02:43.900 --> 03:02:44.940
You think you're up for it?

03:02:45.900 --> 03:02:47.900
It doesn't attack, Sotosti said.

03:02:48.780 --> 03:02:50.060
Maybe it does.

03:02:50.060 --> 03:02:52.300
Bates kept her voice low.

03:02:52.300 --> 03:02:54.060
I could see the effort it took.

03:02:54.060 --> 03:02:56.380
If Rorschach can control the trajectory of these,

03:02:57.020 --> 03:02:59.580
normal distribution, insignificant corrections,

03:03:00.300 --> 03:03:01.980
he must have meant statistically.

03:03:01.980 --> 03:03:05.420
The torque and grind of the ship's hull felt pretty significant to the others.

03:03:06.060 --> 03:03:08.220
Oh, right, Rorschach said suddenly.

03:03:08.780 --> 03:03:09.980
We get it now.

03:03:09.980 --> 03:03:12.220
You don't think there's anyone here, do you?

03:03:12.220 --> 03:03:15.820
You've got some high-priced consultant telling you there's nothing to worry about.

03:03:16.860 --> 03:03:18.700
Jack was deep in the forest.

03:03:18.700 --> 03:03:21.660
We'd lost most of the tactical overlays to reduced bod.

03:03:22.220 --> 03:03:25.020
In dim visible light, Rorschach's great ridged spines,

03:03:25.020 --> 03:03:28.860
each the size of a skyscraper, hash'd a night-veer view on all sides.

03:03:29.500 --> 03:03:32.940
The feed stuttered as Bates struggled to keep the beam aligned.

03:03:32.940 --> 03:03:36.060
Consensus painted walls and airspace with arcane telemetry.

03:03:36.700 --> 03:03:38.700
I had no idea what any of it meant.

03:03:39.500 --> 03:03:42.780
You think we're nothing but a Chinese room, Rorschach sneered.

03:03:43.580 --> 03:03:46.780
Jack stumbled towards collision, grasping for something to hang onto.

03:03:47.340 --> 03:03:48.700
Your mistake, Theseus.

03:03:49.500 --> 03:03:50.300
It hit something.

03:03:50.860 --> 03:03:51.500
It stuck.

03:03:52.460 --> 03:03:55.180
And suddenly Rorschach snapped into view.

03:03:55.180 --> 03:03:57.180
No refractory composites.

03:03:57.180 --> 03:03:59.580
No profiles or simulations in false color.

03:04:00.220 --> 03:04:02.540
There it was at last, naked even to human eyes.

03:04:03.740 --> 03:04:08.460
Imagine a crown of thorns, twisted, dark and unreflective,

03:04:08.460 --> 03:04:11.340
grown too thickly tangled to ever rest on any human head.

03:04:12.300 --> 03:04:15.660
Put in orbit around a failed star whose own reflected half-light

03:04:15.660 --> 03:04:18.220
does little more than throw in satellites into silhouette.

03:04:19.420 --> 03:04:23.980
Occasional bloody highlights glinted like dim embers from its twists and crannies.

03:04:23.980 --> 03:04:26.140
They only emphasize the darkness everywhere else.

03:04:27.580 --> 03:04:31.260
Imagine an artifact that embodies the very notion of torture.

03:04:31.820 --> 03:04:35.980
Something so wrenched and disfigured that even across uncounted light years

03:04:35.980 --> 03:04:38.940
and unimaginable differences in biology and outlook,

03:04:38.940 --> 03:04:42.300
you can't help feel that somehow the structure itself is in pain.

03:04:43.180 --> 03:04:44.700
Now make it the size of a city.

03:04:45.580 --> 03:04:47.420
It flickered as we watched.

03:04:47.420 --> 03:04:50.620
Lightning arced from recursed spines a thousand meters long.

03:04:51.260 --> 03:04:55.260
Consensus showed us a strobe-lit hellscape, huge and dark and twisted.

03:04:55.980 --> 03:04:57.260
The composites had lied.

03:04:57.980 --> 03:04:59.500
It was not the least bit beautiful.

03:05:00.620 --> 03:05:03.820
Now it's too late, said something from deep inside.

03:05:04.460 --> 03:05:06.460
Now every last one of you is dead.

03:05:07.100 --> 03:05:09.260
And Susan, you there Susan?

03:05:10.060 --> 03:05:11.260
We're taking you first.

03:05:15.260 --> 03:05:18.140
Life's too short for chess, Byron.

03:05:19.660 --> 03:05:21.580
They never sealed the hatch behind them.

03:05:22.140 --> 03:05:24.540
It was too easy to get lost up there in the dome.

03:05:25.020 --> 03:05:28.620
Naked infinite space stretching 180 degrees on every axis.

03:05:29.420 --> 03:05:32.940
They needed all that emptiness, but they needed an anchor in its midst.

03:05:33.660 --> 03:05:35.660
Soft stray light from a stern.

03:05:35.660 --> 03:05:37.100
A gentle draft from the drum.

03:05:37.660 --> 03:05:39.980
The sounds of people and machinery close by.

03:05:40.700 --> 03:05:42.300
They needed to have it both ways.

03:05:43.580 --> 03:05:44.380
I lay in wait.

03:05:45.260 --> 03:05:47.580
Reading a dozen blatant cues in their behavior,

03:05:47.580 --> 03:05:50.620
I was already squirreled away in the forward airlock when they passed.

03:05:51.420 --> 03:05:54.300
I gave them a few minutes and crept forward to the darkened bridge.

03:05:55.340 --> 03:05:57.660
Of course they called her by name, Spindle was saying.

03:05:58.220 --> 03:06:01.020
That was the only name they had, and she told them, remember?

03:06:01.980 --> 03:06:02.220
Yes.

03:06:03.180 --> 03:06:05.020
Some Michelle didn't seem reassured.

03:06:05.660 --> 03:06:08.860
Hey, it was you guys said we were talking to a Chinese room.

03:06:08.860 --> 03:06:09.980
You saying you were wrong?

03:06:10.780 --> 03:06:12.700
We... no, of course not.

03:06:13.660 --> 03:06:16.620
Then it wasn't really threatening, Susan, was it?

03:06:16.620 --> 03:06:18.140
It wasn't threatening any of us.

03:06:18.140 --> 03:06:19.580
It had no idea what it was saying.

03:06:20.380 --> 03:06:21.980
It's rule-based, Isaac.

03:06:22.460 --> 03:06:26.860
It was following some kind of flowchart it drew up by observing human languages in action,

03:06:27.420 --> 03:06:30.780
and somehow those rules told it to respond with threats of violence.

03:06:32.060 --> 03:06:35.580
But if it doesn't even know what it's saying, it doesn't.

03:06:35.580 --> 03:06:36.460
It can't.

03:06:36.460 --> 03:06:39.180
We parsed the phrasing 19 different ways,

03:06:39.180 --> 03:06:41.580
tried out conceptual units of every different length.

03:06:42.540 --> 03:06:44.060
A long, deep breath.

03:06:45.100 --> 03:06:47.340
But it attacked the probe, Isaac.

03:06:48.620 --> 03:06:51.740
Jack just got too close to one of those electrode thingies is all.

03:06:51.980 --> 03:06:52.620
It just arched.

03:06:53.340 --> 03:06:55.260
So you don't think Rorschach is hostile?

03:06:56.780 --> 03:06:57.580
Long silence.

03:06:58.300 --> 03:07:00.380
Long enough to make me wonder if I'd been detected.

03:07:01.260 --> 03:07:03.660
Hostile, Spindle said at last.

03:07:03.660 --> 03:07:04.220
Friendly.

03:07:05.020 --> 03:07:07.180
We learn those words for life on Earth, eh?

03:07:07.740 --> 03:07:09.420
I don't know if they even apply out here.

03:07:10.220 --> 03:07:11.660
Is left smacked faintly.

03:07:12.460 --> 03:07:14.940
But I think it might be something like hostile.

03:07:15.900 --> 03:07:16.860
Michelle sighed.

03:07:17.580 --> 03:07:19.580
Isaac, there's no reason for...

03:07:19.580 --> 03:07:22.380
I mean, it just doesn't make sense that it would be.

03:07:22.380 --> 03:07:23.900
We can't have anything at once.

03:07:25.100 --> 03:07:27.900
It says it wants to be left alone, Spindle said.

03:07:28.620 --> 03:07:29.740
Even if it doesn't mean it.

03:07:32.300 --> 03:07:34.460
They floated quietly for a while.

03:07:34.460 --> 03:07:35.740
Up there past the bulkhead.

03:07:37.020 --> 03:07:39.580
At least the shielding held, Spindle said finally.

03:07:39.580 --> 03:07:40.220
That's something.

03:07:41.260 --> 03:07:43.340
He wasn't just talking about Jack.

03:07:43.340 --> 03:07:45.740
Our own carapace was coated with the same stuff now.

03:07:46.140 --> 03:07:49.500
It had depleted our substrate stockpiles by two-thirds,

03:07:49.500 --> 03:07:52.060
but no one wanted to rely on the ship's usual magnetics

03:07:52.060 --> 03:07:54.780
in the face of anything that could play so easily

03:07:54.780 --> 03:07:56.460
with the electromagnetic spectrum.

03:07:57.100 --> 03:07:59.020
If they attack us, what do we do?

03:07:59.020 --> 03:08:00.060
Michelle said.

03:08:00.860 --> 03:08:02.460
Learn what we can while we can.

03:08:02.940 --> 03:08:04.780
Fight back while we can.

03:08:05.420 --> 03:08:07.740
If we can, look out there, Isaac.

03:08:07.740 --> 03:08:09.980
I don't care how embryonic that thing is.

03:08:10.860 --> 03:08:13.020
Tell me we're not hopelessly outmatched.

03:08:13.580 --> 03:08:15.020
Outmatched for sure.

03:08:15.020 --> 03:08:16.540
Hopelessly. Never.

03:08:17.420 --> 03:08:18.940
That's not what you said before.

03:08:19.580 --> 03:08:21.420
Still, there's always a way to win.

03:08:22.460 --> 03:08:24.700
If I said that, you'd call it wishful thinking.

03:08:25.340 --> 03:08:26.860
If you said that, it would be.

03:08:26.860 --> 03:08:28.940
But I'm saying it, so it's game theory.

03:08:29.660 --> 03:08:30.940
Game theory again.

03:08:30.940 --> 03:08:31.900
Jesus, Isaac.

03:08:32.460 --> 03:08:33.260
No, listen.

03:08:33.260 --> 03:08:34.700
You're thinking about the aliens

03:08:34.700 --> 03:08:36.540
like they were some kind of mammal.

03:08:36.540 --> 03:08:37.660
Something that cares.

03:08:37.660 --> 03:08:39.580
Something that looks after its investments.

03:08:39.660 --> 03:08:41.180
How do you know they aren't?

03:08:42.140 --> 03:08:43.820
Because you can't protect your kids

03:08:43.820 --> 03:08:45.340
when they're light years away.

03:08:45.340 --> 03:08:46.700
They're on their own,

03:08:46.700 --> 03:08:48.540
and it's a big, cold, dangerous universe,

03:08:48.540 --> 03:08:50.780
so most of them aren't going to make it, eh?

03:08:51.100 --> 03:08:53.740
The most you can do is crank out millions of kids,

03:08:53.740 --> 03:08:55.980
take comfort in knowing that a few always luck out

03:08:55.980 --> 03:08:57.180
through random chance.

03:08:57.500 --> 03:08:59.180
It's not mammal mindset, Mish.

03:08:59.660 --> 03:09:00.860
You want an earthbound simile?

03:09:00.860 --> 03:09:02.380
Think of dandelion seeds.

03:09:02.380 --> 03:09:03.580
Or herring.

03:09:04.460 --> 03:09:05.580
A soft sigh.

03:09:05.980 --> 03:09:07.740
So, they're interstellar herring.

03:09:08.380 --> 03:09:10.540
That hardly means they can't crush us.

03:09:11.340 --> 03:09:13.820
But they don't know about us, not in advance.

03:09:14.540 --> 03:09:16.620
Dandelion seed doesn't know what it's up against

03:09:16.620 --> 03:09:17.420
before it sprouts.

03:09:17.980 --> 03:09:18.860
Maybe nothing.

03:09:18.860 --> 03:09:22.380
Maybe some spastic weed that goes over like straw in the wind.

03:09:22.780 --> 03:09:24.380
Or maybe something that kicks its ass

03:09:24.380 --> 03:09:26.140
halfway to the Magellanic clouds.

03:09:26.860 --> 03:09:27.900
It doesn't know,

03:09:27.900 --> 03:09:31.500
and there's no such thing as a one size fits all survival strategy.

03:09:32.300 --> 03:09:33.900
Something that aces against one player

03:09:33.900 --> 03:09:35.740
blows goats against a different one.

03:09:36.860 --> 03:09:39.020
So the best you can do is mix up your strategies

03:09:39.020 --> 03:09:39.980
based on the odds.

03:09:40.620 --> 03:09:41.660
It's a weighted dice roll,

03:09:41.660 --> 03:09:44.540
and it gives you the best mean payoff over the whole game.

03:09:44.540 --> 03:09:45.820
But you're bound to crap out

03:09:45.820 --> 03:09:48.220
and choose the wrong strategy at least some of the time.

03:09:48.220 --> 03:09:49.340
Price of doing business.

03:09:50.140 --> 03:09:51.340
And that means...

03:09:51.740 --> 03:09:52.780
THAT means...

03:09:53.500 --> 03:09:56.380
that weak players not only can win against stronger ones,

03:09:56.380 --> 03:09:59.260
but they're statistically bound to win against stronger ones.

03:10:00.060 --> 03:10:02.620
But they're statistically bound to in some cases.

03:10:03.660 --> 03:10:04.620
Michelle Snorted.

03:10:05.180 --> 03:10:06.860
That's your game theory?

03:10:06.860 --> 03:10:08.700
Rock, paper, scissors with statistics?

03:10:09.900 --> 03:10:12.060
Manebeek Spindle didn't know the reference.

03:10:12.060 --> 03:10:12.860
He didn't speak.

03:10:13.420 --> 03:10:14.940
Long enough to call out a subtitle.

03:10:15.580 --> 03:10:17.260
Then he braided like a horse.

03:10:17.260 --> 03:10:18.940
Rock, paper, scissors, yes!

03:10:20.540 --> 03:10:23.100
Michelle digested that for a moment.

03:10:23.980 --> 03:10:25.180
You're sweet for trying,

03:10:25.180 --> 03:10:28.780
but that only works if the other side is just blindly playing the odds,

03:10:28.780 --> 03:10:30.380
and they don't have to do that

03:10:30.380 --> 03:10:32.700
if they know who they're going up against in advance.

03:10:33.340 --> 03:10:37.500
And my dear, they have so very much information about us.

03:10:38.780 --> 03:10:39.900
They threaten Susan.

03:10:40.700 --> 03:10:41.260
By name.

03:10:42.700 --> 03:10:45.100
They don't know everything, Spindle insisted.

03:10:45.100 --> 03:10:47.180
And the principle works for any scenario

03:10:47.180 --> 03:10:48.780
involving incomplete information,

03:10:48.780 --> 03:10:50.300
not just the ignorant extreme.

03:10:51.260 --> 03:10:51.980
Not as well.

03:10:52.780 --> 03:10:54.780
But some, and that gives us a chance.

03:10:54.780 --> 03:10:57.980
Doesn't matter how good you are at poker when it comes to the D.I.A.

03:10:58.060 --> 03:10:59.820
Cards still deal out with the same odds.

03:11:00.620 --> 03:11:02.380
So that's what we're playing, poker.

03:11:03.180 --> 03:11:04.620
Be thankful it's not chess.

03:11:04.620 --> 03:11:05.820
We wouldn't have a hope in hell.

03:11:06.540 --> 03:11:09.500
Hey, I'm supposed to be the optimist in this relationship.

03:11:10.300 --> 03:11:10.780
You are.

03:11:11.420 --> 03:11:13.180
I'm just fatalistically cheerful.

03:11:13.740 --> 03:11:16.140
We all come into the story halfway through.

03:11:16.140 --> 03:11:17.820
We all catch up as best we can,

03:11:17.820 --> 03:11:19.500
and we're all going to die before it ends.

03:11:20.380 --> 03:11:23.020
That's my Isaac, master of the no-win scenario.

03:11:23.660 --> 03:11:24.700
You can win.

03:11:24.700 --> 03:11:27.580
Winner's the guy who makes the best guess on how it all comes out.

03:11:28.300 --> 03:11:29.900
So you ARE just guessing.

03:11:30.540 --> 03:11:31.260
Yep.

03:11:31.260 --> 03:11:33.660
And you can't make an informed guess without D.I.A., eh?

03:11:34.220 --> 03:11:36.220
And we could be the very first to find out

03:11:36.220 --> 03:11:38.060
what's going to happen to the whole human race.

03:11:38.700 --> 03:11:41.020
I'd say that puts us into the semifinals easy.

03:11:41.980 --> 03:11:43.980
Michelle didn't answer for a long time.

03:11:44.700 --> 03:11:46.860
When she did, I couldn't hear her words.

03:11:47.580 --> 03:11:48.540
Neither could Spindle.

03:11:49.260 --> 03:11:49.660
Sorry?

03:11:50.460 --> 03:11:53.100
Covert to invulnerable, you said, remember?

03:11:53.740 --> 03:11:54.380
Uh-huh.

03:11:54.380 --> 03:11:55.900
Rorschach's graduation day.

03:11:56.700 --> 03:11:57.660
How soon, you think?

03:11:58.700 --> 03:12:02.700
No idea, but I don't think it's the kind of thing that's going to slip by unnoticed,

03:12:02.700 --> 03:12:04.460
and that's why I don't think it attacked us.

03:12:05.340 --> 03:12:06.540
She must have looked a question.

03:12:07.420 --> 03:12:10.060
Because when it does, it won't be some debatable,

03:12:10.060 --> 03:12:12.700
candy-ass bitch-slap, he told her.

03:12:12.700 --> 03:12:14.700
When that fucker rises up, we're going to know.

03:12:15.820 --> 03:12:17.340
A sudden flicker from behind.

03:12:18.220 --> 03:12:20.940
I spun in the cramped passageway and bit down on a cry.

03:12:21.740 --> 03:12:24.380
Something squirmed out of sight right around a corner.

03:12:24.380 --> 03:12:25.900
Something with arms.

03:12:25.900 --> 03:12:27.180
Barely glimpsed.

03:12:27.180 --> 03:12:28.140
Gone in an instant.

03:12:29.100 --> 03:12:29.740
Never there.

03:12:30.300 --> 03:12:31.100
Couldn't be there.

03:12:31.740 --> 03:12:32.380
Impossible.

03:12:33.500 --> 03:12:34.540
Did you hear that?

03:12:34.540 --> 03:12:35.420
Spindle asked.

03:12:36.300 --> 03:12:38.700
But I'd fled to Stern before Michelle could answer him.

03:12:43.340 --> 03:12:46.780
We'd fallen so far that the naked eye didn't see a disc.

03:12:46.780 --> 03:12:48.540
Barely even saw curvature anymore.

03:12:49.340 --> 03:12:51.340
We were falling towards a wall.

03:12:51.340 --> 03:12:53.420
A vast, roiling expanse of dark,

03:12:53.500 --> 03:12:56.780
thunder-clouds that extended in all directions to some new,

03:12:56.780 --> 03:12:58.300
infinitely distant horizon.

03:12:59.180 --> 03:13:02.060
Ben filled half the universe, and still we fell.

03:13:03.260 --> 03:13:07.020
Far below, Jack clung to Rorschach's ridged surface with

03:13:07.020 --> 03:13:09.260
bristly gecko-feet fenders and set up camp.

03:13:09.900 --> 03:13:12.940
It sent X-rays and ultrasound into the ground, tapped

03:13:12.940 --> 03:13:16.220
inquiring fingers and listened to the echoes, planted tiny

03:13:16.220 --> 03:13:19.180
explosive charges and measured the resonance of their detonations.

03:13:19.980 --> 03:13:23.180
It shed seeds like pollen, tiny probes and sensors

03:13:23.180 --> 03:13:26.940
by the thousands, self-powered, nearsighted, stupid and expendable.

03:13:27.660 --> 03:13:30.940
The vast majority were sacrificial offerings to random chance.

03:13:31.500 --> 03:13:34.940
Only one in a hundred lasted long enough to return usable telemetry.

03:13:36.060 --> 03:13:38.860
While our advanced scout took measure of its local neighborhood,

03:13:38.860 --> 03:13:42.140
thesius drew larger-scale bird's-eye maps in the closing sky.

03:13:42.860 --> 03:13:45.740
It spat out thousands of its own disposable probes,

03:13:45.740 --> 03:13:48.940
spread them across the heavens and collected stereoscopic data from

03:13:48.940 --> 03:13:50.780
a thousand simultaneous perspectives.

03:13:51.500 --> 03:13:54.620
Pachwork insights assembled in the drum.

03:13:55.580 --> 03:13:59.100
Rorschach's skin was 60% superconducting carbon nanotube.

03:13:59.900 --> 03:14:01.980
Rorschach's guts were largely hollow.

03:14:02.540 --> 03:14:05.340
At least some of these hollows appeared to contain an atmosphere.

03:14:06.140 --> 03:14:08.860
No earthly life would have lasted a second in there, though.

03:14:09.420 --> 03:14:12.220
Intricate topographies of radiation and electromagnetic

03:14:12.220 --> 03:14:14.860
force seethe around the surface, seethe within it.

03:14:15.580 --> 03:14:18.380
In some places, the radiation was intense enough to turn

03:14:18.380 --> 03:14:20.380
unshielded flesh to ash in an instant.

03:14:20.940 --> 03:14:23.980
Calmer backwaters would merely kill in the same span of time.

03:14:24.780 --> 03:14:28.940
Charged particles raced around invisible race tracks at relativistic speeds,

03:14:28.940 --> 03:14:34.220
erupting from jagged openings, hugging curves of magnetic force strong enough for neutron stars,

03:14:34.220 --> 03:14:37.580
arcing through open space and plunging back into black mass.

03:14:40.060 --> 03:14:45.420
Occasional protuberances swelled and burst and released clouds of microparticulates,

03:14:45.420 --> 03:14:47.420
seeding the radiation belts like spores.

03:14:48.300 --> 03:14:53.660
Rorschach resembled nothing so much as a nest of half-naked cyclotrons, tangled with each other.

03:14:55.100 --> 03:14:59.340
Neither Jack below nor Thesias above could find any points of entry.

03:14:59.340 --> 03:15:03.020
Beyond these impossible gaps that spat out streams of charged particles,

03:15:03.020 --> 03:15:08.460
just swallowed them back down, no airlocks or hatches or viewports resolved with increasing

03:15:08.460 --> 03:15:13.980
proximity. The fact that we'd been threatened by a laser beam implied some kind of optical

03:15:13.980 --> 03:15:17.900
antennae or tight-cast array, we weren't even able to find that much.

03:15:18.940 --> 03:15:22.380
A central hallmark of von Neumann machines was self-replication.

03:15:23.340 --> 03:15:27.580
Whether Rorschach would meet that criterion, whether it would germinate or divide or give

03:15:27.580 --> 03:15:32.860
birth when it passed some critical threshold, whether it had done so already, remained an open

03:15:32.860 --> 03:15:39.260
question. One of a thousand. At the end of it all, after all the measurements, the theorizing

03:15:39.260 --> 03:15:44.460
and deduction and outright guesswork, we settled into orbit with a million trivial details and no

03:15:44.460 --> 03:15:50.060
answers. In terms of the big questions, there was only one thing we knew for sure. So far,

03:15:50.060 --> 03:15:51.660
Rorschach was holding its fire.

03:15:53.580 --> 03:15:56.620
It sounded to me like it knew what it was saying, I remarked.

03:15:57.500 --> 03:16:02.860
I guess that's the whole point, Bates said. She had no one to confide in, partook of no

03:16:02.860 --> 03:16:08.220
intimate dialogues that could be overheard. With her I used the direct approach. Thesias

03:16:08.380 --> 03:16:14.220
was birthing a litter, two by two. They were nasty-looking things, armored, squashed egg shapes,

03:16:14.220 --> 03:16:19.500
twice the size of a human torso, and studded with gardening implements, antennae, optical ports,

03:16:19.500 --> 03:16:27.660
retractable thread saws, weapons muzzles. Bates was summoning her troops. We floated before

03:16:27.660 --> 03:16:32.940
the primary fab port at the base of Thesias' spine. The plant could just as easily have

03:16:32.940 --> 03:16:37.100
disgorged the grunts directly into the hold beneath the carapace. That was where they'd be stored

03:16:37.100 --> 03:16:42.220
anyway until called upon. But Bates was giving each a visual inspection before sending it through

03:16:42.220 --> 03:16:49.020
one of the airlocks a few meters up the passageway. Ritual, perhaps. Military tradition. Certainly,

03:16:49.020 --> 03:16:53.100
there was nothing she could see with her eyes that wouldn't be glaringly obvious to the most basic

03:16:53.100 --> 03:17:00.460
diagnostic. Would it be a problem, I asked, running without your interface? Run themselves just fine.

03:17:00.460 --> 03:17:05.420
Response time actually improves without spamming the network. I'm more of a safety precaution.

03:17:05.420 --> 03:17:11.900
Thesias growled, giving us more attitude. The plating trembled a stern, another piece of local

03:17:11.900 --> 03:17:17.500
debris no longer in our path. We were angling towards an equatorial orbit just a few minuscule

03:17:17.500 --> 03:17:22.620
kilometers above the artifact. Insanely, the approach curved right through the accretion belt.

03:17:23.500 --> 03:17:28.860
It didn't bother the others. Like surviving high traffic in a high speed lane, Sasha had said,

03:17:28.860 --> 03:17:34.700
disdainful of my misgivings. Try creeping across on your roadkill. Gotta speed up, go with the flow.

03:17:35.740 --> 03:17:39.740
But the flow was turbulent. We hadn't gone five minutes without a course correction since

03:17:39.740 --> 03:17:46.860
Warshaw could stop talking to us. So do you buy it? I asked. Pattern matching, empty threats,

03:17:46.860 --> 03:17:53.980
nothing to worry about? Nobody's fired on us yet, she said. Meaning, not for a second.

03:17:54.940 --> 03:17:58.780
What's your take on Susan's argument? Different niches, no reason for conflict.

03:17:59.660 --> 03:18:02.540
Makes sense, I guess. Out of bullshit.

03:18:03.740 --> 03:18:07.020
Can you think of any reason why something with different needs would attack us?

03:18:07.980 --> 03:18:12.540
That depends, she said, on whether the fact that we are different is reason enough.

03:18:13.900 --> 03:18:19.260
I saw playground battlefields reflected in her topology. I remembered my own and wondered if

03:18:19.260 --> 03:18:25.740
there was another kind. Then again, that only proved the point. Humans didn't really fight over

03:18:25.740 --> 03:18:30.540
skin tone or ideology. Those were just handy cues or kin selection purposes.

03:18:31.260 --> 03:18:34.620
Ultimately, it always came down to bloodlines and limited resources.

03:18:35.900 --> 03:18:42.780
I think Isaac would say this is different. I guess. Bates sent one grunt humming off to the hold,

03:18:42.780 --> 03:18:46.060
two more emerged in formation, spine light glinting off their armor.

03:18:46.860 --> 03:18:51.660
How many of these are you making, anyway? We're breaking an entering series, not wise to leave

03:18:51.740 --> 03:18:56.380
our own house unguarded. I inspected her services as she inspected theirs.

03:18:57.100 --> 03:19:02.700
Doubt and resentment simmered just beneath. You're in a tough spot, her marked. We all are.

03:19:04.060 --> 03:19:07.580
But you're responsible for defending us against something we don't know anything about.

03:19:08.220 --> 03:19:09.260
We're only guessing that...

03:19:09.980 --> 03:19:15.980
Sadasti doesn't guess, Bates said. The man's in charge for a reason. Doesn't make much sense

03:19:15.980 --> 03:19:19.980
to question his orders, given we're all about a hundred IQ points short of understanding the

03:19:19.980 --> 03:19:26.300
answer, anyway. And yet he's got that whole predatory side nobody talks about, I remarked.

03:19:27.180 --> 03:19:31.900
It must be difficult for him, all that intellect coexisting with so much instinctive aggression.

03:19:32.620 --> 03:19:37.820
Make sure the right part wins. She wondered in that instant whether Sadasti might be listening in.

03:19:38.620 --> 03:19:43.100
She decided in the next that it didn't matter. Why should he care what the cattle thought as

03:19:43.100 --> 03:19:48.940
long as they did what they were told? All she said was, I thought you jargonauts weren't supposed

03:19:48.940 --> 03:19:55.260
to have opinions. That wasn't mine. Bates paused, returned to her inspection.

03:19:56.140 --> 03:20:02.620
You do know what I do, I said. Uh-huh. The first of the current pair passed muster and

03:20:02.620 --> 03:20:08.860
hummed up off the spine. She turned to the second. You simplify things, so the folks back home can

03:20:08.860 --> 03:20:15.100
understand what the specialists are up to. That's part of it. I don't need a translator, Ciri.

03:20:15.180 --> 03:20:19.180
I'm just a consultant assuming things go well. A bodyguard if they don't.

03:20:20.300 --> 03:20:24.940
You're an officer and a military expert. I'd say that makes you more qualified when it comes to

03:20:24.940 --> 03:20:31.180
assessing Warshawk's threat potential. I'm muscle. Shouldn't you be simplifying Yuka or Isaac?

03:20:31.740 --> 03:20:34.620
That's exactly what I'm doing. She looked at me.

03:20:35.580 --> 03:20:42.380
You interact, I said. Every component of the system affects every other. Processing Sadasti

03:20:42.380 --> 03:20:46.460
without factoring you in would be like trying to calculate acceleration while ignoring mass.

03:20:47.420 --> 03:20:51.020
She turned back to her brood. Another robot passed muster.

03:20:52.140 --> 03:20:56.540
She didn't hate me. What she hated was that what my presence implied.

03:20:57.500 --> 03:21:03.420
They don't trust us to speak for ourselves, she wouldn't say. No matter how qualified we are,

03:21:03.420 --> 03:21:10.060
no matter how far ahead of the pack, maybe even because of that, or contaminated, or subjective.

03:21:10.860 --> 03:21:13.660
So they send Ciri Keaton to tell them what we really mean.

03:21:15.100 --> 03:21:21.580
I get it, I said after a moment. Do you? It's not about trust, major. It's about location.

03:21:22.140 --> 03:21:26.300
Nobody gets a good view of a system from the inside no matter who they are. The view is distorted.

03:21:27.260 --> 03:21:32.540
And yours isn't. I'm outside the system. You're interacting with me now.

03:21:33.500 --> 03:21:38.300
As an observer only, perfection's unattainable, but it isn't unapproachable, you know?

03:21:39.020 --> 03:21:43.740
I don't play a role in decision making or research. I don't interfere in any aspect of the mission

03:21:43.740 --> 03:21:48.140
that I'm assigned to study. But of course I ask questions. The more information I have,

03:21:48.140 --> 03:21:53.740
the better my analysis. I thought you didn't have to ask. I thought you guys could just

03:21:53.740 --> 03:21:59.740
read the signs or something. Everybody helps. It all goes into the mix. You're doing it now,

03:21:59.740 --> 03:22:05.260
synthesizing? I nodded. And you do this without any specialized knowledge at all.

03:22:05.500 --> 03:22:12.060
I'm as much of a specialist as you. I specialize in processing informational topologies

03:22:13.100 --> 03:22:17.420
without understanding their content. Understanding the shapes is enough.

03:22:19.100 --> 03:22:23.420
Bates seemed to find some small imperfection in the battle bot under scrutiny,

03:22:23.420 --> 03:22:27.740
scratched a shell with a fingernail. Software couldn't do that without your help.

03:22:28.940 --> 03:22:34.700
Software can do a lot of things. We've chosen to do some for ourselves. I nodded at the grunt.

03:22:35.420 --> 03:22:39.980
Your visual inspections, for example. She smiled faintly, conceding the point.

03:22:40.860 --> 03:22:44.940
So I'd encourage you to speak freely. You know I'm sworn to confidentiality.

03:22:45.820 --> 03:22:50.220
Thanks, she said. Meaning, on this ship, there's no such thing.

03:22:51.660 --> 03:22:57.820
Thesias chimed. Sadasti spoke in its wake. Orbital insertion in 15 minutes. Everyone

03:22:57.820 --> 03:23:04.140
to the drum in five. Well, Bates said, sending one last grunt on its way. Here we go.

03:23:05.100 --> 03:23:09.740
She pushed off and sailed up the spine. The newborn killing machines clicked at me.

03:23:10.300 --> 03:23:11.660
They smelled like new cars.

03:23:12.780 --> 03:23:17.980
By the way, Bates called over her shoulder. You missed the obvious one. Sorry.

03:23:19.180 --> 03:23:24.300
She spun 180 degrees in the passageway, landed like an acrobat beside the drum hatch.

03:23:24.940 --> 03:23:29.660
The reason? Why, something would attack us even if we didn't have anything it wanted.

03:23:30.620 --> 03:23:36.460
I read it off her. If it wasn't attacking at all, if it was defending itself.

03:23:37.820 --> 03:23:43.820
You asked about Sadasti. Smart man, strong leader. Maybe you could spend a little bit more time with

03:23:43.820 --> 03:23:51.340
the troops. Vampire doesn't respect command. Doesn't listen to advice. Hides away half the time.

03:23:52.380 --> 03:23:59.100
I remember to transient killer whales. Maybe he's being considerate. He knows he makes us nervous.

03:24:00.060 --> 03:24:04.460
I'm sure that's it, Bates said. Vampire doesn't trust himself.

03:24:07.180 --> 03:24:12.380
It wasn't just Sadasti. They all hid from us, even when they had the upper hand.

03:24:13.020 --> 03:24:18.620
They always stayed just to the other side of myth. It started pretty much the same way it did for

03:24:18.620 --> 03:24:23.580
anything else. Vampires were far from the first to learn the virtues of energy conservation.

03:24:24.460 --> 03:24:29.180
Shrews and hummingbirds, saddled with tiny bodies and overclocked metabolic engines,

03:24:29.180 --> 03:24:33.020
would have starved to death overnight if not for the torpor that overtook them at sundown.

03:24:33.900 --> 03:24:39.020
Cometose elephant seals lurked at the bottom of the sea, rousing only for passing prey or red

03:24:39.020 --> 03:24:45.100
line lactate levels. Bears and chipmunks cut costs by sleeping away the impoverished winter months

03:24:45.100 --> 03:24:51.020
and lungfish, Devonian black belts in the art of estivation, could curl up and die for years waiting

03:24:51.020 --> 03:24:56.940
for the rains. With vampires it was a little different. It wasn't the shortness of breath

03:24:56.940 --> 03:25:01.500
or metabolic overdrive or some blanket of snow that locked the pantry every winter.

03:25:02.140 --> 03:25:07.980
The problem wasn't so much the lack of prey as the lack of difference from it. Vampires were

03:25:07.980 --> 03:25:13.020
such a recent split from the ancestral baseline that the reproductive rates hadn't diverged.

03:25:13.660 --> 03:25:18.700
There was no woodland variety, Link's hair dynamic, or prey outnumbered predators 101.

03:25:19.260 --> 03:25:22.220
Vampires fed on things that bred fairly faster than they did.

03:25:22.540 --> 03:25:28.220
They would have wiped out their own food supply in no time if they hadn't learned how to ease off

03:25:28.220 --> 03:25:33.740
the throttle. By the time they went extinct, they'd learned to shut down for decades.

03:25:35.100 --> 03:25:40.620
It made two kinds of sense. It not only slashed their metabolic needs while prey bred itself back

03:25:40.620 --> 03:25:46.380
to harvestable levels, it gave us time to forget that we were prey. You were so smart by the pleous

03:25:46.460 --> 03:25:52.380
cysteine, smart enough for easy skepticism. If you hadn't seen any night-stalking demons in

03:25:52.380 --> 03:25:57.500
all your years on the savannah, why would you believe some senile campfire ramblings passed down

03:25:57.500 --> 03:26:04.540
by your mother's mother? It was murder on our ancestors, even if those same enemy genes co-opted

03:26:04.540 --> 03:26:10.780
now served us so well when we left the sun a half million years later. But it was almost

03:26:10.780 --> 03:26:15.260
heartening, I guess, to think that maybe Sadasti felt the tug of other genes,

03:26:15.260 --> 03:26:19.260
some aversion to prolonged visibility shaped by generations of natural selection.

03:26:20.300 --> 03:26:24.780
Maybe he spent every moment in our company fighting voices that urged him to

03:26:24.780 --> 03:26:32.460
hide, hide, let them forget. Maybe he retreated when I got too loud. Maybe we made him as uneasy

03:26:32.460 --> 03:26:35.260
as he made us. We could always hope.

03:26:36.220 --> 03:26:47.580
Our final orbit combined discretion and valor in equal measure. Rorschach described a perfect

03:26:47.580 --> 03:26:54.860
equatorial circle 87,900 kilometers from Big Bend center of gravity. Sadasti was unwilling to let

03:26:54.860 --> 03:26:59.900
it out of sight, and you didn't have to be a vampire to mistrust relay sats when swinging the

03:26:59.900 --> 03:27:05.180
irradiation-soaked blizzard of rock and machinery. The obvious alternative was to match orbits.

03:27:06.140 --> 03:27:10.620
At the same time, all the debate over whether or not Rorschach had meant or even understood the

03:27:10.620 --> 03:27:15.260
threats it made was a bit beside the point. Counter intrusion measures were a distinct

03:27:15.260 --> 03:27:22.380
possibility either way. An ongoing proximity increased the risk. So Sadasti had derived some

03:27:22.380 --> 03:27:27.740
optimum compromise, a mildly eccentric orbit that nearly brushed the artifact at perigee,

03:27:27.740 --> 03:27:33.180
but kept a discrete distance the rest of the time. It was a longer trajectory than Rorschach's

03:27:33.180 --> 03:27:43.740
and higher. We had to burn on the descending arc to keep in sync, but the end result was continuously

03:27:43.740 --> 03:27:49.260
line of sight, and only brought us within striking distance for three hours of either side, bottoming

03:27:49.260 --> 03:27:55.660
out. Our striking distance, that is. For all we knew, Rorschach could have reached out and swatted

03:27:55.660 --> 03:28:01.340
us from the sky before we even left the solar system. Sadasti gave the command from his tent.

03:28:01.900 --> 03:28:06.620
A consensus carried his voice into the drum as thesius coasted to apogee. Now.

03:28:07.820 --> 03:28:13.500
Jack had erected a tent about itself. A blister glued to Rorschach's hull, and blown semi-tod

03:28:13.500 --> 03:28:19.260
against vacuum with the mere swift of nitrogen. Now it brought lasers to bear and started digging.

03:28:19.260 --> 03:28:24.460
If we read the vibrations right, the ground should only be 34 centimeters deep beneath its feet.

03:28:25.180 --> 03:28:29.020
The beams stuttered as they cut, despite six millimeters of dope shielding.

03:28:29.820 --> 03:28:32.380
Son of a bitch, spindle murmured. It's working.

03:28:33.580 --> 03:28:38.460
We burned through tough fibrous epidermis. We burned through veins of insulation that might

03:28:38.460 --> 03:28:43.900
have been some sort of programmable asbestos. We burned through alternating layers of super

03:28:43.900 --> 03:28:49.980
conducting mesh, and then strata of flaking carbon separating them. We burned through.

03:28:49.980 --> 03:28:57.500
The lasers shut down instantly. Within seconds, Rorschach's intestinal gases had blown taut the

03:28:57.500 --> 03:29:03.660
skin of the tent. Black carbon smoke swirled and danced in sudden thick atmosphere. Nothing shot

03:29:03.660 --> 03:29:11.260
back at us. Nothing reacted. Partial pressures piled up on consensus. Methane, ammonia, hydrogen,

03:29:11.820 --> 03:29:17.900
lots of water vapor freezing as fast as it registered. Spindle grunted. Reducing atmosphere.

03:29:18.540 --> 03:29:21.340
Pre-snowball. He sounded disappointed.

03:29:22.220 --> 03:29:25.820
Maybe it's a work in progress, James suggested, like the structure itself.

03:29:26.860 --> 03:29:32.860
Maybe. Jock stuck out its tongue, a giant mechanical sperm with a myo-optical tail.

03:29:33.580 --> 03:29:39.500
Its head was a thick-skinned lozenge, at least half ceramic shielding by cross-section. The tiny

03:29:39.500 --> 03:29:44.300
payload of sensors at its core was rudimentary, but small enough for the whole assembly to thread

03:29:44.300 --> 03:29:50.140
through the pencil-thin hole the laser had cut. It unspooled down the hole, rimming Rorschach's

03:29:50.140 --> 03:30:00.380
newly torn orifice. Dark down there, James observed. Bates, but warm. 281 degrees Kelvin, above freezing.

03:30:01.740 --> 03:30:07.660
The endoscope emerged in darkness. Infrared served up a great grainy gray scale of

03:30:08.460 --> 03:30:12.620
a tunnel it looked like, replete with mist and exotic rock formations.

03:30:13.340 --> 03:30:17.660
The walls curved up like a honeycomb, like the insides of a fossilized intestine.

03:30:18.460 --> 03:30:24.140
Cold as sacks and branches proliferated down the passage. The basic substrate appeared to be a dense

03:30:24.140 --> 03:30:29.980
pastry of carbon fiber leaves. Some of the gaps between those layers are barely as thick as fingernails.

03:30:30.540 --> 03:30:32.620
Others looked wide enough to stack bodies.

03:30:33.580 --> 03:30:37.740
Ladies and gentlemen, Spindle said softly, the Devil's baklava.

03:30:38.060 --> 03:30:45.740
I could have sworn I saw something move. I could have sworn it looked familiar. The camera died.

03:30:51.500 --> 03:30:52.220
Rorschach.

03:30:54.860 --> 03:30:59.660
Mothers are fonder than fathers of their children, because they are more certain they are their own.

03:31:00.940 --> 03:31:01.660
Aristotle.

03:31:08.700 --> 03:31:12.700
I couldn't say goodbye to dad. I didn't even know where he was.

03:31:13.660 --> 03:31:19.260
I didn't want to say goodbye to Helen. I didn't want to go back there. That was the problem. I

03:31:19.260 --> 03:31:23.980
didn't have to. There was nowhere left in the world where the mountain couldn't simply pick up and

03:31:23.980 --> 03:31:29.180
move to Muhammad. Heaven was merely a suburb of the global village, and the global village left

03:31:29.180 --> 03:31:35.660
me no excuse. I linked for my own apartment. My new inlays, mission-specific slid into my head

03:31:35.660 --> 03:31:40.380
just the week before, shook hands with the new sphere and knocked upon the pearly gates.

03:31:41.180 --> 03:31:46.300
Some tame spirit more plausible than St. Peter, if no less ethereal, took a message and disappeared.

03:31:47.100 --> 03:31:48.140
And I was inside.

03:31:49.980 --> 03:31:55.260
There was no antechamber, no visiting room. Heaven was not intended for the casual visitor.

03:31:56.060 --> 03:32:00.540
Any paradise in which the flesh constrained would feel at home would have been intolerably

03:32:00.540 --> 03:32:05.980
pedestrian to the disembodied souls who lived there. Of course, there was no reason why visitor

03:32:05.980 --> 03:32:11.420
and resident had to share the same view. I could have pulled any conventional world view off the

03:32:11.420 --> 03:32:17.180
shelf if I'd wanted, seeing this place rendered in any style I chose. Except for the ascended

03:32:17.180 --> 03:32:23.260
themselves, of course. That was one of the perks of the afterlife. Only they got to choose the face

03:32:23.260 --> 03:32:30.460
we saw. But the thing my mother had become had no face, and I was damned if she was going to see

03:32:30.460 --> 03:32:39.020
me hide behind some mask. Hello, Helen. Siri, what a wonderful surprise! She was an abstraction within

03:32:39.020 --> 03:32:45.020
an abstraction, an impossible intersection of dozens of bright pains, as if the disembezzled

03:32:45.020 --> 03:32:50.380
tiles of a stained glass window had each been set aglow and animated. She swirled before me like a

03:32:50.380 --> 03:32:56.620
school of fish. Her world echoed her body. Lights and angles and three-dimensional escher

03:32:56.620 --> 03:33:02.300
impossibilities piled like bright thunderheads. And yet somehow I would have recognized her anywhere.

03:33:03.100 --> 03:33:07.580
Heaven was a dream. Only upon waking do you realize the characters you encountered look

03:33:07.580 --> 03:33:12.860
nothing like they do in real life. There was only one familiar landmark anywhere in the whole

03:33:12.860 --> 03:33:19.500
sensorium. My mother's heaven smelled of cinnamon. I beheld her luminous avatar and imagined the

03:33:19.500 --> 03:33:25.180
corpus soaking in a tank of nutrient deep underground. How are you doing? Very well,

03:33:25.180 --> 03:33:30.380
very well. Of course, it takes a little getting used to knowing your mind isn't quite yours anymore.

03:33:31.420 --> 03:33:36.780
Heaven didn't just feed the brains of its residents. It fed off them. Used the surplus power of idle

03:33:36.780 --> 03:33:41.980
synapses to run its own infrastructure. You have to move in here sooner rather than later. You'll

03:33:41.980 --> 03:33:49.020
never leave. Actually, I am leaving, I said. We're shipping out tomorrow. Shipping out?

03:33:49.900 --> 03:33:56.140
The Kuiper. You know, the Fireflies? Oh yes, I think I heard something about that. We don't get

03:33:56.140 --> 03:34:01.340
much news from the outside world, you know. Anyway, just thought I'd call in and say goodbye.

03:34:02.140 --> 03:34:06.780
I'm glad you did. I've been hoping to see you without, you know, without what?

03:34:07.660 --> 03:34:13.820
You know, without your father listening in. Not again. Dad's in the field, Helen.

03:34:13.820 --> 03:34:18.780
In her planetary crisis. You might have heard something. I certainly have. You know,

03:34:18.780 --> 03:34:23.740
I haven't always been happy about your father's extended assignments, but maybe it was really

03:34:23.740 --> 03:34:31.100
a blessing in disguise. The less he was around, the less he could do. Do? To you. The apparations

03:34:31.100 --> 03:34:37.660
stilled for a few moments. Feigning hesitation. I've never told you this before, but no, I shouldn't.

03:34:38.620 --> 03:34:43.580
Shouldn't what? Bring up, well, old hurts. What old hurts?

03:34:44.460 --> 03:34:49.740
Right on cue. I couldn't help myself. The training went too deep. I always barked on command.

03:34:50.540 --> 03:34:56.380
Well, she began. Sometimes you'd come back. You were so very young, and your face would be so set

03:34:56.380 --> 03:35:02.300
and hard, and I'd wonder, why are you so angry, little boy? What can someone so young have to

03:35:02.300 --> 03:35:06.860
be so angry about? Helen, what are you talking about, back from where?

03:35:08.060 --> 03:35:13.020
Just from the places he'd take you. Something like a shiver passed across her facets.

03:35:13.820 --> 03:35:18.380
He was still around back then. He wasn't so important. He was just an accountant with a karate

03:35:18.380 --> 03:35:23.340
fetish. Going on about forensics and game theory and astronomy until he put everyone to sleep.

03:35:24.300 --> 03:35:29.100
I tried to imagine it. My father, the chatterbox. That doesn't sound like Dad.

03:35:29.900 --> 03:35:33.820
Well, of course not. You were too young to remember, but he was just a little man then.

03:35:33.820 --> 03:35:38.540
He still is, really, under all the secret missions and classified briefings. I've never

03:35:38.540 --> 03:35:44.700
understood why people saw that. But even back then he liked to, well, it wasn't his fault, I suppose.

03:35:45.260 --> 03:35:49.420
He had a very difficult childhood, and he never learned to deal with the problems like an adult.

03:35:50.140 --> 03:35:55.740
Well, he would throw his weight around, I guess you'd say. Of course, I didn't know that before

03:35:55.740 --> 03:36:01.900
we married. If I had, I... but I made a commitment. I made a commitment and I never broke it.

03:36:03.100 --> 03:36:07.340
What, are you saying you were abused? Back from the places he'd take you.

03:36:08.220 --> 03:36:14.220
Are you... are you saying I was? There are all kinds of abuse, Siri. Words can hurt more than

03:36:14.220 --> 03:36:20.620
bullets sometimes, and child abandonment. He didn't abandon me. He left me with you.

03:36:21.580 --> 03:36:27.660
He abandoned us, Siri. Sometimes for months at a time, and I... and we never knew if he was coming

03:36:27.660 --> 03:36:32.940
back, and he chose to do that to us, Siri. He didn't need that job. There were so many other

03:36:32.940 --> 03:36:38.220
things he was qualified to do. Things that had been redundant for years. I shook my head,

03:36:38.220 --> 03:36:43.900
incredulous, unable to say it aloud. She hated him because he hadn't had the good grace to grow

03:36:43.900 --> 03:36:50.140
unnecessary. It's not Dad's fault that planetary security is still an essential service, I said.

03:36:51.100 --> 03:36:55.580
She continued as if she hadn't heard. Now, there was a time when it was unavoidable,

03:36:55.580 --> 03:37:01.340
when people our age had to work just to make ends meet. But even back then, people wanted to spend

03:37:01.340 --> 03:37:07.500
time with their families. Even if they couldn't afford to. To choose to stay working when it

03:37:07.500 --> 03:37:14.140
isn't even necessary, that's... she shattered and reassembled at my shoulder. Yes, Siri, I believe

03:37:14.140 --> 03:37:19.740
that's a kind of abuse. And if your father had been as half as loyal to me as I've been to him

03:37:19.740 --> 03:37:25.980
all these years, I remember Jim, the last time I'd seen him, snorting Vasopressin under the

03:37:25.980 --> 03:37:31.100
restless eyes of robot sentries. I don't think Dad's been disloyal to either of us.

03:37:32.220 --> 03:37:38.060
Hell inside. I don't really expect you to understand. I'm not completely stupid. I've seen how it

03:37:38.060 --> 03:37:43.660
played out. I pretty much had to raise you myself all these years. I've always had to play the heavy,

03:37:43.660 --> 03:37:47.580
always had to be the one to hand out the discipline because your father was off on some

03:37:47.580 --> 03:37:52.380
secret assignment, and then he'd come home for a week or two and he was the golden-haired boy

03:37:52.380 --> 03:37:57.820
just because he'd seen fit to drop in. I don't really blame you for that anymore than I blame him.

03:37:57.820 --> 03:38:03.580
Blame doesn't solve anything at this stage. I just thought, well, really, I thought you ought to know.

03:38:03.580 --> 03:38:10.220
Take it for what it's worth. A memory, unbidden. Called into Helen's bed when I was nine,

03:38:10.220 --> 03:38:15.900
her hand stroking my scar, her stale, sweet breath stirring against my cheek. You're the man of the

03:38:15.900 --> 03:38:22.300
house now, Ciri. We can't count on your father anymore. It's just you and me. I didn't say anything

03:38:22.300 --> 03:38:29.980
for a while. Finally, didn't it help at all? What do you mean? I glanced around at all the

03:38:29.980 --> 03:38:35.740
customized abstraction. Internal feedback, lucidly dreamed. You're omnipotent in here.

03:38:35.740 --> 03:38:40.540
Desire anything? Imagine anything? There it is. I thought it would have changed you more.

03:38:41.500 --> 03:38:46.540
Rainbow tiles danced and forced to laugh. This isn't enough of a change for you?

03:38:47.580 --> 03:38:54.300
Not nearly. Because heaven had a catch. No matter how many constructs and avatars Helen built in

03:38:54.300 --> 03:38:59.420
there, no matter how many empty vessels sang her praises or commiserated over the injustices she'd

03:38:59.420 --> 03:39:05.100
suffered, when it came right down to it she was only talking to herself. There were other realities

03:39:05.100 --> 03:39:10.300
over which she had no control, other people who didn't play by her rules. And if they thought

03:39:10.300 --> 03:39:16.620
of Helen at all, they thought of, then they thought as they damn well pleased. She could go the rest

03:39:16.620 --> 03:39:22.060
of her life without ever meeting any of them, but she knew they were out there and it drove her crazy.

03:39:23.260 --> 03:39:27.180
Taking my leave of heaven, it occurred to me that unimpeted though she was,

03:39:27.180 --> 03:39:31.100
there was only one way my mother would ever be truly happy in her own personal creation.

03:39:31.900 --> 03:39:33.660
The rest of creation would have to go.

03:39:34.540 --> 03:39:41.500
This shouldn't keep happening, Bates said. The shielding was good.

03:39:42.540 --> 03:39:46.220
The gang was up across the drum, squaring away from something in their tent.

03:39:46.780 --> 03:39:50.380
Sadasti lurked off stage today, monitoring the proceedings from his quarters.

03:39:51.020 --> 03:39:53.260
That left me with Bates and Spindle in the commons.

03:39:54.140 --> 03:39:57.580
Maybe against Direct-EM, Spindle Stretch, Stifle Yon.

03:39:58.300 --> 03:40:02.620
Ultrasound boots up magnetic fields through shielding sometimes and living tissue at least.

03:40:03.340 --> 03:40:05.900
Any chance something like that could be happening with your electronics?

03:40:06.780 --> 03:40:11.260
Bates spread her hands. Who knows, might as well be black magic and elves down there.

03:40:12.060 --> 03:40:15.020
Well, it's not a total wash. We could make a few smart guesses, eh?

03:40:15.740 --> 03:40:21.580
Such as, Spindle raised one finger, the layers we cut through couldn't result from any metabolic

03:40:21.580 --> 03:40:27.660
process I know of. So it's not alive, not in the biological sense. Not that that means anything

03:40:27.660 --> 03:40:33.500
these days, he added, glancing around the belly of our beast. What about life inside the structure?

03:40:34.220 --> 03:40:39.580
Anoxic atmosphere probably rules out complex multicellular life. Microbe is maybe, although if

03:40:41.980 --> 03:40:47.660
so, I wish to hell they'd show it in the samples. But anything complex enough to think, let alone

03:40:47.660 --> 03:40:52.620
build something like that, a wave at the image in consensus, is going to need a high energy

03:40:53.340 --> 03:40:59.740
metabolism, and that means oxygen. So you think it's empty? Didn't say that, did I? I know aliens

03:40:59.740 --> 03:41:03.740
are supposed to be all mysterious and everything, but I still don't see why anyone would build a

03:41:04.300 --> 03:41:10.860
city-sized wildlife refuge for anaerobic microbes. It's gotta be a habitat for something.

03:41:10.860 --> 03:41:14.140
Why any atmosphere at all if it's just some kind of terraforming machine?

03:41:15.340 --> 03:41:20.860
Spindle pointed up at the gang's tent. What Susan said, atmosphere still under construction and we

03:41:20.860 --> 03:41:27.180
get a free ride until the owners show up. Free? Free-ish. And I know we've only seen a fraction

03:41:27.180 --> 03:41:32.620
of a fraction of what's inside, but something obviously saw us coming. It yelled at us if I recall.

03:41:38.140 --> 03:41:42.780
If they're smart and they're hostile, why aren't they shooting? Maybe they are.

03:41:43.740 --> 03:41:48.060
If something's hiding down the hall wrecking your robots, it's not frying them any faster

03:41:48.060 --> 03:41:53.900
than the baseline environment do anyway. What you call a baseline environment might be an active

03:41:53.900 --> 03:42:01.900
counter intrusion measure. Why else would a habitat be so uninhabitable? Spindle rolled his eyes.

03:42:02.620 --> 03:42:06.620
Okay, I was wrong. We don't know enough to make a few smart guesses.

03:42:07.980 --> 03:42:13.180
Not that we hadn't tried. Once Jack's sensor head had been irreparably fried, we'd relegate it to

03:42:13.180 --> 03:42:18.700
surface excavation. It had widened the bore in infinitesimal increments, patiently burning back

03:42:18.700 --> 03:42:24.380
the edges of our initial peephole until it measured almost a meter across. Meanwhile, we'd customized

03:42:24.380 --> 03:42:29.580
bait's grunts, shield them against nuclear reactors in the insides of cyclotrons, and

03:42:29.580 --> 03:42:35.020
compared we'd thrown them at Rorschach like stones chucked into a haunted forest. Each had gone

03:42:35.020 --> 03:42:39.660
through Jack's portal, unspooling, whisper-thin fiber-op behind them to pass intelligence through

03:42:39.740 --> 03:42:48.060
charged atmosphere. They'd sent glimpses mostly, a few extended vignettes. We'd seen Rorschach's

03:42:48.060 --> 03:42:56.380
walls move, slow, lazy waves of periostellis rippling along its gut. We'd seen treocally

03:42:56.380 --> 03:43:01.420
invignations in progress, painstaking constrictions that would presumably, given time, seal off a

03:43:01.420 --> 03:43:06.380
passageway. Our grunts had sailed through some quarters, staggered through others where the

03:43:06.380 --> 03:43:11.740
magnetic ambience threw them off balance. They'd passed through strange throats lined with razor

03:43:11.740 --> 03:43:18.620
thin teeth, thousands of triangular blades in parallel rows, helically twisted. They'd edged

03:43:18.620 --> 03:43:23.900
cautiously around clouds of mists sculpted into abstract fractal shapes, shifting and endlessly

03:43:23.900 --> 03:43:28.700
recursive, their charged droplets strung along the myriad converging lines of electromagnetic force.

03:43:30.060 --> 03:43:36.060
Ultimately, every one of them had died or disappeared. Any way to increase the shielding,

03:43:36.060 --> 03:43:41.900
I wondered. Spindle gave me a look. We've shielded everything except the sensor heads,

03:43:41.900 --> 03:43:47.500
Bates explained. If we shield those, we're blind. But visible light's harmless enough,

03:43:47.500 --> 03:43:52.860
what about purely optical light? We're using optical links, Commisar, Cyndall snapped.

03:43:53.980 --> 03:43:59.260
And you may have noticed the shits getting through anyway. But aren't there, you know,

03:43:59.260 --> 03:44:04.700
I groped for the word, bandpass filters? Something that lets visible light wavelengths through,

03:44:04.700 --> 03:44:10.300
cuts out lethal stuff on both sides? E snorted. Sure, it's called an atmosphere,

03:44:10.300 --> 03:44:15.260
if we brought one with us about 50 times deeper than Earth's, it might block some of the soup down

03:44:15.260 --> 03:44:20.700
there. Of course, Earth also gets a lot of help from its magnetic field, but I'm not betting my life

03:44:20.700 --> 03:44:29.820
on any EM we can set up in that place. If we didn't keep running into these spikes, Bates said,

03:44:29.820 --> 03:44:35.740
that's the real problem. Are they random? I wondered. Spindle shrugged was a half shiver.

03:44:36.620 --> 03:44:40.460
I don't think anything about that place is random, but who knows? We need more data.

03:44:41.260 --> 03:44:45.580
Which we're not likely to get, James said, walking around the ceiling to join us,

03:44:46.140 --> 03:44:52.460
if our drones keep shorting out. The conditional was pure formality. We tried playing the odds,

03:44:52.460 --> 03:44:57.100
sacrificing drone after drone in the hope that one of them would get lucky. Survival rates

03:44:57.180 --> 03:45:02.220
tailed exponentially to zero with distance in the base camp. We tried shielding the fiber

03:45:02.220 --> 03:45:07.020
op to reduce aperture leakage. The resulting tethers were stiff and unwieldly, wrapped in so

03:45:07.020 --> 03:45:11.100
many layers of ferroceramic they were virtually waving the bots around on the end of a stick.

03:45:11.740 --> 03:45:16.140
We tried cutting the tethers entirely, sending the machines out to explore on their own,

03:45:16.140 --> 03:45:19.980
squinting against the radiant blizzard and storing their findings for later download.

03:45:20.620 --> 03:45:23.260
None had returned. We tried everything.

03:45:23.500 --> 03:45:28.940
We can go in ourselves, James said. Almost everything.

03:45:30.220 --> 03:45:34.140
Right. Spindle replied in a voice that couldn't meet anything but wrong.

03:45:35.020 --> 03:45:39.900
It's the only way to learn anything useful. Yeah, like how many seconds it would take

03:45:39.900 --> 03:45:45.180
your brain to turn it a synchrotron soup. Our suits can be shielded. Oh, you mean like

03:45:45.180 --> 03:45:49.820
Mandy's drones? I really prefer you didn't call me that, Bates remarked.

03:45:50.700 --> 03:45:56.300
The point is Rorschach kills you whether you're meat or mechanical.

03:45:57.100 --> 03:46:03.260
My point is that it kills me differently. James replied. It takes longer. Spindle shook his head.

03:46:03.260 --> 03:46:07.500
You'd be good as dead in 50 minutes, even shielded, even in the so-called cool zones.

03:46:08.460 --> 03:46:12.940
And be completely asymptomatic for three hours or more. And even after that,

03:46:12.940 --> 03:46:17.180
it would take days for us to actually die. And we'd be back here long before then,

03:46:17.260 --> 03:46:22.300
and the ship could patch us up just like that. We even know that much, Isaac. It's right there in

03:46:22.300 --> 03:46:27.340
consensus. And if we know it, you know it. So we shouldn't even be having this argument.

03:46:28.380 --> 03:46:32.540
That's your solution. We saturate ourselves with radiation every 30 hours,

03:46:32.540 --> 03:46:35.660
and I get to cut out the tumors and stitch everyone's cells back together.

03:46:36.700 --> 03:46:39.180
The pods are automatic. You wouldn't have to lift a finger.

03:46:40.060 --> 03:46:44.060
Not to mention what those magnetic fields would do to your brain.

03:46:44.060 --> 03:46:47.100
We'd be hallucinating from the moment we fair data suits.

03:46:47.820 --> 03:46:54.860
Ah, so we go in deft, dumb, and blind. Good idea. We can let light pass. Infrared. It's all EM, Suze.

03:46:57.740 --> 03:47:01.340
Even if we blacked out our helmets completely and used a camera feed,

03:47:01.340 --> 03:47:08.300
we'd get leakage where the wire went through. Sure, yes, but it'd be better than Jesus,

03:47:08.940 --> 03:47:12.860
a tremor-sense spittle sailing from the corner of Spindle's mouth.

03:47:13.820 --> 03:47:14.860
Let me talk to M-

03:47:15.420 --> 03:47:18.700
I've discussed it with the rest of the gang, Isaac. We're all agreed.

03:47:19.740 --> 03:47:24.140
All agreed? You don't have a working majority in there, Suze. Just because you cut your brain

03:47:24.140 --> 03:47:28.540
into pieces doesn't mean they each get a vote. I don't see why not. We're at least

03:47:28.540 --> 03:47:34.460
as sentient as you are. They're all you, just partitioned. You don't seem to have any trouble

03:47:34.460 --> 03:47:40.380
treating Michelle as a separate individual. Michelle's, I mean, yes, you're all different

03:47:40.380 --> 03:47:44.860
facets, but there's only one original. Your altars don't call us that.

03:47:45.740 --> 03:47:51.980
Sasha erupted with a voice as cold as locks. Ever. Spindle tried to pull back.

03:47:52.780 --> 03:47:56.380
I didn't mean you know I didn't, but Sasha was gone.

03:47:57.100 --> 03:48:02.700
What are you saying? said the softer voice in her wake. Do you think I'm just- I'm just mom play

03:48:02.700 --> 03:48:05.820
acting? Do you think we're together? You're alone with her?

03:48:05.820 --> 03:48:09.900
Michelle, Spindle said miserably. No, what I think-

03:48:10.460 --> 03:48:13.580
Doesn't matter, Sir Asti said. We don't vote here.

03:48:14.540 --> 03:48:19.660
He floated above us, visor'd and unreadable in the center of the drum. None of us had seen him

03:48:19.660 --> 03:48:24.540
arrive. He turned slowly on his axis, keeping us in view as we rotated around him.

03:48:25.740 --> 03:48:31.340
Prepping Silla. Amanda needs two untethered grunts with precautionary armament. Cams from

03:48:31.420 --> 03:48:35.500
one to a million angstroms, shielded in panics, no autonomous circuitry.

03:48:36.300 --> 03:48:41.740
Played lid boosters. Diamond hydranate and potassium iodide for everyone by 1350.

03:48:42.940 --> 03:48:46.060
Everyone, Bates asked. Sir Asti nodded.

03:48:46.860 --> 03:48:50.860
Window opens four hours 23. He turned back down the spine.

03:48:51.740 --> 03:48:54.700
Not me, I said. Sir Asti paused.

03:48:55.500 --> 03:48:59.020
I don't participate in field ops, I reminded him. Now you do.

03:48:59.980 --> 03:49:06.300
I'm a synthesis. He knew that. Of course he knew everyone did. You can't observe the system unless

03:49:06.300 --> 03:49:12.940
you say outside the system. On earth, you're a synthesis, he said. In the Kuiper, you're a synthesis.

03:49:12.940 --> 03:49:16.300
Hear your mass, do what you're told. He disappeared.

03:49:17.580 --> 03:49:23.660
Welcome to the big picture, Bates said softly. I looked at her as the rest of the group broke up.

03:49:24.540 --> 03:49:30.860
You know I, we're a long way out, Siri. Can't wait 14 months or feedback from your bosses and you know it.

03:49:31.740 --> 03:49:36.940
She leapt from a standing star, arc smoothly through holograms into the weightless core of the drum,

03:49:37.580 --> 03:49:40.940
but then she stopped herself as if distracted by some sudden insight.

03:49:41.500 --> 03:49:44.220
She grabbed a spinal conduit and swung back to face me.

03:49:45.420 --> 03:49:51.260
You shouldn't sell yourself short, she said. Or Sir Asti, either. You're an observer, right?

03:49:51.340 --> 03:49:54.300
It's a safe bet there's going to be a lot down there worth observing.

03:49:55.420 --> 03:50:01.340
Thanks, I said. But I already knew why Sir Asti was sending me into Rorschach and there was more

03:50:01.340 --> 03:50:08.380
to it than observation. Three valuable agents in harm's way. A decoy about one in four odds

03:50:08.380 --> 03:50:16.620
that an enemy would aim somewhere else. The Lord will take control of you. You will dance and shout

03:50:16.700 --> 03:50:20.780
and become a different person. 1 Samuel 10 6

03:50:23.580 --> 03:50:28.140
We were probably fractured during most of our evolution. James once told me back when we were

03:50:28.140 --> 03:50:33.500
all still getting acquainted. She tapped her temple. There's a lot of room up here. A modern

03:50:33.500 --> 03:50:38.220
brain can run dozens of sentient cores without getting too crowded. And parallel multitasking

03:50:38.220 --> 03:50:45.340
has obvious survival advantages. I nodded. Ten heads are better than one. Our integration may

03:50:45.340 --> 03:50:50.460
have actually occurred quite recently. Some experts think we can still revert to multiples

03:50:50.460 --> 03:50:55.980
under the right circumstances. Well, of course, you're living proof. She shook their head.

03:50:56.860 --> 03:51:01.420
I'm not talking about physical partitioning. We're the state of the arts, certainly, but

03:51:01.420 --> 03:51:05.980
theoretically surgery isn't even necessary. Simple stress could do something like it if it was strong

03:51:05.980 --> 03:51:13.100
enough. If it happened early in childhood. No kidding. Well, in theory, James admitted and

03:51:13.100 --> 03:51:18.540
changed into Sasha, who said, bullshit in theory, there's documented cases as recently as 50 years

03:51:18.540 --> 03:51:24.940
ago. Really? I resisted the temptation to look it up on my inlays. The unfocused eyes can be a

03:51:24.940 --> 03:51:31.180
giveaway. I didn't know. Well, it's not like anyone talks about it now. People were fucking

03:51:31.180 --> 03:51:36.620
barbarians about multi-cores back then, called it a disorder, treated it like some kind of disease.

03:51:36.620 --> 03:51:40.700
And their idea of a cure was to keep one of the cores and murder all the others.

03:51:40.780 --> 03:51:44.700
Not that they called it murder, of course, they called it integration or some shit.

03:51:45.580 --> 03:51:49.740
That's what people did back then, created other people to suck up all the abuse and torture,

03:51:49.740 --> 03:51:54.540
then got rid of them when they weren't needed anymore. It hadn't been the tone most of us

03:51:54.540 --> 03:51:59.100
were looking for at an ice breaking party. James had gently eased back into the driver's

03:51:59.100 --> 03:52:04.620
seat and the conversation had steered closer to community standards. But I hadn't heard any of

03:52:04.620 --> 03:52:10.300
the gang use altered to describe each other than or since. It seemed innocuous enough when Spindle

03:52:10.300 --> 03:52:15.260
had said it. I wondered why they'd taken such offense. And now floating alone in my tent with

03:52:15.260 --> 03:52:22.060
a few pre-op minutes to kill. There was no one to see my eyes glaze. Alter carried baggage over a

03:52:22.060 --> 03:52:30.460
sensory old, consensus told me. Sasha was right. There'd been a time when MCC was MPD, a disorder

03:52:30.460 --> 03:52:36.380
rather than a complex, and it had never been induced deliberately. According to the experts

03:52:36.380 --> 03:52:41.580
of that time, multiple personalities arose spontaneously from unimaginable cauldrons of abuse.

03:52:42.220 --> 03:52:47.580
Fragmentary persona offered up to suffer rapes and beatings while the child hid behind some

03:52:47.580 --> 03:52:54.060
unknowable sanctuary in the folds of the brain. It was both survival strategy and ritual self-sacrifice.

03:52:54.780 --> 03:52:59.340
Powerless souls hacking themselves to pieces, offering up quivering chunks of self in the

03:52:59.340 --> 03:53:03.580
desperate hope that the vengeful gods called mom and dad might not be insatiable.

03:53:03.820 --> 03:53:10.380
None of it had been real as it turned out, or at least none of it had been confirmed. The experts

03:53:10.380 --> 03:53:14.220
of the day had been little more than witch doctors dancing through improvised rituals,

03:53:14.220 --> 03:53:19.420
mandering free-form interviews full of leading questions and non-verbal cues, scavenger hunts

03:53:19.420 --> 03:53:24.700
through regurgitated childhoods, sometimes a shot of lithium or haloper at all when the

03:53:24.700 --> 03:53:30.300
beads and rattles didn't work. The technology to map minds was barely off the ground. The technology

03:53:30.380 --> 03:53:35.820
to edit them was gears away. So the therapists and psychiatrists poked at their victims and

03:53:35.820 --> 03:53:40.540
invented names for things they didn't understand and argued over the shrines of Freud and Klein

03:53:40.540 --> 03:53:44.860
and the Old Astrologers, doing their best to sound like practitioners of science.

03:53:45.980 --> 03:53:51.660
Inevitably, it was science that turned them all into roadkill. MPD was a half-forgotten

03:53:51.660 --> 03:53:57.580
fad even before the advent of synaptic rewiring. But altar was a word from that time,

03:53:57.660 --> 03:54:01.900
and its resonance had persisted. Among those who remembered the tale,

03:54:01.900 --> 03:54:07.020
altar was code for betrayal and human sacrifice. Altar meant cannon fodder.

03:54:08.540 --> 03:54:13.980
Imagining the topology of the gang's co-existing souls, I could see why Sasha embraced the

03:54:13.980 --> 03:54:20.860
mythology. I could see why Susan let her. After all, there was nothing implausible about the concept.

03:54:20.860 --> 03:54:26.700
The gang's very existence proved that much. And when you've been peeled off from a pre-existing

03:54:26.700 --> 03:54:32.060
entity, sculpted it from non-existence straight into adulthood, a mere fragment of personhood

03:54:32.060 --> 03:54:36.860
without even a full-time body to call your own, you can be forgiven a certain amount of anger.

03:54:37.500 --> 03:54:42.300
Sure, you're all equal, all in it together. Sure, no persona is better than any other.

03:54:43.020 --> 03:54:48.620
Susan's still the only one with a surname. Better to direct that resentment at old grudges,

03:54:48.620 --> 03:54:53.500
real or imagined, less problematic at least than taking it out on someone who shares the same flesh.

03:54:54.460 --> 03:54:59.980
I realized something else too. Surrounded by displays documenting the relentless growth of

03:54:59.980 --> 03:55:04.700
the Leviathan beneath us, I could not only see why Sasha had objected to the word,

03:55:04.700 --> 03:55:09.180
I could also see why Isaac Spindle, no doubt unconsciously, had spoken it in the first place.

03:55:09.980 --> 03:55:13.900
As far as Earth was concerned, everyone on theseas was an altar.

03:55:16.140 --> 03:55:19.340
Sonoste stayed behind. He hadn't come with a backup.

03:55:19.500 --> 03:55:25.020
There were the rest of us, though, crammed into the shuttle, embedded in custom spacesuits so

03:55:25.020 --> 03:55:29.740
padded with shielding we might have been deep-sea divers in a previous century. It was a fine

03:55:29.740 --> 03:55:33.740
balance. Too much shielding would have been worse than none at all, would split primary

03:55:33.740 --> 03:55:38.780
particles into secondary ones just as lethal and twice as numerous. Sometimes you had to live

03:55:38.780 --> 03:55:42.700
with moderate exposure. The only alternative was to embed yourself like a bug in lead.

03:55:43.660 --> 03:55:49.340
We launched six hours from Paragy. Silla raced on ahead like an eager child, leaving its parent

03:55:49.340 --> 03:55:55.660
behind. There is no eagerness in the systems around me, though, except for one. The gang of four

03:55:55.660 --> 03:56:01.260
are almost shimmered behind her faceplate. Excited, I asked. Sasha answered.

03:56:01.260 --> 03:56:04.060
Fucking right! Fieldwork, Keaton! First contact!

03:56:05.100 --> 03:56:08.300
What if there's nobody there? What if there is and they don't like us?

03:56:09.180 --> 03:56:13.180
Even better, we get a crack at their signs and cereal boxes without the traffic cops

03:56:13.180 --> 03:56:19.340
leaning over our shoulders. I wondered if she spoke for the others. I was pretty sure she

03:56:19.340 --> 03:56:23.500
didn't speak for Michelle. Silla's ports had all been sealed.

03:56:28.300 --> 03:56:32.940
There was no outside view, nothing to see inside but bots and bodies and the tangled

03:56:32.940 --> 03:56:39.740
silhouette swelling on my helmet-hud. But I could feel the radiation slicing through our armor as

03:56:39.740 --> 03:56:45.340
if it were tissue paper. I could feel the knotted crests and troughs of Rorschach's magnetic field.

03:56:45.980 --> 03:56:50.780
I could feel Rorschach itself drawing nearer, the charred canopy of some fire-sormed alien

03:56:50.780 --> 03:56:56.620
forest, more landscape than artifact. I imagined titanic bolts of electricity arcing between

03:56:56.620 --> 03:57:02.140
its branches. I imagined getting in the way. What kind of creatures would choose to live in

03:57:02.140 --> 03:57:08.620
such a place? You really think we'll get along, I said. James' shrug was almost lost under the

03:57:08.620 --> 03:57:14.220
armor. Maybe not at first. We may have gotten off on the wrong foot. We might have to sort through

03:57:14.220 --> 03:57:19.660
all kinds of misunderstandings, but we'll figure each other out eventually. Evidentially, she

03:57:19.660 --> 03:57:25.740
thought that answered my question. The shuttle slewed. We bumped up against each other like 10 pins.

03:57:26.540 --> 03:57:31.500
Thirty seconds of micromaneuver has brought us to a solid stop. A cheery animation played

03:57:31.500 --> 03:57:36.140
across the hut in greens and blues. The shuttle's docking seal, easing through the membrane that

03:57:36.140 --> 03:57:41.260
served as our entrance into Rorschach's inflatable vestibule. Even as a cartoon, it looked vaguely

03:57:41.260 --> 03:57:48.860
pornographic. Bates had been pre-packed next to the airlock. She slid back the inner door. Everybody

03:57:48.860 --> 03:57:54.780
ducked. Not an easy maneuver, swaddled in life support and ferroceramic. Helmets tilted and

03:57:54.780 --> 03:58:00.620
bumped. The grunts flattened overhead like lethal cockroaches, hummed to life and disengaged from

03:58:00.620 --> 03:58:06.140
the ceiling. They scraped past in the narrow headroom, bobbing cryptically to their mistress

03:58:06.140 --> 03:58:12.620
and exited stage left. Bates closed the inner hatch. The lock cycled, opened again on an empty

03:58:12.620 --> 03:58:18.380
chamber. Everything normal, according to the board. The drones waited patiently in the vestibule.

03:58:19.020 --> 03:58:24.620
Nothing had jumped out at them. We had to wait forever for the image. The bot rate was less than

03:58:24.620 --> 03:58:31.820
a trickle. Words moved back and forth easily enough. No surprises so far. Bates reported and

03:58:31.820 --> 03:58:38.300
distorted Jews' harp vibrato, but any picture worth a million of them and... there. Through the eyes of

03:58:38.300 --> 03:58:44.700
the grunt behind, we saw the grunt head in motionless grainy monochrome. It was a postcard from the past.

03:58:44.700 --> 03:58:49.980
Sight turned to sound, a thick clumsy vibrations of methane bumping against the hull. It took long

03:58:49.980 --> 03:58:56.300
seconds for each static-ridden image to accrete on the HUD. Grunts descended into the pit,

03:58:56.300 --> 03:59:03.020
grunts emerging from into Rorschach's duodenum, a cryptic hostile cave-scape in systematic

03:59:03.020 --> 03:59:08.620
increments. Down in the lower left-hand corner of each image, timestamps and Teslas ran down the

03:59:08.620 --> 03:59:15.020
clock. You gave up a lot when you don't trust the EM spectrum. Looks good, Bates reported, going in.

03:59:15.260 --> 03:59:19.740
In a friendlier universe, machines would have cruised the boulevards, sending perfect images in

03:59:19.740 --> 03:59:24.540
crystal resolution. Spindled and ganged would be sipping coffee back in a drum, telling the grunts

03:59:24.540 --> 03:59:29.900
to take a sample of this or get a close-up of that. In a friendlier universe, I wouldn't even be here.

03:59:30.940 --> 03:59:36.780
Bates appeared in the next postcard, emerging from the fistula. In the next back... er, in the next

03:59:36.780 --> 03:59:42.220
her back was to the camera, apparently panning the perimeter. In the one after that, she was looking

03:59:42.940 --> 03:59:51.500
right at us. Oh, okay, she said. Come on. Down. Not so fast, Spindle said. How are you feeling?

03:59:52.220 --> 03:59:55.820
Fine. A bit odd, but odd how.

03:59:59.820 --> 04:00:05.420
Radiation sickness announced itself with nausea, but unless we'd seriously aired in our calculations,

04:00:05.420 --> 04:00:09.980
that wouldn't happen for another hour or two. Not until well after we'd all been lehally cooked.

04:00:10.700 --> 04:00:15.820
Mild disorientation, Bates reported. It's a bit spooky in here, but

04:00:15.820 --> 04:00:22.380
must be gray syndrome. It's tolerable. I looked at the gang. The gang looked at Spindle. Spindle

04:00:22.380 --> 04:00:29.420
shrugged. It's not gonna get any better, Bates said from afar. The clock is ticking, people. Get down

04:00:29.420 --> 04:00:36.460
here. We got. Not living. Not by a long shot. Haunted.

04:00:40.620 --> 04:00:47.740
Not living. Not by a long shot. Haunted. Even when the walls didn't move, they did.

04:00:48.540 --> 04:00:51.660
Always at the corner of the eye, that sense of crawling motion.

04:00:52.700 --> 04:00:57.420
Always at the back of the mind, the sense of being watched, the dread certainty of malign and

04:00:57.420 --> 04:01:02.860
alien observers just out of sight. More than once I turned, expecting to catch one of those

04:01:02.860 --> 04:01:08.220
plantems in the open. All I ever saw was a half-blind grunt floating down the passageway,

04:01:08.220 --> 04:01:13.500
or a wide-eyed and jittery crewmate returning my stare, and the walls of some glistening

04:01:13.500 --> 04:01:18.140
black lava tube with a hundred embedded eyes all snapped shut just the instant before.

04:01:18.940 --> 04:01:22.940
Our lights pushed the darkness back, perhaps twenty meters in either direction,

04:01:22.940 --> 04:01:29.740
beyond mist and shadows seethe, and the sounds, roar-shock creaked around us like some ancient

04:01:29.740 --> 04:01:36.700
wooden hull trapped in pack ice, electricity hissed like rattlesnakes. You tell yourself,

04:01:36.700 --> 04:01:41.900
it's mostly in your head. You remind yourself it's well-documented and inevitable consequence of

04:01:41.900 --> 04:01:47.900
meetin' magnetism brought too close together. High energy fields released the ghosts and the

04:01:47.900 --> 04:01:53.180
grays from your temporal lobe, dredge up paralyzing dread from the midbrain to saturate the conscious

04:01:53.180 --> 04:01:59.100
mind. They fuck with your motor nerves and make even dormant inlays sing like fine fragile crystal.

04:02:00.380 --> 04:02:06.620
Energy artifacts. That's all they are. You repeat that to yourself. You repeat it so often it loses

04:02:06.620 --> 04:02:12.220
any pretense of rationality and devolves into rodent cantation, a spell to ward off evil spirits.

04:02:12.940 --> 04:02:17.500
They're not real, these whispering voices just outside your helmet. Those half-seen

04:02:17.580 --> 04:02:22.460
creatures flickering at the edge of vision. They're tricks of the mind, the same neurological

04:02:22.460 --> 04:02:26.940
smoke and mirrors that convinced people throughout the ages that they were being haunted by ghosts,

04:02:26.940 --> 04:02:34.860
abducted by aliens, hunted by vampires. And you wonder whether Soastie really stayed behind,

04:02:34.860 --> 04:02:41.020
or if he was here all along, waiting for you. Another spike, Bates warned as Tesla and Sea

04:02:41.020 --> 04:02:48.300
Virts surged on my hood. Hang on. I was installing the Faraday bell, trying to. It should have been

04:02:48.300 --> 04:02:52.460
simple enough. I'd already run the main anchor line down from the vestibule to the flaccid

04:02:52.460 --> 04:02:57.980
sack floating in the middle of the passageway. I was, that's right, something about a spring line

04:02:58.700 --> 04:03:05.340
to keep the bell centered. The wall glistened in my headlamp like wet clay. Satanic runes

04:03:05.420 --> 04:03:12.460
sparkled in my imagination. I jammed at the spring line's pad against the wall. I could have sworn

04:03:12.460 --> 04:03:17.740
the substrate flinched. I fired my thrust pistol, repeating back to the center of the passage.

04:03:18.620 --> 04:03:25.260
They're here, James whispered. Something was. I could feel it always behind me no matter where

04:03:25.260 --> 04:03:31.340
I turned. I could feel some great roaring darkness swirling just out of sight, a ravenous mouth as

04:03:31.340 --> 04:03:36.540
wide as the tunnel itself, any moment now it would lunge forward at impossible speed and engulf us all.

04:03:37.500 --> 04:03:43.420
They're beautiful, James said. There was no fear in her voice at all. She sounded awestruck.

04:03:44.780 --> 04:03:51.500
What? Where? Bates never stopped turning. Keep trying to keep the whole 360 in sight at once.

04:03:52.140 --> 04:03:56.860
The drones under her command wobbled restlessly to either side, armored parentheses pointing down

04:03:56.940 --> 04:04:04.300
the passageway in opposite directions. What do you see? Not out there, in here, everywhere. Can't you see it?

04:04:05.340 --> 04:04:08.780
I can't see anything, Spindle said, his voice shaking.

04:04:09.820 --> 04:04:15.340
It's in the E.M. fields, James said. That's how they communicate. The whole structure is full of

04:04:15.340 --> 04:04:22.380
language. It's... I can't see anything, Spindle repeated. His breath echoed loud and fast over

04:04:23.260 --> 04:04:31.500
the link. I'm blind. Shit. Bates swung on Spindle. How can that... the radiation... I... I don't think

04:04:31.500 --> 04:04:37.660
that's it. Nine Tesla and the ghosts were everywhere. I smelled asphalt and honeysuckle.

04:04:38.540 --> 04:04:46.140
Keaton, Bates called. You with us? Yeah. Barely. I was back at the bell, my hand on the ripcord,

04:04:46.140 --> 04:04:51.580
trying to ignore whatever kept tapping me on the shoulder. Leave that, get him inside. No.

04:04:51.580 --> 04:04:56.060
Spindle floated helplessly in the passage, his pistol bouncing against its wrists tether.

04:04:56.060 --> 04:05:01.660
No, throw me something. What? It's all in your head. It's all in your... throw something, anything.

04:05:02.620 --> 04:05:05.740
Bates hesitated. You said you were blind. Just do it.

04:05:07.340 --> 04:05:12.860
Bates pulled a spare suit battery off her belt and lobbed it. Spindle reached, fumbled.

04:05:12.860 --> 04:05:15.660
Battery slipped from his grasp and bounced dust off the wall.

04:05:16.620 --> 04:05:19.740
I'll be okay, he asked. Just get me into the tent.

04:05:20.940 --> 04:05:25.180
I yanked the cord. The bell inflated like a great gun-ventil marshmallow.

04:05:25.980 --> 04:05:31.740
Everyone inside. Bates ran her pistol with one hand, grabbed Spindle with the other. She handed

04:05:31.740 --> 04:05:36.620
him off to me and slapped a sensor pod onto the skin of the tent. I pulled back the shield and

04:05:36.620 --> 04:05:42.220
entrance flap as though pulling a scab from a wound. The single molecule beneath, infinitely long,

04:05:42.220 --> 04:05:45.740
endlessly folded against itself, swirled and glistened like a soap bubble.

04:05:46.460 --> 04:05:51.180
Get him in. James, get down here. I pushed Spindle through the membrane.

04:05:51.180 --> 04:05:56.060
It split around him with airtight intimacy, hugged each tiny crack and contour as he passed through.

04:05:56.860 --> 04:05:59.020
James, are you... get it off me!

04:06:02.300 --> 04:06:07.340
Harsh voice, raw and scared and scary, as male as female could sound.

04:06:07.900 --> 04:06:09.980
Cruncher in control. Get it off!

04:06:10.940 --> 04:06:16.300
I looked back. Susan James' body tumbled slowly in the tunnel, grasping its right leg with both

04:06:16.300 --> 04:06:23.420
hands. James, Bates sailed over to the other woman. Keaton, help out. She took the gang by the arm.

04:06:23.420 --> 04:06:24.620
Cruncher, what's the problem?

04:06:25.340 --> 04:06:30.540
That! You blind? He wasn't just grasping at the limb I realized as I joined them. He was

04:06:30.540 --> 04:06:35.420
tugging at it. He was trying to pull it off. Something laughed hysterically, right inside

04:06:36.380 --> 04:06:41.260
Take his arm. Bates told me, taking his right one, trying to pry the fingers from their death

04:06:41.260 --> 04:06:45.420
grip on the gang's leg. Cruncher, let go. Now. Get it off me!

04:06:46.140 --> 04:06:51.820
It's your leg, Cruncher. We wrestled our way towards the diving bell. It's not my leg. Just

04:06:51.820 --> 04:06:56.300
look at it. How could it? It's dead. It's stuck to me. Almost there.

04:06:56.300 --> 04:06:59.900
Cruncher, listen. Bates snapped. Are you with me? Get it off!

04:07:00.140 --> 04:07:05.740
We stuffed the gang into the tent. Bates moved aside as I dove in after them.

04:07:06.460 --> 04:07:10.780
Amazing the way she held it together. Somehow she kept the demons at bay,

04:07:10.780 --> 04:07:14.220
herded us to shelter like a border calling in a thunderstorm. She was...

04:07:15.260 --> 04:07:21.420
She wasn't following us in. She wasn't even there. I turned to see her body floating outside the

04:07:21.420 --> 04:07:26.380
tent, one gloved hand grasping the edge of the flap, but even under all those layers of captain

04:07:26.460 --> 04:07:31.740
and chromel and polycarbonate, even behind the distorted half reflections on her face plate,

04:07:31.740 --> 04:07:36.540
I could tell that something was missing. All her services had just disappeared.

04:07:37.740 --> 04:07:42.940
That couldn't be Amanda, Bates. The thing before me had no more topology than a mannequin.

04:07:44.140 --> 04:07:48.940
Amanda? The gang givered at my... at my back softly hysteric.

04:07:48.940 --> 04:07:50.700
It's Bindle. What's happening?

04:07:51.660 --> 04:07:55.660
I'll stay out here, Bates said. She had no affect whatsoever.

04:07:56.220 --> 04:07:57.260
I'm dead anyway.

04:07:58.140 --> 04:08:01.900
What? Spindle had lots. You will be if you don't.

04:08:01.900 --> 04:08:06.780
You leave me here, Bates said. That's an order. She sealed us in.

04:08:09.180 --> 04:08:15.020
It wasn't the first time, not for me. I'd had invisible fingers poking through my brain before,

04:08:15.020 --> 04:08:20.220
stirring up the muck, ripping open the scabs. It was far more intense when Rorschach did it to me,

04:08:20.220 --> 04:08:23.660
but Chelsea was more... precise, I guess you'd say.

04:08:24.540 --> 04:08:30.380
Macrame, she called it. Glieljum starts, cascade effects, the splice and dice of critical ganglia.

04:08:31.260 --> 04:08:33.900
While I trafficked in the reading of human architecture,

04:08:33.900 --> 04:08:37.980
Chelsea changed it, finding the critical nodes and nudging them just so,

04:08:37.980 --> 04:08:42.460
dropping a pebble into some trickle at the headwaters of memory, and watching the ripples,

04:08:42.460 --> 04:08:45.660
they'll do a great rolling cascade deep in the downstream psyche.

04:08:46.300 --> 04:08:50.860
She'd get hotwire happiness in the time it took to fix a sandwich, reconcile you with

04:08:50.860 --> 04:08:54.060
your whole childhood in the course of a lunch hour or three.

04:08:55.100 --> 04:08:59.900
Like so many other domains of human invention, this one had learned to run without her.

04:08:59.900 --> 04:09:04.700
Human nature was becoming an assembly line edit, humanity itself increasingly relegated

04:09:04.700 --> 04:09:10.860
from production to product. Still, for me, Chelsea's skill set recast a strange old world

04:09:10.940 --> 04:09:16.380
in an entirely new light. The cut and paste of mine's not for the greater good of some abstract

04:09:16.380 --> 04:09:19.900
society, but for the simple selfish wants of the individual.

04:09:21.100 --> 04:09:28.540
Let me give you the gift of happiness, she said. I am pretty happy. I'll make you happier, a TAT on me.

04:09:29.660 --> 04:09:34.940
TAT? Transient, attitudinal tweak. I've got privileges at Sacks.

04:09:35.980 --> 04:09:39.740
I've been tweaked plenty, changed one more synapse and I might turn it to someone else.

04:09:40.540 --> 04:09:45.100
That's ridiculous and you know it, or every experience you had would turn you into a different

04:09:45.100 --> 04:09:51.820
person. I thought about that. Maybe it does. But she wouldn't let it go, and even the strongest

04:09:51.820 --> 04:09:56.620
anti-happiness argument was bound to be an uphill proposition. Some one afternoon,

04:09:56.620 --> 04:10:01.900
Chelsea fished around in her cupboards and dredged up a hairnet studded with greasy gray washers.

04:10:01.900 --> 04:10:05.660
The net was a superconducting spider web fine as mist that mapped the fields of

04:10:05.660 --> 04:10:10.460
mirrored thought. The washers were ceramic magnets that bathe the brain in fields of their own.

04:10:11.020 --> 04:10:15.180
Chelsea's inlay is linked to a base station that played with the interference patterns between the

04:10:15.180 --> 04:10:20.300
two. They used to need a machine the size of a bathroom just to house the magnets.

04:10:25.420 --> 04:10:28.780
She laid me back on the couch and stretched the mesh across my skull.

04:10:29.820 --> 04:10:33.100
That's the only outright miracle you get with a portable setup like this.

04:10:33.740 --> 04:10:36.940
We can find hotspots and we can even zap them if they need zapping.

04:10:40.620 --> 04:10:45.420
But TMS effects fade after a while. We'll have to go to a clinic for anything permanent.

04:10:46.140 --> 04:10:51.900
So we're fishing for what exactly? Repressed memories? No such thing. She grinned in a toothy

04:10:51.900 --> 04:10:57.100
reassurance. They're only memories we choose to ignore or kind of think around if you know what I mean.

04:10:57.900 --> 04:11:02.620
I thought this was a gift of happiness. Why? She laid a fingertip across my lips.

04:11:03.260 --> 04:11:07.740
Believe it or not, Sigur's, some people sometimes choose to ignore even good memories.

04:11:07.740 --> 04:11:11.580
Like say if they enjoyed something they didn't think they should or

04:11:11.580 --> 04:11:14.860
she kissed my forehead. If they don't think they deserve to be happy.

04:11:15.740 --> 04:11:21.100
So we're going for potluck. You can never tell till you get a bite. Close your eyes.

04:11:22.940 --> 04:11:25.500
A soft hum started up somewhere between my ears.

04:11:26.060 --> 04:11:31.420
Chelsea's voice led me through the darkness. Now keep in mind, memories aren't historical archives.

04:11:31.500 --> 04:11:36.460
They're improvisations really. A lot of the stuff you associate with a particular event

04:11:36.460 --> 04:11:41.740
might be factually wrong no matter how you clearly remember it. The brain has a funny habit of

04:11:41.740 --> 04:11:47.340
building composites. Inserting details after the fact. But that's not to say your memories aren't

04:11:47.340 --> 04:11:51.980
true, okay? They're an honest reflection of how you saw the world and every one of them went into

04:11:51.980 --> 04:11:57.020
shaping how you see it. But they're not photographs. More like impressionist paintings, okay?

04:11:57.020 --> 04:12:05.740
Okay. Ah, she said. There's something. What? Functional cluster. Getting a lot of low level

04:12:05.740 --> 04:12:10.540
use but not enough to intrude into conscious awareness. Let's just see what happens when we,

04:12:10.540 --> 04:12:15.020
and I was 10 years old and I was home early and I just let myself into the kitchen and the smell

04:12:15.020 --> 04:12:19.900
of burned butter and garlic hung in the air. Dad and Helen were fighting in the next room.

04:12:19.900 --> 04:12:23.500
The flip top on our kitchen catcher had been left up which was something

04:12:23.500 --> 04:12:28.460
sometimes enough to get Helen going all by itself. But they were fighting about something else.

04:12:29.100 --> 04:12:34.060
Helen only wanted what was best for us all and dad said there were limits and this was not the

04:12:34.060 --> 04:12:38.860
way to go about it. And Helen said you don't know what it's like. You hardly ever see him.

04:12:38.860 --> 04:12:42.940
And then I knew they were fighting about me. Which in and of itself was nothing unusual.

04:12:43.980 --> 04:12:47.660
What really scared me was that for the first time ever dad was fighting back.

04:12:48.940 --> 04:12:53.020
You do not force something like that onto someone, especially without their knowledge.

04:12:53.660 --> 04:12:58.780
My father never shouted. His voice was low and level as ever. But it was colder than I'd ever

04:12:58.780 --> 04:13:04.300
heard and heart as iron. That's just garbage Helen said. Parents always make decisions for

04:13:04.300 --> 04:13:08.220
their children and their best interests. Especially when it comes to medical issues.

04:13:08.220 --> 04:13:15.100
This is not a medical issue. This time my father's voice did rise. It's not a medical issue. That's

04:13:15.100 --> 04:13:21.020
a new height of denial even for you. They would cut out half his brain in case you missed it.

04:13:21.020 --> 04:13:25.660
Do you think he could recover from that without help? Is that more of your father's tough love

04:13:25.660 --> 04:13:30.700
shining through? Why not just deny him food and water while you're at it? If Muops were called

04:13:30.700 --> 04:13:37.100
for they'd have been prescribed. I felt my face scrunching at an unfamiliar word. Something small

04:13:37.100 --> 04:13:42.780
and white beckoned from the open garbage pail. Jim be reasonable. He's so distant he barely even

04:13:42.780 --> 04:13:48.540
talks to me. They said it would take time. But two years there's nothing wrong with helping nature

04:13:48.620 --> 04:13:53.740
a little. We're not even talking black market. It's over the counter for God's sake. That's not the

04:13:53.740 --> 04:13:59.820
point. An empty pill bottle. That's what one of them had thrown out before forgetting to close the

04:13:59.820 --> 04:14:06.780
lid. I salvaged it from the kitchen discards and sounded out the label in my head. Maybe the point

04:14:06.780 --> 04:14:11.740
should be that someone who's barely home three months of the year has got his bloody nerve passing

04:14:11.740 --> 04:14:16.620
judgment on my parenting skills. If you want to say in how he's raised then you can damn well pay

04:14:16.620 --> 04:14:23.900
some dues first. Until then just fuck right off. You will not put that shit into my son ever again.

04:14:23.900 --> 04:14:31.980
My father said. Bonfast formula is for Mu opioid receptor promoters maternal response stimulant

04:14:31.980 --> 04:14:37.980
strengthening ties between mother and child since 2042. Yeah and how are you gonna stop me you little

04:14:37.980 --> 04:14:42.540
geek? You can't even make the time to find out what's going on in your own family. You think you

04:14:42.540 --> 04:14:47.660
can control me all the way from fucking orbit you think? Suddenly nothing came from the living

04:14:47.660 --> 04:14:53.340
room with soft choking sounds. I peeked around the corner. My father had hell in by the throat.

04:14:54.220 --> 04:15:00.940
I think he growled that I can stop you from doing anything to Siri ever again if I have to and I

04:15:00.940 --> 04:15:08.780
think you know that. Then she saw me and then he did and my father took his hand from around my

04:15:08.780 --> 04:15:14.940
mother's neck and his face was utterly unreadable but there was no mistaking the triumph on hers.

04:15:16.620 --> 04:15:21.900
I was up off the couch the skull cat clenched in one hand. Chelsea stood wide-eyed before me the

04:15:21.900 --> 04:15:30.620
butterfly still is death on her cheekbone. She took my hand. Oh god I'm so sorry. You you saw that?

04:15:30.620 --> 04:15:37.260
No of course not it can't read minds but that obviously wasn't a happy memory. It wasn't all that

04:15:37.260 --> 04:15:43.980
bad. I felt sharp disembodied pain from somewhere nearby like an ink spot or on a white tablecloth.

04:15:44.540 --> 04:15:51.260
After a moment I fixed it, teeth in my lip. She ran her hand up my arm. It really stressed you out.

04:15:51.260 --> 04:15:58.940
Your vitals were are you okay? Yeah of course no big deal tasting salt. I am curious about something

04:15:58.940 --> 04:16:05.820
though. Ask me why would you do this to me? Because we can make it go away Cygnus that's the whole

04:16:05.900 --> 04:16:11.420
point. Whatever that was whatever you didn't like about it we know where it is now. We can go back

04:16:11.420 --> 04:16:16.380
and damp it out just like that and then we've got days to get it removed permanently if that's what

04:16:16.380 --> 04:16:24.300
you want. Just put the cap back on and she put her arms around me drew me close. She smelled like

04:16:24.300 --> 04:16:30.700
sand and sweat. I love the way she smelled. For a while I could feel a little bit safe.

04:16:31.420 --> 04:16:34.860
For a while I could feel like the bottom wasn't going to drop out at any moment.

04:16:35.820 --> 04:16:41.500
Somehow when I was with Chelsea I mattered. I wanted her to hold me forever.

04:16:42.780 --> 04:16:50.780
I don't think so I said. No she blinked look up at me. Why ever not? I shrugged.

04:16:51.740 --> 04:16:54.300
You know what they say about people who don't remember the past.

04:16:55.180 --> 04:17:02.860
Predators run for their dinner. Pray run for their lives. Old ecologists proverb.

04:17:04.780 --> 04:17:10.220
We were blind and helpless jammed into a fragile bubble behind enemy lines. But finally the

04:17:10.220 --> 04:17:16.540
whispers were silent. The monsters just stayed behind the covers. And a man of bates was out there

04:17:16.540 --> 04:17:23.340
with them. What the fuck? Spindle breathed. The eyes behind his faceplate were active and searching.

04:17:23.980 --> 04:17:29.980
You can see I asked. He nodded. What happened to Bates? Her soup breach? I don't think so.

04:17:30.620 --> 04:17:36.780
Then why'd she say she was dead? What? She meant it literally I told him. Not as I'm as good as dead

04:17:36.780 --> 04:17:45.260
or I'm going to die. She met dead now like she was a talking corpse. How did you know? Stupid question.

04:17:45.260 --> 04:17:51.980
His face ticked and trembled in the helmet. That's crazy eh? Define crazy. The gang floated

04:17:51.980 --> 04:17:58.140
quietly. Cheek to jowl behind Spindle in the cramped enclosure. Cruncher had stopped obsessing

04:17:58.140 --> 04:18:03.340
about the leg as soon as we'd sealed up. Or maybe he'd simply been overridden. I thought I saw facets

04:18:03.340 --> 04:18:08.860
of Susan in the twitching of those thick-fingered gloves. Spindle's breath echoed second hand over

04:18:08.860 --> 04:18:15.260
the link. If Bates is dead then so are we. Maybe not. We wait out the spike we get out of here.

04:18:15.820 --> 04:18:20.060
Besides, I added, she wasn't dead. She only said she was.

04:18:21.420 --> 04:18:25.660
Fuck. Spindle reached out and pressed his gloved palm against the skin of the tent.

04:18:26.220 --> 04:18:31.340
He felt back and forth along the fabric. Someone did put out a transducer.

04:18:32.380 --> 04:18:39.020
Eight o'clock, I said, about a meter. Spindle's hand came to rest about across the wall from the pod.

04:18:39.580 --> 04:18:44.380
My HUD floated with second hand numbers, vibrated down his arm and relayed to our suits.

04:18:45.100 --> 04:18:50.140
Still five Tesla out there, falling though. The tent expanded around us as if breathing,

04:18:50.140 --> 04:18:54.940
shrank back in the next second as if some transient low pressure front moved past.

04:18:55.980 --> 04:18:59.260
When did your sight come back, I wondered. Soon as we came inside.

04:19:00.060 --> 04:19:03.660
Sooner. You saw the battery. Fumbled it, he grunted.

04:19:04.300 --> 04:19:09.100
Not that I'm much less of a spaz even when I'm not blind, eh? Bates, you out there?

04:19:09.900 --> 04:19:13.020
You reached for it. You almost caught it. That wasn't blind chance.

04:19:13.660 --> 04:19:19.340
Not blind chance, blind sight. Amanda, respond please. Blind sight?

04:19:20.380 --> 04:19:24.460
Nothing wrong with the receptors, he said distractedly. Brain processes the image,

04:19:24.460 --> 04:19:29.660
but I can't access it. Brainstem takes over. Your brainstem can see, but you can't.

04:19:30.460 --> 04:19:34.620
Something like that. Shut up and let me- Amanda, can you hear me? No.

04:19:35.100 --> 04:19:40.700
No. Not from anyone in the tent, that voice. It had shivered down Spindle's arm,

04:19:40.700 --> 04:19:43.740
barely audible with the rest of the data. From outside.

04:19:44.780 --> 04:19:47.420
Major Mandy, Spindle exclaimed. You're alive.

04:19:48.460 --> 04:19:54.460
No. A whisper like white noise. Well, you're talking to us so you sure as shit ain't dead.

04:19:55.260 --> 04:20:00.300
No. Spindle and I exchanged looks. What's the problem, Major?

04:20:00.380 --> 04:20:00.860
Major?

04:20:01.500 --> 04:20:06.700
Silence. The gang bumped gently against the wall behind us, all fast and opaque.

04:20:07.820 --> 04:20:10.540
Major Bates, can you hear me? No.

04:20:11.980 --> 04:20:17.580
It was a dead voice, sedated, trapped in the fishbowl, transmitted through limbs and led at

04:20:17.580 --> 04:20:21.100
a three digit bod rate, but it was definitely Bates' voice.

04:20:22.220 --> 04:20:25.500
Major, you've gotta get in here, Spindle said. Can you come inside?

04:20:26.380 --> 04:20:29.740
No. Are you injured? Are you pinned by something?

04:20:31.100 --> 04:20:35.980
No. Maybe not her voice, after all. Maybe just her vocal cords.

04:20:37.180 --> 04:20:41.500
Look, Amanda, it's dangerous. It's too damn hot out there. Do you understand? You...

04:20:42.220 --> 04:20:46.060
I'm not out here, said the voice. Where are you?

04:20:47.100 --> 04:20:53.340
Nowhere. I looked at Spindle. Spindle looked at me. Neither of us spoke.

04:20:54.300 --> 04:20:59.500
James did. At long last and softly. And what are you, Amanda?

04:21:00.300 --> 04:21:06.540
No answer. Are you Rorschach? Here in the belly of the beast, it was so easy to believe.

04:21:08.780 --> 04:21:10.540
No. Then what?

04:21:11.740 --> 04:21:16.220
Nothing. The voice was flat and mechanical. I'm nothing.

04:21:17.260 --> 04:21:20.140
You're saying you don't exist, Spindle said slowly.

04:21:20.860 --> 04:21:23.740
Yes. The tent breathed around us.

04:21:24.700 --> 04:21:30.220
Then how can you speak, Susan asked the voice. If you don't exist, what are we talking to?

04:21:31.340 --> 04:21:32.460
Something else.

04:21:33.900 --> 04:21:37.180
A sigh. A breath of static. Not me.

04:21:38.860 --> 04:21:43.740
Shit, Spindle muttered. His service has brightened with resolve and sudden insight.

04:21:43.740 --> 04:21:47.180
He pulled his hand from the wall. My head thinned instantly.

04:21:47.180 --> 04:21:51.180
Her brain's frying. We gotta get her inside. He reached for the release.

04:21:51.980 --> 04:21:54.380
I put out my own hand. The spike,

04:21:54.380 --> 04:21:56.940
sequestered already, Commisar, and we're past the worst of it.

04:21:57.660 --> 04:22:02.220
Are you saying it's safe? It's lethal. It's always lethal, and she's out there in it,

04:22:02.220 --> 04:22:06.700
and she could do some serious damage to herself and oppress something bumped the tent from the

04:22:06.700 --> 04:22:13.020
outside. Something grabbed the outer catch and pulled. Our shelter opened like an eye.

04:22:13.020 --> 04:22:15.580
Amanda Bates looked into this through the exposed membrane.

04:22:16.220 --> 04:22:19.020
I'm reading 3.8. She said, that's tolerable, right?

04:22:20.060 --> 04:22:22.700
Nobody moved. Come on, people. Breaks over.

04:22:23.340 --> 04:22:29.260
I met. Spindle stared. Are you okay? In here? Not likely. We've got a job to do.

04:22:30.060 --> 04:22:35.820
Do you exist? I asked. What kind of stupid question is that? Spindle, how's the field

04:22:35.820 --> 04:22:42.940
strength? Can we work in it? He swallowed audibly. Maybe we should abort, major. That spike was,

04:22:43.020 --> 04:22:47.020
according to my readings, the spike is pretty much over, and we've got less than two hours to

04:22:47.020 --> 04:22:51.500
finish setting up, run our ground truths, and then get out of here. Can we do that without

04:22:51.500 --> 04:22:57.180
hallucinating? I don't think we'll shake the heebie-jeebies, Spindle admitted, but we shouldn't

04:22:57.180 --> 04:23:03.820
have to worry about extreme effects until another spike hits. Good. Which could be at any time.

04:23:04.620 --> 04:23:10.140
We weren't hallucinating, James said quietly. We can discuss it later, Bates said. Now,

04:23:10.780 --> 04:23:17.180
there was a pattern there, James insisted. In the fields, in my head, Rorschach was talking.

04:23:17.180 --> 04:23:22.780
Maybe not to us, but it was talking. Good. Bates pushed herself back to let us past.

04:23:23.660 --> 04:23:29.420
Maybe now we can all learn to talk back. Maybe we can learn to listen, James said.

04:23:33.500 --> 04:23:38.780
We fled like frightened children with brave faces. We left the base camp behind.

04:23:38.780 --> 04:23:43.740
Jack, still miraculously functional in his vestibule, a tunnel into the haunted mansion,

04:23:43.740 --> 04:23:46.940
for alluring magnometers left to die in the faint hope they might not.

04:23:47.500 --> 04:23:52.380
Crude pyrometers and thermographs, antique radiation-proof devices that measured the

04:23:52.380 --> 04:23:56.860
world through the flex and stretch of metal tabs and etched their findings on rolls of plastic.

04:23:57.500 --> 04:24:00.860
Glow globes and diving bells and guide ropes strung to one another.

04:24:01.420 --> 04:24:05.500
We left it all behind. It promised to return in 36 hours if we lived so long.

04:24:06.460 --> 04:24:12.380
Inside each of us, infinitesimal lacerations were turning our cells to mush. Plasma membrane

04:24:12.380 --> 04:24:17.660
sprang countless leaks, overwhelmed repair enzymes clung desperately to shredded genes,

04:24:17.660 --> 04:24:22.940
and barely delayed the inevitable. Anxious to avoid the rush, patches of my intestinal lining

04:24:22.940 --> 04:24:27.900
began flaking away before the rest of the body had a chance to die. By the time we docked with

04:24:27.900 --> 04:24:33.500
Theseus, both Michelle and I were feeling nauseous. The rest of the gang, oddly, was not. I had no

04:24:33.500 --> 04:24:38.300
idea how that was possible. The others would be presenting the same symptoms within minutes.

04:24:39.260 --> 04:24:43.180
Without intervention, we would all be vomiting our guts out for the following two days.

04:24:43.820 --> 04:24:48.220
Then the body would pretend to recover. Perhaps a week, we would feel no pain and have no future.

04:24:52.940 --> 04:24:57.500
We would walk and talk and move like any living thing and perhaps convince ourselves we were

04:24:57.500 --> 04:25:02.780
immortal after all. Then we would collapse into ourselves, rotted from the inside out.

04:25:02.860 --> 04:25:07.100
We would bleed from our eyes and mouths and assholes, and if any god was merciful, we would

04:25:07.100 --> 04:25:13.180
dive before splitting out open like rotten fruit. But of course, Theseus, our redeemer, would save

04:25:13.180 --> 04:25:18.140
us from such a fate. We filed from the shuttle into a great balloon that Sarashti had erected to

04:25:18.140 --> 04:25:23.580
capture our personal effects. We shed our contaminated spacesuits and clothing and emerged naked into

04:25:23.580 --> 04:25:30.220
the spine. We passed single file through the drum, the flying dead in formation. Yuka Sarashti,

04:25:30.220 --> 04:25:35.260
discreetly distant on the turning floor, leapt up in our wake and disappeared aft to feed our

04:25:35.260 --> 04:25:41.820
radioactive castoffs into the decompiler. Into the crypt, our coffins lay across the rear bulkhead.

04:25:42.380 --> 04:25:47.500
We sank gratefully and wordlessly into their embrace. Bates coughed blood as the lids came down.

04:25:48.620 --> 04:25:55.100
My bones hummed as the captain began to shut me off. I went to sleep a dead man. I had only theory

04:25:55.100 --> 04:26:01.740
and the assurances of fellow machinery that I would ever be born again. Keaton, come forth.

04:26:03.020 --> 04:26:09.740
I woke up ravenous. Faint voices drifted forward from the drum. I floated in my pod for a few moments,

04:26:09.740 --> 04:26:16.140
eyes closed, savoring absences. No pain, no nausea, no terrifying subliminal sense of one's own

04:26:16.140 --> 04:26:23.660
body sloughing incrementally to mush. Weakness and hunger, otherwise I fell fine. I opened my eyes.

04:26:23.820 --> 04:26:31.420
Something like an arm. Gray and glistening, far too, too attenuate to be human. No hand at its tip.

04:26:32.460 --> 04:26:38.940
Too many joints, a limb broken in a dozen places. It extended from a body barely visible over the

04:26:38.940 --> 04:26:45.100
lip of the pod, a suggestion of dark bulk and other limbs in disjoint motion. It hovered motionless

04:26:45.100 --> 04:26:51.180
before me, as if it startled in the midst of some shameful act. By the time I had breath enough to

04:26:51.180 --> 04:26:57.180
cry out, it had whipped back out of sight. I erupted from the pod, eyes everywhere. Now they

04:26:57.180 --> 04:27:03.660
saw nothing. An empty crypt, a naked note-taker. The mirrored bulk had reflected vacant pods to

04:27:03.660 --> 04:27:11.100
either side. I called up consensus, all systems nominal. It didn't reflect, I remembered. The

04:27:11.100 --> 04:27:17.900
mirror didn't show it. I headed aft, heart still pounding. The drum opened up around me, spindle

04:27:17.900 --> 04:27:23.260
in the gang conversing in low tones aft. Spindle glanced up and waved a trembling hand and greeting.

04:27:26.860 --> 04:27:31.260
You need to check me out, I called. My voice wasn't nearly as steady as I'd hoped.

04:27:31.820 --> 04:27:36.700
Admitting you have a problem is the first step, spindle called back. Just don't expect miracles.

04:27:37.580 --> 04:27:42.620
He turned back to the gang. James on top, they sat in a diagnostic couch, staring at some test

04:27:43.420 --> 04:27:48.940
pattern shimmering on the rear bulkhead. I grabbed the tip of a stairway and pulled myself down.

04:27:48.940 --> 04:27:54.060
Coriolis pushed me sideways like a flag in the breeze. I'm either hallucinating or there's

04:27:54.060 --> 04:28:00.620
something on board. You're hallucinating. I'm serious. So am I. Take a number. Wait your turn.

04:28:01.500 --> 04:28:06.460
He was serious. Once I forced myself to calm down and read the signs, I could see he wasn't

04:28:06.460 --> 04:28:11.820
even surprised. Guess she's pretty hungry after all that exhausting lying around, eh? Spindle

04:28:11.900 --> 04:28:17.420
waved at the galley. Eat something, be with you in a few minutes. I forced myself to work up my

04:28:17.420 --> 04:28:22.620
latest synopsis while I ate, but that only took half a mind. The others still shivered in residual

04:28:22.620 --> 04:28:29.100
thrall to fight flight. I tried to distract it by tapping the bio med feed. It was real,

04:28:29.100 --> 04:28:35.500
James was saying. We all saw it. No, couldn't have been. James cleared his throat. Tried this one.

04:28:36.540 --> 04:28:40.700
The feed showed what she saw, a black triangle on a white background.

04:28:40.780 --> 04:28:44.860
In the next instant, it shattered into a dozen identical copies and a dozen dozen.

04:28:45.420 --> 04:28:50.620
The proliferating brood rotated around the center screen, geometric primitives ballroom dancing in

04:28:50.620 --> 04:28:55.980
precise formation, each sprouting smaller triangles from its tip, fractalizing, rotating,

04:28:57.660 --> 04:29:04.460
evolving into an infinite intricate tilework. That sketch pad, I realized. An interactive eye

04:29:04.460 --> 04:29:10.060
witness reconstruction without the verbiage. Susan's own pattern matching wetwear reacted to what she

04:29:10.060 --> 04:29:15.500
saw. No, there were more of them. No, the orientation's wrong. Yes, that's it, but bigger.

04:29:16.060 --> 04:29:20.620
And spindle's machine picked those reactions right out of her head and amended the display in real

04:29:20.620 --> 04:29:26.940
time. It was a big step up from the half-assed workaround called language. Easily impressed,

04:29:26.940 --> 04:29:32.620
mind had even called it mind reading. It wasn't, though. It was all just feedback and correlation.

04:29:32.620 --> 04:29:36.540
It doesn't take a telepath to turn one set of patterns into another, fortunately.

04:29:37.180 --> 04:29:42.220
That's it, that's it! Susan cried. The triangles had iterated out of existence.

04:29:42.860 --> 04:29:47.900
Now the display was full of interlocking asymmetrical pedigrams, a spider web of fish scales.

04:29:48.700 --> 04:29:51.740
Don't tell us that's random noise, she said triumphantly.

04:29:52.380 --> 04:29:54.860
No, spindle said. It's a clover constant.

04:29:55.500 --> 04:30:01.340
Uh, it's a hallucination, Seuss. Of course, but something planted in our head, right? And

04:30:01.980 --> 04:30:06.060
it was in your head all along. It was in your head the day you were born. No,

04:30:07.100 --> 04:30:11.980
it's an artifact of deep brain structure. Even congenitally blind people see them sometimes.

04:30:12.700 --> 04:30:18.140
None of us have ever seen them before, ever. I believe you, but there's no information there,

04:30:18.140 --> 04:30:22.220
eh? That wasn't Rorschach talking, it was just interference, like everything else.

04:30:23.020 --> 04:30:27.820
But it was so vivid. Not that flickering corner of your eye stuff we saw everywhere,

04:30:27.820 --> 04:30:32.620
this was solid. It was realer than real. That's how you can tell it wasn't.

04:30:32.620 --> 04:30:36.700
Since you don't actually see it, there's no SE eyeball optics to limit resolution.

04:30:37.500 --> 04:30:45.820
Oh, James said, and then softly. Shit. Yeah, sorry. And then, anytime you're ready.

04:30:47.100 --> 04:30:52.620
I looked up. Spindle was waving me over. James rose from her chair, but it was Michelle who gave

04:30:52.620 --> 04:30:57.260
him a quick disconsolate squeeze, and Sasha who grumbled past me on her way out of the tent.

04:30:58.140 --> 04:31:01.980
By the time I reached him, Spindle had unfolded the couch to a half-caught.

04:31:01.980 --> 04:31:07.740
Lie down. I did. I wasn't talking about back on Rorschach, you know. I meant here.

04:31:07.740 --> 04:31:09.980
I saw something right now when I woke up.

04:31:10.860 --> 04:31:16.300
Raise your left hand, he said. Then, just your left, eh? I lowered my right,

04:31:16.300 --> 04:31:21.660
winced at the pinprick. That's a bit primitive. He eyed the blood-filled cuvette between his thumb

04:31:21.660 --> 04:31:27.260
and forefinger, a shivering ruby teardrop the size of a fingernail. Wet samples still the best for

04:31:27.260 --> 04:31:32.860
some things. Aren't the pods supposed to do everything? Spindle nodded. Call it a quality

04:31:32.860 --> 04:31:37.820
control test. Keep the ship on its toes. He dropped the sample onto the nearest countertop.

04:31:37.820 --> 04:31:43.420
The teardrop flattened and burst. The surface drank my blood as if parched. Spindle spacked his

04:31:43.420 --> 04:31:50.220
lips. Elevated, glowing... Koleynester ace inhibitors in the ret. Yum.

04:31:51.820 --> 04:31:55.660
For all I knew, my blood results actually did taste good to the man.

04:31:55.660 --> 04:32:00.780
Spindle didn't just read the results, he felt them. He smelled and saw and experienced each datum,

04:32:00.780 --> 04:32:05.100
like drops of citrus on the tongue. The whole Biomed sub-drum was a part of the...

04:32:05.660 --> 04:32:11.180
was but a part of the spindle prostheses. An extended body with dozens of different sensory

04:32:11.180 --> 04:32:16.620
modes. Forced to talk to a brain that only knew five. No wonder he'd bonded with Michelle.

04:32:16.620 --> 04:32:22.140
He was almost synthetic himself. You spent a bit longer in there than the rest of us, he remarked.

04:32:22.780 --> 04:32:29.100
That significant? A jerking shrug. Maybe your organs got a bit more cooked than ours.

04:32:29.100 --> 04:32:32.860
Maybe you just got a delicate constitution. Your pod would have caught anything...

04:32:33.500 --> 04:32:40.140
imminent, so I figured... ah. What? Some cells along your brain pan going into overdrive,

04:32:40.140 --> 04:32:45.500
more on your bladder and kidney. Tumors? What you expect? Or a shock's no reduce, ba.

04:32:46.060 --> 04:32:53.180
But the pod... Spindle grimaced, his idea of a reassuring smile. Repairs 99.9% of the damage,

04:32:53.180 --> 04:32:59.660
sure. By the time you get to the last 0.1 you're into diminishing returns. These are small, commissar.

04:32:59.660 --> 04:33:02.940
Chances are your own bodily would take care of them. If not, we know where they live.

04:33:03.900 --> 04:33:09.340
The ones in my brain, could they be causing? Not a chance. He chewed on his lower lip for a moment.

04:33:09.900 --> 04:33:15.420
Of course, cancer is not all that thing did to us. What I saw up in the crypt,

04:33:15.420 --> 04:33:19.500
it had these multi-jointed arms from a central mass, big as a person maybe.

04:33:20.140 --> 04:33:24.060
Spindle nodded. Get used to it. The others are seeing these things?

04:33:24.940 --> 04:33:31.260
I doubt it. Everyone is a different take, like... his twitching face conveyed, dare I say it? Rorschach

04:33:31.260 --> 04:33:37.980
bots. I was expecting hallucinations in the field, I admitted, but up here. TMS effects.

04:33:38.060 --> 04:33:42.940
Spindle snapped his fingers. They're sticky, eh? Neurons get kicked into one state, take a while

04:33:42.940 --> 04:33:50.940
to come unstuck. You never got a TAT? Well, just a boy like you? Once or twice, I said. Maybe. Same

04:33:50.940 --> 04:33:56.940
principle. So I'm gonna keep seeing this stuff. Party line is they fade over time, week or two,

04:33:56.940 --> 04:34:03.340
you're back to normal. But out here with that thing, he shrugged. Too many variables, not the least of

04:34:03.340 --> 04:34:09.660
which is, I assume we'll keep going back until Siddasti says otherwise. But they're basically

04:34:09.660 --> 04:34:14.940
magnetic effects. Probably, although I'm not betting on anything where that fucker's concerned.

04:34:15.900 --> 04:34:20.380
Could something else be causing them? I asked. Something on this ship? Like what?

04:34:21.420 --> 04:34:26.540
I don't know. Leakage, enthusiast, magnetic shielding maybe? Not normally. Of course,

04:34:26.540 --> 04:34:30.620
we've all got little implanted networks in our heads, eh? And you've got a whole hemisphere

04:34:30.700 --> 04:34:35.660
of prosthetics up there. Who knows what kinds of side effects those might let you in for? Why?

04:34:36.460 --> 04:34:42.620
Rorschach, not a good enough reason for you? I saw them before, I might have said. And this

04:34:42.620 --> 04:34:49.020
spindle would say, oh, when? Where? And then maybe I'd reply, when I was spying on your private life,

04:34:49.020 --> 04:34:55.500
and any chances of non-invasive observation be flushed down to the atoms. It's probably nothing.

04:34:55.500 --> 04:35:00.460
I've just been jumpy lately. I thought I saw something weird in the spinal bundle back before

04:35:00.460 --> 04:35:05.340
we landed on Rorschach. Just for a second, you know, and it disappeared as soon as I focused on it.

04:35:05.900 --> 04:35:12.220
One multi-jointed arms with a central mass? God, no. Just a flicker, really. If it was anything at

04:35:12.220 --> 04:35:17.900
all, it was probably just a man-as-rubber ball floating around up there. Probably, spindle seemed

04:35:17.900 --> 04:35:22.940
almost amused. Couldn't hurt to check for leakage into the shielding, though, just in case. Not like

04:35:22.940 --> 04:35:27.900
we need something else making us see things, eh? I shook my head and remembered nightmares.

04:35:28.460 --> 04:35:34.060
How are the others? Gang's fine if a bit disappointed. Haven't seen the major. He shrugged.

04:35:34.060 --> 04:35:39.820
Maybe she's avoiding me. It hit her pretty hard. Though worse than the rest of us, really. She

04:35:39.820 --> 04:35:45.020
might not even remember it. How could she possibly believe she didn't even exist?

04:35:45.820 --> 04:35:50.780
Spindle shook his head. Didn't believe it. Knew it. For a fact. But how...

04:35:51.580 --> 04:35:56.540
charge gauge in your car, right? Sometimes the contacts corrode. Readout freezes unempty,

04:35:56.540 --> 04:35:59.980
so you think it's empty. What else are you supposed to think? Not like you can go in and

04:35:59.980 --> 04:36:05.980
count the electrons. You're saying the brain's got some kind of existence gauge? Brain's got all

04:36:05.980 --> 04:36:11.020
kinds of gauges. You can know you're blind even when you're not. You can know you can see even

04:36:11.020 --> 04:36:17.340
when you're blind. And yeah, you can know you don't exist even when you do. It's a long list, Commissar.

04:36:17.340 --> 04:36:23.260
Kotards, Antons, Damascus disease just for starters. He hadn't said blindsight.

04:36:23.420 --> 04:36:29.100
What was it like? I asked. Like? Although I knew exactly what I meant.

04:36:30.060 --> 04:36:35.660
Did your arm move by itself when it reached for that battery? Oh, no. You're still in control.

04:36:35.660 --> 04:36:41.500
You just... you get a feeling, that's all. A sense of where to reach. One part of the brain playing

04:36:41.500 --> 04:36:47.100
charades with another, eh? He gestured at the couch. Get off. Seen enough of your ugly guts for now.

04:36:47.100 --> 04:36:51.820
And send Bates up here if you can find where she's hiding. Probably back at FAB building a bigger

04:36:51.820 --> 04:36:55.100
army. The misgivings glinted off of him like sunlight.

04:36:55.900 --> 04:37:00.940
You have a problem with her, I said. He started to deny it then remembered who he was talking to.

04:37:01.660 --> 04:37:07.260
Not personally, just human-node running mechanical infantry. Electronic reflexes,

04:37:07.260 --> 04:37:10.620
slaved or meat reflexes. You'd tell me where the weak spot is.

04:37:11.820 --> 04:37:15.340
Down in Rorschach, I'd have to say all the links are pretty weak.

04:37:16.140 --> 04:37:21.500
Not talking about Rorschach, Spindle said. We go there. What stops them from coming here?

04:37:22.460 --> 04:37:27.500
Them. Maybe they haven't arrived yet, he admitted. But when they do,

04:37:27.500 --> 04:37:30.940
I'm betting we're going up against something bigger than anaerobic microbes.

04:37:31.980 --> 04:37:37.740
When I didn't answer, he continued, his voice lowered. And anyway, Mission Control didn't know

04:37:37.740 --> 04:37:42.060
shit about Rorschach. They thought they were sending us some place where drones could do

04:37:42.060 --> 04:37:47.260
all the heavy lifting. But they just hate not being in command, eh? Can't admit the grunts are

04:37:47.260 --> 04:37:52.700
smarter than the generals. So our defenses get compromised for political appearances. Not like

04:37:52.700 --> 04:37:59.100
that's any kind of news. And I'm no jarhead, but it strikes me as real bad strategy. I remember

04:37:59.100 --> 04:38:06.780
it Amanda Bates, midwifing the birth of her troops. I'm more of a safety precaution. Amanda, I began.

04:38:07.420 --> 04:38:13.180
Like Mandy Fine. Nice mammal. But if we're cruising into a combat situation, I don't want my ass

04:38:13.260 --> 04:38:18.780
covered by some network held back by its weakest link. If you're going to be surrounded by a swarm

04:38:18.780 --> 04:38:24.620
of killer robots, maybe. Yeah, people keep saying that, can't trust the machines. Luddites love to

04:38:24.620 --> 04:38:29.260
go on about computer malfunctions and how many accidental wars we might have prevented because

04:38:29.260 --> 04:38:35.260
a human had the final say. But funny thing, Commissar, nobody talks about how many intentional wars

04:38:35.260 --> 04:38:39.820
got started for the same reason. You still writing those postcards to posterity?

04:38:40.780 --> 04:38:46.300
I nodded and didn't wince inwardly. It was just spindle. Well, feel free to stick in this conversation

04:38:46.300 --> 04:38:57.900
or the next one for all the good it'll do. Imagine you are a prisoner of war. You've

04:38:57.900 --> 04:39:04.140
got to admit you sought coming. You've been crashing tech and seeding biosoles for solid

04:39:04.300 --> 04:39:09.900
18 months. That's a good run by anyone's standards. Realist saboteurs do not as a rule enjoy long

04:39:09.900 --> 04:39:16.700
careers. Everyone gets caught eventually. It wasn't always thus. There was a day you might have even

04:39:16.700 --> 04:39:21.820
hoped for a peaceful retirement. But then they brought the vampires back from the Pleistocene and

04:39:21.820 --> 04:39:27.660
great grieving Ganga. Did that ever turn the balance of power upside down? Those fuckers are

04:39:27.660 --> 04:39:33.100
always 10 steps ahead. It only makes sense after all hunting people is what bloodsuckers evolved to

04:39:33.100 --> 04:39:40.140
do. There's this line from an early pop dine textbook, really old, maybe even Twensen. It's

04:39:40.140 --> 04:39:44.860
something of a mantra. Maybe prayer would be a better word among those in your profession.

04:39:45.660 --> 04:39:51.820
Predators run for their dinner, it goes. Prey run for their lives. The moral is supposed to be that

04:39:51.820 --> 04:39:57.180
on average the hunted escape the hunters because they're more motivated. Maybe that was true when

04:39:57.180 --> 04:40:02.780
it all came down to who ran faster. Doesn't seem to hold when the strategy involves tactical force

04:40:02.780 --> 04:40:09.180
sight and double reverse mind fucks though. The vampires win every time. And now you're caught.

04:40:09.180 --> 04:40:13.820
And while it may have been vampires that set the trap, it was regular turncoat baseline humans who

04:40:13.820 --> 04:40:20.140
pulled the trigger. For six hours now you've been gecko to the wall of some unnamed, unlisted,

04:40:20.140 --> 04:40:25.580
underground detention facility watching as some of those self sane humans played games with your

04:40:25.580 --> 04:40:31.660
boyfriend and co-conspirator. These are not your average games. They involve pliers and glowing

04:40:31.660 --> 04:40:38.540
wires and body parts that were not designed to detach. You wish by now that your lover were dead

04:40:38.540 --> 04:40:42.940
like the two others in your cell whose parts are scattered around the room. But they're not letting

04:40:42.940 --> 04:40:50.300
that happen. They're having too much fun. That's what it all comes down to. This is not an interrogation.

04:40:50.300 --> 04:40:56.300
They're less invasive ways to get reliable answers. These are simply a few more sadistic thugs with

04:40:56.300 --> 04:41:01.660
authority killing time and other things. And you can only cry and squeeze your ice tight and whimper

04:41:01.660 --> 04:41:06.700
like an animal even though they haven't laid a hand on you yet. You can only wish they hadn't saved

04:41:06.700 --> 04:41:12.140
you for last because you know what that means. Suddenly your tormentors stop in mid game and

04:41:12.140 --> 04:41:18.220
cock their heads as if listening to some collective inner voice. Presumably it tells them to take you

04:41:18.220 --> 04:41:23.420
off the wall bring you to the next room and sit you down for in one of two gel padded chairs on

04:41:23.420 --> 04:41:28.620
opposite sides of a smart desk because this is what they do far more gently than you'd expect

04:41:28.620 --> 04:41:34.540
before retiring. You can also assume that whoever has given these instructions is both powerful and

04:41:34.540 --> 04:41:39.020
displeased because all the arrogant sadistic cockiness has drained from their faces in the

04:41:39.020 --> 04:41:45.820
space of a heartbeat. You sit and wait. The table glows with soft cryptic symbols that would be of no

04:41:45.820 --> 04:41:50.540
earthly interest to you even if you could understand them even if they contain the very secret of the

04:41:50.540 --> 04:41:56.700
vampires themselves. Some small part of you wonders if this last development might be cause for hope.

04:41:56.700 --> 04:42:01.820
The rest of you doesn't dare believe it. You hate yourself for caring about your own survival when

04:42:01.820 --> 04:42:08.060
chunks of your friends and allies are still warm on the other side of the wall. A stocky emmer and

04:42:08.060 --> 04:42:14.060
woman appears in the room with you clad in nondescript military weave. Her hair is buzzed short.

04:42:14.060 --> 04:42:19.580
Her throat veined with the faint mesh of a sub-q antenna. Your brainstem sees that she is 10 meters

04:42:19.660 --> 04:42:25.740
tall even though some impertinent gelatinous overlays insist that she is of only average height.

04:42:26.620 --> 04:42:33.900
The name tag on her left breast says Bates. You see no sign of rank. Bates extracts a weapon from

04:42:33.900 --> 04:42:39.020
a cheeth on her thigh. You flinch but she does not point it at you. She sets it on the desk

04:42:39.020 --> 04:42:45.580
easily within your reach and sits across from you. A microwave pistol fully charged, unlocked.

04:42:45.660 --> 04:42:50.700
On its lowest setting it causes sunburn and nausea. On its highest it flash boils brains

04:42:50.700 --> 04:42:56.060
in the skull. At any setting in between it inflicts pain and injury and increments as fine as your

04:42:56.060 --> 04:43:02.940
imagination. Your imagination has been retooled for great sensitivity along such scales. You stare

04:43:02.940 --> 04:43:08.700
numbly at the gun trying to figure the trick. Two of your friends are dead, Bates says, as though

04:43:08.700 --> 04:43:17.340
you hadn't just watched them die. Irrecoverably so. Irrecoverably dead. Good one. We could reconstitute

04:43:17.340 --> 04:43:22.060
the bodies but the brain damage. Bates clears her throat as if uncomfortable, as if embarrassed.

04:43:22.620 --> 04:43:28.620
It's a surprisingly human gesture for a monster. We're trying to save the other one. No promises.

04:43:29.340 --> 04:43:35.820
We need information, she says, cutting the bechace. Of course. What came before was psychology,

04:43:35.820 --> 04:43:43.340
softening up. Bates is the good cop. I've got nothing to tell you, you manage. It's 10% defiance,

04:43:43.340 --> 04:43:47.420
90% deduction. They wouldn't have been able to catch you at all in the first place unless

04:43:47.420 --> 04:43:51.740
they already knew everything. Then we need an arrangement, Bates says.

04:43:56.940 --> 04:44:04.220
We need to come to some kind of accommodation. She has to be kidding. Your incredulity must be

04:44:04.220 --> 04:44:10.380
showing. Bates addresses it. I'm not completely unsympathetic. My gut doesn't much like the idea

04:44:10.380 --> 04:44:15.980
of swapping reality for simulation and it doesn't buy that what is truth spin the body economic

04:44:15.980 --> 04:44:21.660
cells to get around it. Maybe there's reason to be scared. Not my problem, not my job, just my

04:44:21.660 --> 04:44:26.780
opinion and it could be wrong. But if we kill each other in the meantime we don't find out either

04:44:26.780 --> 04:44:33.100
way. It's unproductive. You see the dismembered bodies of your friends. You see pieces on the

04:44:33.100 --> 04:44:37.660
floor still a little bit alive. And this has the nerve to talk about productivity.

04:44:38.700 --> 04:44:44.140
We didn't start it, you say. I don't know and I don't care. Like I said, it's not my job.

04:44:54.620 --> 04:44:58.460
Bates jerks a thumb over her shoulder at a door in the wall behind her, the door she

04:44:58.460 --> 04:45:03.100
must have entered through. In there, she says, are the ones who killed your friends.

04:45:03.740 --> 04:45:08.220
They've been disarmed. When you go through the door the room will go offline and remain

04:45:08.220 --> 04:45:13.740
unmonitored for a period of 60 seconds. Nobody besides yourself will ever hold you accountable

04:45:13.740 --> 04:45:18.700
for whatever happens in there during that time. It's a trick. It has to be.

04:45:19.580 --> 04:45:24.380
What do you have to lose, Bates wonders? We can already do anything we want to you. It's not

04:45:24.460 --> 04:45:30.220
like we need you to give us an excuse. Hezitently you take the gun. Bates doesn't stop you.

04:45:31.100 --> 04:45:37.180
She's right, you realize. You have absolutely nothing to lose. You stand and suddenly fearless

04:45:37.180 --> 04:45:41.580
point the weapon at her face. Why go in there? I can kill you right here.

04:45:43.100 --> 04:45:50.300
She shrugs. You could try. Waste of an opportunity if you ask me. So why go in there and I come out

04:45:50.300 --> 04:45:57.340
in 60 seconds and then what? Then we talk. We just think of it as a gesture of good faith,

04:45:57.340 --> 04:46:03.660
she says. Restitution even. The door opens at your approach, closes in your wake,

04:46:04.540 --> 04:46:08.220
and there they are, all four of them spread up across the wall like a chorus line of

04:46:08.220 --> 04:46:14.380
Christ's on crosses. There's no gleam in their eyes now. There's only a bright animal terror

04:46:14.380 --> 04:46:19.660
and the reflection of turntables. Two of the Christs stain their pants when you look them in the eye.

04:46:20.300 --> 04:46:27.100
What's left? Maybe 50 seconds? It's not a lot. You could have done so much more with just a little

04:46:27.100 --> 04:46:32.700
extra time, but it's enough and you don't want to impose on the good graces of this base woman

04:46:33.740 --> 04:46:38.380
because she may be, she may at last be someone you can deal with.

04:46:42.460 --> 04:46:47.580
Under other circumstances, Lieutenant Amanda Bates would have been court-martialed and executed

04:46:47.660 --> 04:46:53.260
within the month. No matter who died had been guilty of multiple counts of rape, torture,

04:46:53.260 --> 04:46:58.540
and homicide. That's just what people did in wartime. It's what they'd always done. There was

04:46:58.540 --> 04:47:03.340
nothing polite about war, no honorable code beyond the chain of command and circling the wagons.

04:47:03.980 --> 04:47:08.380
Deal within discretions if you must, punish the guilty if you have to, for appearance of nothing

04:47:08.380 --> 04:47:13.580
else, but for God's sake close the doors first. Never give your enemy the satisfaction of seeing

04:47:13.580 --> 04:47:18.780
discord in the ranks. Show them nothing but unity and flinty-eyed resolve. There may be

04:47:18.780 --> 04:47:24.220
murderers and rapists in our midst, but by God they're our murderers and rapists. You certainly

04:47:24.220 --> 04:47:29.020
don't give right of revenge to some terrorist twat over a hundred friendly scraps on our belt.

04:47:30.220 --> 04:47:34.780
Still, it was hard to argue with results, a negotiated ceasefire with the third largest

04:47:34.780 --> 04:47:40.460
realist franchise in the hemisphere, an immediate 46% decline in terrorist activities throughout

04:47:40.460 --> 04:47:46.220
the affected territories, the unconditional cancellation of several in-progress campaigns

04:47:46.220 --> 04:47:50.780
which could have seriously compromised three major catacombs and taken out the deluth staging

04:47:50.780 --> 04:47:57.180
grounds entirely, all because Lieutenant Amanda Bates, feeling her way through her first command,

04:47:57.180 --> 04:48:04.220
had gambled on empathy as a military strategy. It was collaborating with the enemy. It was treason.

04:48:04.220 --> 04:48:09.180
It was a betrayal of the rank and file. Diplomats and politicians were supposed to do those things,

04:48:09.180 --> 04:48:16.380
not soldiers. Still, results. It was all there in the record. Initiative, creativity,

04:48:16.940 --> 04:48:21.820
a willingness to succeed by whatever means necessary at whatever cost. Perhaps those

04:48:21.820 --> 04:48:27.260
inclinations needed to be punished, perhaps only tempered. The debate might have gone on forever

04:48:27.260 --> 04:48:31.900
if the story hadn't leaked, but it had and suddenly the generals had a hero on their hands.

04:48:33.180 --> 04:48:38.060
Sometime during her court-martial, Bates' death sentence turned into a rehabilitation.

04:48:38.060 --> 04:48:41.820
The only question was whether it would take place in the Stockade or Officer's College.

04:48:42.540 --> 04:48:47.420
As it turned out, Leavenworth had both. It took her to its bosom and squeezed hard enough that

04:48:47.420 --> 04:48:54.060
virtually every guarantee- to virtually guarantee promotion, if it didn't kill her first. Three

04:48:54.060 --> 04:48:59.980
years later, Major Bates was bound for the stars where she was heard to say, or breaking an entering

04:48:59.980 --> 04:49:06.460
series. Spindle was not the first to register doubts. Others had wondered whether her assignment

04:49:06.460 --> 04:49:13.580
owed as much to the superior qualifications as to resolution of inconvenient PR. I, of course,

04:49:13.580 --> 04:49:18.060
had no opinion one way or the other, but I could see how she might strike some as a double-edged

04:49:18.060 --> 04:49:22.940
sword. When the fate of the world hangs in the balance, you want to keep an eye on anyone whose

04:49:22.940 --> 04:49:31.100
career-defining moment involves consorting with the enemy. If you can see it, chances are it

04:49:31.100 --> 04:49:39.420
doesn't exist. Kate Coe, Grounds for Suicide. Five times we did it. Over five consecutive

04:49:39.420 --> 04:49:45.100
orbits we threw ourselves between the monster's jaws, let it chew at us with a trillion microscopic

04:49:45.100 --> 04:49:50.620
teeth until Thesias reeled us in and stitched us back together. We crept through Rorschach's belly

04:49:50.620 --> 04:49:55.740
in fits and starts, focusing as best we could on the tasks at hand, trying to ignore the ghosts

04:49:55.820 --> 04:50:01.500
that tickled our midbrains. Sometimes the walls flecked subtly around us. Sometimes we only

04:50:01.500 --> 04:50:07.180
thought they did. Sometimes we took refuge in our diving bell while waves of charge and magnetism

04:50:07.180 --> 04:50:13.260
spiraled languidly past, like bullises of ectoplasm coursing down the intestine of some poltergeist

04:50:13.260 --> 04:50:19.900
god. Sometimes we got caught in the open. The gang would squabble amongst itself, uncertain which

04:50:19.900 --> 04:50:25.580
persona was which. Once I fell into a kind of waking paralysis, while alien hands dragged me

04:50:25.580 --> 04:50:30.300
away down the hall. Fortunately, other hands brought me home, and voices that claimed to be real

04:50:30.300 --> 04:50:36.620
told me I'd made the whole thing up. Twice, a man debates found God, saw the fucker right there in

04:50:36.620 --> 04:50:41.340
front of her, knew beyond any shadow of a doubt that the creator not only existed but spoke to her,

04:50:41.900 --> 04:50:47.420
and her alone. Both times she lost her faith once we got her into the bell, but it was touch

04:50:47.420 --> 04:50:53.020
and go for a while. Her warrior drones, drunk on power but still under line of sight control,

04:50:53.020 --> 04:50:57.020
staggered from their perimeters and pointed their weapons along bearings too close for comfort.

04:50:58.700 --> 04:51:04.540
The grunts died fast. Some barely lasted into a single foray. A few died in minutes.

04:51:05.260 --> 04:51:09.980
The longest lived were the slowest on the draw. Half blind, thick-witted, every command and

04:51:09.980 --> 04:51:14.540
response bottlenecked by raw high-frequency sound buzzing across their shielded eardrums.

04:51:15.260 --> 04:51:19.820
Sometimes we backed them up with others that spoke optically, faster but nervous and even more

04:51:19.820 --> 04:51:24.460
vulnerable. Together they guarded against an opposition that had not yet shown its face.

04:51:25.580 --> 04:51:29.900
It hardly had to. Our troops fell even in the absence of enemy fire.

04:51:31.260 --> 04:51:35.580
We worked through it all, through fits and hallucinations and occasional convulsions.

04:51:36.140 --> 04:51:40.220
We tried to watch each other's backs while magnetic tendrils tugged our inner ears and made

04:51:40.220 --> 04:51:46.380
a seasick. Sometimes we vomited into our helmets. Then we'd just hang on, white-faced, sucking sour

04:51:46.380 --> 04:51:50.380
air through clenched teeth while the recyclers filtered chunks and blobs in our headspace.

04:51:51.180 --> 04:51:55.580
And we'd give silent thanks for the small mercy of non-stick, static-repellent faceplates.

04:51:56.860 --> 04:52:00.780
It rapidly became obvious that my presence served more than cannon fodder.

04:52:01.340 --> 04:52:11.260
It didn't matter that I lacked the gang's linguistic skills or spindle's expertise in biology.

04:52:11.820 --> 04:52:16.060
I was another set of hands in a place where anyone could be laid out at a moment's notice.

04:52:16.620 --> 04:52:20.460
The more people Sarasthi kept in the field, the greater the odds that at least one of them

04:52:20.460 --> 04:52:26.140
would be halfway functional at any given moment. Even so, we were in barely any condition to

04:52:26.140 --> 04:52:31.340
accomplish anything. Every incursion was an exercise in reckless endangerment.

04:52:32.540 --> 04:52:35.180
We did it anyway. It was that or go home.

04:52:36.620 --> 04:52:42.940
The work proceeded in infinitesimal increments, hamstrung on every front. The gang wasn't finding

04:52:42.940 --> 04:52:47.900
any evidence of signage or a speech to decipher, but the gross mechanics of this thing were easy

04:52:47.900 --> 04:52:54.300
enough to observe. Sometimes Rorschach partitioned itself, extruded ridges around its passageways,

04:52:54.380 --> 04:53:00.300
like the cartonagia's hoops encircling a human trachea. Over hours, some of them might develop

04:53:00.300 --> 04:53:07.020
into contracting irises, into complete septa, lazy as warm candle wax. We seemed to be witnessing the

04:53:07.020 --> 04:53:12.620
growth of the structure in discrete segments. Rorschach grew mainly from the tips of its thorns.

04:53:13.180 --> 04:53:17.500
We had made our incursion hundreds of meters from the nearest, but evidently the process

04:53:17.500 --> 04:53:23.020
extended at least this far back. If it was part of the normal growth process, though,

04:53:23.580 --> 04:53:28.300
it was a feeble echo of what must have been going on in the heart of the apical zones.

04:53:29.260 --> 04:53:34.060
We couldn't observe those directly, not from inside, barely a hundred meters towards the

04:53:34.060 --> 04:53:40.140
thorn the tube grew too lethal even for suicidal flesh. But over those five orbits, Rorschach grew

04:53:40.140 --> 04:53:44.140
by another eight percent, as mindless and mechanical as a growing crystal.

04:53:46.860 --> 04:53:51.020
Through it all, I tried to do my job. I compiled and collated,

04:53:51.020 --> 04:53:56.380
massaged data I would never understand. I watched the systems around me as best I could,

04:53:56.940 --> 04:54:01.900
factored each tick and trait into the mix. One part of my mind produced synapses and

04:54:01.900 --> 04:54:07.340
synthesis, while another watched, incredulous and uncomprehending. Neither part could trace

04:54:07.340 --> 04:54:13.340
where those insights had come from. It was difficult, though. So, Oste wouldn't let me back

04:54:13.340 --> 04:54:18.380
outside the system. Every observation was contaminated by my own confounding presence in

04:54:18.380 --> 04:54:23.820
the mix. I did my best. I made no suggestions that might affect critical decisions.

04:54:24.620 --> 04:54:30.140
In the field, I did what I was told to, and no more. I tried to be like one of Bates' drones,

04:54:30.140 --> 04:54:33.420
a simple tool with no initiative and no influence on the group dynamic.

04:54:34.140 --> 04:54:39.980
I think I pulled it off, for the most part. My insights accumulated on schedule and piled up

04:54:39.980 --> 04:54:45.100
enthusiast transmission stack, unsent. There was too much local interference to get a signal through

04:54:45.100 --> 04:54:52.620
to Earth. Spindle was right. The ghosts followed us back. We began to hear voices other than

04:54:52.620 --> 04:54:58.220
Sarastis, whispering up the spine. Sometimes even the brightly-lip-wrapped world of the drum would

04:54:58.220 --> 04:55:03.100
warp and jiggle from the corner of my eye, and more than once I saw bony, headless phantoms with

04:55:03.100 --> 04:55:07.900
too many arms nested in the scaffolding. They seemed solid enough from the corner of my eye

04:55:07.900 --> 04:55:12.780
that any spot I focused on faded to shadow, to a dark translucent stain against the background.

04:55:13.740 --> 04:55:18.780
They were so very fragile, these ghosts. The mere act of observation drilled holes through them.

04:55:19.820 --> 04:55:25.020
Spindle had rattled off to menches like raindrops. I went to consensus for enlightenment and found

04:55:25.020 --> 04:55:29.820
a whole other self buried below the limbic system, below the hindbrain, below even the cerebellum.

04:55:30.540 --> 04:55:33.740
It lived in the brainstem, and it was older than the vertebrates themselves.

04:55:34.380 --> 04:55:39.020
It was self-contained. It heard and saw and felt, independent of all those other parts,

04:55:39.100 --> 04:55:44.460
layered over top like evolutionary afterthoughts. It dwelt on nothing but its own survival.

04:55:45.260 --> 04:55:50.700
It had no time for planning or abstract analysis, spared effort for only the most rudimentary

04:55:50.700 --> 04:55:56.460
sensor processing. But it was fast, and it was dedicated, and it could react to threats in a

04:55:56.460 --> 04:56:00.140
fraction of the time it took for its smarter roommates to even become aware of them.

04:56:01.500 --> 04:56:06.620
And even when it couldn't, when the obstinate, unyielding neocortex refused to let it off the

04:56:06.620 --> 04:56:12.220
leash, still it tried to pass on what it saw, and Isaac Spindle experienced an inevitable sense of

04:56:12.220 --> 04:56:18.220
where to reach. In a way, he had a stripped-down version of the gang in his head. Everyone did.

04:56:19.340 --> 04:56:23.660
I looked further and found God itself in the meat of the brain, found the static that had

04:56:23.660 --> 04:56:29.180
sent baits into rapture and Michelle into convulsions. I tracked Grey's syndrome to its headwaters in

04:56:29.180 --> 04:56:35.420
the temporal lobe. I heard voices ranting in the brains of Schizophrenics. I found cortical infarcts

04:56:35.420 --> 04:56:40.220
that inspired people to reject their own limbs. Imagine the magnetic fields that must have acted

04:56:40.220 --> 04:56:45.740
in their stead when Cruncher tried to dismember himself. An often some half-forgotten pest-hole

04:56:45.740 --> 04:56:51.660
of 20th-century case studies, filed under Katard's syndrome. I found a man to baits and others of

04:56:51.660 --> 04:56:57.340
her kind, their brains torqued into denial of the very self. I used to have a heart, one of them

04:56:57.340 --> 04:57:03.180
said listlessly from the archives. Now I have something that beats in its place. Another demanded

04:57:03.180 --> 04:57:08.700
to be buried because his corpse was already stinking. There was more, a whole catalogue of

04:57:08.700 --> 04:57:14.620
finely-tuned dysfunctions that Rorschach had not yet inflicted on us. Some nambulism. Agnosias.

04:57:15.180 --> 04:57:21.180
Heminegalact. Consensus served up a freak show to make any mind real at its own fragility.

04:57:21.180 --> 04:57:25.740
A woman dying of thirst with an easy reach of water, not because she couldn't see the faucet,

04:57:25.740 --> 04:57:31.820
but because she couldn't recognize it. A man for whom the left side of the universe did not exist,

04:57:31.820 --> 04:57:37.340
who could neither perceive nor conceive of the left side of his body, of a room, of a line of

04:57:37.340 --> 04:57:44.380
text. A man for whom the very concept of leftness had become literally unthinkable. Sometimes we

04:57:44.380 --> 04:57:48.300
could conceive of things and still not see them, although they stood right before us.

04:57:49.020 --> 04:57:53.660
Skyscrapers appeared out of thin air, and the person talking to us changed into something else

04:57:53.660 --> 04:57:59.660
during a momentary distraction, and we didn't notice. It wasn't even magic. It was barely even

04:57:59.660 --> 04:58:05.740
misdirection. They called it inattentional blindness, and it had been well known for a

04:58:05.740 --> 04:58:11.340
century or more. Tendency for the eye to simply not notice. Things that evolutionary experience

04:58:11.340 --> 04:58:17.260
classed as unlikely. I found the opposite of Spindle's blind sight. A malady not in which

04:58:17.260 --> 04:58:22.540
the sighted believe they are blind, but one in which the blind insist they can see. The very

04:58:22.540 --> 04:58:28.300
idea was absurd unto insanity, and yet there were, there they were, retinas detached,

04:58:28.300 --> 04:58:33.420
optic nerves burned away, any possibility of vision denied by the laws of physics,

04:58:33.420 --> 04:58:37.980
bumping into walls, stripping over furniture, inventing endless ludicrous explanations for

04:58:37.980 --> 04:58:43.500
their clumsiness. The lights unexpectedly turned off by some other party. A colorful bird glimps

04:58:43.500 --> 04:58:47.900
through the window, distracting attention from the obstacle ahead. I can see perfectly well,

04:58:47.900 --> 04:58:54.220
thank you. Nothing wrong with my eyes. Gages in the head, Spindle called them. But there were other

04:58:54.220 --> 04:58:59.180
things in there too. There was a model of the world, and we didn't look outward at all. Our

04:58:59.180 --> 04:59:04.540
conscious selves saw only the simulation in our heads, an interpretation of reality, endlessly

04:59:04.540 --> 04:59:09.900
refreshed by input from the senses. What happens when those senses go dark, but the model, throw

04:59:09.900 --> 04:59:15.900
it off kilter by some trauma or tumor, fails to refresh? How long do we stare in at that obsolete

04:59:15.900 --> 04:59:20.620
rendering, recycling and massaging the same old data and desperate subconscious active, utterly

04:59:20.620 --> 04:59:26.060
honest denial? How long before it dawns on us that the world we see no longer reflects the world

04:59:26.060 --> 04:59:33.020
we inhabit, that we are blind? Months sometimes, according to the case files, for one poor woman

04:59:33.020 --> 04:59:39.740
a year and more, appeals to logic fail entirely. How could you see the bird when there is no window?

04:59:40.300 --> 04:59:44.700
How do you decide where your seen half world ends and you can't see the other half to wait

04:59:44.700 --> 04:59:50.460
against? If you are dead, how can you smell your own corruption? If you do not exist, Amanda,

04:59:50.460 --> 04:59:56.860
what is talking to us now? Useless. When you're in the grip of Katara's syndrome or having neglect,

04:59:56.860 --> 05:00:01.980
you cannot be swayed by argument. When you're enthralled to some alien artifact, you know the

05:00:01.980 --> 05:00:07.180
self is gone, that reality ends at the midline. You know it with the same unshakable certainty of

05:00:07.180 --> 05:00:12.060
any man regarding the location of his own limbs, with that hard-wired awareness that needs no

05:00:12.060 --> 05:00:18.940
other confirmation. Against that conviction, what is reason? What is logic? Inside Rorschach,

05:00:18.940 --> 05:00:27.900
they had no place at all. On the sixth orbit, it acted. It's talking to us, James said. Her eyes

05:00:27.900 --> 05:00:33.580
were wide behind the faceplate, but not bright, not manic. Around us, Rorschach's guts oozed and

05:00:33.580 --> 05:00:38.860
crawled at the corner of my eye. It still took effort to ignore the illusion. Foreign words

05:00:38.860 --> 05:00:43.660
scrambled like small animals below my brainstem as I tried to focus on a ring of finger-sized

05:00:43.740 --> 05:00:49.420
protrusions that picketed a patch of wall. It's not talking, Spindle said from across the artery.

05:00:49.420 --> 05:00:54.860
You're hallucinating again. Bates said nothing. Two grunts hovered in the middle of the space,

05:00:54.860 --> 05:01:01.420
panning across three axes. It's different this time, James insisted. The geometry, it's not so

05:01:01.420 --> 05:01:06.620
symmetrical, looks almost like the Feistos disc. She spun slowly, pointing down the passage.

05:01:07.260 --> 05:01:12.860
I think it's stronger down here. Bring Michelle out, Spindle suggested. Maybe she can talk some

05:01:12.860 --> 05:01:18.780
sense into you. James laughed weakly. Never say die, do you? She tweaked her pistol and

05:01:18.780 --> 05:01:24.780
coasted it into the deeper gloom. Yes, it's definitely stronger here. There's content super

05:01:24.780 --> 05:01:38.460
opposed on... quick as a blink. Rorschach cut her off. James laughed weakly. Never say die, do you?

05:01:38.460 --> 05:01:43.740
She tweaked her pistol and coasted it into deeper gloom. Yes, it's definitely stronger here. There's

05:01:43.740 --> 05:01:50.620
content superimposed on... quick as a blink. Rorschach cut her off. I'd never seen anything move so

05:01:50.620 --> 05:01:55.180
fast before. There was none of the languor we'd grown accustomed to from Rorschach's septa,

05:01:55.180 --> 05:02:00.860
no lazy drift of contraction. The iris snapped shut in an instant. Suddenly the artery just

05:02:00.860 --> 05:02:05.740
ended three meters ahead with a matte black membrane filigree in fine spiral. And the

05:02:05.980 --> 05:02:10.780
gang of four was on the other side. The grunts were on it immediately, lasers crackling through

05:02:10.780 --> 05:02:15.580
the air. Bates was yelling, get behind me, stick to the walls, kicking herself into space like

05:02:15.580 --> 05:02:19.900
an acrobat and fast forward, taking some tactical high ground that must have been obvious to her,

05:02:19.900 --> 05:02:25.900
at least. I edged towards the perimeter. Threads of superheated plasma sliced the air, shimmering.

05:02:25.900 --> 05:02:30.940
Spindle at the corner of my eye hugged the opposite side of the tunnel. The walls crawled.

05:02:31.020 --> 05:02:37.180
I could see the lasers taking it all. The septum peeled back from their torch like burning paper,

05:02:37.180 --> 05:02:42.940
black oily smoke writhing in its crisping edges and sudden brightness everywhere. A riot of

05:02:42.940 --> 05:02:47.340
fractured light flooded the artery, a thousand shifting angles of incidence and reflection.

05:02:47.980 --> 05:02:51.180
It was like being trapped in the belly of a kaleidoscope pointed at the sun,

05:02:51.900 --> 05:02:58.940
light, and a needle-sharp pain in my side, in my left arm, the smell of charred meat, a scream cut

05:02:58.940 --> 05:03:08.300
off. Susan, you there, Susan? We're taking you first. Around me the light died. Inside us

05:03:08.300 --> 05:03:12.540
me a swarm of floaters mixed it up to the chronic half-visions Rorschach had already planted in my

05:03:12.540 --> 05:03:20.540
hedge. Alarms chirped irritatingly in my helmet, breech, breech, breech, until the small fabric

05:03:20.540 --> 05:03:25.660
of the suit softened and congealed where the holes had been. Something stung maddeningly in my left

05:03:25.660 --> 05:03:32.300
side. I felt as if I had been branded. Kaden, check spindle! Bates had called off the lasers.

05:03:32.300 --> 05:03:37.180
The grunts closed for hand-to-hand, reaching with fiery nozzles and diamond-tip claws to grapple

05:03:37.180 --> 05:03:43.500
with some prismatic material glowing softly behind that burnt black skin. The fibrous reflector, I

05:03:43.500 --> 05:03:48.380
realized. It had shattered the laser light, termed it to luminous shrapnel and thrown it back at our

05:03:48.380 --> 05:03:55.580
faces. Clever. But its surface was still light, even with the lasers down. A diffuse glow,

05:03:55.580 --> 05:03:59.820
dipping and weaving, filtered from the far side of the barrier while the drones chewed doggedly

05:03:59.820 --> 05:04:03.980
through the near one. After a moment and struck me, James headlamp.

05:04:04.700 --> 05:04:12.060
Kaden! Right, spindle. His faceplate was intact. The laser had melted the Faraday mesh laminated

05:04:12.060 --> 05:04:17.580
onto the crystal, but the suit was sealing a tiny hole even now. The hole behind,

05:04:17.580 --> 05:04:22.220
drilled neatly through his forehead, remained. The eyes beneath stared at infinity.

05:04:22.940 --> 05:04:29.980
Well, Bates asked. She could read the vitals as easily as I, but Thesias was capable of post-mortem

05:04:29.980 --> 05:04:38.140
rebuilds. Barring brain damage. No. The whine of drills and shredders stopped. The ambience

05:04:38.140 --> 05:04:43.580
brightened. I looked away from spindle's remains. The grunts had cut a hole in the septum's fibrous

05:04:43.580 --> 05:04:49.180
underlayer. One of them nosed its way through the other side. A new sound rose into the mix.

05:04:49.180 --> 05:04:54.140
A soft animal keening haunted and dissonant. For a moment I thought Rorschach was whispering to us

05:04:54.140 --> 05:04:59.740
again. Its walls seemed to contract slightly around me. James? Bates snapped. James!

05:05:00.860 --> 05:05:05.660
Not James. A little girl in a woman's body in an armored space suit, scared out of her wits.

05:05:06.620 --> 05:05:10.780
The grunt nudged her curled-up body back into our company. Bates took it gently.

05:05:11.420 --> 05:05:15.900
Susan? Come back, Suze. You're safe. The grunts hovered restlessly,

05:05:15.900 --> 05:05:21.260
alert in every direction, pretending everything was under control. Bates spared me a glance.

05:05:21.260 --> 05:05:24.540
Take Isaac and turn back to James. Susan?

05:05:26.060 --> 05:05:29.580
No. Whispered a small voice. A little girl's voice.

05:05:30.460 --> 05:05:31.740
Michelle? Is that you?

05:05:32.780 --> 05:05:37.660
There was a thing, the little girl said. It grabbed me. It grabbed my leg.

05:05:38.460 --> 05:05:42.140
We're out of here. Bates pulled the gang back along the passage.

05:05:42.140 --> 05:05:44.780
One grunt lingered, watching the whole. The other took point.

05:05:45.420 --> 05:05:48.780
It's gone, Bates said gently. There's nothing there now. See the feed?

05:05:49.500 --> 05:05:55.340
You can't see it, Michelle whispered. It's in... it's invisible.

05:05:56.940 --> 05:06:02.140
The septum receded around a curve as we retreated. The whole torn through its center watched us,

05:06:02.140 --> 05:06:07.580
like the ragged pupil of some great unblinking eye. It stayed empty as long as it had

05:06:07.580 --> 05:06:11.180
stayed in sight. Nothing came out after us, nothing we could see.

05:06:12.220 --> 05:06:17.020
A thought began cycling through my head. Some half-assed eulogy stolen from an eavesdropped

05:06:17.020 --> 05:06:23.900
confessional. Tries I might, I couldn't shut it down. Isaac Spindle hadn't made the semi-finals after all.

05:06:29.820 --> 05:06:34.140
Susan James came back to us on the way up. Isaac Spindle did not.

05:06:34.300 --> 05:06:40.300
We stripped wordlessly in the Deacon Balloon. Bates, first out of her suit, reached for Spindle,

05:06:40.300 --> 05:06:45.500
but the gang stopped her with a hand and a head shake. Persona segwayed into one another as

05:06:45.500 --> 05:06:51.260
they stripped the body. Susan removed helmet and backpack and breastplate. Cruncher peeled away

05:06:51.260 --> 05:06:56.060
the silvery-ledded skin from collar to toe. Sasha stripped the jumpsuit and left the pale

05:06:56.060 --> 05:07:01.820
flesh naked and exposed. Except for the gloves. They left his feedback gloves in place, their

05:07:01.820 --> 05:07:07.500
fingertips forever tactile, the flesh inside forever numb. Through it all Spindle stared

05:07:07.500 --> 05:07:12.620
unblinking beneath the hole in his forehead. His glazed eyes focused on distant quasars.

05:07:13.580 --> 05:07:17.340
I expected Michelle to appear in her turn and close them, but she never did.

05:07:19.260 --> 05:07:23.020
You have eyes, but you do not see. Jesus then Azorian.

05:07:24.540 --> 05:07:30.140
I don't know how to feel about this, I thought. He was a good man. He was decent. He was kind to me,

05:07:30.140 --> 05:07:35.100
even when he didn't know I was listening in. I didn't know him long. He wasn't a friend exactly,

05:07:35.100 --> 05:07:42.540
but still. I should miss him. I should mourn. I should feel more than this sick, sinking fear

05:07:42.540 --> 05:07:50.060
that I could be next. So Dosty hadn't wasted any time. Spindle's replacement met us as we emerged,

05:07:50.060 --> 05:07:54.540
freshly thawed Nicotine sent him. The rehydration of his flesh was ongoing.

05:07:55.100 --> 05:07:59.820
Saline bladders clung to each thigh, although it would never erase the sharpness of his features.

05:08:00.380 --> 05:08:04.380
His bones cracked when he moved. He looked past me and took the body.

05:08:05.100 --> 05:08:12.540
Susan, Michelle, I… the gang turned away. He coughed, began fumbling a body condom over the corpse.

05:08:13.260 --> 05:08:14.940
Sldosty wants everyone in the drum.

05:08:15.900 --> 05:08:22.060
We're hot, Bates said. Even cut short, the excursion had piled up a lethal seaward count.

05:08:22.060 --> 05:08:25.820
Faint nausea tickled the back of my throat. Decontaminate later.

05:08:26.540 --> 05:08:30.540
One long pull of a zipper and Spindle was gone, engulfed in an oily gray shroud.

05:08:31.180 --> 05:08:35.900
You, he turned in my direction, pointed at the scorched holes in my dump suit, with me.

05:08:37.740 --> 05:08:43.660
Robert Cunningham. Another prototype. Dark-haired, hollow-cheeked, a jaw you could use as a ruler.

05:08:44.220 --> 05:08:46.940
Both smoother and harsher than the man he'd replaced.

05:08:47.900 --> 05:08:52.300
Where Spindle had ticked and jerked as if static-charged, Cunningham's face held

05:08:52.300 --> 05:08:56.700
all the expression of a waxed dummies. The wet-wear that ran those muscles had been

05:08:56.700 --> 05:09:01.900
press-gangued into other pursuits. Even the tremors that afflicted the rest of the body were muted,

05:09:01.900 --> 05:09:04.540
soothed by the nicotine he drew with every second breath.

05:09:05.420 --> 05:09:10.300
He held no cigarette now. He held only the shrouded body of his hard luck primary in his

05:09:10.300 --> 05:09:14.060
ongoing, fleshly thawed distaste for the ship's synthesis.

05:09:14.300 --> 05:09:16.460
His fingers trembled.

05:09:17.820 --> 05:09:22.220
Bates and the gang moved silently up the spine. Cunningham and I followed,

05:09:22.220 --> 05:09:27.820
guiding the shroud of Spindle between us. My leg and side were stinging again now that Cunningham

05:09:27.820 --> 05:09:32.300
had reminded them to. There wouldn't be much he could do about them, though. The beams would

05:09:32.300 --> 05:09:39.980
have cauterized the flesh on their way through. And if they'd hit anything vital, I'd have been

05:09:39.980 --> 05:09:46.300
dead already. At the hatch we broke into single file. Spindle first, Cunningham pushing at his heels.

05:09:51.660 --> 05:09:56.140
By the time I emerged into the drum, Bates and the gang were already down on deck and taking

05:09:56.140 --> 05:10:01.180
their usual seats. Siddhasthi, in the flesh, watched them from the end of the conference table.

05:10:01.980 --> 05:10:06.620
His eyes were naked. From this angle, the soft, full-strecked-room light of the drum

05:10:06.620 --> 05:10:11.340
washed the shine from them. If you didn't look too closely for too long, you might almost think

05:10:11.340 --> 05:10:17.820
those eyes were human. Biomed had been spun down from my arrival. Cunningham pointed to a

05:10:17.820 --> 05:10:22.780
diagnostic couch on a section of the still deck that had served as our infirmary. I floated over

05:10:22.780 --> 05:10:27.820
and strapped myself in. Two meters away, past a waist-high guardrail that had been risen from

05:10:27.820 --> 05:10:33.180
the deck, the rest of the drum rolled smoothly past. It slung Bates and the gang and Siddhasthi

05:10:33.180 --> 05:10:39.100
around like weights on a string. I tapped consensus to hear them. James was speaking,

05:10:39.100 --> 05:10:44.060
quietly without expression. I noticed a new pattern in the form constant, something in the

05:10:44.060 --> 05:10:49.660
grating. It looked like a signal. It got stronger as I went down the tunnel. I followed it. I blacked

05:10:49.660 --> 05:10:55.260
out. I don't remember anything more until we were on our way back. Michelle filled me in as much as

05:10:55.260 --> 05:11:01.980
she could. That's all I know. Sorry. A hundred degrees away in the no-G zone, Cunningham maneuvered

05:11:01.980 --> 05:11:05.340
his predecessor into a coffin with different options than those up front.

05:11:09.260 --> 05:11:14.540
I wondered if it would embark on an autopsy during the debriefing. I wondered if we'd be able to hear

05:11:14.540 --> 05:11:22.620
the sounds it made. Sasha, Siddhasthi said. Yeah? Sasha's trademark drawl infected the voice.

05:11:23.740 --> 05:11:29.740
I was writing, Mom. Went deaf dumb and stark fucking blind when she passed out. I tried to take over

05:11:29.740 --> 05:11:34.860
but something was blocking me. Michelle, I guess. Never thought she had it in her. I couldn't even see.

05:11:35.820 --> 05:11:41.340
But you don't lose consciousness. I was awake the whole time, far as I know, just completely in the

05:11:41.340 --> 05:11:48.300
dark. Smell, tactile. I could feel it when Michelle pissed in the suit, but I didn't notice anything

05:11:48.300 --> 05:11:53.580
else. Cunningham was back at my side. The inevitable cigarette had appeared between his lips.

05:11:54.380 --> 05:11:57.980
Nothing touches you, the vampire surmised. Nothing grabs your leg.

05:11:58.940 --> 05:12:04.700
No, Sasha said. She didn't believe Michelle's stories about invisible monsters. None of us did.

05:12:04.700 --> 05:12:08.780
Why bother when dementia could so easily explain anything we experienced?

05:12:10.060 --> 05:12:16.300
Cruncher. Don't know anything. I still wasn't used to the maleness of the voice now emanating from

05:12:16.300 --> 05:12:20.940
James Throat. Cruncher was a workaholic. He hardly ever surfaced in mixed company.

05:12:21.660 --> 05:12:25.020
You're there, Sadastia reminded him. You must remember some...

05:12:25.580 --> 05:12:30.300
Mom sent me patterns to parse. I was working on them. I'm still working on them, he added

05:12:30.300 --> 05:12:36.700
pointedly. I didn't notice anything. Is that all? I'd never been able to get a good read on him.

05:12:37.340 --> 05:12:41.980
Sometimes Cruncher seemed to have more in common with the dozens of non-conscious modules working

05:12:41.980 --> 05:12:45.740
in James' head than the sentient hubs comprising the rest of the gang.

05:12:46.460 --> 05:12:50.060
You feel nothing? Sadastia pressed. Just the patterns.

05:12:51.100 --> 05:12:57.180
Anything significant? Standard phenomath spirals and gradings, but I haven't finished. Can I go now?

05:12:57.900 --> 05:13:03.020
Yes, call Michelle, please. Cunningham stabbed at my wounds with anabolizers,

05:13:03.020 --> 05:13:06.220
muttering to himself. Faint blue smoke curled between us.

05:13:07.260 --> 05:13:12.620
Isaac found some tumors, he observed. I nodded and coughed. My throat was sore.

05:13:12.620 --> 05:13:15.420
The nausea had grown heavy enough to sink below my diaphragm.

05:13:16.460 --> 05:13:18.380
Michelle, Sadastia repeated.

05:13:19.420 --> 05:13:24.060
I see some more here, Cunningham continued, along the bottom of your brain pan. Only a few

05:13:24.060 --> 05:13:29.340
dozen cells so far, they're not worth burning yet. Here, Michelle's voice was barely audible,

05:13:29.340 --> 05:13:33.660
even through consensus. But at least it was the voice of an adult. I'm here.

05:13:34.780 --> 05:13:35.980
What do you remember, please?

05:13:36.940 --> 05:13:43.420
I... I felt... I was just writing mom, and then she was gone, and there was no one else,

05:13:43.420 --> 05:13:47.820
so I had to take over. Do you see the septum close?

05:13:48.940 --> 05:13:53.420
Not really. I felt it going dark, but when I turned around we were already trapped,

05:13:53.420 --> 05:13:58.540
and then I felt something behind me. It wasn't loud or harsh, it just sort of bumped,

05:13:58.620 --> 05:14:06.540
and it grabbed me and... and... I'm sorry, she said after a moment. I'm a bit woozy.

05:14:08.140 --> 05:14:14.940
Sadastia waited. Isaac, Michelle whispered, he... yes, a pause.

05:14:15.980 --> 05:14:22.380
We're very sorry about that. Maybe... can he be fixed? No, there's brain damage.

05:14:23.420 --> 05:14:27.980
There was something like sympathy in the vampire's voice, the practice defection of an

05:14:27.980 --> 05:14:33.260
accomplished mimic. There was something else too, an all but imperceptible hunger,

05:14:33.260 --> 05:14:39.820
a subtle edge of temptation. I don't think anyone heard it but me. We were sick and getting sicker.

05:14:40.540 --> 05:14:42.460
Predators are drawn to the weak and injured.

05:14:43.820 --> 05:14:48.460
Michelle had fallen silent again, when she continued her voice only faltered a little.

05:14:49.420 --> 05:14:55.420
I can't tell you much, it grabbed me, it let me go. I went to pieces and I can't explain why

05:14:55.500 --> 05:15:02.140
except that fucking place just does things to you and I was... weak. I'm sorry, there's not much

05:15:02.140 --> 05:15:10.220
else to tell you. Thank you, Sadastia said after a long moment. Can I... I'd like to leave if that's

05:15:10.220 --> 05:15:18.140
okay? Yes, Sadastia said. Michelle sank below the surface as the commons rotated past. I didn't see

05:15:18.140 --> 05:15:24.140
who took her place. The grunts didn't see anything, Bates remarked. By the time we broke through the

05:15:24.140 --> 05:15:29.660
septum the tunnel behind was empty. Any bogey would have had plenty of time to hightail, Cunningham

05:15:29.660 --> 05:15:35.420
said. He planted his feet on the deck and grabbed a handhold, the sub-drum began to move. I drifted

05:15:35.420 --> 05:15:40.940
obliquely against my restraints. I don't disagree, Bates said, but if there's anything we've learned

05:15:40.940 --> 05:15:47.900
about that place it's that we can't trust our senses. Trust Michelle's, Sadastia said. He opened

05:15:47.900 --> 05:15:53.340
a window as I grew heavier, a grunt's eye view of a fuzzy bright blob weaving behind the translucent

05:15:53.420 --> 05:15:58.540
waxed paper fibers of the skin septum. James headlight from the wrong side of the barrier.

05:15:59.260 --> 05:16:03.420
The image wobbled a bit as the drone staggered through some local pocket of magnetism then

05:16:03.420 --> 05:16:09.900
replayed. Wobbled, replayed. A six second loop. See something next to the gang.

05:16:11.340 --> 05:16:16.780
Non-vampires saw no such thing. Sadastia froze the image evidently realizing as much.

05:16:17.500 --> 05:16:21.180
Diffraction patterns aren't consistent with a single light source in open space.

05:16:21.820 --> 05:16:27.180
I see dimmer elements, reflective elements. Two dark objects close together, similar size,

05:16:27.180 --> 05:16:32.220
scattering light here. A cursor appeared, two utterly nondescript points on the image,

05:16:32.860 --> 05:16:36.380
and here. One's the gang, the other's unaccounted for.

05:16:37.500 --> 05:16:42.540
Just a minute, Cunningham said. If you can see through all that, why didn't Su-

05:16:42.540 --> 05:16:44.220
why didn't Michelle see anything?

05:16:45.180 --> 05:16:50.540
Th-Synthesiac, Sarastia reminded him. You see. She feels.

05:16:51.980 --> 05:16:55.420
Biomed jerked slightly, locking into sink spin with the drum.

05:16:56.220 --> 05:17:01.420
The guardrail sank back onto the deck. Often some far off corner, something without eyes,

05:17:01.420 --> 05:17:03.020
watched me with it and watching it.

05:17:04.140 --> 05:17:07.660
Shit, Bates whispered. There's someone home.

05:17:10.380 --> 05:17:13.900
They never really talked like that, by the way. You'd hear gibberish.

05:17:14.220 --> 05:17:18.860
Half dozen languages, whole battle of personal idioms, if I spoke in their real voices.

05:17:19.740 --> 05:17:23.900
Some of the simpler ticks make it through. Sasha's good-natured belligerence,

05:17:23.900 --> 05:17:29.100
Sarastia's aversion to past tense. Cunningham lost most of his gender pronouns to an

05:17:29.100 --> 05:17:33.180
unforeseen glitch during the work on his temporal lobe, but it went beyond that.

05:17:33.740 --> 05:17:38.860
The whole of them threw English and Hindi and Hadzane into every sing- every second sentence.

05:17:38.860 --> 05:17:43.100
No real scientist would allow their thoughts to be hamstrung by the conceptual limitations

05:17:43.100 --> 05:17:47.740
of a single language. Other times they acted almost as synthesis in their own right,

05:17:48.300 --> 05:17:51.660
conversing in grunts and gestures that would be meaningless to any baseline.

05:17:52.460 --> 05:17:57.340
It's not so much that the bleeding edge lacks social skills, it's just that once you get past

05:17:57.340 --> 05:18:04.780
a certain point, formal speech is too damn slow. Except for Susan James. The walking contradiction,

05:18:04.780 --> 05:18:10.220
the woman so devoted to communication as unifier that she'd cut her own brain into disunified

05:18:10.220 --> 05:18:15.100
chunks to make the point. She was the only one who ever seemed to care who she was talking to.

05:18:15.820 --> 05:18:20.860
The other spoke only for themselves, even when they spoke to each other. Even James's other

05:18:20.860 --> 05:18:25.580
cores would speak their own minds in their own way and let everyone else translate as best they

05:18:25.580 --> 05:18:31.180
could. It wasn't a problem, any of her own enthusiasts could read everyone else. But that

05:18:31.180 --> 05:18:37.580
didn't matter to Susan James. She fit each of her words to their intended recipient. She accommodated.

05:18:38.540 --> 05:18:43.660
I am a conduit. I exist to bridge the gap and I'd bridge nothing if I only told you what these

05:18:43.660 --> 05:18:49.260
people said. So I am telling you what they meant and it will mean as much to you as you can handle.

05:18:50.300 --> 05:18:55.260
Except for Susan James, linguist and ringleader, who I trust to speak for herself.

05:19:01.100 --> 05:19:06.220
Fifteen minutes to Apogee, maximum safe distance in case Rorschach decided to hit back.

05:19:07.100 --> 05:19:11.580
Far below the artifacts magnetic field pressed into Ben's atmosphere like God's little finger.

05:19:12.220 --> 05:19:17.500
Great dark thunderheads converged behind it. Turbulent moon-sized curlicues collided in its

05:19:17.500 --> 05:19:23.340
wake. Fifteen minutes to Apogee and Bates was still hoping Sarasthi would change his mind.

05:19:24.460 --> 05:19:30.700
In a way this was her fault. If she had just treated this new travail as one more cross to bear,

05:19:30.700 --> 05:19:35.980
perhaps things would have gone on more or less as before. There would have been some faint hope

05:19:35.980 --> 05:19:41.180
that Sarasthi would let us grit our teeth and keep on going, besieged now by spring-loaded

05:19:41.180 --> 05:19:45.580
trap doors as well as the usual gauntlet of sieverts and magnets and monsters from the Id.

05:19:46.620 --> 05:19:52.220
But Bates had made an issue out of it. It wasn't just another piece of shit in the sewer to her.

05:19:52.220 --> 05:19:57.500
It was the one that clogged the pipe. We're on the brink as it is, just surviving the baseline

05:19:57.500 --> 05:20:02.300
environment of this thing. If it started taking deliberate countermeasures, I don't see how we

05:20:02.300 --> 05:20:08.140
can risk it. Fourteen minutes to Apogee and Amanda Bates was still regretting those words.

05:20:09.100 --> 05:20:13.740
On previous expeditions we'd charted 26 septa in various stages of development.

05:20:14.380 --> 05:20:20.460
We'd X-rayed them. We'd done ultrasound. We'd watched them ooze their way across passages

05:20:20.460 --> 05:20:25.980
or ebb slowly back into the walls. The iris that had snapped shut behind the gang of four had been

05:20:25.980 --> 05:20:35.020
a whole different animal. And what are the odds that the first one with a hair trigger just happened

05:20:35.020 --> 05:20:41.100
also come with anti-laser prismatics? That was no routine growth event. That thing was set for us.

05:20:42.140 --> 05:20:48.780
Set by, that was the other thing, 13 minutes to Apogee and Bates was worried about the tenants.

05:20:49.340 --> 05:20:58.220
It had always been breaking and entering, of course. That much hadn't changed. But when we'd

05:20:58.220 --> 05:21:02.700
jimmied the lock, we thought we were vandalizing an empty summer cottage still under construction.

05:21:03.420 --> 05:21:08.300
We thought the owners would be out of the picture for a while. We hadn't been expecting one of them

05:21:08.300 --> 05:21:13.980
to catch us on his way to take a late night piss. And now that one had and vanished into the labyrinth,

05:21:14.700 --> 05:21:19.580
we're not sure what weapons it might keep stashed under the pillow. Those septic could spring on us at any time.

05:21:19.580 --> 05:21:24.300
How many are there? Aren't they fixed or portable? We can't proceed without knowing these things.

05:21:25.340 --> 05:21:29.100
At first, Bates had been surprised and delighted when Sarashti agreed with her.

05:21:29.980 --> 05:21:35.180
12 minutes to Apogee. From this high ground, well above the static, Thesias peered down through

05:21:35.180 --> 05:21:40.220
war shocks, wrenched and twisted anatomy to keep rock-steady eyes on the tiny wound we'd burned

05:21:40.220 --> 05:21:45.820
in its side. Our limpid tent covered it like a blister. Inside, Jack fetus a second first-person

05:21:45.820 --> 05:21:52.460
view of the unfolding experiment. Sir, we know roar shock is inhabited. Do we want to risk further

05:21:52.460 --> 05:21:58.940
provoking the inhabitants? Do we want to risk killing them? Sarashti hadn't quite looked at her and

05:21:58.940 --> 05:22:04.620
hadn't quite spoken. If he had, he might have said, I do not understand how meat like you survive to

05:22:04.620 --> 05:22:11.500
adulthood. 11 minutes to Apogee and Amanda Bates was lamenting the fact, not for the first time,

05:22:11.500 --> 05:22:17.180
that this mission was not under military jurisdiction. We were waiting for maximum

05:22:17.180 --> 05:22:22.220
distance before performing the experiment. Roar shock might interpret this as a hostile act,

05:22:22.220 --> 05:22:25.980
Sarashti had conceded in a voice that contained no trace of irony whatsoever.

05:22:26.700 --> 05:22:32.700
Now he stood before us, watching consensus play on the table. Reflections rived across his naked

05:22:32.940 --> 05:22:38.860
eyes, not quite masking the deeper reflections behind them. 10 minutes to Apogee. Susan James

05:22:38.860 --> 05:22:44.300
was wishing that Cunningham would put out that goddamn cigarette. The smoke stank on its way to

05:22:44.300 --> 05:22:49.820
the ventilators, and anyway it wasn't necessary. It was just an anachronistic affectation, an

05:22:49.820 --> 05:22:54.860
attention-getting device. If he needed the nicotine, a patch could have soothed his tremors just as

05:22:54.860 --> 05:23:00.620
easily without the smoke and the stink. That wasn't all she was thinking, though. She was wondering

05:23:00.620 --> 05:23:04.940
why Cunningham had been summoned to Sarashti's quarters earlier in the shift, why he'd looked

05:23:04.940 --> 05:23:12.140
at her so strangely afterwards. I wondered about that myself. A quick check on the consensus timestamps

05:23:12.140 --> 05:23:17.180
showed that her medical file had been accessed during that period. I checked those stats,

05:23:17.180 --> 05:23:22.460
let the shapes bounce between hemispheres, part of my brain locked on elevated oxytocin,

05:23:22.460 --> 05:23:28.620
as the probable reason for that conference. There was an 82% chance that James had become too

05:23:28.620 --> 05:23:34.700
trusting for Sarashti's liking. I had no idea how I knew that. I never did.

05:23:36.220 --> 05:23:41.980
9 minutes to Apogee. Barely a molecule of Rorschach's atmosphere had been lost on our account.

05:23:42.620 --> 05:23:47.260
That was about to change. Our view of base camp split like a dividing bacterium.

05:23:47.900 --> 05:23:52.860
One window now focused on the limpet tent, the other on a wide-angle tactical enhance of the

05:23:52.860 --> 05:24:00.620
space around it. 8 minutes to Apogee. Sarashti pulled the plug. Down on Rorschach, our tent

05:24:00.620 --> 05:24:06.860
burst like a bug beneath a boot. A geyser erupted from the wound. A snowstorm swirled its edges.

05:24:06.860 --> 05:24:12.940
Its charged curlicues intricate as lace. Atmosphere gushed into vacuum, spread thin, crystallized.

05:24:13.660 --> 05:24:17.740
Briefly, the space around base camp sparkled. It was almost beautiful.

05:24:17.980 --> 05:24:23.580
Bates didn't think it was beautiful at all. She watched that bleeding wound with a face as

05:24:23.580 --> 05:24:28.940
expressionless as Cunningham's, but her job was cleansed onto tetanus. Her eyes darted

05:24:28.940 --> 05:24:34.220
between views, watching for things gasping in the shadows. Rorschach convulsed.

05:24:37.020 --> 05:24:42.300
Vast trunks and artery shuttered, a seismic tremor radiating out along the structure.

05:24:43.100 --> 05:24:47.020
The epicenter began to twist, a vast segment rotating on its axis,

05:24:47.020 --> 05:24:53.020
the breach midway along its length. Stress lines appeared, where the length rotated sheared against

05:24:53.020 --> 05:24:57.260
the lengths to either side that didn't. The structure seemed to soften and stretch there,

05:24:57.260 --> 05:25:01.740
constricting like a great elongate balloon, torquing itself into sausage links.

05:25:05.260 --> 05:25:10.220
Sarashti clicked. Cats made something like that sound when they spied a bird on the far

05:25:10.220 --> 05:25:16.140
side of a window pane. Consensus groaned with the sound of world scraping against each other,

05:25:16.140 --> 05:25:19.180
telemetry from the on-site sensors, their ears to the ground.

05:25:19.980 --> 05:25:25.900
Jack's camera controls had frozen again. The image it sent was canted and grainy. The pick-up

05:25:25.900 --> 05:25:31.340
stared blankly at the edge of the hole we'd bored into the underworld. The groaning subsided.

05:25:32.060 --> 05:25:36.860
A final faint cloud of crystal and stardust dissipated into space, barely visible even on

05:25:36.860 --> 05:25:45.100
max enhance. No bodies, none visible anyway. Sudden motion at base camp. At first I thought it was

05:25:45.100 --> 05:25:50.620
static on Jack's feed, playing along lines of high contrast, but no, something was definitely

05:25:50.620 --> 05:25:55.740
moving along the edges of the hole we'd burned. Something almost wriggled there, a thousand

05:25:55.740 --> 05:26:00.300
degree mycelia extruding from the cut surface and writhing slowly into the darkness.

05:26:01.100 --> 05:26:07.180
It's... huh, Bates said. Triggered by the pressure drop, I guess. That's one way to seal a breach.

05:26:08.460 --> 05:26:12.540
Two weeks after we wounded it, Rorschach had begun to heal itself.

05:26:14.060 --> 05:26:20.540
Apigee behind us now. All downhill from here. Thesias began the long drop back into enemy

05:26:20.540 --> 05:26:24.620
territory. Doesn't use scepta, Sarasti said.

05:26:28.380 --> 05:26:35.180
My genes done gone and tricked my brain by making fucking feel so great. That's how the little creeps

05:26:35.180 --> 05:26:42.140
attain their plan to fucking replicate. But brains got tricks itself, you see. To get the bang, but

05:26:42.140 --> 05:26:50.300
not the bite. I got this here vasectomy. My genes can fuck themselves tonight. The arselectors

05:26:50.620 --> 05:26:59.660
trunclade. First person sex, real sex, as Chelsea insisted on calling it, was an acquired taste.

05:27:00.220 --> 05:27:04.940
Jagged breathing, the raw slap and stink of sweaty skin full of pores and blemishes,

05:27:05.500 --> 05:27:10.700
a whole other person with a whole other set of demands and dislikes. There was definite

05:27:10.700 --> 05:27:15.580
animal peel, no doubt about it. This was, after all, how we'd done it for millions of years.

05:27:16.540 --> 05:27:20.940
But this, the third world calamity, had always carried an element of struggle,

05:27:20.940 --> 05:27:26.540
of asynchronous patterns and conflict. There was no convergence here. There was only the rhythm of

05:27:26.540 --> 05:27:31.420
bodies and collision, a struggle for dominance, each trying to force the other into sync.

05:27:32.940 --> 05:27:38.700
Chelsea regarded it as love in its purest form. I came to think of it as hand to hand combat.

05:27:39.340 --> 05:27:44.380
Before, whether fucking creations from my own menu or slip on skins from someone else's,

05:27:45.020 --> 05:27:48.780
I had always selected the contrast and the res, the texture and the attitude,

05:27:49.420 --> 05:27:54.300
the bodily functions, the resistance of competing desires, the endless foreplay that wears your

05:27:54.300 --> 05:28:00.380
tongue to the root and leaves your face sticky and glistening. Just kinks today. Options for the

05:28:00.380 --> 05:28:06.380
masochistic. But there were no options with Chelsea. With her everything came standard.

05:28:07.340 --> 05:28:11.740
I indulged her. I guess I was no more patient with her perversions than she was with my

05:28:11.820 --> 05:28:17.580
ineptitude at them. Other things made it worth the effort. Chelsea would argue about anything under

05:28:17.580 --> 05:28:24.460
the sun. Ryan insightful and curious as a cat. She would pounce without warning. Retired to the

05:28:24.460 --> 05:28:31.420
redundant majority, she still took such simple joy in the very act of being alive. She was impulsive

05:28:31.420 --> 05:28:41.260
and impetuous. She cared about people. Pag. Me. She wanted to know me. She wanted in. That was proving

05:28:41.340 --> 05:28:48.380
to be a problem. We could try it again. She said once in an aftermath of sweat and pheromones.

05:28:49.260 --> 05:28:53.900
And you won't even remember what you were so upset about. You won't even remember you were upset if

05:28:53.900 --> 05:28:59.180
you don't want to. I smiled and looked away. Suddenly the planes of her face were coarse and

05:28:59.180 --> 05:29:07.580
unappealing. How many times is that now? Eight? Nine? I just want you to be happy, Sig. True happiness

05:29:07.660 --> 05:29:13.340
is one hell of a gift. And I can give it to you if you'll let me. You don't want me happy, I said

05:29:13.340 --> 05:29:20.300
pleasantly. You want me customized. She mmmed into the hollow of my throat for a moment. Then

05:29:21.100 --> 05:29:25.740
what? You just want to change me into something more more accommodating.

05:29:26.940 --> 05:29:33.900
Chelsea lifted her head. Look at me. I turned my head. She'd shut down the chromatophores in

05:29:33.980 --> 05:29:37.660
her cheek. The tattoo transplanted, fluttered now on her shoulder.

05:29:38.380 --> 05:29:45.340
Look at my eyes, Chelsea said. I looked at the imperfect skin around them, at the capillaries

05:29:45.340 --> 05:29:50.620
wriggling across the whites. I felt distant amusement that such flawed decaying organs were

05:29:50.620 --> 05:29:58.540
still able to hypnotize me on occasion. Now, Chelsea said, what do you mean by that? I shrugged.

05:29:59.340 --> 05:30:03.100
You keep pretending this is a partnership. We both know it's a competition.

05:30:04.140 --> 05:30:10.380
A competition. You're trying to manipulate me into playing by your rules. What rules?

05:30:11.740 --> 05:30:16.140
The way you want the relationship run. I don't blame you, Chelsea, not in the least.

05:30:16.700 --> 05:30:21.260
We've been trying to manipulate each other for as long as, hell, it's not even human nature,

05:30:21.260 --> 05:30:27.900
it's mammalian. I don't believe it, she shook her head. Ropey tendrils of hair swung across her face.

05:30:28.780 --> 05:30:33.500
It's the middle of the 21st century and you're hitting me with this war of the sexes bullshit?

05:30:34.940 --> 05:30:39.660
Granted, your tweaks are a pretty radical iteration. Get right in there and reprogram

05:30:39.660 --> 05:30:45.420
your mate for optimum servility. You actually think I'm trying to housebreak you. You think

05:30:45.420 --> 05:30:50.060
I'm trying to train you like a puppy. You're just doing what comes naturally.

05:30:51.260 --> 05:30:56.460
I can't believe you'd pulled a shit on me. I thought you valued honesty in relationships.

05:30:57.260 --> 05:31:00.540
What relationship? According to you, there's no such thing. This is just

05:31:01.260 --> 05:31:07.420
mutual rape or something. That's what relationships are. Don't pull that shit on me.

05:31:08.220 --> 05:31:14.540
She sat up, swung her feet over the edge of the bed, putting her back to me. I know how I feel.

05:31:14.540 --> 05:31:18.620
If I know anything, I know that much. And I only wanted to make you happy.

05:31:19.660 --> 05:31:24.700
I know you believe that, I said gently. I know it doesn't feel like a strategy.

05:31:24.700 --> 05:31:28.620
Nothing does when it's wired that deeply. It just feels right. It feels natural.

05:31:29.260 --> 05:31:36.700
It's nature's trick. It's someone's fucking trick. I sat up next to her, let my shoulder brush hers.

05:31:37.340 --> 05:31:44.060
She leaned away. I know this stuff, I said after a while. I know how people work. It's my job.

05:31:45.420 --> 05:31:50.380
It was hers too, for that matter. Nobody who sliced brains for a living could possibly be

05:31:50.380 --> 05:31:56.380
unaware of all that basic wiring in the subbasement. Chelsea had simply chosen to ignore it. To have

05:31:56.380 --> 05:32:01.420
admitted anything would have compromised her righteous anger. I could have pointed that out too,

05:32:01.420 --> 05:32:05.980
I suppose, but I knew how much stress the system could take and I wasn't ready to test it to

05:32:05.980 --> 05:32:12.380
destruction. I didn't want to lose her. I didn't want to lose that feeling of safety. That sense

05:32:12.380 --> 05:32:18.700
that it made a difference whether I lived or died. I only wanted her to back off a bit. I only wanted

05:32:18.700 --> 05:32:26.140
room to breathe. You can be such a reptile sometimes, she said. Mission accomplished.

05:32:29.340 --> 05:32:34.460
Our first approach had been all caution and safety margins. This time we came in like a

05:32:34.460 --> 05:32:40.620
strike force. Silla burned towards a workshop at over two Gs, its trajectory a smooth and predictable

05:32:40.620 --> 05:32:46.220
arc ending at the ruptured base camp. It may have even landed there for all I know. Perhaps Sotosti

05:32:46.220 --> 05:32:51.820
had too burdened the mission, programmed the shuttle for some collecting of its own. If so,

05:32:51.820 --> 05:32:57.100
it wouldn't land with us on board. Silla spat us into space almost 50 kilometers short of the new

05:32:57.100 --> 05:33:02.060
beachhead, left us naked and plummeting on some wireframe contraption with barely enough reaction

05:33:02.060 --> 05:33:08.780
mass for a soft landing and a quick getaway. We didn't even have control over that. Success

05:33:08.780 --> 05:33:13.820
depended on unpredictability and how better to ensure than to not even know ourselves that we

05:33:13.820 --> 05:33:23.260
were doing. Sotosti's logic. Vampire logic. We could follow it partway, the colossal deformation

05:33:23.260 --> 05:33:28.380
that had sealed Warshawk's breach was so much slower, so much more expensive than the drop gate

05:33:28.380 --> 05:33:33.580
that had trapped the gang. The fact that drop gates hadn't been used implied that they took

05:33:33.580 --> 05:33:39.500
climb to deploy. To redistribute necessary mass perhaps, or spring load its reflexes.

05:33:40.220 --> 05:33:46.220
That gave us a window. We could still venture into the den so long as the lions couldn't predict

05:33:46.220 --> 05:33:51.660
our destination and set traps in advance. So long as we got out again before they could set them

05:33:51.660 --> 05:33:59.180
afterwards. 37 minutes, Sotosti had said, and none of us could fathom how he'd come to that number.

05:34:00.140 --> 05:34:07.420
Only Bates stared to ask aloud and he merely glinted at her. You can't follow. Vampire logic.

05:34:07.660 --> 05:34:13.580
From an obvious premise to an opaque conclusion. Our lives depended on it.

05:34:15.180 --> 05:34:19.660
The retros followed some pre-programmed algorithm that made it Newton with the role of the dice.

05:34:20.300 --> 05:34:25.020
Our vector wasn't completely random. Once we'd eliminated raceways and growth zones,

05:34:25.020 --> 05:34:29.580
areas without line of sight escape routes, dead ends and unbranched segments,

05:34:29.580 --> 05:34:35.020
boring, Sotosti had said, dismissing them. Barely 10% of the artifact remained in the running.

05:34:35.980 --> 05:34:40.380
Now we dropped towards a warren of brambles eight kilometers from our original landing site.

05:34:41.180 --> 05:34:45.580
Here in the midst of our final approach, there was no way that even we could predict our precise

05:34:45.580 --> 05:34:55.020
point of impact. If Rorschach could, it deserved to win. We fell. Ridged spires and gnarled limbs

05:34:55.020 --> 05:34:59.580
sectioned the sky wherever I looked, cut the distance darscape and the imminent super-Jovian

05:34:59.580 --> 05:35:04.940
into a jagged mosaic vein in black. Three kilometers away or 30, the tip of some swollen

05:35:04.940 --> 05:35:09.820
extremity burst in a silent explosion of charged particles, a distant fog of ruptured,

05:35:09.820 --> 05:35:15.660
freezing atmosphere. Even as it faded, I could make out wisps and streamers swirling into complex

05:35:15.660 --> 05:35:21.260
spirals, Rorschach's magnetic field sculpting the artifact's very breath into radioactive sleet.

05:35:22.940 --> 05:35:28.380
I'd never seen it with naked eyes before. I felt like an insect on starry midwinter's night,

05:35:28.380 --> 05:35:35.420
falling through the aftermath of a forest fire. The sled fired its brakes. I snapped back against

05:35:35.420 --> 05:35:39.420
the webbing of my harness, bumped against the rebounding armored body next to me.

05:35:40.220 --> 05:35:47.100
Sasha. Only Sasha, I remembered. Cunningham had sedated the rest of them, left this one core

05:35:47.100 --> 05:35:53.340
lonely and alone in the group body. I hadn't even realized that was possible with multiple personalities.

05:35:54.220 --> 05:35:59.020
She stared back at me from behind her faceplate. None of her services showed through the suit.

05:35:59.740 --> 05:36:04.060
I could see nothing in her eyes. This was happening so often these days.

05:36:05.740 --> 05:36:10.220
Cunningham was not with us. Nobody asked why when Sadastia signed the births.

05:36:11.100 --> 05:36:15.420
The biologist was first among equals now, a backup restored with no other behind him,

05:36:16.060 --> 05:36:22.620
the second least replaceable of our irreplaceable crew. It made me a better bargain. The odds I

05:36:22.620 --> 05:36:28.940
bought had increased to one in three. A silent bump shuttered up the frame. I looked forward again,

05:36:28.940 --> 05:36:33.580
passed baits on the front pallet, passed the anchored drones that flanked her two to each side.

05:36:34.380 --> 05:36:39.500
The sled had launched its assault, a prefab inflatable vestibule, mounted on an explosive

05:36:39.500 --> 05:36:44.220
injection assembly that would punch through Rorschach's skin like a virus penetrating a host cell.

05:36:45.180 --> 05:36:53.500
The spindle-legged contraption dwindled and disappeared from my sight.

05:36:54.300 --> 05:36:58.780
Moments later a pinpoint sodium sun flared and died against the adony landscape ahead.

05:36:59.420 --> 05:37:03.980
Anti-meta charge, so small you could almost count the atoms shot directly into the hull.

05:37:04.860 --> 05:37:07.660
A lot rougher than the tentative foreplay of our first date.

05:37:09.100 --> 05:37:11.820
We landed hard while the vestibule was still inflating.

05:37:12.700 --> 05:37:17.100
The grunts were off the sled an instant before contact, spitting tiny puffs of gas in their

05:37:17.100 --> 05:37:22.540
nozzles, arranging themselves around us in a protective rosette. Bates was up next,

05:37:22.540 --> 05:37:25.980
leaping free of her restraint since sailing directly towards the swelling hab.

05:37:26.940 --> 05:37:32.700
Sasha and I unloaded the fiber off hub, a clamshell drum half a meter thick and three times as wide,

05:37:32.700 --> 05:37:37.020
lugging it between us while one of the grunts slipped through the vestibule's membranous airlock.

05:37:37.740 --> 05:37:41.820
Let's move, people. Bates was hanging off one of the inflatable's handholds.

05:37:42.460 --> 05:37:49.500
Thirty minutes to... she fell silent. I didn't have to ask why. The advanced grunt had positioned

05:37:49.500 --> 05:37:55.340
itself over the newly blasted entrance and sent back its first postcard. Light from below.

05:37:57.740 --> 05:38:02.700
You'd think that would have made it easier. Our kind has always feared the dark. For millions

05:38:02.700 --> 05:38:06.620
of years we huddled in caves and burrows while unseen things snuffled and growled,

05:38:07.180 --> 05:38:12.780
or just waited, silent and undetectable, in the night beyond. You'd think that any light,

05:38:12.780 --> 05:38:17.500
no matter how meagre, might strip away some of the shadows, leave fewer holes to the mind to

05:38:17.500 --> 05:38:26.940
fill with worst imaginings. You'd think. We followed the grunt down into a dim soupy glow like blood

05:38:26.940 --> 05:38:32.300
curdled milk. At first it seemed as though the atmosphere itself was a light, a luminous fog

05:38:32.460 --> 05:38:37.980
that obscured anything more than ten meters distant. An illusion, as it turned out, the tunnel we

05:38:37.980 --> 05:38:44.220
emerged into was about three meters wide and lit by rows of raised glowing dashes, the size and

05:38:44.220 --> 05:38:50.860
approximate shape of human fingers, wound in a loose triple helix around the walls. We'd recorded

05:38:50.860 --> 05:38:55.020
similar ridges at the first sight, although the breaks had not been so pronounced and the ridges

05:38:55.020 --> 05:39:01.500
had been anything but luminous. Stronger than an near-infrared, Bates reported, flashing a spectrum

05:39:01.500 --> 05:39:07.980
to our huds. The air would have been transparent to pit-fipers. It was transparent to sonar.

05:39:11.500 --> 05:39:16.780
The lead grunt sprayed the fog with click-trains and discovered the tunnel widened into some kind

05:39:16.780 --> 05:39:22.780
of chamber 17 meters further along. Squinting in that direction, I could just make out subterranean

05:39:22.780 --> 05:39:27.900
outlines of the mist. I could just make out jawed things, pulling back out of sight.

05:39:28.780 --> 05:39:36.300
Let's go, Bates said. We plugged in the grunts, left one guarding the way out. Each of us took

05:39:36.300 --> 05:39:45.580
another as a guardian angel on point. The machine spoke to our huds via laser link. They spoke to

05:39:45.580 --> 05:39:50.380
each other along stiffened lengths of shielded fiber-op that unspooled from the hub trailing in

05:39:50.380 --> 05:39:56.540
our wake. It was the best available compromise in an environment without any optima. Our tethered

05:39:56.540 --> 05:40:01.180
bodyguards would keep us all in touch during lone excursions around corners or down dead ends.

05:40:02.300 --> 05:40:08.700
Yeah. Lone excursions. Forced to either split the group or cover less ground, we were to split the

05:40:08.700 --> 05:40:15.100
group. We were speed cartographers panning for gold. Everything we did here was an act of faith.

05:40:15.100 --> 05:40:19.740
Faith that the unifying principles of Rorschach's internal architecture could be derived from the

05:40:19.740 --> 05:40:26.060
raw dimensions we'd grab on the run. Faith that Rorschach's internal architecture even had unifying

05:40:26.060 --> 05:40:32.380
principles. Earlier generations had worshipped malign and capricious spirits. Ours put its faith

05:40:32.380 --> 05:40:38.140
in an ordered universe. Here in the Devil's Baklava, it was easy to wonder if our ancestors

05:40:38.140 --> 05:40:44.780
hadn't been closer to the mark. We moved along the tunnel. Our destination resolved to merely

05:40:44.780 --> 05:40:51.180
humanize. Not so much chamber as nexus, a knot of space formed by the convergence of a dozen

05:40:51.180 --> 05:40:57.100
tunnels angling in from different orientations. Ragged meshes of quick silver dots gleamed

05:40:57.100 --> 05:41:02.620
along several glistening surfaces. Shiny protrusions poked through the substrate like a scattershot

05:41:02.620 --> 05:41:08.460
blast of ball bearings pressed into wet clay. I looked at Bates and Sasha. Control panel?

05:41:09.580 --> 05:41:14.540
Bates shrugged. Her drones panned the throats around us, spraying sonar down each.

05:41:15.340 --> 05:41:21.500
My HUD sketched a patchy 3D model from the echoes. Swaths of paint thrown against invisible walls.

05:41:22.620 --> 05:41:27.820
We were dots near the center of a ganglion, a tiny swarm of parasites infesting some great

05:41:27.820 --> 05:41:33.580
hollowed host. Each tunnel curved away in a gradual spiral, each along a different orientation.

05:41:34.540 --> 05:41:38.300
Sonar could peep around those bends a few meters further than we could.

05:41:39.180 --> 05:41:43.020
Neither eyes nor ultrasonics saw anything could distinguish one choice from another.

05:41:44.300 --> 05:41:51.260
Bates pointed down one of the passageways, Keaton, and another, Sasha, before turning to

05:41:51.260 --> 05:41:59.420
coast off down her own unbeaten path. I looked uneasily down mine. Any particular 25 minutes,

05:41:59.420 --> 05:42:06.700
she said. I turned and jetted slowly down my assigned passageway. The passage curved clockwise,

05:42:06.780 --> 05:42:11.820
a long unremarkable spiral. After 20 meters, that curvature would have blocked any view of its

05:42:11.820 --> 05:42:17.660
entrance, even if the foggy atmosphere hadn't. My drone kept point across the tunnel. It's

05:42:17.660 --> 05:42:22.700
sonar clicking like the chattering of a thousand tiny teeth, its tether unspooling back to the

05:42:22.700 --> 05:42:30.380
distant drum in the nexus. It was a comfort, that leash. It was short. The grunts could stray 90

05:42:30.380 --> 05:42:35.420
meters and no further, and we were under strict orders to stay under their wings at all times.

05:42:36.220 --> 05:42:41.420
This dim infested burrow might lead all the way to hell, but I would not be expected to follow it

05:42:41.420 --> 05:42:50.540
nearly so far. My cowardice had official sanction. 50 meters to go. 50 meters and I could turn and run

05:42:50.540 --> 05:42:55.900
with my tail between my legs. In the meantime, all I had to do was grip my teeth and focus and

05:42:55.900 --> 05:43:02.220
record. Everything you can see, Sadastiy had said. As much as possible of what you can't.

05:43:03.180 --> 05:43:07.820
And I hoped that this new reduced time limit would expire before Rorschach spiked this into a

05:43:07.820 --> 05:43:13.260
gibbering dementia. The walls around me twitched and shivered like the flesh of something just

05:43:13.260 --> 05:43:19.820
killed, something darted in and out of sight with a faint cackle of laughter. Focus. Record.

05:43:20.460 --> 05:43:27.900
If the grunt doesn't see it, it's not real. 65 meters in, one of the ghosts got inside my helmet.

05:43:28.860 --> 05:43:35.260
I tried to ignore it. I tried to look away. But this phantom wasn't flickering at the edge of vision.

05:43:35.980 --> 05:43:40.620
It hovered near the center of my faceplate, floating like a spot of swirling dizziness between

05:43:40.620 --> 05:43:45.660
me and the HUD. I gritted my teeth and tried to look past, stared into the dim bloody haze in

05:43:45.660 --> 05:43:50.780
the middle distance, watched the jerky unfolding travelogues in the little windows labeled Bates

05:43:51.740 --> 05:43:58.300
and James. Nothing out there. But in here, floating before my eyes, Rorschach's latest

05:43:58.300 --> 05:44:04.300
head fuck smeared a fuzzy thumbprint right in front of the sonar feed. New symptom, I called in.

05:44:04.940 --> 05:44:10.140
Non-peripheral hoose nation. Stable, pretty formless though, no spiking that I can...

05:44:10.860 --> 05:44:17.900
the inset marked Bates skitted hard about. Keat. Window and voice cut out all together.

05:44:18.860 --> 05:44:23.340
Not just Bates's window, either. Sasha's inset and the drone's eyes sonar

05:44:23.340 --> 05:44:28.380
escape flickered and died at the same moment, stripped my HUD bare except for in-suit feeds

05:44:28.380 --> 05:44:33.980
and the little readout flashing, link down. I spun, but the grunt was still there,

05:44:33.980 --> 05:44:39.500
three meters off my right shoulder. Its optical port was clearly visible, a ruby thumbnail set

05:44:39.580 --> 05:44:48.220
into the plastering. Its gun ports are visible too, pointing at me. I froze. The drone shivered

05:44:48.220 --> 05:44:54.460
in some local electromagnetic nod as if terrified of me or of something behind me.

05:44:55.660 --> 05:45:02.060
I started to turn. My helmet filled with sudden static and with what sounded faintly like a voice.

05:45:02.860 --> 05:45:04.700
Fucking move, Keat. Not...

05:45:06.620 --> 05:45:08.220
Bates? Bates?

05:45:09.500 --> 05:45:15.340
Another icon had bloomed in place of link down. The grunt was using radio for some reason,

05:45:15.340 --> 05:45:18.540
and although almost close enough to touch, I could barely make out the signal.

05:45:19.500 --> 05:45:26.860
A hash of bake speed. To your right in front of, and Sasha a bit more clearly,

05:45:27.820 --> 05:45:28.700
he see it.

05:45:29.980 --> 05:45:33.820
See what? Sasha, someone tell me what? See what?

05:45:35.100 --> 05:45:41.580
Read, Keaton, do you read? Somehow Bates had boosted the signal, static roared like an ocean,

05:45:41.580 --> 05:45:48.140
but I could hear the words behind it. Yes, what? Keep absolutely still. Do you understand?

05:45:48.140 --> 05:45:55.100
Absolutely still. Acknowledge. Acknowledged. The drone kept me in its shaky sights,

05:45:55.180 --> 05:46:01.340
dark stereocam irises spasming wide, stuttering into pinpoints. What? There's something in front

05:46:01.340 --> 05:46:06.700
of you, Keaton, directly between you and the grunt. Can't you see it? No, my HUD's down.

05:46:07.420 --> 05:46:13.180
Sasha broke in. How can he not see it? It's right there. Bates barked over her.

05:46:13.180 --> 05:46:20.620
It's man-sized, radially symmetrical, eight, nine arms, like tentacles, but segmented. Spiky.

05:46:21.580 --> 05:46:28.140
I don't see anything, I said, but I did. I saw something reaching for me in my pod

05:46:28.140 --> 05:46:33.820
back aboard Thesias. I saw something curled up motionless in the ship's spine, watching as we

05:46:33.820 --> 05:46:42.060
laid our best plans. I saw Michelle, the Synthesia, curled into a fetal ball. You can't see it, it's

05:46:42.620 --> 05:46:49.180
invisible. What's it doing, I called. Why can't I see it? Why can't I see it?

05:46:49.260 --> 05:46:56.780
Just floating there, kind of waving. Oh sh- Keat! The grunt skidded sideways as if

05:46:56.780 --> 05:47:01.420
slapped by a giant hand. It bounced off the wall and suddenly the laser link was back,

05:47:01.420 --> 05:47:06.300
filling the HUD with intelligence. First-person perspectives of Bates and Sasha racing along

05:47:06.300 --> 05:47:11.500
alien tunnels, a grunt's eye view of a space suit with Keaton stenciled across its breastplate,

05:47:11.500 --> 05:47:15.900
and there, right beside it, something like a rippling starfish with too many arms.

05:47:16.860 --> 05:47:22.460
The gang barreled around a curve, and now I could almost, could see something with my own eyes,

05:47:23.020 --> 05:47:29.580
flickering like heat lightning off to one side. It was large, it was moving, but somehow my eyes

05:47:29.580 --> 05:47:35.580
just slid off every time they tried to get a fix. It's not real, I thought, giddy with hysterical

05:47:35.580 --> 05:47:41.100
relief. It's just another hallucination. But then Bates sailed into view and it was right there,

05:47:41.100 --> 05:47:46.620
no flickering, no uncertainty, nothing but a collapsed probability wave and a solid undeniable

05:47:46.620 --> 05:47:52.940
mass. Exposed, it grabbed the nearest wall and scrambled over our heads, segmented arms flailing

05:47:52.940 --> 05:47:57.900
like whips, a sudden crackling buzz in the back of my head and it was drifting free again, charred

05:47:57.900 --> 05:48:05.820
and smoking. A stuttering click. The whine of machinery gearing down. Three grunts hovered

05:48:05.900 --> 05:48:11.740
in formation in the middle of the passageway. One faced the alien. I glimpsed to the tip of some

05:48:11.740 --> 05:48:16.940
lethal proboscis sliding back into its sheath. Bates shut down the grunt before it had finished

05:48:16.940 --> 05:48:29.660
closing its mouth. Optical links and three sets of lungs filled my helmet with a roar of heavy

05:48:29.740 --> 05:48:38.940
breathing. The offline grunt drifted in the murky air. The alien carcass bumped gently off the wall,

05:48:38.940 --> 05:48:45.500
twitching. A hydra of human backbone scorched and fleshless. It didn't look much like my on-board

05:48:45.500 --> 05:48:51.020
visions after all. For some reason that I couldn't put my finger on, I almost found that reassuring.

05:48:52.620 --> 05:48:57.900
The two active grunts panned the fog until Bates gave them new orders. Then one turned to secure

05:48:57.900 --> 05:49:03.500
the carcass. The other is steady, it's fallen comrade. Bates grabbed the dead grunt and unplugged

05:49:03.500 --> 05:49:12.460
its tether. Fall back. Slowly, I'm right behind you. I tweaked my jets. Sasha hesitated. Coils of

05:49:12.460 --> 05:49:18.780
shielded cable floated about us like umbilical cords. Now, Bates said, plugging a feed from her own

05:49:18.780 --> 05:49:25.980
suit directly into the offline grunt. Sasha started after me. Bates took up the rear. I watched my

05:49:26.060 --> 05:49:33.180
head. A swarm of multi-armed monsters would appear there any moment. They didn't. But the blackened

05:49:33.180 --> 05:49:39.580
thing against the belly of Bates' machine was real enough. Not a hallucination. Not even some

05:49:39.580 --> 05:49:46.460
understandable artifact of fear and synthesia. Rorschach was inhabited. Its inhabitants were

05:49:46.460 --> 05:49:53.660
invisible. Sometimes. Sort of. And oh yeah, we just killed one.

05:50:03.180 --> 05:50:06.780
Bates threw the deactivated grunt into the sky as soon as we'd made vacuum.

05:50:07.500 --> 05:50:11.820
Its comrades used it for target practice while we strapped in, firing and firing until there

05:50:11.820 --> 05:50:17.900
was nothing left but cooling vapor. Rorschach spun even that faint plasma into filigree before it faded.

05:50:18.700 --> 05:50:25.340
Halfway back to Thesias, Sasha turned to the Major. You know. But they do that shit on their own,

05:50:25.340 --> 05:50:33.500
right? Autonomous. Not when they're slaved. Malfunction? Spike? Bates didn't answer. She

05:50:33.500 --> 05:50:39.420
called ahead. By the time we made it back, Cunningham had grown another little tumor on Thesias' spine,

05:50:39.500 --> 05:50:45.340
a remote surgery packed with telops and sensors. One of the surviving grunts grabbed the carcass

05:50:45.340 --> 05:50:49.820
and jumped ship as soon as we passed beneath the carapace, completing the delivery as we docked.

05:50:53.260 --> 05:50:59.020
We were born again to the fruits of a preliminary necropsy. The holographic ghost of the dissected

05:50:59.020 --> 05:51:04.780
alien rose from consensus like some flayed and horrific feast. Its splayed arms looked like

05:51:04.860 --> 05:51:10.060
human spinal columns. We sat around the table and waited for someone else to take the first bite.

05:51:13.660 --> 05:51:18.220
Did you have to shoot it with microwaves? Cunningham sniped, tapping the table.

05:51:18.220 --> 05:51:21.980
You completely cooked the animal. Every cell was blown out from the inside.

05:51:22.780 --> 05:51:29.180
Bates shook her head. There was a malfunction. He gave her a sour look. A malfunction that

05:51:29.180 --> 05:51:33.980
just perhaps to involve precise targeting of a moving object. It doesn't sound random to me.

05:51:34.940 --> 05:51:41.260
Bates looked back evenly. Something flipped autonomous targeting from off to on. A coin toss.

05:51:41.260 --> 05:51:46.460
Random. Random is, give it a rest, Cunningham. I don't need this shit from you right now.

05:51:47.340 --> 05:51:52.940
His eyes rolled in that smooth, dead face focused suddenly on something overhead. I followed his gaze.

05:51:58.380 --> 05:52:03.900
Solasty stared down at us like an owl, panning for meadow voles, drifting slowly in the Coriolis

05:52:03.900 --> 05:52:12.460
breeze. No visor this time either. I knew he hadn't lost it. He fixed Cunningham. Your findings?

05:52:13.500 --> 05:52:18.220
Cunningham swallowed. Bits and pieces of alien anatomy flickered with color-coded

05:52:18.220 --> 05:52:23.580
highlights as he tapped his fingers. Right then, I'm afraid I can't give you much at the cellular

05:52:23.580 --> 05:52:29.420
level. There's not much left inside the membranes. Not many membranes left for that matter. In terms

05:52:29.420 --> 05:52:34.540
of gross morphology, the specimens d-dorse eventually compressed and radially symmetrical,

05:52:34.540 --> 05:52:39.980
as you can see. Calcarus exoskeleton, keratinized plasticutical, nothing special.

05:52:41.260 --> 05:52:47.180
Bates looked skeptical. Plastic skin is nothing special? Given the environment,

05:52:47.180 --> 05:52:52.620
I was half expecting a sendoviciu plasma. Plastic simply refined petroleum. Organic

05:52:52.620 --> 05:52:57.580
carbon. This thing is carbon-based. It's even protein-based, although its proteins are a great

05:52:57.580 --> 05:53:03.260
deal tougher than ours. Numerous sulfur cross bonds for lateral bracing. As far as I could tell

05:53:03.260 --> 05:53:09.980
from what your grunts did in de-nature. Cunningham's eyes looked past it as all. His consciousness was

05:53:09.980 --> 05:53:16.620
obviously far aft, haunting remote sensors. The thing's tissues are saturated with magnetite.

05:53:16.620 --> 05:53:21.420
On Earth, you find that material in dolphin brains, migratory birds, even some bacteria.

05:53:21.420 --> 05:53:27.020
Anything that navigates or orients using magnetic fields. Moving up the macros to macro structures,

05:53:27.020 --> 05:53:31.180
we've got a pneumatic internal skeleton, which as far as I can tell doubles as musculature.

05:53:32.060 --> 05:53:36.860
Contractal tissue squeezes gas through a system of bladders that stiffen or relax each segment of

05:53:36.860 --> 05:53:42.460
the arms. The light came back into Cunningham's eyes long enough to focus on his cigarette.

05:53:42.460 --> 05:53:45.340
He brought it to his mouth, dragging deeply and set it down again.

05:53:46.540 --> 05:53:49.260
Note the invaginations around the base of each arm.

05:53:49.980 --> 05:53:52.700
Flaccid balloons glowed orange on the virtual carcass.

05:53:53.260 --> 05:53:58.300
Cloaca, you could call them. Everything opens into them. They eat, breathe, and defecate through

05:53:58.300 --> 05:54:03.660
the same little compartment. No other major orifices. The gang made a face that said,

05:54:03.660 --> 05:54:11.740
Sasha, grossed out. Don't things get clogged up? Seems inefficient. If one gets plugged,

05:54:11.740 --> 05:54:16.380
there's eight other doors into the same system. You'll wish you were so inefficient the next time

05:54:16.380 --> 05:54:22.940
you choke on a chicken bone. What does it eat? Bates asked. I couldn't say. I found

05:54:22.940 --> 05:54:28.060
gizzard-like contractiles around the cloaca, which implies they chew on something, or did at some

05:54:28.060 --> 05:54:33.900
point in their history. Other than that, he spread his hands, the cigarette left faint streamers in

05:54:33.900 --> 05:54:38.700
its wake. Inflate those contractiles enough and you create an airtight seal, by the way.

05:54:39.340 --> 05:54:43.980
In conjunction with the cuticle, this would allow this organism to survive briefly in vacuum.

05:54:44.620 --> 05:54:48.620
And we already know it can handle the ambient radiation, although don't ask me how.

05:54:49.260 --> 05:54:52.380
Whatever it uses for genes must be a great deal tougher than ours.

05:54:53.820 --> 05:54:59.980
So it can survive in space, Bates mused. In the sense that a dolphin survives under water,

05:54:59.980 --> 05:55:07.500
limited time only. How long? I'm not certain. Central nervous system, Sudasti said.

05:55:08.460 --> 05:55:14.780
Bates and the gang grew suddenly, subtly still. James's affect seeped out over her body, supplanting

05:55:14.780 --> 05:55:21.500
sashes. Smoke curled from Cunningham's mouth and nose. There's nothing central about it as it

05:55:21.500 --> 05:55:27.340
transpires. No sephalization, not even clustered sense organs. The bodies covered with something

05:55:27.340 --> 05:55:34.060
like eye spots or chromatophores are both. There are satay everywhere. As far as I can tell, if all

05:55:34.140 --> 05:55:38.620
those little cooked filaments I've been able to put back together after your malfunction really are

05:55:38.620 --> 05:55:43.820
nerves and not something completely different, every one of those structures is under independent

05:55:43.820 --> 05:55:52.460
control. Bates sat up straight. Seriously? He nodded. It would be akin to independently controlling

05:55:52.460 --> 05:55:56.620
the movement of each individual hair on your head, although this creature is covered with little

05:55:56.620 --> 05:56:02.220
hair from tip to tip. The same thing applies to the eyes. Hundreds of thousands of eyes all over

05:56:02.220 --> 05:56:07.260
the cuticle. Each one is barely more than a pinhole camera, but each is capable of independent

05:56:07.260 --> 05:56:13.100
focus and I'm guessing all the different inputs integrate somewhere up the line. The entire body

05:56:13.100 --> 05:56:19.820
acts like a single diffuse retina. In theory, that gives it enormous visual acuity. A distributed

05:56:19.820 --> 05:56:26.220
telescope array, Bates murmured. A chromatophore underlies each eye. The pigment's some kind of

05:56:26.220 --> 05:56:31.340
cryptochrome, so it's probably involved in vision, but it can also diffuse or contract through the

05:56:31.420 --> 05:56:37.900
local tissue. That implies dynamic pigment patterns like a squid or chameleon.

05:56:39.020 --> 05:56:43.820
Background pattern matching, Bates asked. Would that explain why Siri couldn't see it?

05:56:45.020 --> 05:56:49.980
Cunningham opened a new window and played a grainy looped imagery of Siri Keaton and his

05:56:49.980 --> 05:56:55.020
unseen dance partner. The creature I hadn't noticed was ominously solid to the cameras.

05:56:55.580 --> 05:57:00.380
A floating discoid twice as wide as my own torso, arms extending from its edges like

05:57:00.380 --> 05:57:05.820
thick knotted ropes. Patterns rippled across its surface and waves, sunlight and shadow playing

05:57:05.820 --> 05:57:11.980
on a shallow seabed. As you can see, the background doesn't match the pattern, Cunningham said.

05:57:12.620 --> 05:57:18.140
It's not even close. Can you explain Siri's blindness to it? Sardasti said.

05:57:19.260 --> 05:57:25.420
I can't, Cunningham admitted. It's beyond ordinary crypts. But Rorschach makes you see

05:57:25.420 --> 05:57:29.900
all sorts of things that aren't there. Not seeing something that is there might come down to

05:57:29.900 --> 05:57:37.020
essentially the same thing. Another hallucination, I asked. Another shrug while Cunningham stuck

05:57:37.020 --> 05:57:42.860
smoke. There are many ways to fool the human visual system. It's interesting that the illusion

05:57:42.860 --> 05:57:47.180
failed when multiple witnesses were present. But if you want a definitive mechanism, you'll have

05:57:47.180 --> 05:57:53.580
to give me more to work with than that. He stabbed a cigarette at the crisp remains. But James took

05:57:53.580 --> 05:58:02.460
a breath bracing herself. We're talking about something sophisticated at least, something

05:58:02.460 --> 05:58:09.020
very complex, a great deal of processing power. Cunningham nodded again. I'd estimate nervous

05:58:09.020 --> 05:58:15.740
tissue accounts for about 30% of body mass. So it's intelligent. Her voice was almost a whisper.

05:58:16.460 --> 05:58:26.460
Not remotely. But 30%! 30% motor and sensory wiring. Another drag. Much like an octopus,

05:58:26.460 --> 05:58:30.060
an enormous number of neutrons, but half of them used up running the suckers.

05:58:31.260 --> 05:58:34.620
My understanding is that Occupy are quite intelligent, James said.

05:58:35.580 --> 05:58:40.780
By Maluskan standard, certainly. But do you have any idea how much extra cabling you'd need if the

05:58:40.780 --> 05:58:45.420
photoreceptors in your eye were spread out across your entire body? You'd need about 300

05:58:45.420 --> 05:58:50.220
million extension cords to begin with, ranging from half a millimeter to two meters long.

05:58:50.220 --> 05:58:54.620
Which means all your signals are staggered and out of sync. Which means billions of additional

05:58:54.620 --> 05:59:00.620
logic gates to go here the input. And that just gets you a single static image with no filtering,

05:59:00.620 --> 05:59:08.060
no interpretation, no time series integration at all. Shiver. Drag. Now multiply all that by

05:59:08.060 --> 05:59:13.260
the extra wiring needed to focus all those eye spots on an object or to send information

05:59:13.260 --> 05:59:17.740
back to individual chromatophores and then add in the processing power you need to drive

05:59:17.740 --> 05:59:23.500
those chromatophores one at a time. 30% might do all that, but I strongly doubt you have much

05:59:23.500 --> 05:59:28.300
left over for philosophy and science. He waved his hand in the general direction of the hold.

05:59:29.020 --> 05:59:35.900
That... that scrambler, James suggested. Cunningham rolled his tongue around it.

05:59:36.460 --> 05:59:41.820
Very well. That scrambler is an absolute miracle of evolutionary engineering.

05:59:42.460 --> 05:59:46.140
It's also as dumb as a stick. A moment's silence.

05:59:47.580 --> 05:59:54.620
So what is it? James asked at last. Somebody's pet? Canary in a coal mine, they'd suggested.

05:59:55.740 --> 06:00:00.380
Perhaps not even that, Cunningham said. Perhaps no more than a white blood cell with

06:00:00.380 --> 06:00:05.900
walldoze. Maintenance bought maybe. Tele-operated or in-string driven. But people, we've been

06:00:05.900 --> 06:00:12.220
ignoring far greater questions here. How could an anorob even develop complex multi-cellular

06:00:12.220 --> 06:00:17.580
anatomy, much less move as fast as this thing did? That level of activity burns a great deal of ATP.

06:00:18.540 --> 06:00:25.420
Maybe they don't use ATP, Bain said as I thumbnailed. Adenosine dry phosphate. Cellular energy source.

06:00:26.140 --> 06:00:31.340
It was crammed with ATP, Cunningham told her. You can tell that much even with these remains.

06:00:32.060 --> 06:00:36.700
The question is, how can it synthesize this stuff fast enough to keep up with demand?

06:00:36.700 --> 06:00:41.580
Purely anaerobic pathways wouldn't suffice. Nobody offered any suggestions.

06:00:42.380 --> 06:00:47.500
Anyway, he said. So end of the lesson. If you want gory details, check consensus.

06:00:48.140 --> 06:00:53.180
He wiggled the fingers of his freehand. The spectral dissection vanished. I'll keep working,

06:00:53.180 --> 06:00:57.740
but if you want any real answers, go get me a live one. He butted out his cigarette against

06:00:57.740 --> 06:01:03.260
the bulkhead and stared defiantly around the drum. The others hardly reacted. Their topologies

06:01:03.260 --> 06:01:08.540
still sparkled from the revelations of a few minutes before. Perhaps Cunningham's pet peeve

06:01:08.540 --> 06:01:14.620
was more important to the big picture. Perhaps in a reductionist universe, biochemical basics

06:01:14.620 --> 06:01:19.260
should always take priority over the finer points of ETI and interspecies etiquette.

06:01:20.060 --> 06:01:26.300
But Bates and the gang were time lagged, processing earlier revelations. Not just processing either,

06:01:26.300 --> 06:01:31.500
wallowing. They clung to Cunningham's findings like convicted felons who just discovered they

06:01:31.500 --> 06:01:37.740
might have been freed on a technicality. Because the scrambler was dead at our hands, no doubt about

06:01:37.740 --> 06:01:44.700
it. But it wasn't an alien. Not really. It wasn't intelligent. It was just a blood cell with

06:01:44.700 --> 06:01:51.340
wall-dose. It was dumb as a stick. And property damage is so much easier to live with than murder.

06:01:51.580 --> 06:01:59.260
Problems cannot be solved at the same level of awareness that created them. Einstein.

06:02:02.220 --> 06:02:07.260
Robert Poglino had set me up with Chelsea in the first place. Maybe he felt responsible when

06:02:07.260 --> 06:02:12.700
the relationships started jumping arrails. Or maybe Chelsea, Madam Fix-It that she was,

06:02:12.700 --> 06:02:16.940
had approached him for an intervention. For whatever reason, it was obvious the moment we

06:02:16.940 --> 06:02:20.540
took our seats at Cubits that his invitation had not been entirely social.

06:02:25.180 --> 06:02:29.420
He went for some neurotrope cocktail on the rocks. I stuck with records.

06:02:30.300 --> 06:02:34.940
Still old school, Pag said. Still into foreplay, I observed.

06:02:35.740 --> 06:02:41.660
That obvious, huh? He took a sip. That'll teach me to try the subtle approach with a professional

06:02:41.660 --> 06:02:46.300
jargonaut. Jargonaut's got nothing to do with it. You wouldn't a fool to border collie.

06:02:47.180 --> 06:02:51.100
Truth be told, Pag's topology never really told me much that I didn't already know.

06:02:51.820 --> 06:02:55.740
I never really had much of an edge in reading him. Maybe we just knew each other too well.

06:02:56.540 --> 06:03:03.500
So, he said, spill. Nothing to spill. She just got to know the real me. That is bad.

06:03:04.540 --> 06:03:09.900
What did she tell you? Me? Nothing at all. I gave him a look over the top of my glass.

06:03:10.700 --> 06:03:13.580
He sighed. She knows you're cheating on her.

06:03:14.540 --> 06:03:21.180
I'm what? Cheating. With the skin. It's based on her. But it isn't her.

06:03:21.980 --> 06:03:26.940
No, it isn't. It doesn't fart or fight or break into tears every time you don't want to be dragged

06:03:26.940 --> 06:03:32.060
off to meet its family. Look, I love the woman dearly, but come on. When was the last time you

06:03:32.060 --> 06:03:38.300
tried first person fucking? 74, he said. You're kidding. I'd have guessed never.

06:03:38.380 --> 06:03:44.220
Did some third world medical missionary work between gigs? They still bump and grind in Texas.

06:03:44.940 --> 06:03:51.420
Pag's wigged his trope. Actually, I thought it was alright. The novelty wears off. Evidently.

06:03:52.380 --> 06:03:57.580
And it's not like I'm doing anything unusual here, Pag. She's the one with the kink. And it's not

06:03:57.580 --> 06:04:05.020
just the sex. She keeps asking about... She keeps wanting no things. Like what? Irrelevant stuff.

06:04:05.020 --> 06:04:11.100
My life as a kid. My family. Nobody's fucking business. She's just taking an interest. Not

06:04:11.100 --> 06:04:15.500
everyone considers childhood memories off limits, you know? Thanks for the insight.

06:04:16.460 --> 06:04:21.820
As if people had never taken an interest before. As if Helen hadn't taken an interest when she

06:04:21.820 --> 06:04:26.620
went through my drawers and filtered my mail and followed me from room to room, asking the drapes

06:04:26.620 --> 06:04:31.340
and furniture why I was always so sullen and withdrawn. She'd taken an interest that she

06:04:31.340 --> 06:04:36.300
wouldn't let me out of the door until I confided in her. At 12, I'd been stupid enough to throw

06:04:36.300 --> 06:04:41.660
myself on her mercy. It's personal, Mom. I'd just rather not talk about it. And then I'd made my

06:04:41.660 --> 06:04:46.380
escape into the bathroom when she demanded to know if it was trouble online, trouble at school,

06:04:46.380 --> 06:04:51.660
was it a girl, was it... was it a boy? What was it? Why couldn't I just trust my own mother?

06:04:51.660 --> 06:04:56.620
Don't I know I can trust her with anything? I laid it out the persistent knocking and the

06:04:56.620 --> 06:05:02.700
insistent concerned voice through the door and the final grudging silence that followed.

06:05:03.340 --> 06:05:09.100
I waited until I was absolutely sure she'd gone away. I'd waited for five fucking hours before

06:05:09.100 --> 06:05:14.860
I came out and there she was, arms folded in the hall, eyes brimming with reproach and disappointment.

06:05:16.300 --> 06:05:21.100
That night she took the lock off the bathroom door because family should never shut each other out.

06:05:22.060 --> 06:05:23.340
Still taking an interest.

06:05:24.780 --> 06:05:29.980
Siri, Pag said quietly. I slowed my breathing, tried again.

06:05:31.980 --> 06:05:38.060
She doesn't just want to talk about family. She wants to meet them. She keeps trying to drag

06:05:38.060 --> 06:05:42.860
me to meet hers. I thought I was hooking up with Chelsea, you know? Nobody ever told me I'd have

06:05:42.860 --> 06:05:50.220
to share airspace with... you do it? Once. Reaching, grasping things, feigning acceptance,

06:05:50.300 --> 06:05:51.260
feigning friendship.

06:05:54.940 --> 06:06:00.140
It was great. If you like being ritually pawed by a bunch of play acting strangers who can't

06:06:00.140 --> 06:06:04.780
stand the sight of you and don't have the guts to admit it. Pag shrugged unsympathetic.

06:06:05.580 --> 06:06:10.940
Sounds like typical old school family. You're a synthesis man. You deal with way walkier dynamics

06:06:10.940 --> 06:06:17.020
than that. I deal with other people's information. I don't vomit my own personal life into the public

06:06:17.100 --> 06:06:24.140
sphere. Whatever hybrids and the constructs I work with, they don't... touch. Interrogate, I finished.

06:06:25.260 --> 06:06:27.820
You knew Chelsea was an old fashioned girl right off the top.

06:06:28.940 --> 06:06:35.260
Yeah, when it suits her, I gulped ale. But she's cutting edge when she's got a splicer in her hand,

06:06:35.260 --> 06:06:41.500
which isn't to say that her strategies couldn't use some work. Strategies. It's not a strategy

06:06:41.500 --> 06:06:45.980
for God's sake. Can't you see I'm hurting? I'm on the fucking floor, Siri. I'm curled up in the

06:06:45.980 --> 06:06:51.180
ball because I'm hurting so much and all you can do is criticize my tactics. What do I have to do?

06:06:51.180 --> 06:06:59.340
Slash my goddamn wrists? I shrugged and turned away. Nature's trick. She cries, I said now.

06:07:00.140 --> 06:07:04.780
High blood lactic levels make it easier for her. It's just chemistry, but she holds it up like it

06:07:04.780 --> 06:07:12.860
was some kind of IOU. Pag pursed his lips. Doesn't mean it's an act. Everything's an act.

06:07:12.860 --> 06:07:19.420
Everything's strategy. You know that. I snorted. And she's miffed because I base a skin on her?

06:07:20.620 --> 06:07:24.940
I don't think it's so much the actual skin as the fact that you didn't tell her.

06:07:24.940 --> 06:07:30.140
You know how she feels about honesty and relationships. Sure, she doesn't want any.

06:07:30.940 --> 06:07:35.820
He looked at me. Give me some credit, Pag. You think I should tell her that sometimes the side

06:07:35.820 --> 06:07:41.660
of her makes me shudder? The system called Robert Poglino sack quietly, sipped his drugs,

06:07:41.660 --> 06:07:45.100
and set the things he was about to say in order. He took a breath.

06:07:46.060 --> 06:07:53.180
I can't believe you could be so fucking dumb, he said. Yeah, enlighten me. Of course,

06:07:53.180 --> 06:07:58.140
she wants you to tell her you only have eyes for her. You love her pores and her morning breath.

06:07:58.140 --> 06:08:03.500
And why stop at one tweak? How about ten? But that doesn't mean she wants you to lie, you idiot.

06:08:03.500 --> 06:08:07.980
She wants all that stuff to be true. And, well, why can't it be?

06:08:08.860 --> 06:08:15.100
It isn't, I said. Jesus, Siri, people aren't rational. You aren't rational. We're not thinking

06:08:15.100 --> 06:08:20.780
machines. We're feeling machines and happen to think. He took a breath and another hit.

06:08:21.820 --> 06:08:27.580
And you already know that, or you couldn't do your job, or at least, he grimaced. The system knows.

06:08:28.540 --> 06:08:34.780
The system. Me and my protocols, he meant. My Chinese room. I took a breath.

06:08:35.660 --> 06:08:41.020
It doesn't work with everyone, you know. So I've noticed. Can't read systems you two entangled

06:08:41.020 --> 06:08:47.340
with, right? Observer effect? I shrugged. Just as well, he said. I don't think I'd like you all

06:08:47.340 --> 06:08:54.460
that much in that room of yours. It came out before I could stop it. Chell said she'd prefer a real one.

06:08:55.260 --> 06:09:01.340
He raised his eyebrows. Real what? Chinese room. She says it would have better comprehension.

06:09:01.580 --> 06:09:05.660
The cube murmured and clattered around us for a few moments.

06:09:06.700 --> 06:09:12.620
I can see why she'd say that, bag said at last. But you, you did okay, pod man.

06:09:13.820 --> 06:09:19.580
I don't know. He nodded empathetic. You know what they say about the road less traveled?

06:09:19.580 --> 06:09:25.100
Well, you carved your own road. I don't know why. It's like learning calligraphy using your toes,

06:09:25.100 --> 06:09:31.900
you know, or proprioseceptive polyneuropathy. It's amazing you can do it at all. It's mind

06:09:31.900 --> 06:09:38.860
boggling that you actually got good at it. I squinted at him. Proprio, there used to be people

06:09:38.860 --> 06:09:43.740
without any sense of, well, themselves physically. They couldn't feel their bodies in space, had no

06:09:43.740 --> 06:09:49.900
idea of their own limbs, were arranged or if they hadn't had limbs. Some of them said they felt pithed,

06:09:49.900 --> 06:09:54.860
disembodied. It sent a motor signal to the hand and just have to take it on faith that it arrived.

06:09:55.580 --> 06:10:00.060
So they'd use vision to compensate. They couldn't feel where their hand was, so they'd look at it

06:10:00.060 --> 06:10:05.420
while it moved. Use sight as a substitute for normal force feedback that you and I take for granted.

06:10:06.460 --> 06:10:10.700
They could walk if they kept their eyes focused on their legs and concentrate on every step.

06:10:11.340 --> 06:10:15.820
They'd get pretty good at it. But even after years of practice, if you distracted them in

06:10:15.820 --> 06:10:20.780
mid-step, they'd go over like a beanstalk without a counterweight. You were saying I'm like that?

06:10:21.740 --> 06:10:27.500
You use your Chinese room the way they used vision. You've reinvented empathy almost from scratch and

06:10:27.500 --> 06:10:31.900
in some ways, not all obviously, or I wouldn't have to tell you this, but in some ways yours

06:10:31.900 --> 06:10:38.540
is better than the original. So why are you so good at synthesis? I shook my head. I just observe,

06:10:38.540 --> 06:10:42.620
that's all. I watch what people do and then I imagine what it would make them do that.

06:10:44.060 --> 06:10:50.300
Sounds like empathy to me. It's not. Empathy is not so much about imagining how the other guy feels.

06:10:50.860 --> 06:10:53.900
It's more about imagining how you'd feel in the same place.

06:10:54.780 --> 06:10:57.260
Pag frowned. So?

06:10:59.340 --> 06:11:05.580
So what if you don't know how you'd feel? He looked at me and his surfaces were serious and

06:11:05.580 --> 06:11:12.140
completely transparent. You're better than that friend. You may not always act like it, but I know

06:11:12.140 --> 06:11:19.820
you. I knew you before. You knew someone else. I'm pod man, remember? Yeah, that was someone else.

06:11:19.900 --> 06:11:24.300
And maybe I remember him better than you do, but I'll tell you one thing. He leaned forward.

06:11:24.940 --> 06:11:29.180
Both of you would have helped me out that day. And maybe he would have got there with a good

06:11:29.180 --> 06:11:34.140
old fashioned empathy while you had to cobble together some kind of improvised flowchart out of

06:11:34.140 --> 06:11:39.420
surplus parts, but that just makes your accomplishment all the greater, which is why I continue to stick

06:11:39.420 --> 06:11:43.900
it out with you old buddy. Even though you have a rod up your ass the size of the Rio Spire,

06:11:44.780 --> 06:11:49.740
he held out his glass. Dutifully, I clinked it against my own. We drank.

06:11:51.020 --> 06:11:57.340
I don't remember him. I said after a while. What, the other Siri? Prepod Siri? I nodded.

06:11:57.980 --> 06:12:04.220
Nothing at all? I thought back. Well, he was wracked by convulsions all the time, right?

06:12:04.220 --> 06:12:10.700
There'd be constant pain. I don't remember any pain. My glass was almost empty. I sipped to make it

06:12:10.700 --> 06:12:19.660
last. I dream about him sometimes, though, about being him. What's it like? It was colorful.

06:12:20.380 --> 06:12:25.420
Everything was more saturated, you know? Sounds, smells, richer than life. And now,

06:12:26.300 --> 06:12:34.380
I looked at him. You said it was colorful. What changed? I don't know. Maybe nothing. I just,

06:12:35.340 --> 06:12:40.620
I don't actually remember the dreams when I wake up anymore. So how do you know you still have them?

06:12:40.860 --> 06:12:48.380
Pag asked. Fuck it. I thought. I tipped back the last of my pint in a single gulp. I know. How?

06:12:49.420 --> 06:12:53.580
I frowned, taken aback. I had to think for a few moments before I remembered.

06:12:54.460 --> 06:13:01.820
I wake up smiling, I said. Grunts look the enemy in the eye. Grunts know the stakes.

06:13:02.460 --> 06:13:08.460
Grunts know the price of poor strategy. What do the generals know? Overlays and tactical plots.

06:13:09.020 --> 06:13:13.740
The whole chain of command is upside down. Kenneth Lubin, zero sum.

06:13:15.660 --> 06:13:20.540
It went bad from the moment we breached. The plan had called for a precise havoc along the new

06:13:20.540 --> 06:13:25.100
beachhead, subtly arranged to entrap some blood cell with walldoze as it sought to repair the

06:13:25.100 --> 06:13:30.540
damage. Our job admitted is set to trap and stand back, trusting Sadasi's assurances that we would

06:13:30.540 --> 06:13:35.980
not have long to wait. We had no time at all. Something squirmed in the squirreling dust the

06:13:35.980 --> 06:13:39.900
moment we breached. Serpentine movement down the hole that instantly kicked Bates around

06:13:39.900 --> 06:13:46.380
Field Initiative into high gear. Her grunts dived through and caught a scrambler twitching in their

06:13:46.380 --> 06:13:51.420
crosshairs, clinging to the wall the passageway. It must have been stunned by the blast of our

06:13:51.420 --> 06:13:57.180
entry, a classic case of wrong place, wrong time. Bates took a split second to appraise the opportunity

06:13:57.180 --> 06:14:02.860
and the plan was plasma. One of the grunts plugged the scrambler with a biopsy dart before I even had

06:14:02.860 --> 06:14:08.140
a chance to blink. We would have bagged the whole animal right there if Borschak's magnetosphere

06:14:08.140 --> 06:14:13.420
hadn't chosen that moment to kick sand in our faces. As it was, by the time our grunts staggered

06:14:13.420 --> 06:14:18.300
back into action their quarry was already disappearing around the bend. Bates was tethered to her

06:14:18.300 --> 06:14:24.940
troops. They yanked her down the rabbit hole. Set it up! She yelled back at Shasa the moment she

06:14:24.940 --> 06:14:31.420
let them loose. I was tethered to Bates. I barely had a chance to exchange a wide-eyed look with

06:14:31.420 --> 06:14:38.060
Shasa before being yanked away in turn. Suddenly I was inside again. The sated biopsy dart bounced

06:14:38.060 --> 06:14:43.180
off my faceplate and fasht plats, still attached to a few meters of discarded monofilament.

06:14:43.900 --> 06:14:48.060
Hopefully Shasa would pick it up while Bates and I were hunting. At least the mission wouldn't be a

06:14:48.060 --> 06:14:54.380
total loss if we never made it back. The grunts dragged us about like bait on a hook. Bates flew

06:14:54.380 --> 06:14:58.460
like a dolphin just ahead of me, keeping effortlessly to the center of the bore with an occasional

06:14:58.540 --> 06:15:03.740
tweak of her jets. I careened off the walls just behind trying to stabilize myself,

06:15:03.740 --> 06:15:09.340
trying to look as though I too might be in control. It was an important pretense. The whole point of

06:15:09.340 --> 06:15:14.460
being a decoy is to pass yourself off as an original. They'd even give me my own gun, pure

06:15:14.460 --> 06:15:19.500
precaution of course, more for comfort than protection. It hugged my forearm and fired

06:15:19.500 --> 06:15:27.100
plastic slugs impervious to induction fields. Just Bates and I now. A pacifist soldier and the odds

06:15:27.100 --> 06:15:33.900
of a coin toss. Goose flesh prickled my skin as it always had. The usual ghosts scrambled and

06:15:33.900 --> 06:15:40.620
clawed through my mind. This time though the dread seemed muted. Distant. Perhaps it was just a matter

06:15:40.620 --> 06:15:45.180
of timing. Perhaps we were moving so quickly through the magnetic landscape that no one phantom had a

06:15:45.180 --> 06:15:50.700
chance to stick. Or maybe it was something else. Maybe I wasn't so afraid of ghosts because this

06:15:50.700 --> 06:15:55.820
time we were after monsters. The scrambler seemed to have thrown off whatever cobwebs our entrance

06:15:55.900 --> 06:16:00.940
had spun. It surged along the wall now at full speed. Its arm shooting ahead like a succession of

06:16:00.940 --> 06:16:05.740
striking snakes slinging the body forward so fast the drones could barely keep it in sight,

06:16:05.740 --> 06:16:11.900
arriving silhouette in the fog. Suddenly it left sideways sailing across the width of the passage

06:16:11.900 --> 06:16:17.500
way and down some minor tributary. The grunts veered in pursuit crashing into walls, stumbling,

06:16:18.380 --> 06:16:23.820
stopping. And suddenly Bates was breaking hard, shooting past me as I flailed with my pistol.

06:16:24.540 --> 06:16:28.860
I was past the drones in the next instant. My leash snapped tight and snapped back,

06:16:28.860 --> 06:16:34.460
bringing me to a dead drifting stop. For a second or two I was on the front line. For a second or

06:16:34.460 --> 06:16:41.820
two I was the front line. Ciri Keaton, note-taker, mole, professional, uncomprehend her. I just floated

06:16:41.820 --> 06:16:47.180
there, breath roaring in my helmet as a few meters further out of the walls squirmed.

06:16:48.140 --> 06:16:54.460
Peristalysis, I thought at first. But this motion was utterly unlike the slow undulating waves that

06:16:54.460 --> 06:17:00.780
usually ripple along Rorschach's passageways. So hallucination, I thought instead. And then those

06:17:00.780 --> 06:17:05.500
writhing walls reached out with a thousand whiplike calciferous tongues that grabbed our query from

06:17:05.500 --> 06:17:12.060
every direction and tore it to pieces. Something grabbed me and spun me around. Suddenly I was

06:17:12.060 --> 06:17:16.220
locked against the chest of one of the grunts, its rear guns firing as we retracted back up the

06:17:16.300 --> 06:17:21.660
tunnel at full speed. Bates was in the arms of the other. Seething motion receded behind us,

06:17:21.660 --> 06:17:26.220
but the image stayed stuck to the backs of my eyes, lucinatory and point blank in its clarity.

06:17:27.020 --> 06:17:33.180
Scramblers everywhere. A seething infestation squirmed across the walls, reaching out for the

06:17:33.180 --> 06:17:38.460
intruder, leaping into the lumen of the passageway to press their counterattack. Not against us.

06:17:39.260 --> 06:17:43.900
They had attacked one of their own. I'd seen three of its arms ripped off before it had disappeared

06:17:43.900 --> 06:17:49.900
into a rioting ball in the center of the passageway. We fled. I turned to Bakes. Did you see,

06:17:49.900 --> 06:17:55.340
but held my tongue. The deathly concentration on her face was unmistakable even across two

06:17:55.340 --> 06:18:00.700
faceplates and three meters of methane. According to HUD, she'd lobotomized both grunts, bypassed

06:18:00.700 --> 06:18:05.820
all that wonderful autonomous decision-making circuitry entirely. She was running both machines

06:18:05.820 --> 06:18:11.740
herself, as manually as marionettes. Graney turbulent echoes appeared on the rear sonar display.

06:18:12.300 --> 06:18:16.140
The scramblers had finished with their sacrifice. Now they were coming after us.

06:18:17.020 --> 06:18:19.740
My grunts stumbled and creed against the side of the passage.

06:18:20.700 --> 06:18:26.540
Shards of alien decor dug parallel gouges across my faceplate, tenderized chunks of thigh through

06:18:26.540 --> 06:18:33.420
the shielded fabric of my suit. I clenched down on a cry. It got on anyway. Some ridiculous

06:18:33.420 --> 06:18:39.020
in-suit alarm chirped indignantly an instant before a dozen rotten eggs broke open inside my helmet.

06:18:39.020 --> 06:18:44.460
I coughed. My eyes stung and watered in the reek. I could barely see sea-verts on the HUD,

06:18:44.460 --> 06:18:48.460
flashing instantly into the red. Bakes drove us on without a word.

06:18:49.500 --> 06:18:53.180
My faceplate healed enough to shut off the alarm. My air began to clear.

06:18:53.820 --> 06:18:58.380
The scramblers had gained. By the time I could see clearly again, they were only a few meters behind

06:18:58.380 --> 06:19:03.820
us. Up ahead, Sasha came into view around the bend. Sasha, who had no backup, whose other

06:19:03.820 --> 06:19:08.460
course had been shut down on Sarasi's orders. Susan had protested at first.

06:19:09.100 --> 06:19:15.580
If there's any opportunity to communicate, there won't be, he'd said. So there was Sasha,

06:19:15.580 --> 06:19:20.780
who was more resistant to Rorschach's influence, according to some criteria, and I never understood.

06:19:20.780 --> 06:19:25.420
Curled up in a fetal ball with her gloves clamped against her helmet, and I could only hope to some

06:19:25.420 --> 06:19:31.180
dusty deity that she'd set the trap before this place had got her. And here came the scramblers,

06:19:31.180 --> 06:19:36.220
and Bates was shouting, Sasha, get out of the fucking way! And breaking hard, way too soon,

06:19:36.220 --> 06:19:41.820
the scrambling whore nipping at our heels like a riptide, and Bates yelled, Sasha! And again,

06:19:41.820 --> 06:19:47.180
and finally Sasha moved, kicking herself into gear and off the nearest wall, and fled right back up

06:19:47.180 --> 06:19:53.820
the hole we'd blown in through. Bates yanked some joystick in her head, and our warrior sedan slued

06:19:53.820 --> 06:19:59.500
and shat sparks and bullets and dove out after her. Sasha had set the trap just within the mouth

06:19:59.500 --> 06:20:05.100
of the breach. Bates armed it in passing with a slap of one-gloved hand. Motion sensors were

06:20:05.100 --> 06:20:10.540
supposed to do the rest, but the enemy was close behind and there was no room to spare. It went

06:20:10.540 --> 06:20:15.740
off just as I was emerging into the vestibule. The cannon net shot out behind me in a glorious

06:20:15.740 --> 06:20:20.220
exploding conic, caught something, snapped back up the rabbit hole and slammed it in my grunt from

06:20:20.220 --> 06:20:25.500
behind. The recoil kicked us against the top of the vestibule so hard I thought the fabric would

06:20:25.580 --> 06:20:31.980
tear. It held and threw us back against the scrumming things enmeshed in our midst. Riding

06:20:31.980 --> 06:20:37.580
backbones everywhere, articulated arms lashing like bony whips, one of them entwined my leg and

06:20:37.580 --> 06:20:45.900
squeezed like a brick python. Bates' hands waved an frantic dance before me, and that arm came apart

06:20:45.900 --> 06:20:52.140
into dismembered segments, bouncing around the enclosure. This was all wrong. They were supposed

06:20:52.140 --> 06:20:58.860
to be in the net, they were supposed to be contained. Sasha, launch! Bates barked. Another arm separated

06:20:58.860 --> 06:21:04.460
from its body and careened into the wall, coiling and uncoiling. The hole had flooded with aerosome

06:21:04.460 --> 06:21:09.420
foam core as soon as we'd pulled the net. A scrambler writhed half embedded in that matrix,

06:21:09.420 --> 06:21:14.780
cautious to split second too late. Its central mass protruded like some great round tumor writhing

06:21:14.780 --> 06:21:22.380
with monstrous worms. Sasha! Artillery. The floor of the vestibule iris shut quick as a leg hold

06:21:22.380 --> 06:21:27.980
trap and everything slammed against it, grunts, people, scramblers, hole and in pieces. I couldn't

06:21:27.980 --> 06:21:33.580
breathe. Every thimble full of flesh weighed a hundred kilograms. Something slapped us to one

06:21:33.580 --> 06:21:39.100
side, a giant hand, batting an insect. Maybe a course correction. Maybe a collision.

06:21:39.260 --> 06:21:46.060
But ten seconds later we were weightless again and nothing had torn us open. We floated like mites

06:21:46.060 --> 06:21:51.340
in a ping pong ball surrounded by a confusion of machinery and twitching body parts. There was little

06:21:51.340 --> 06:21:56.300
of anything that might pass from blood. What there was floated in clear shuttering spherules.

06:21:57.020 --> 06:22:01.500
The cannon net floated like a shrink-wrapped asteroid in our midst. The things inside had

06:22:01.500 --> 06:22:06.540
wrapped their arms around themselves, around each other, curled into a shivering and unresponsive ball.

06:22:07.500 --> 06:22:11.420
Compressed methonia hissed around them, keeping them fresh for the long trip home.

06:22:12.300 --> 06:22:16.940
Holy shit! Sasha breathed, watching them. The bloodsucker called it.

06:22:18.380 --> 06:22:23.180
He hadn't called everything. He hadn't called a mob of multi-armed aliens ripping one of their

06:22:23.180 --> 06:22:29.180
own to pieces before my eyes. He hadn't seen that coming. Or at least he hadn't mentioned it.

06:22:30.300 --> 06:22:35.100
I was already feeling nauseous. Bates was carefully bringing her wrists together.

06:22:35.180 --> 06:22:38.460
For a moment I could barely make out a taut dark thread of freak wire,

06:22:38.460 --> 06:22:43.420
find a smoke between them. Her caution was well advised. That stuff would slice through human

06:22:43.420 --> 06:22:48.620
limbs as easily as alien ones. One of the grunts groomed its mouthparts at her shoulder, cleaning

06:22:48.620 --> 06:22:54.860
gore from its mandibles. The freak wire vanished from my sight. The sight itself was dimming now.

06:22:55.580 --> 06:22:58.540
The inside of this great lead balloon was going dark around me.

06:22:59.260 --> 06:23:04.300
You were coasting, purely ballistic. We had to trust that Scylla would swoop in and snatch us once

06:23:04.300 --> 06:23:09.500
we'd achieved a discrete distance from the scene of the crime. We had to trust Sarasti.

06:23:11.020 --> 06:23:15.900
That was getting harder by the hour. But he'd been right so far, mostly.

06:23:17.260 --> 06:23:20.620
How do you know? Bates had asked when he'd first laid out the plan.

06:23:21.420 --> 06:23:26.860
He hadn't answered. Chances are he couldn't have, not to us. A more than a baseline could have

06:23:26.860 --> 06:23:32.700
explained a brain theory to the inhabitants of Flatland. But Bates hadn't been asking about tactics

06:23:32.700 --> 06:23:37.740
anyway, not really. Maybe she'd been asking for a reason, something to justify this ongoing

06:23:37.740 --> 06:23:44.140
trespass into foreign soil, with the capture and slaughter of its natives. On one level,

06:23:44.140 --> 06:23:49.500
she already knew the reason, of course. We all did. We could not afford to merely react.

06:23:49.500 --> 06:23:55.260
The risks were too great. We had to preempt. Sarasti, wise beyond all of us, saw this more

06:23:55.260 --> 06:24:01.020
clearly than we. Amanda Bates knew he was right in her mind. But sure, perhaps she didn't feel it

06:24:01.020 --> 06:24:06.780
in her gut. Perhaps, I thought, as my vision failed, she was asking Sarasti to convince her.

06:24:08.220 --> 06:24:16.620
But that wasn't all she was doing. Imagine you are Amanda Bates. The control you wheel over your

06:24:16.620 --> 06:24:21.740
troops would give wet dreams and nightmares to generals of ages past. You can drop instantly

06:24:21.740 --> 06:24:26.220
into the sensorium of anyone under your command, experience the battlefield from any number of

06:24:26.220 --> 06:24:31.740
first person perspectives. Your every soldier is loyal unto death, asking no questions, obeying

06:24:31.740 --> 06:24:35.980
all commands of the Lackardy and dedication to which mere flesh could never even aspire.

06:24:36.620 --> 06:24:42.540
You don't just respect a chain of command. You are one. You are a little bit scared of your own

06:24:42.540 --> 06:24:48.220
power. You are a little bit scared of the things you've already done with it. Taking orders comes

06:24:48.220 --> 06:24:54.300
as naturally as giving them. Oh, you've known to question policy on occasion, or seek a bigger

06:24:54.380 --> 06:24:59.420
picture than may be strictly necessary for the job at hand. Your command initiative has become the

06:24:59.420 --> 06:25:05.260
stuff of legends. But you have never disobeyed a direct order. When asked for your perspective,

06:25:05.260 --> 06:25:09.820
you serve it straight up and unvarnished, until the decision is made and the order is handed down.

06:25:10.540 --> 06:25:16.300
Then you do your job without question. Even when the questions arise, you would hardly waste time

06:25:16.300 --> 06:25:22.140
asking them unless you expected an answer you could use. Why then demand analytical details from a

06:25:22.140 --> 06:25:28.140
vampire? Not for information. Might as well expect the sighted to explain vision to the

06:25:28.140 --> 06:25:35.100
congenitally blind. Not for clarification. There is no ambiguity in Sotosti's bottom line. Not even

06:25:35.100 --> 06:25:40.300
for the benefit of poor dumb Ciri Keaton, who may have missed some salient point, but it's too

06:25:40.300 --> 06:25:45.980
ashamed to raise his own hand. No, there is only one reason why you might ask for such details.

06:25:46.620 --> 06:25:51.980
To challenge. To rebel. To the infinitesimal degree that rebellion is permitted once the word

06:25:51.980 --> 06:25:58.300
is given. You argued and advocated as forcefully as you could back when Sotosti was soliciting input.

06:25:59.020 --> 06:26:03.660
But he ignored yours, abandoned any attempt at communication and preemptively invaded foreign

06:26:03.660 --> 06:26:10.300
territory. He knew that Rorschach might contain living beings and still he tore it open without

06:26:10.300 --> 06:26:16.860
regard for their welfare. He may have killed hapless innocents. He may have roused an angry giant.

06:26:17.740 --> 06:26:24.300
You don't know. All you know is you've been helping him do it. You've seen this kind of arrogance

06:26:24.300 --> 06:26:30.380
before among your own kind. You had hopes that smarter creatures would be wiser ones. That enough

06:26:30.380 --> 06:26:35.980
to see such arrogance, stupidity inflicted on their helpless, but to do it at these stakes begers

06:26:35.980 --> 06:26:41.740
belief. Killing innocents is the least of the risks you're running. You're gambling with the fate of

06:26:41.740 --> 06:26:47.260
worlds, provoking conflict with the starfaring technology whose sole offense was to take your

06:26:47.260 --> 06:26:54.620
picture without permission. Your descent has changed nothing. So you reign it in. All that flips out

06:26:54.620 --> 06:26:59.980
now is the occasional pointless question with no hope of an answer. It's inherent in subordination

06:26:59.980 --> 06:27:05.100
so deeply buried you don't even see it in yourself. If you did see it, you'd keep your mouth shut

06:27:05.100 --> 06:27:09.740
entirely. Because the last thing you want is to remind Sotosti that you think he's wrong.

06:27:10.620 --> 06:27:14.860
You don't want him dwelling on that. You don't want him to think you're up to something.

06:27:15.820 --> 06:27:19.740
Because you are, even if you're not quite ready to admit it to yourself.

06:27:20.860 --> 06:27:24.540
Amanda Bates is beginning to confidently change of command.

06:27:27.900 --> 06:27:33.740
The laceration of my suit had done a real number on the gears. It took three solid days for Thesias

06:27:33.740 --> 06:27:38.460
to bring me back to life. But death was no excuse for falling behind the curve. I was

06:27:38.460 --> 06:27:43.580
resurrected with a head full of updates clogging my inlays. I flipped through them climbing into

06:27:43.580 --> 06:27:48.300
the drum. The gang of four sat at the galley below me staring at untouched portions of

06:27:48.300 --> 06:27:53.660
nutritionally balanced sludge on her plate. Cunningham over in his inherited domain grunted

06:27:53.660 --> 06:27:58.460
my appearance and turned back to work, the fingers of one hand tapping compulsively on the desktop.

06:27:59.740 --> 06:28:04.940
Thesias orbit had widened during my absence and most of its eccentricities had been plain

06:28:04.940 --> 06:28:11.580
to weigh. Now we kept our target in view for a more or less constant range of 3000 kilometers.

06:28:12.460 --> 06:28:18.300
Our orbital period lagged rorshawks by an hour. The alien crept implacably ahead of us

06:28:18.300 --> 06:28:23.100
along its lower trajectory. But a supplementary burn every couple of weeks would be enough to

06:28:23.100 --> 06:28:28.700
keep it in sight. We had specimens now, things to be examined under conditions of our own choosing,

06:28:28.700 --> 06:28:33.340
no point in risking any more close approaches until we'd rung every useful datum from what we had.

06:28:33.420 --> 06:28:39.100
Cunningham had expanded his lab space during my time in the sepulcher. He'd built

06:28:39.100 --> 06:28:44.140
holing pens, one for each scrambler, modules partitioned by a common wall and installed

06:28:44.140 --> 06:28:49.500
in a whole new hab. The microwaved carcass had been sidelined like a discarded toy from a previous

06:28:49.500 --> 06:28:53.740
birthday, although according to the access logs Cunningham still visited every now and again.

06:28:55.500 --> 06:29:00.860
Not that he visited any part of the new wing in person, of course. Not that he was even able to,

06:29:00.860 --> 06:29:05.980
not without suiting up and jumping across the hold. The whole compartment had been disconnected

06:29:05.980 --> 06:29:11.420
from its spinal lock and pushed to a tethered anchorage midway between the spine and carapace,

06:29:11.420 --> 06:29:17.420
so to us these orders, given to minimize risk of contamination. It was no skin off Cunningham's

06:29:17.420 --> 06:29:22.460
nose. He was happier leaving his body in pseudo-gravity anyway while his consciousness flitted

06:29:22.460 --> 06:29:25.820
between the wall-dose and sensors and brick-a-bracks surrounding his new pets.

06:29:26.780 --> 06:29:31.660
Thesias saw me coming and pushed a squeeze-bulb of sugary electrolytes from the galley dispenser.

06:29:32.300 --> 06:29:37.500
The gang didn't look up as I passed. One forefinger tapped ascent against their temple,

06:29:37.500 --> 06:29:42.540
the lips pursed and twitched in the characteristic mode that said internal dialogue and progress.

06:29:43.100 --> 06:29:45.580
I could never tell who was on top when they were like that.

06:29:46.540 --> 06:29:51.900
I sucked on the squeeze-bulb and looked in on the pens. Two cubes suffused in pale red light.

06:29:52.460 --> 06:29:57.420
In one, a scrambler floated center stage, waving at segmented arms like seaweed and gentle surge.

06:29:57.980 --> 06:30:02.460
The occupant of the other cage was squeezed into a corner. Four arms splayed across the

06:30:02.460 --> 06:30:08.380
converging walls, four others extended, waving again into open space. The bodies from which

06:30:08.380 --> 06:30:13.580
those arms sprouted were spheroids, not flattened discs as our first sample had been.

06:30:14.860 --> 06:30:20.300
They were only slightly compressed. Their arms sprouted and not from a single equatorial band,

06:30:20.300 --> 06:30:26.300
from across the whole surface. Fully extended, the floating scrambler was over two meters across.

06:30:27.180 --> 06:30:31.980
The other seemed roughly the same size, neither moved except for those drifting arms.

06:30:32.780 --> 06:30:37.500
Navy Blue Mosaics, almost black in the long wave, rippled across their surfaces like the

06:30:37.500 --> 06:30:43.340
patterns of wind on grass. Superimposed graphics plotted methane and hydrogen at reassuring

06:30:43.340 --> 06:30:49.500
Worshack norms, temperature and lighting ditto. An icon for ambient electromagnetics remained dark.

06:30:50.620 --> 06:30:54.620
I dipped into the archives, watched the arrival of the aliens from two days past,

06:30:54.620 --> 06:30:59.260
each tumbling unceremoniously into its pen, balled up, hugging themselves as they bounced

06:30:59.260 --> 06:31:04.940
gently around their enclosures. Fetal position, I thought. But after a few moments, the arms

06:31:04.940 --> 06:31:10.300
uncoiled like the blooming of calciferous flowers. Robert says Worshack grows them,

06:31:10.300 --> 06:31:16.300
Susan James said behind me. I turned. Definitely James in there, but muted somehow.

06:31:17.020 --> 06:31:19.900
Her meal remained untouched, their surfaces were dim.

06:31:21.420 --> 06:31:24.940
Except for those eyes. They were deep and a little hollow.

06:31:25.980 --> 06:31:32.540
Grows, I repeated. In stacks, they have two navels each. She managed a weak smile,

06:31:32.540 --> 06:31:37.180
touched her belly with one hand and the small of her back with the other. One in front, one behind.

06:31:37.740 --> 06:31:42.780
He thinks they grow in a kind of column, piled up. When the top one develops to a certain point,

06:31:42.940 --> 06:31:48.940
buds off from the stack and becomes free living. The archived scramblers were exploring their new

06:31:48.940 --> 06:31:53.500
environment now, climbing gingerly along the walls, unrolling their arms along the corners

06:31:53.500 --> 06:32:00.460
where the panels met. Their swollen central bodies struck me again. So that first one with the flattened

06:32:01.020 --> 06:32:07.980
juvenile, she agreed. Fresh off the stack. These ones are older. They plump out as they mature,

06:32:07.980 --> 06:32:13.580
Robert says. She had it after a moment. I sucked the dregs to my squeeze bulb.

06:32:14.380 --> 06:32:20.060
The ship grows its own crew. If it's a ship, James shrugged. If they're crew.

06:32:21.500 --> 06:32:27.660
I watched them move. There wasn't much to explore. The walls were almost bare, innocent of anything,

06:32:27.660 --> 06:32:32.780
but a few sensor heads and gas nozzles. The pens had their own tentacles and manipulators and more

06:32:32.780 --> 06:32:37.100
invasive research needs, but those have been carefully sheathed during introduction.

06:32:38.540 --> 06:32:43.180
Still, the creatures covered the territory in careful increments, moving back and forth along

06:32:43.180 --> 06:32:50.140
parallel invisible paths, almost as if they were running transects. James had noticed it too.

06:32:51.500 --> 06:32:58.300
It seems awfully systematic, doesn't it? What does Robert say about that? He says the behavior

06:32:58.300 --> 06:33:03.740
of honeybees and specksbloss is just as complex, and it's all road hardwiring, not intelligence.

06:33:04.060 --> 06:33:10.060
But bees still communicate, right? They do that dance, they tell the hive where the flowers are.

06:33:10.940 --> 06:33:15.740
She shrugged, conceding the point. So you might still be able to talk to these things.

06:33:16.780 --> 06:33:23.340
Maybe. You'd think. So you massaged her brow between thumb and forefinger. We haven't got

06:33:23.340 --> 06:33:27.980
anywhere, though. We played some of their pigment patterns back to them with variations.

06:33:27.980 --> 06:33:33.100
They don't seem to make sounds. Robert synthesized a bunch of noises that they might squeeze out of

06:33:33.100 --> 06:33:37.740
their cloaca if they were so inclined, but those didn't get us anywhere. Harmonic farts, really.

06:33:39.100 --> 06:33:43.980
So we're sticking to the blood cells of Waldo's model. Pretty much, but you know,

06:33:43.980 --> 06:33:49.340
they didn't go into a loop. Hardwired animals repeat themselves, even smart ones pace or chew

06:33:49.340 --> 06:33:55.100
their fur. Stereotype behaviors. But these two, they gave everything a very careful once over,

06:33:55.100 --> 06:34:01.020
and then just shut down. They were still at it in consensus, slithering across one wall,

06:34:01.100 --> 06:34:06.140
than another, than another. A slow screw thread track that would leave no square centimeter

06:34:06.140 --> 06:34:12.940
uncovered. Have they done anything since? I asked. She shrugged again. Nothing spectacular.

06:34:12.940 --> 06:34:16.860
They squirm when you poke them. Wave their arms back and forth. They do that pretty much

06:34:16.860 --> 06:34:21.980
constantly, but there's no information in it that we can tell. They haven't gone invisible on us or

06:34:21.980 --> 06:34:28.300
anything. We blanked the adjoining wall for a while so they could see each other, even piped

06:34:28.300 --> 06:34:33.900
audio and air feeds. Robert thought there might be some kind of pheromonal communication, but nothing.

06:34:33.900 --> 06:34:40.380
They didn't even react to each other. Have you tried, well, motivating them? With what,

06:34:40.380 --> 06:34:45.020
Siri? They don't seem to care about their own company. We can't bribe them with food unless

06:34:45.020 --> 06:34:50.060
we know what they eat, which we don't. Robert says they're in no immediate danger of starvation

06:34:50.060 --> 06:34:55.980
anyway. Maybe they, when they get hungry, but they can deal. I killed the archival feed and

06:34:55.980 --> 06:35:02.860
reverted the real time. Maybe they eat, I don't know, radiation or magnetic energy. The cage can

06:35:02.860 --> 06:35:09.180
generate magnetic fields, right? Try it. She took a breath and squared her shoulders. But I guess

06:35:09.180 --> 06:35:13.980
these things take time. He's only had a couple of days and I only got out of the crypt myself a day

06:35:13.980 --> 06:35:21.260
ago. We'll keep trying. What about negative reinforcement? I wondered. She blinked. Hurt

06:35:21.260 --> 06:35:26.700
them, you mean. Not necessarily anything extreme. And if they're not sent to you in any way.

06:35:27.660 --> 06:35:33.820
Just like that, Susan went away. Why, Keaton, you just made a suggestion. You're giving up on this

06:35:33.820 --> 06:35:39.580
whole non-interference thing? Hello, Sasha. No, of course not. Just making a list of what's been

06:35:39.580 --> 06:35:46.380
tried. Good. There was an edge to her voice. Hate to think you were slipping. We're going to grab

06:35:46.380 --> 06:35:52.940
some downtime now, so maybe you could go and talk to Cunningham for a bit. Yeah, do that. And be sure

06:35:52.940 --> 06:35:57.100
to tell him your theory about radiation-eating aliens. I bet he could use a laugh.

06:36:00.380 --> 06:36:06.140
He stood at his post in Biomed, though his empty chair was barely a meter away. The ubiquitous

06:36:06.140 --> 06:36:11.820
cigarette hung from between the fingers of one hand, burned down and burned out. His other hand

06:36:11.820 --> 06:36:16.620
played with itself, fingers tapping against them in sequence, little to index, index to little.

06:36:17.260 --> 06:36:20.300
Windows crawled with intelligence in front of him. He wasn't watching.

06:36:21.340 --> 06:36:26.860
I approached him from behind. I watched his surfaces in motion. I heard the soft syllables

06:36:26.860 --> 06:36:37.100
rising from his throat. Yid par, yish taba, vid par, vid romam. Not his usual litany.

06:36:37.820 --> 06:36:43.260
Not even his usual language, Hebrew consensus said. It sounded almost like a prayer.

06:36:44.620 --> 06:36:49.260
He must have heard me. His topology went flat and hard and almost impossible to decipher.

06:36:49.980 --> 06:36:55.420
It was increasingly difficult getting a fix on anyone these days, but even through these topological

06:36:55.420 --> 06:36:58.460
cataracts, Cunningham as always was a tougher read than most.

06:36:59.420 --> 06:37:01.660
Keaton, he said, without turning.

06:37:02.620 --> 06:37:04.220
You're not Jewish, I said.

06:37:05.100 --> 06:37:11.100
It was. Spindle, I realized after a moment. Cunningham didn't do gender pronouns.

06:37:12.460 --> 06:37:17.900
But Isaac Spindle had been an atheist. All of us were. We'd all started out that way, at least.

06:37:19.420 --> 06:37:23.340
I didn't know you knew him, I said. It certainly wasn't policy.

06:37:23.420 --> 06:37:28.780
Cunningham sank into his chair without looking at me. In his head and in mine,

06:37:28.780 --> 06:37:32.860
a new window opened within a frame marked Electroferophoresis.

06:37:34.060 --> 06:37:39.020
I tried again. I'm sorry, I didn't mean to intrude. What can I do for you, Siri?

06:37:40.300 --> 06:37:43.340
I was hoping you could bring me up to speed on your findings.

06:37:44.700 --> 06:37:50.060
A periodic chart of alien elements scrolled through the feed. Cunningham logged it and started

06:37:50.060 --> 06:37:53.900
another sample. I have documented everything. It's all in consensus.

06:37:55.100 --> 06:37:59.820
I made a play for ego. It would really help to know how a huge thumbnail it, though.

06:38:00.540 --> 06:38:03.740
What you think is important can be just as vital as the data themselves.

06:38:04.860 --> 06:38:08.620
He looked at me a moment. He muttered something repetitive and irrelevant.

06:38:09.500 --> 06:38:15.260
What's important is what's missing, he said after a moment. I've got good samples now and I still

06:38:15.260 --> 06:38:20.220
can't find the genes. Protein synthesis is almost prionic. Reconformation instead of the

06:38:20.220 --> 06:38:25.980
usual transcription pathways. But I can't figure out how those bricks get slotted into the wall

06:38:25.980 --> 06:38:33.980
once they're made. Any progress on the energy front? I asked. Energy? Aerobic metabolism on

06:38:33.980 --> 06:38:40.220
an anaerobic budget, remember? You said they had too much ATP. That I solved. He puffed smoke,

06:38:40.300 --> 06:38:44.540
far discerned a flak of alien tissue liquefied and banded into chemical strata.

06:38:45.180 --> 06:38:53.420
They're sprinting. Rotate that if you can. I couldn't. How do you mean? He sighed.

06:38:54.460 --> 06:38:59.980
Biochemistry is a trade-off. The faster you synthesize ATP, the more expensive each molecule

06:38:59.980 --> 06:39:04.860
becomes. It turns out scramblers are a lot more energy efficient in making it than we are.

06:39:04.860 --> 06:39:09.180
They're just extremely slow at it, which might not be a big drawback for something that spends

06:39:09.180 --> 06:39:14.540
most of its time inactive. Rorschach, whatever Rorschach started out as, could have drifted

06:39:14.540 --> 06:39:22.380
from millennia before it washed up here. That's a lot of time to build up an energy reserve for

06:39:22.380 --> 06:39:28.220
bouts of high activity. And once you've laid the groundwork, glycolysis is explosive. 2000

06:39:28.220 --> 06:39:36.060
fold boost and no oxygen demand. Scramblers sprint their whole lives. They may come preloaded with

06:39:36.060 --> 06:39:40.540
ATP and burn it off throughout their lifespan. How long would that be?

06:39:41.420 --> 06:39:45.180
Good question, he'd made it. Live fast, die young. If they ration it out,

06:39:45.180 --> 06:39:51.420
stay dormant most of the time. Who knows? Huh. The free-floating scrambler had drifted away

06:39:51.420 --> 06:39:56.380
from the center of its pen. One extended arm held a wall at bay. The others continued their

06:39:56.380 --> 06:40:03.740
hypnotic swaying. I remembered other arms, their motion not so gentle. Amanda and I chased one into

06:40:03.740 --> 06:40:10.940
a crowd. It... Cunningham was back at his samples. I saw the record. They tore it to pieces.

06:40:12.060 --> 06:40:19.420
Uh-huh. Any idea why? He shrugged. Bates thought there might be some kind of civil war going on

06:40:19.420 --> 06:40:26.620
down there. What do you think? I don't know. Maybe it's right. Or maybe scramblers are ritual

06:40:26.620 --> 06:40:33.500
cannibals or... or they're aliens, Keaton. What do you want from me? But they're not really aliens,

06:40:33.500 --> 06:40:38.780
at least not intelligent ones. War implies intelligence. Ants wage war all the time, proves

06:40:38.780 --> 06:40:45.580
nothing except that they're alive. Are scramblers even alive? I asked. What kind of question is that?

06:40:46.700 --> 06:40:51.500
You think Rorschach grows them on some kind of assembly line. You can't find any genes. Maybe

06:40:51.500 --> 06:40:56.940
they're just biomechanical machines. That's what life is, Keaton. That's what you are.

06:40:57.740 --> 06:41:01.340
Another hit of nicotine. Another storm of numbers. Another sample.

06:41:02.300 --> 06:41:08.540
Life isn't either or. It's a matter of degree. What I'm asking is, are they natural? Could they be

06:41:08.540 --> 06:41:15.820
constructs? Is a termite mound a construct? Beaver dam? Spaceship? Of course. Were they built by

06:41:15.820 --> 06:41:21.580
naturally evolved organisms, acting naturally? They were. So tell me how anything in the whole

06:41:21.580 --> 06:41:27.980
deep multiverse can either be anything but natural. I try to keep the irritation out of my voice.

06:41:28.940 --> 06:41:33.980
You know what I mean. It's a meaningless question. Get your head out of the 20th century.

06:41:35.340 --> 06:41:41.260
I gave up. After a few seconds, Cunningham seemed to notice the silence. He withdrew his

06:41:41.260 --> 06:41:45.340
consciousness from the machinery and looked around with fleshly eyes as if searching for

06:41:45.340 --> 06:41:47.820
some mosquito that had mysteriously stopped whining.

06:41:49.020 --> 06:41:55.420
What's your problem with me? I asked. Stupid question. Obvious question. Unworthy of any

06:41:55.420 --> 06:42:04.060
synthesis to be so so direct. His eyes glittered in that dead face. Processing without comprehension.

06:42:04.060 --> 06:42:08.540
That's what you do, isn't it? That's a colossal oversimplification.

06:42:09.580 --> 06:42:16.620
Hmm. Cunningham nodded. Then why can't you seem to comprehend how pointless it is to keep peeking

06:42:16.620 --> 06:42:21.740
over our shoulders and riding home to our masters? Someone has to keep Earth in the loop.

06:42:22.540 --> 06:42:30.220
Seven months each way. Long loop. Still. We're on our own out here, Keaton. You're on your own.

06:42:30.220 --> 06:42:35.420
The game's going to be long over before our masters even know it started. He sucked smoke.

06:42:36.860 --> 06:42:43.500
Or perhaps not. Perhaps you're talking to someone closer, hmm? That it? Is the fourth wave telling

06:42:43.500 --> 06:42:50.860
you what to do? There is no fourth wave. Not that anyone's told me anyway. Probably not.

06:42:50.860 --> 06:42:55.100
They'd never risk their lives out here, would they? Too dangerous even to hang back and

06:42:55.100 --> 06:43:01.340
waft from a distance. That's why they built us. We're all self-made. Nobody forced you to get

06:43:01.340 --> 06:43:07.020
the rewire. No, nobody forced me to get the rewire. I could have just let them cut out my

06:43:07.020 --> 06:43:13.020
brain and pack it into heaven, couldn't I? That's the choice we have. We can be utterly useless,

06:43:13.020 --> 06:43:16.940
or we can try and compete against the vampires and the constructs of the AIs.

06:43:17.820 --> 06:43:21.180
And perhaps you could tell me how to do that without turning into a

06:43:21.740 --> 06:43:28.860
another freak. So much in the voice. Nothing at all in the face. I said nothing.

06:43:30.060 --> 06:43:34.380
See what I mean? No comprehension. You managed a tight smile.

06:43:35.420 --> 06:43:40.620
So I'll answer your questions. I'll delay my own work and hold your hand because the last

06:43:40.620 --> 06:43:45.980
he's told us to. I'll guess that superior vampire mind sees some legitimate reason to

06:43:46.060 --> 06:43:50.380
indulge your constant ankle nipping, and it's in charge, so I'll play along.

06:43:51.340 --> 06:43:55.100
But I'm not nearly that smart, so you'll forgive me if it all seems a bit naff.

06:43:56.220 --> 06:44:01.980
I'm just... you're just doing your job, I know. But I don't like being played, Keaton.

06:44:02.780 --> 06:44:04.140
And that's what your job is.

06:44:08.940 --> 06:44:13.980
Even back on Earth, Robert Cunningham had barely disguised his opinion of the ship's commissar.

06:44:14.620 --> 06:44:20.140
It had been obvious even at the topologically blind. I'd always had a hard time imagining the man.

06:44:20.940 --> 06:44:27.020
It wasn't just his expressionless face. Sometimes, not even the subtler things behind

06:44:27.020 --> 06:44:31.180
would show up in his topology. Perhaps he repressed them deliberately,

06:44:31.180 --> 06:44:36.300
resenting the presence of this mole among the crew. It would hardly have been the first time

06:44:36.300 --> 06:44:42.940
I'd encountered such a reaction. Everyone resented me to some extent. Oh, they liked me well enough,

06:44:42.940 --> 06:44:48.300
or thought they did. They tolerated my intrusions and cooperated and gave away far more than they

06:44:48.300 --> 06:44:54.460
thought they did. But beneath spindles, gruff camaraderie, beneath James' patient explanations,

06:44:54.460 --> 06:44:59.100
there was no real respect. How could there be? These people were the bleeding edge,

06:44:59.100 --> 06:45:04.540
the incandescent apex of hominid achievement. They were trusted with the fate of the world.

06:45:04.540 --> 06:45:10.540
I was just a tattletale for small minds back home. Not even that much when home receded too deeply

06:45:10.540 --> 06:45:16.380
into the distance. Superfluous mass. Couldn't be helped. No use getting bothered over it.

06:45:17.500 --> 06:45:23.340
Still, spindle had only coined commissar half jokingly. Cunningham believed it and didn't laugh.

06:45:24.060 --> 06:45:26.860
And while I'd encountered many others like him over the years,

06:45:26.860 --> 06:45:31.580
those had only tried to hide themselves from sight. Cunningham was the first it seemed to succeed.

06:45:32.460 --> 06:45:36.300
I tried to build a relationship all the way through the training, tried to find the missing

06:45:36.300 --> 06:45:42.380
pieces. I watched him working the simulator's telops one day, exercising the shiny new interfaces

06:45:42.380 --> 06:45:47.100
that spread him through the walls and wires. He was practicing his surgical skills on some

06:45:47.100 --> 06:45:52.300
hypothetical alien the computer had conjured up to test his technique. Sensors and jointed

06:45:52.300 --> 06:45:57.820
telops sprouted like the legs of an enormous spider crab from an overhead mount. Spirit possessed.

06:45:57.820 --> 06:46:03.180
They dipped and weaved around some semi plausible holographic creature. Cunningham's own body

06:46:03.180 --> 06:46:08.540
merely trembled slightly, cigarette jiggling at the corner of its mouth. I waited for him to take

06:46:08.540 --> 06:46:13.660
a break. Eventually the tension ebbed from his shoulders. His vicarious limbs relaxed.

06:46:14.780 --> 06:46:20.780
So I tapped my temple. Why'd you do it? He didn't turn. Above the dissection,

06:46:20.780 --> 06:46:26.060
sensors swiveled and stared back like dismembered ice docks. That was the center of Cunningham's

06:46:26.060 --> 06:46:32.220
awareness right now. Not this nicotine stained body in front of me. Those were his eyes or his tongue

06:46:32.220 --> 06:46:38.220
or whatever unimaginable bastard senses he used to parse with the machine sent him. Those clusters

06:46:38.220 --> 06:46:43.820
aimed back at me at us. As if Robert Cunningham still possessed anything that might be called vision.

06:46:43.820 --> 06:46:47.740
He was watching himself eyes two meters outside of his own skull.

06:46:49.260 --> 06:46:52.220
Do what exactly? He said at last. The enhancements?

06:46:53.420 --> 06:46:57.900
Enhancements. As though he'd upgraded his wardrobe instead of ripping out his senses and

06:46:57.900 --> 06:47:04.140
grafting new ones into the wounds. I nodded. It's vital to keep current, he said. If you

06:47:04.140 --> 06:47:08.940
don't reconfigure you can't retrain. If you don't retrain you're obsolete within a month,

06:47:08.940 --> 06:47:13.660
and then you're not much good for anything except heaven or dictation. I ignored the jibe.

06:47:14.300 --> 06:47:21.180
Pretty radical transformation though. Not these days. Didn't it change you? His body dragged on

06:47:21.180 --> 06:47:26.460
the cigarette. Targeted ventilation sucked away the smoke before it reached me. That's the whole

06:47:26.460 --> 06:47:34.380
point. Surely he were affected personally though. Surely. Ah, he nodded at the far end of shared

06:47:34.380 --> 06:47:39.660
motor nerves, tail ops jiggled in sympathy. Changed the eyes to look at the world, changed the me

06:47:39.660 --> 06:47:45.660
that does the looking. Something like that. Now he was watching me with fleshly eyes.

06:47:45.660 --> 06:47:50.300
Across the membrane those snakes and eye stocks returned to their work on the virtual carcass,

06:47:50.300 --> 06:47:55.740
as if deciding they wasted enough time on pointless distraction. I wondered which body he was in now.

06:47:56.940 --> 06:48:02.460
I'm surprised you'd have to ask, the meat one said. Doesn't my body language tell you everything?

06:48:02.460 --> 06:48:07.500
Aren't jargonauts supposed to read minds? He was right of course. I wasn't interested in

06:48:07.500 --> 06:48:12.940
Cunningham's words. Those were just the carrier wave. He couldn't hear the real conversation we

06:48:12.940 --> 06:48:18.220
were having. All his angles and services spoke volumes, and although their voices were strangely

06:48:18.220 --> 06:48:22.940
fizzled with feedback and distortion, I knew I'd be able to understand them eventually. I only had

06:48:22.940 --> 06:48:29.900
to keep him talking. But Yuka Sarasti chose that moment to wander past and surgically trash my best

06:48:29.900 --> 06:48:36.540
laid plans. Ciri is the best in the field, he remarked, but not when it gets too close to home.

06:48:39.900 --> 06:48:45.260
Why should man expect his prayer for mercy to be heard by what is above him when he shows no

06:48:45.340 --> 06:48:49.500
mercy to what is under him? Pierre Trobetskoy.

06:48:51.340 --> 06:48:57.980
The thing is, Chelsea said, this whole first person thing takes effort. You have to care

06:48:57.980 --> 06:49:03.260
enough to try, you know? I've been working my ass off on this relationship. I've been working so

06:49:03.260 --> 06:49:09.260
hard, but you just don't seem to care. She thought she was breaking the news. She thought I hadn't

06:49:09.260 --> 06:49:15.020
seen it coming because I hadn't said anything. I'd probably seen it before she had. I hadn't

06:49:15.020 --> 06:49:19.660
said anything because I'd been scared of giving her an opening. I felt sick to my stomach.

06:49:20.700 --> 06:49:27.340
I care about you, I said. As much as you care about anything, she admitted. But you, I mean,

06:49:27.340 --> 06:49:31.980
sometimes you're fine sickness, sometimes you're wonderful to be around, and whenever anything

06:49:31.980 --> 06:49:37.260
gets the least bit intense, you just go away and leave this battle computer running your body,

06:49:37.260 --> 06:49:42.620
and I just can't deal with it anymore. I stared at the butterfly on the back of her hand.

06:49:43.420 --> 06:49:51.900
Its wings flexed and folded, lazy and iridescent. I wondered how many of those tattoos she had.

06:49:52.540 --> 06:49:55.980
I'd seen five of them on different body parts, albeit only one at a time.

06:49:56.780 --> 06:49:59.580
I thought about asking her, but this didn't seem like the right moment.

06:50:00.540 --> 06:50:08.460
You can be so, so brutal sometimes, she was saying. I know you don't mean to be, but I don't know.

06:50:08.460 --> 06:50:13.260
Maybe I'm your pressure release valve or something. Maybe you have to submerge yourself

06:50:13.260 --> 06:50:17.340
so much on the job that everything just builds up and you need some kind of punching bag.

06:50:17.900 --> 06:50:22.780
Maybe that's why you say the things you do. She waited for me to say anything now.

06:50:23.900 --> 06:50:29.980
I've been honest, I said. Yeah, pathologically. Have you ever had a negative thought that you

06:50:29.980 --> 06:50:36.300
haven't said out loud? Her voice trembled, but her eyes for one stayed dry. I guess it's as much

06:50:36.300 --> 06:50:41.980
my fault as yours, maybe more. I could tell you were disconnected from the day we met. I guess

06:50:41.980 --> 06:50:48.540
on some level I always saw it coming. Why even try then, if you knew we were just going to crash

06:50:48.540 --> 06:50:55.020
and burn like this. Oh, sickness. Aren't you the one who says everyone crashes and burns eventually?

06:50:55.020 --> 06:51:00.940
Aren't you the one that says it never lasts? Mom and Dad lasted longer than this anyway.

06:51:01.580 --> 06:51:05.740
I frowned, astonished that I'd even let the thought form in my head.

06:51:06.540 --> 06:51:12.860
Chels read the silence as a wounded one. I guess... maybe I thought I could help, you know?

06:51:13.420 --> 06:51:16.940
Help fix whatever made you so, so angry all the time.

06:51:17.980 --> 06:51:22.060
The butterfly was starting to fade. I'd never seen that happen before.

06:51:22.860 --> 06:51:27.740
Do you understand what I'm saying? She asked. Sure, I'm a fixer upper.

06:51:28.700 --> 06:51:33.340
Siri, you wouldn't even get a tweak when I offered. You were so scared of being manipulated,

06:51:33.340 --> 06:51:38.940
you wouldn't even try a basic cascade. You're the one guy I've met who might be truly eternally

06:51:38.940 --> 06:51:45.740
unfixable. Maybe that's even something to be proud of. I opened my mouth and closed it.

06:51:46.860 --> 06:51:52.460
She gave me a sad smile. Nothing, Siri, nothing at all. There was a time when you always knew

06:51:52.460 --> 06:51:56.700
exactly what to say. She looked back at some earlier version of me.

06:51:58.140 --> 06:52:00.460
Now I wonder if you actually meant any of it.

06:52:02.220 --> 06:52:09.260
That's not fair. No, she pursed her lips. No, it isn't. That's not really what I'm trying to say.

06:52:09.980 --> 06:52:15.420
I guess it's not so much that you don't mean any of it. It's more like you don't know what any of

06:52:15.420 --> 06:52:21.420
it means. The color was gone from the wings. The butterfly was a delicate charcoal dusting,

06:52:21.420 --> 06:52:27.580
almost motionless. I'll do it now, I said. I'll get the tweaks. If it's that important to you,

06:52:27.580 --> 06:52:35.100
I'll do it now. It's too late, Siri. I'm used up. Maybe she wanted me to call her back.

06:52:36.060 --> 06:52:41.420
All these words ending in question marks, all these significant silences. Maybe she was giving me

06:52:41.420 --> 06:52:47.180
the opportunity to plead for my case, to beg for another chance. Maybe she wanted a reason to

06:52:47.180 --> 06:52:53.820
change her mind. I could have tried. Please don't, I could have said. I'm begging you. I never meant

06:52:53.820 --> 06:53:00.620
to drive you away completely, just a little, just to a safer distance. Please. In thirty long years,

06:53:00.620 --> 06:53:06.300
the only time I haven't felt worthless is when we were together. But when I looked up again,

06:53:06.300 --> 06:53:11.900
the butterfly was gone and so was she, taking all baggage with her. She carried doubt and guilt for

06:53:11.980 --> 06:53:17.260
having led me on. She left believing that our incompatibility was no one's fault, that she

06:53:17.260 --> 06:53:23.420
tried as hard as she could, even that I had under the tragic weight of all my issues. She left,

06:53:23.420 --> 06:53:27.660
and maybe she didn't even blame me, and I never even knew who'd made that final decision.

06:53:29.020 --> 06:53:33.660
I was good at what I did. I was so damned good I did it without even meaning to.

06:53:35.660 --> 06:53:41.260
My god, did you hear that? Susan James bounced around the drum like a pranking wheeled a beast

06:53:41.260 --> 06:53:45.100
in the half gravity. I could see the whites of her eyes from ninety degrees away.

06:53:45.900 --> 06:53:51.980
Check your feeds, check your feeds, the pens! I checked. One scrambler afloat, the other still

06:53:51.980 --> 06:53:57.980
jammed into its corner. James landed at my side with a two-footed thump, wobbling for balance.

06:53:57.980 --> 06:54:03.180
Turn the sound up! The hissing of the air conditioners, the clank of distant machinery

06:54:03.180 --> 06:54:09.900
echoing along with spine, theseus usual intestinal rumblings, nothing else. Okay, they're not doing

06:54:09.900 --> 06:54:14.060
it now. James brought up a split-screen window and threw it into reverse.

06:54:14.060 --> 06:54:19.420
THERE, she pronounced, replaying the record with the audio crank and filtered. In the right side

06:54:19.420 --> 06:54:23.580
of the window, the floating scrambler had drifted so that the tip of one outstretched

06:54:23.580 --> 06:54:28.220
arm brushed against the wall to join the other pen. In the left side, the huddled scrambler

06:54:28.220 --> 06:54:33.820
remained unmoving. I thought I heard something. Just for an instant, the brief buzz of an insect,

06:54:33.820 --> 06:54:39.020
perhaps if the nearest insect hadn't been five trillion kilometers away. Replay that,

06:54:39.020 --> 06:54:48.220
slow it down. A buzz, definitely. A vibration. Way down. A click train, squirted from the dolphin's

06:54:48.220 --> 06:54:55.420
forehead. Farting lips. No, let me. James bullied into Cunningham's headspace and yanked the slider

06:54:55.420 --> 06:55:04.780
to the left. Tick-tick-tick, tick-tick-tick, tick-tick-tick. Doppler down near absolute zero,

06:55:04.780 --> 06:55:09.580
it went on for almost a minute. Total elapsed real time was about half a second.

06:55:10.540 --> 06:55:14.620
Cunningham zoomed the split-screen. The huddled scrambler had remained motionless,

06:55:14.620 --> 06:55:18.460
except for the rippling of its cuticle and the undulation of its free arms.

06:55:19.260 --> 06:55:24.620
But before, I'd only seen eight arms. Now I could make out the bony spur of a ninth from peaking

06:55:24.620 --> 06:55:30.460
from behind the central mass. A ninth arm curled up and hidden from view, tick-tick-ticking while

06:55:30.460 --> 06:55:36.060
another creature casually leaned against the other side of the wall. Now there was nothing.

06:55:36.060 --> 06:55:39.740
The floating scrambler had drifted aimlessly back to the center of its enclosure.

06:55:41.020 --> 06:55:43.820
James' eyes shone. We've got to check the rest of...

06:55:44.780 --> 06:55:49.740
But Thesias had been watching and was way ahead of us. It had already searched the archives and

06:55:49.740 --> 06:55:55.580
served up the results. Three similar exchanges over two days, ranging in duration from a tenth

06:55:55.580 --> 06:56:03.420
of a second to almost two. They're talking, James said. Cunningham shrugged, a forgotten

06:56:03.420 --> 06:56:09.020
cigarette burning down between his fingers. So do a lot of things, and at that rate of exchange,

06:56:09.020 --> 06:56:13.820
they're not exactly doing calculus. You'd get as much information out of a dancing honeybee.

06:56:14.780 --> 06:56:19.100
That's nonsense and you know it, Robert. What I know is that...

06:56:19.740 --> 06:56:24.380
Honeybees don't deliberately hide what they're saying. Honeybees don't develop new whole new

06:56:24.380 --> 06:56:30.380
modes of communication configured specifically to confound observers. That's flexible, Robert.

06:56:30.380 --> 06:56:35.900
That's intelligent. And what if it is, hm? Forget for a moment the inconvenient fact that these

06:56:35.900 --> 06:56:41.420
things don't even have brains. I really don't think you've thought this through. Of course I have.

06:56:42.540 --> 06:56:46.300
Indeed, the more you're so happy about, don't you know what this means?

06:56:47.180 --> 06:56:52.380
Suddenly, prickling on the back of my neck, I looked around. I looked up.

06:56:53.260 --> 06:56:59.020
Yucca Sardosti had appeared in the center of the drum, eyes gleaming, teeth bared, watching us.

06:56:59.900 --> 06:57:04.220
Cunningham followed my gaze and nodded. I had wager it does.

06:57:07.420 --> 06:57:10.460
There was no way to learn what they'd whispered across that wall.

06:57:11.180 --> 06:57:17.660
Enough. Parse every tick and tap they'd exchanged. But you can't decipher a code without some idea of

06:57:17.660 --> 06:57:22.940
content. We had patterns of sound that could have meant anything. We had creatures whose grammar

06:57:22.940 --> 06:57:28.140
and syntax, if their mode of communication even contained such attributes, were unknown.

06:57:28.940 --> 06:57:35.580
And perhaps unknowable. We had creatures smart enough to talk and smart enough to hide this fact.

06:57:36.220 --> 06:57:39.980
No matter how much we wanted to learn, they were obviously unwilling to teach us.

06:57:40.860 --> 06:57:44.700
Not without, how had I put it, negative reinforcement.

06:57:46.300 --> 06:57:51.820
It was Yucca Sardosti who made the decision. We did it on his orders, as we did everything else.

06:57:52.700 --> 06:57:56.780
But after the word had come down, after Sardosti had disappeared into the night,

06:57:56.780 --> 06:58:01.100
and Bates had retreated down the spine and Robert Cunningham had returned to his studies at the back

06:58:01.100 --> 06:58:08.140
of the drum, I was the one Susan James was left with. The first to speak the vile thought aloud,

06:58:08.140 --> 06:58:13.180
the official witness to posterity. I was the one she looked at and looked away from,

06:58:13.180 --> 06:58:20.940
her surfaces hard and refractory. And then she started. This is how you break down a wall.

06:58:22.140 --> 06:58:26.540
Start with two beings. They can be human if you like, but that's hardly a prerequisite.

06:58:27.180 --> 06:58:33.340
All that matters is that they know how to talk among themselves. Separate them. Let them see each

06:58:33.340 --> 06:58:39.900
other. Let them speak. Perhaps a window between their cages. Perhaps an audio feed. Let them

06:58:39.900 --> 06:58:46.780
practice the art of conversation in their own chosen way. Hurt them. It may take a while to figure

06:58:46.780 --> 06:58:53.980
out how. Some may shrink from fire, others some toxic gas or a liquid. Some creatures may be

06:58:53.980 --> 06:58:58.620
invulnerable to blow torches and grenades, but shriek in terror at the threat of ultrasonic sound.

06:58:59.580 --> 06:59:03.820
You have to experiment. And when you discover just the right stimulus,

06:59:03.820 --> 06:59:08.860
the optimum balance between pain and injury, you must inflict it without remorse.

06:59:10.060 --> 06:59:14.860
You leave them an escape hatch, of course. That's the very point of the exercise. Give

06:59:14.860 --> 06:59:20.140
one of your subjects the means to end the pain, but give the other the information required to use it.

06:59:21.500 --> 06:59:25.500
To one, you might present a single shape, while showing the other a whole selection.

06:59:26.460 --> 06:59:31.100
The pain will stop when the being with the menu chooses the item its partner has seen.

06:59:32.380 --> 06:59:39.580
So let the games begin. Watch your subjects squirm. If, when, they trip the off switch,

06:59:40.300 --> 06:59:43.580
you'll know at least some of the information was exchanged.

06:59:45.340 --> 06:59:50.220
And if you record everything that passed between them, you'll start to get some idea of how they

06:59:50.220 --> 06:59:57.100
exchanged it. When they solve one puzzle, give them a new one. Mix things up. Switch their roles.

06:59:57.100 --> 07:00:02.460
See how they do its circles versus squares. Try them out on factorials and fibonaches.

07:00:02.460 --> 07:00:09.580
Continue until Rosetta Stone results. This is how you communicate with a fellow intelligence.

07:00:10.460 --> 07:00:16.060
You hurt it and keep on hurting it until you can distinguish the speech from the screams.

07:00:16.140 --> 07:00:21.180
Susan James, congenital optimist, high priestess of the Church of the Healing Word,

07:00:21.180 --> 07:00:26.940
was best qualified to design and execute the protocols. Now at her command, the scramblers

07:00:26.940 --> 07:00:33.260
writhe. They pulled themselves around their cages in elliptical loops, desperately seeking any small

07:00:33.260 --> 07:00:38.780
corner free of stimulus. James had piped the feet into consensus, although there was no mission

07:00:38.780 --> 07:00:42.460
critical reason for Thezi as whole crew to bear witness to the interrogation.

07:00:42.540 --> 07:00:48.620
Let them block it at their ends, she said quietly, if they want to.

07:00:50.300 --> 07:00:55.580
For all his reluctance to accept that these were beings intelligent and aware, Cunningham had named

07:00:55.580 --> 07:01:01.180
the prisoners. Stretch tended to float spread eagle, clench was the bald up corner hugger.

07:01:02.220 --> 07:01:06.940
Susan, playing her own part in this perverse role reversal, had simply numbered them one and two.

07:01:07.900 --> 07:01:12.780
It wasn't that Cunningham's choices were too cheesy for her to stomach, or that she objected to

07:01:12.780 --> 07:01:18.620
the slave names on principle. She'd just fallen back on the oldest trick in the torturer's handbook,

07:01:18.620 --> 07:01:22.540
the one that lets you go home to your family after work and play with your children and sleep at

07:01:22.540 --> 07:01:29.580
night. Never humanize your victims. It shouldn't have been such an issue when dealing with methane

07:01:29.580 --> 07:01:36.700
breathing Medusae. I guess every little bit helped. Bio-telemetry danced across the headspace beside

07:01:36.780 --> 07:01:42.620
each alien, luminous annotation shuddering through thin air. I had no idea what constituted normal

07:01:42.620 --> 07:01:48.300
relings for these creatures, but I couldn't imagine these jagged spikes passing for anything but bad

07:01:48.300 --> 07:01:54.620
news. The creatures themselves seethed subtly with fine mosaics in blue and gray, fluid patterns

07:01:54.620 --> 07:02:00.300
rippling across their cuticles. Perhaps it was a reflexive reaction to the microwaves, for all we

07:02:00.300 --> 07:02:06.940
knew it was a mating display. More likely they were screaming. James killed the microwaves.

07:02:07.660 --> 07:02:13.660
In the left hand enclosure a yellow square dimmed. In the right, an identical icon nested among others

07:02:13.660 --> 07:02:19.820
had never lit. The pigment flowed faster in the wake of the onslaught. The arms slowed but didn't

07:02:19.820 --> 07:02:28.060
stop. They swept back and forth like listless skeletal eels. Baseline exposure, five seconds,

07:02:28.140 --> 07:02:35.100
350 watts. She spoke for the record. Another affectation. Theseus recorded every breath on

07:02:35.100 --> 07:02:43.020
record, every trickle of current to five decimal places. Repeat. The icon lit up. More tile patterns

07:02:43.020 --> 07:02:50.300
flash flooding across alien skin. But this time, a nether alien moved from where it was. Their

07:02:50.300 --> 07:02:56.220
arms continued to squirm slightly. A torqued, trembling variation on the undulation that they

07:02:56.220 --> 07:03:02.460
affected at rest. The telemetry was as harsh as ever, though. They learned helplessness fast

07:03:02.460 --> 07:03:08.140
enough, I reflect them. I glanced at Susan. Are you going to do this all by yourself?

07:03:09.020 --> 07:03:14.620
Her eyes were bright and wet as she killed the current. Clenches icon dimmed. Stretches remained

07:03:14.620 --> 07:03:23.820
dormant. I cleared my throat. I mean, who else is going to do this, Siri? Yuka? You? The rest of

07:03:23.820 --> 07:03:31.900
the gang. Sasha could. Sasha, she stared at me. Siri, I created them. Do you think I did this so I

07:03:31.900 --> 07:03:37.580
could hide behind them when, so I could force them to do things like this? She shook her head.

07:03:38.380 --> 07:03:43.020
I'm not bringing them out. Not for this. I wouldn't do that to my worst enemy.

07:03:44.140 --> 07:03:49.580
She turned away from me. There were drugs she could have taken. Neuro inhibitors to wash away

07:03:49.580 --> 07:03:55.180
the guild. Short-sers could get right down to the molecules. Sodasti had offered them up as if he were

07:03:55.180 --> 07:04:00.700
tempting some solitary messiah in the desert. James had refused him and would not say why.

07:04:02.060 --> 07:04:05.980
Repeat, she said. The current flickered on and off.

07:04:06.780 --> 07:04:13.660
Repeat, she said again. Not a twitch. I pointed. I see it, she said.

07:04:13.740 --> 07:04:20.940
Clench had pressed the tip of one arm against the touchpad. The icon there glowed like a candle flame.

07:04:23.100 --> 07:04:27.580
Six and a half minutes later, they'd graduated from yellow squares to time-lapse four-dimensional

07:04:27.580 --> 07:04:34.060
polyhedrons. It took them as long to distinguish between two 26-faceted shifting solids,

07:04:34.620 --> 07:04:39.420
differing by one facet in a single frame, as it took them to tell the difference between a yellow

07:04:39.500 --> 07:04:44.700
square and a red triangle. Intricate patterns played across their surfaces the whole time.

07:04:44.700 --> 07:04:47.980
Dynamic needlepoint mosaics flickering almost too fast to see.

07:04:48.940 --> 07:04:55.500
Fuck, James whispered. Could be Splinter skills. Cunningham joined us in consensus,

07:04:55.500 --> 07:05:01.020
although his body remained halfway around Biomed. Splinter skills, she repeated dully.

07:05:01.900 --> 07:05:06.700
Savantism. High performance at one kind of calculation doesn't necessarily connote

07:05:06.700 --> 07:05:12.780
high intelligence. I know what Splinter skills are, Robert. I just think you're wrong. Prove it.

07:05:14.140 --> 07:05:19.580
So she gave up on geometry and told the scramblers that 1 plus 1 equal 2. Evidently,

07:05:19.580 --> 07:05:23.900
they knew that already. Ten minutes later, they were predicting 10-digit prime numbers on demand.

07:05:24.780 --> 07:05:29.820
She showed them a sequence of two-dimensional shapes. They picked the next one in the series from a menu

07:05:29.820 --> 07:05:35.500
of subtly different alternatives. She denied them multiple choice, showed the beginning of a whole

07:05:35.500 --> 07:05:39.980
new sequence, and taught them to draw on the touch-sensitive interface with the tips of their arms.

07:05:40.780 --> 07:05:45.420
They finished that series in precise freehand, rendered a chain of logical descendants ending

07:05:45.420 --> 07:05:52.220
with a figure that led inexorably back to the starting point. These aren't drones. James' voice

07:05:52.220 --> 07:05:58.380
caught in her throats. This is all just crunching, Cunningham said. Millions of computer programs

07:05:58.380 --> 07:06:04.380
do it without ever waking up. They're intelligent, Robert. They're smarter than us. Maybe they're

07:06:04.460 --> 07:06:10.620
smarter than Yuka. And we're... why can't you just admit it? I could see it all over her.

07:06:11.340 --> 07:06:17.500
Isaac would have admitted it. Because they don't have the circuitry, Cunningham insisted. How could...

07:06:18.060 --> 07:06:23.820
I don't know how, she cried. That's your job. All I know is that I'm torturing beings that can

07:06:23.820 --> 07:06:28.380
think rings around us. Not for much longer, at least. Once you figure out the language,

07:06:29.100 --> 07:06:34.380
she shook her head. Robert, I haven't a clue about the language. We've been at it for

07:06:34.380 --> 07:06:39.660
four hours, haven't we? The gang's all here. Language databases, 4,000 years, thick,

07:06:39.660 --> 07:06:44.620
all the latest linguistic algorithms. And we know exactly what they're saying. We're watching every

07:06:44.620 --> 07:06:50.780
possible way they could be saying it, right down to the angstrom. Precisely. So, I've got nothing.

07:06:51.340 --> 07:06:56.140
I know they're talking through pigment mosaics. There might even be something in the way they

07:06:56.140 --> 07:07:01.500
move those bristles, but I can't find the pattern. I can't even follow how they count, much less tell

07:07:01.500 --> 07:07:09.420
them I'm... sorry. Nobody spoke for a while. Bates washed us from the galley on our ceiling,

07:07:09.420 --> 07:07:14.780
but made no attempt to join the proceedings. On consensus, the reprieved scramblers floated

07:07:14.780 --> 07:07:21.100
in their cages like multi-armed martyrs. Well, Cunningham said at last. Since this seems to

07:07:21.100 --> 07:07:27.020
be the day for bad news, here's mine. They're dying. James put her face in her hand.

07:07:27.900 --> 07:07:31.740
It's not your interrogation for whatever that's worth. The biologists continued.

07:07:32.380 --> 07:07:35.900
As far as I can determine, some of their metabolic pathways are just missing.

07:07:37.180 --> 07:07:42.220
Obviously, you just haven't found them yet. That was Bates speaking up from across the drum.

07:07:43.020 --> 07:07:48.780
No, Cunningham said, and slowly and distinctly. Obviously, those parts are available to the

07:07:48.780 --> 07:07:54.380
organism. Because they're falling apart pretty much the same way you'd expect one of us to, if

07:07:55.420 --> 07:08:00.380
all the mitotic spindles in our cells just vanished out of the cytoplasm, for example.

07:08:01.260 --> 07:08:05.100
As far as I can tell, they started deteriorating the moment we took them off Rorschach.

07:08:06.060 --> 07:08:10.860
Susan looked up. Are you saying they left part of their biochemistry behind?

07:08:12.380 --> 07:08:15.740
Some essential nutrient? Bates suggested. They're not eating.

07:08:16.540 --> 07:08:22.700
Yes to the linguist, no to the major. Cunningham fell silent. I glanced across the drum to see

07:08:22.700 --> 07:08:29.020
him sucking on a cigarette. I think a lot of the cellular processes in these things are mediated

07:08:29.020 --> 07:08:34.620
externally. I think the reason I can't find any genes in my biopsies is because they don't have any.

07:08:35.900 --> 07:08:40.300
So what do they have instead? Bates asked. Touring morphogens.

07:08:40.620 --> 07:08:48.300
Blank looks. Subtitling looks. Cunningham explained anyway. A lot of biology doesn't use genes.

07:08:48.300 --> 07:08:53.900
Sunflowers look the way they do because of purely physical buckling stress. You get Fibonacci sequences

07:08:53.900 --> 07:08:58.700
and golden ratios everywhere in nature, and there's no gene codes for them. It's all just mechanical

07:08:58.700 --> 07:09:04.940
interactions. Take a developing embryo. The genes say start growing or stop growing, but the number

07:09:04.940 --> 07:09:09.020
of digits in vertebrae result from the mechanics of cells bumping up against other cells.

07:09:09.660 --> 07:09:15.020
Those mitotic spindles I mentioned? Absolutely essential for replication in every eukaryotic cell,

07:09:15.020 --> 07:09:19.740
and they accrete like crystals without any genetic involvement. You'd be surprised how much of life

07:09:19.740 --> 07:09:26.300
is like that. But you still need genes, Bates protested, walking around to join us.

07:09:27.180 --> 07:09:32.940
Genes just establish the starting conditions to enable the process. The structure that proliferates

07:09:32.940 --> 07:09:37.820
afterwards doesn't need specific instructions. It's classic emergent complexity. We've

07:09:37.820 --> 07:09:44.060
known about it for over a century. Another drag on the stick. Or even longer. Darwin cited

07:09:44.060 --> 07:09:51.660
Honeycomb way back in the 1800s. Honeycomb, Bates repeated. Perfect hexagonal tubes in a packed

07:09:51.660 --> 07:09:57.260
array. Bees are hardwired to lay them down, but how does an insect know enough geometry to lay

07:09:57.260 --> 07:10:03.820
down a precise hexagon? It doesn't. It's programmed to chew up wax and spit it out while turning on

07:10:04.780 --> 07:10:10.780
its axis. And that generates a circle. Put a bunch of bees on the same surface, chewing side by side

07:10:10.780 --> 07:10:16.060
in the circles but butt against each other. To form each other into hexagons, which just happened

07:10:16.060 --> 07:10:23.180
to be more efficient for close packing anyway. Bates pounced. But bees are programmed. Genetically.

07:10:24.060 --> 07:10:30.940
You misunderstand. Scramblers are the honeycomb. Rorschach is the bees, Jates murmured.

07:10:31.740 --> 07:10:37.580
Cunningham nodded. Rorschach is the bees. And I don't think Rorschach's magnetic fields are

07:10:37.580 --> 07:10:42.540
counter intrusion mechanisms at all. I think they're part of the life support system. I think

07:10:42.540 --> 07:10:47.900
they mediate and regulate a good chunk of scrambler metabolism. What we've got back in the hold is a

07:10:47.900 --> 07:10:52.300
couple of creatures dragged out of their element and holding their breath. And they can't hold it

07:10:52.300 --> 07:10:59.260
forever. How long, James asked. How should I know? If I'm right, I'm not even dealing with complete

07:10:59.260 --> 07:11:06.860
organisms here. Guess, Bates said. He shrugged. A few days. Maybe.

07:11:09.580 --> 07:11:14.380
That which does not kill us makes us stranger, Trevor Goodchild.

07:11:16.140 --> 07:11:23.100
You still don't vote, Sotosti said. We would not be releasing the prisoners. Too risky.

07:11:23.100 --> 07:11:27.020
Out here in the endless wastelands of the oar, there was no room for a live and let live.

07:11:27.660 --> 07:11:33.340
Never mind what the other has done or what it hasn't. Think of what it could do, if it were

07:11:33.340 --> 07:11:37.740
just a little stronger. Think of what it might have done if we had arrived as late as we were

07:11:37.740 --> 07:11:43.580
supposed to. You look at Rorschach and perhaps you see an embryo or a developing child. Alien

07:11:43.580 --> 07:11:49.740
beyond comprehension perhaps, but not guilty. Not by default. But what if those are the wrong eyes?

07:11:50.780 --> 07:11:55.900
What if you should be seeing an omnipotent murdering god, a planet killer, not yet finished?

07:11:56.620 --> 07:12:03.420
Vulnerable only now and for a little longer. There was no vampire opacity to that logic.

07:12:03.420 --> 07:12:07.420
No multi-dimensional black boxes for humans to shrug at and throw up their hands.

07:12:08.220 --> 07:12:12.860
There was no excuse for the failure to find fault with Sotosti's reasoning beyond the fact

07:12:12.860 --> 07:12:18.460
that his reasoning was without fault. That made it worse. The others I knew would rather have had

07:12:18.460 --> 07:12:24.700
to take something on faith. But Sotosti had an alternative to capture release, one he evidently

07:12:24.700 --> 07:12:31.260
considered much safer. It took an act of faith to accept that reasoning, at least, by any sane

07:12:31.260 --> 07:12:39.340
measure it averaged on suicide. Now, Theseus gave birth by Caesarean. These progeny were far too

07:12:39.340 --> 07:12:45.100
massive to fit through the canal at the end of the spine. The ship shat them as if constipated,

07:12:45.100 --> 07:12:51.020
directly into the hold. Great monstrous things, bristling with muzzles and antennae. Each stood

07:12:51.020 --> 07:12:56.860
three or four times my height. A pair of massive, rust-colored cubes. Every surface infested with

07:12:56.860 --> 07:13:03.020
topography. Armor plating would hide most of it prior to deployment, of course. Ribbons of piping

07:13:03.020 --> 07:13:08.780
and conduit, ammunition reservoirs, and shark-tooth rows of radiator fins. All to disappear beneath

07:13:08.780 --> 07:13:15.660
smoother, effective shielding. Only a few island landmarks would rise above that surface. Comports,

07:13:15.740 --> 07:13:22.460
thrust nozzles, targeting arrays. And gunports, of course. These things spat fire and brimstone from

07:13:22.460 --> 07:13:29.020
a half dozen mouths apiece. But for the time being, they were just mechanical fetuses. Half extruded,

07:13:29.020 --> 07:13:33.580
their planes and angles a high contrast jigsaw of light and shadow in the harsh white glow of the

07:13:33.580 --> 07:13:39.980
hold's flood lamps. I turned from the port. That's got to take our substrate stockpiles down a bit.

07:13:40.940 --> 07:13:46.460
Shielding the carapace was worse. Bates monitored construction through a dedicated flat screen built

07:13:46.460 --> 07:13:52.140
right into the fab bulkhead. Practicing, perhaps. We'd be losing our inlays as soon as the orbit

07:13:52.140 --> 07:13:57.420
changed. We're tapping out, though. Might have to grab one of the local rocks before long.

07:13:58.700 --> 07:14:04.620
Huh. I looked back into the hold. You think they're necessary? Doesn't matter what I think.

07:14:04.620 --> 07:14:10.620
You're a bright guy, Siri. Why can't you figure that out? It matters to me. That means it matters

07:14:10.620 --> 07:14:16.620
to Earth. Which might mean something if Earth was calling the shots. Some subtext was legible,

07:14:16.620 --> 07:14:23.100
no matter how deep in the system you were. I tacked a port. How about Sadastiy and the captain,

07:14:23.100 --> 07:14:31.020
then? Any thoughts? You're usually a bit more subtle. That much was true. It's just, you know,

07:14:31.100 --> 07:14:36.860
Susan was the one that caught stretch and clench, tapping back and forth, right? Bates wins to the

07:14:36.860 --> 07:14:44.380
names. So? Well, some might think it odd that Theseus wouldn't have seen it first, since quantum

07:14:44.380 --> 07:14:51.100
computers are supposed to be so proficient, pattern matching. Sadastiy took the quantum modules offline.

07:14:51.100 --> 07:14:57.580
The onboard's been running in classical mode since before we even made orbit. Why? Noisy

07:14:57.580 --> 07:15:02.220
environment. Too much risk of decoherence. Quantum computers are finicky things.

07:15:03.260 --> 07:15:10.620
Surely the onboard shielded. The Isius is shielded. Bates nodded. As much as feasible,

07:15:10.620 --> 07:15:14.540
the perfect shielding is perfect blindness, and this is not the kind of neighborhood where you

07:15:14.540 --> 07:15:21.500
want to keep your eyes closed. Actually, it was, but I took her point. I took her other point, too.

07:15:21.500 --> 07:15:27.020
The one she didn't speak out loud. And you missed it. Something sitting right there in consensus

07:15:27.100 --> 07:15:34.140
for anyone to see. Top of the line synthesis like you. Sadastiy knows what he's doing, I guess. I

07:15:34.140 --> 07:15:39.020
admitted endlessly aware that he might be listening. He hasn't been wrong yet, as far as we know.

07:15:40.060 --> 07:15:47.020
As far as we can know, Bates said. If you can second guess a vampire, you wouldn't need a vampire,

07:15:47.020 --> 07:15:54.300
I remembered. She smiled faintly. Isaac was a good man. You can't always believe the PR, though.

07:15:54.380 --> 07:16:01.340
You don't buy it, I asked. But she was already thinking she said too much. I threw out a hook,

07:16:01.340 --> 07:16:06.380
baited with just a right mix of skepticism and deference. Sadastiy did know where those

07:16:06.380 --> 07:16:09.900
scramblers would be. Nailed it almost to the meter, out of that whole maze.

07:16:11.420 --> 07:16:14.780
I suppose that might have taken some superhuman logic, she admitted.

07:16:15.420 --> 07:16:17.980
Thinking I was so fucking dumb she couldn't believe it.

07:16:18.860 --> 07:16:25.660
What? I said. Bates shrugged. Or maybe he just realized that since Rorschach was growing its own

07:16:25.660 --> 07:16:31.420
crew, we'd run into more every time we went in, no matter where we landed. Consensus bleeped into

07:16:31.420 --> 07:16:37.980
my silence. Orbital maneuvers starting in five, Sadastiy announced. Inlays and wireless

07:16:37.980 --> 07:16:45.660
prosthetics offline in 90. That's all. Bates shut down the display. I'm gonna ride this out in the

07:16:45.660 --> 07:16:52.860
bridge. Illusion of control and all that. You? My tent, I think. She nodded and braced to jump and

07:16:52.860 --> 07:17:01.100
hesitated. By the way, she told me. Yes. Sorry? You asked if I thought the emplacements were

07:17:01.100 --> 07:17:07.660
necessary. Right now I think we need all the protection we can get. So you think that Rorschach

07:17:07.660 --> 07:17:15.260
might... hey, it already killed me once. She wasn't talking about radiation. I nodded carefully.

07:17:16.140 --> 07:17:22.940
That must have been... like nothing at all. You couldn't possibly imagine. Bates took a breath

07:17:22.940 --> 07:17:28.220
and let it out. Maybe you don't have to. She added and sailed away up the spine.

07:17:33.100 --> 07:17:39.020
Cunningham and the gang in Biomed, 30 degrees of arc between them. Each poked their captives in

07:17:39.020 --> 07:17:43.820
their own way. Susan James stabbed indifferently at a keypad painted across her desktop.

07:17:44.460 --> 07:17:47.020
Windows to either side looked in on stretch and clench.

07:17:49.340 --> 07:17:52.540
Cookie-cutter shapes scrolled across the desk as James typed.

07:17:53.100 --> 07:17:59.020
Circles, triskellions, a quartet of parallel lines. Some of them pulsed like abstract little hearts.

07:17:59.660 --> 07:18:04.380
In his distant pen, stretch reached out one fraying tentacle and tapped something in turn.

07:18:05.420 --> 07:18:11.980
Any progress? She sighed and shook her head. I've given up trying to understand their language.

07:18:11.980 --> 07:18:17.740
I'm settling for a pigeon. She tapped an icon. Clench vanished from his window,

07:18:17.740 --> 07:18:23.660
a hieroglyphic flowchart sprang up in his place. Half the symbols regal or pulsed endlessly repetitive,

07:18:23.660 --> 07:18:26.540
a riot of dancing noodles. Others just sat there.

07:18:27.420 --> 07:18:34.060
Iconic bass. James waved vaguely at the display. Subject verb phrases render as animated versions

07:18:34.060 --> 07:18:39.420
of noun icons. They're radially symmetrical, so I array modifiers in a circular pattern around

07:18:39.420 --> 07:18:45.980
the central subject. Maybe that comes naturally to them. A new circle of glyphs appeared beneath

07:18:45.980 --> 07:18:51.180
James's. Stretches reply, presumably. But something in the system didn't like what it saw.

07:18:51.820 --> 07:18:57.020
Icons flared in a separate window. Illuminous counter flashed 500 watts since held steady.

07:18:58.460 --> 07:19:03.740
On the screen, stretch writhed. It reached out with squirming backbone arms and stabbed

07:19:03.820 --> 07:19:11.420
repeatedly at its touched pad. James looked away. New glyphs appeared. 500 watts retreated to zero.

07:19:11.980 --> 07:19:16.220
Stretch returned to its holding pattern, the spikes and jags of its telemetry smoothed.

07:19:17.260 --> 07:19:24.220
James let out her breath. What happened, I asked. Wrong answer. She tapped into stretch's feed,

07:19:24.220 --> 07:19:29.420
showed me the display that it tripped it up. A pyramid, a star, a simplified representations

07:19:29.420 --> 07:19:36.220
of a scrambler and of Rorschach rotated on the board. It was stupid. It was just a warm-up exercise,

07:19:36.220 --> 07:19:41.660
really. I asked it to name the objects in the window. She laughed softly and without humor.

07:19:42.300 --> 07:19:46.460
That's the thing about functional languages, you know. If you can't point at it, you can't talk

07:19:46.460 --> 07:19:53.740
about it. And what did it say? She pointed at stretch's first spiral. Polyhedron star Rorschach

07:19:53.740 --> 07:20:00.220
are present. It missed the scrambler. Got it right the second time. Still, stupid mistake for something

07:20:00.220 --> 07:20:06.140
that can think rings around a vampire, isn't it? Susan swallowed. I guess even scramblers slip up

07:20:06.140 --> 07:20:12.220
when they're dying. I didn't know what to say. Behind me, barely audible, Cunningham muttered

07:20:12.220 --> 07:20:18.700
some two-stroke mantra to himself in an endless loop. Yuka says Susan stopped, began again.

07:20:19.500 --> 07:20:25.580
You know that blind sight we get sometimes in Rorschach? I nodded and wondered what Yuka had said.

07:20:27.020 --> 07:20:31.660
Apparently the same thing had happened to the other senses, too, she told me. You can have

07:20:31.660 --> 07:20:38.380
blind touch and blind smell and blind hearing. That would be deafness. She shook her head.

07:20:39.340 --> 07:20:44.780
But it isn't really, is it? Any more than blind sight is really blindness. Something in your

07:20:44.780 --> 07:20:49.260
head is still taking it all in. Something in the brain is still seeing and hearing, even if you're

07:20:49.260 --> 07:20:56.780
not aware of it. Unless someone forces you to guess, or there's some threat, you just get a really

07:20:56.780 --> 07:21:01.100
strong feeling. You should move out of the way. And five seconds later a bus drives over the spot

07:21:01.100 --> 07:21:08.300
you were standing. You knew it was coming somehow. You just don't know how you knew. It's wild, I

07:21:08.300 --> 07:21:14.940
agreed. These scramblers, they know the answer, Siri. They're intelligent. We know they are.

07:21:15.740 --> 07:21:21.100
But it's almost as though they don't know they know unless you hurt them, as if they've got

07:21:21.100 --> 07:21:28.300
blind sight spread over every sense. I tried to imagine it. Life without sensation, without any

07:21:28.300 --> 07:21:33.260
active awareness of one's environment. I tried to imagine existing like that without going mad.

07:21:34.140 --> 07:21:41.420
Do you think that's possible? I don't know. It's just a metaphor, I guess. She didn't believe that,

07:21:41.420 --> 07:21:48.380
or she didn't know, or she didn't want me to know. I should have been able to tell. She should have

07:21:48.380 --> 07:21:55.180
been clear. At first I thought they were just resisting, she said. But why would they? She

07:21:55.180 --> 07:22:01.500
turned bright, begging eyes on me, pleading for an answer. I didn't have one. I didn't have a clue.

07:22:02.460 --> 07:22:07.740
I turned away from Susan James, only to find myself facing Robert Cunningham. Cunningham,

07:22:07.740 --> 07:22:13.420
the mutterer, fingers tapped against tabletop interfaces, inner eyes blinded, vision limited

07:22:13.420 --> 07:22:17.500
now to the picture's consensus sketched in airspace or through against flat surfaces for

07:22:17.500 --> 07:22:23.100
everyone to see. His face remained as empty as a feeling as it had ever been, the rest of his body

07:22:23.100 --> 07:22:30.620
twitched like a bug in a spider web. He might as well have been. We all might. Rorschach loomed

07:22:30.620 --> 07:22:35.740
barely nine kilometers away now, so near it might have eclipsed Ben itself if I had been brave enough

07:22:35.740 --> 07:22:44.060
to look outside. We had closed this insane proximity and parked. Out there, Rorschach grew like a live

07:22:44.060 --> 07:22:50.300
thing. In there, live things grew, butted like jellyfish from some demonic mechanical substrate.

07:22:51.180 --> 07:22:55.740
Those lethal vacant corridors we'd crept along frightened of the shadows planted in our heads.

07:22:56.380 --> 07:23:01.500
They were probably filling with scramblers right now. All those hundreds of kilometers of twisted

07:23:01.500 --> 07:23:08.460
tunnels and passages and chambers filled filling with an army. This was Sadastie's safer alternative.

07:23:09.260 --> 07:23:13.420
This was the path we'd followed because it would have been too dangerous to release the prisoners.

07:23:14.220 --> 07:23:18.780
We were so deep inside the bow shock that we'd had to shut down our internal augments,

07:23:18.780 --> 07:23:23.020
while Rorschach's magnetosphere was orders of magnitude weaker here than within the structure

07:23:23.020 --> 07:23:28.620
itself. Who knew if the alien might find us too tempting a target or too great a threat at this

07:23:28.620 --> 07:23:33.900
range? Who knew when it might choose to plunge some invisible spike through Thesias' heart?

07:23:35.820 --> 07:23:40.460
Any pulse that could penetrate the ship's shielding would doubtlessly fry Thesias' nervous system,

07:23:40.460 --> 07:23:45.420
as well as the wiring in our heads. I suppose that five people in a dead ship would have

07:23:45.420 --> 07:23:49.500
a marginally greater chance of survival if their brains weren't sparking in the bargain,

07:23:49.500 --> 07:23:54.620
but I doubted that such a difference would make much difference. Sadastie had obviously figured

07:23:54.620 --> 07:23:59.580
the odds differently. He'd even shut down the anti-euclidean pump in his own head, resorted

07:23:59.580 --> 07:24:05.340
to manual injections to keep himself from short-circuiting. Stretch and clench were even closer

07:24:05.340 --> 07:24:10.300
to Rorschach than we were. Cunningham's lab and we'd kicked free of the ship. It floated now just

07:24:10.300 --> 07:24:15.260
a few kilometers from the artifacts' outermost spires, deep within the folds of its magnetic field.

07:24:16.060 --> 07:24:21.340
If the scramblers needed radioactive magnetite to function, this was the key they were going to get,

07:24:21.340 --> 07:24:26.540
a taste of the fields but not of freedom. The lab's shielding was being dynamically fine-tuned

07:24:26.540 --> 07:24:32.220
to balance medical necessity against tactical risk, as best the data allowed. The structure

07:24:32.220 --> 07:24:36.860
floated in the watchful crosshairs of our newborn gun emplacements, strategically positioned to the

07:24:36.860 --> 07:24:42.540
other side. Those emplacements could destroy the habit in an instant. They could probably destroy

07:24:42.540 --> 07:24:49.100
anything approaching it as well. They couldn't destroy Rorschach, of course. Maybe nothing could.

07:24:50.540 --> 07:24:56.780
Covert to invulnerable. As far as we knew, that hadn't happened yet. Presumably Thesias could

07:24:56.780 --> 07:25:01.580
still do something about the artifact accreting off our bow, assuming we could decide which thing to do.

07:25:02.540 --> 07:25:07.020
Sadastie wasn't talking. In fact, I couldn't remember the last time any of us had seen the

07:25:07.020 --> 07:25:12.300
vamp higher in the flesh. For several shifts now, he had confined himself to his tent, speaking only

07:25:12.300 --> 07:25:20.060
through consensus. Everyone was on edge, and the transient had gone quiet. Cunningham muttered to

07:25:20.060 --> 07:25:24.220
himself, stabbed at unfamiliar controls with unpracticed fingers, cursed his own clumsiness.

07:25:24.940 --> 07:25:29.340
Stimulus and response flowed through the lasers across six kilometers of ionized vacuum.

07:25:30.060 --> 07:25:34.780
The ever-present nicotine stick hung from one corner of his mouth for want of a free hand.

07:25:35.740 --> 07:25:39.740
Every now and then, flecks of ash broke free and drifted obliquely toward the ventilators.

07:25:39.980 --> 07:25:47.580
He spoke before I could. It's all in consensus. When I didn't leave, he relented but wouldn't look at me.

07:25:50.220 --> 07:25:54.300
Magnetite flecks lined up as soon as they got past the wavefront more or less.

07:25:54.300 --> 07:25:59.740
Membranes started to fix themselves. They're not failing as fast, but it's Rorschach's internal

07:25:59.740 --> 07:26:04.380
environment that will be optimized for scramble metabolism. Out here, I think the most we can

07:26:04.380 --> 07:26:11.340
do is slow the rate of dying. That's something, at least. Cunningham grunted. Some of the pieces

07:26:11.340 --> 07:26:17.420
are coming together. Others, their nerves are frayed for no good reason. Literally, single leakage

07:26:17.420 --> 07:26:24.700
along the cables. Because of the deterioration, I guess. And I can't get the Arianna's equation

07:26:24.700 --> 07:26:30.540
to balance. There's all this nonlinearly at low temperatures. The pre-exponential value is completely

07:26:30.620 --> 07:26:37.020
fucked up. It's almost as though temperature doesn't matter and...shit. Some critical value

07:26:37.020 --> 07:26:41.740
had exceeded a confidence limit on one of his displays. He glanced up at the drum and raised

07:26:41.740 --> 07:26:50.300
his voice. Need another biopsy, Susan. Anywhere central. What? Oh, just a second. She shook her

07:26:50.300 --> 07:26:55.260
head and tapped off a brief spiral of icons, as listless as the captive she commanded.

07:26:55.980 --> 07:27:00.380
On one of Cunningham's windows, Stretch viewed her input with its marvelous sighted skin.

07:27:01.180 --> 07:27:06.300
It floated unresponsive for a moment. Then it folded back the arms facing one wall,

07:27:06.300 --> 07:27:11.820
opening a clear path for Cunningham's telops. He called two of them from their burrows like

07:27:11.820 --> 07:27:17.660
prehensile serpents. The first wielded a clinical core sampler. The second wielded the threat of

07:27:17.660 --> 07:27:23.580
violence in case of foolish resistance. It was hardly necessary. Blindsided or not,

07:27:23.580 --> 07:27:31.500
scramblers were fast learners. Stretch exposed its belly like a victim resigned to imminent rape.

07:27:32.300 --> 07:27:37.820
Cunningham fumbled. The telops bumped together, briefly entangled. He cursed and tried again,

07:27:37.820 --> 07:27:43.580
every move shouting frustration. His extended phenotype had been amputated. Once the very ghost

07:27:43.580 --> 07:27:49.660
in the machine, now he was just another guy punching buttons and...and suddenly something clicked.

07:27:50.620 --> 07:27:56.460
Cunningham's facade swirled a translucency before my eyes. Suddenly I could almost imagine him.

07:27:57.580 --> 07:28:02.220
He got it right the second time. The tip of his machine shot out like a striking snake and darted

07:28:02.220 --> 07:28:07.820
back again, almost too fast to see. Waves of color flushed from Stretch's injury like ripples

07:28:07.820 --> 07:28:13.580
chased across still water by a falling stone. Cunningham must have thought he saw something in

07:28:13.580 --> 07:28:20.620
my face. It helps if you try not to think of them as people, he said. And for the very first time I

07:28:20.620 --> 07:28:27.260
could read the subtext as clear and as sharp as broken glass. Of course, you don't think of anyone

07:28:27.260 --> 07:28:35.980
that way. Cunningham didn't like to be played. No one does. But most people don't think that's

07:28:35.980 --> 07:28:41.500
what I'm doing. They don't know how much their bodies betray when they close their mouths. When

07:28:41.500 --> 07:28:45.820
they speak aloud it's because they want to confide. When they don't, they think they're keeping

07:28:45.820 --> 07:28:51.500
their opinions to themselves. I watched them so closely, customize each word so that no system

07:28:51.500 --> 07:28:57.100
ever feels used. And yet for some reason that didn't work with Robert Cunningham. I think I was

07:28:57.100 --> 07:29:03.980
modeling the wrong system. Imagine you are a synthesisist. You deal in the behavior of systems

07:29:03.980 --> 07:29:09.900
at their services. Infer the machinery beneath from its reflections above. That is the secret of

07:29:09.900 --> 07:29:14.300
your success. You understand the system by understanding the boundaries that contain it.

07:29:15.100 --> 07:29:19.580
Now imagine you encounter someone who has ripped a hole in those boundaries and bled beyond them.

07:29:20.540 --> 07:29:26.460
Robert Cunningham's flesh could not contain him. His duties pulled him beyond the meat sack. Here in

07:29:26.460 --> 07:29:32.220
the oar, his topology rambled all over the ship. That was true of all of us to some extent. Bates

07:29:32.220 --> 07:29:38.540
and her drones. Sudosti and his limbic link, even the consensus inlaze in our heads, diffused us a bit,

07:29:38.540 --> 07:29:44.460
spread us just slightly beyond the confines of our own bodies. But Bates only ran her drones.

07:29:44.460 --> 07:29:50.060
She never inhabited them. The gang of four may have run multiple systems on a single motherboard,

07:29:50.060 --> 07:29:55.260
but each had its own distinct topology, and they only ever surfaced one at a time. And Sudosti,

07:29:56.220 --> 07:30:02.620
well, Sudosti was a whole different story as it turned out. Cunningham didn't just operate his

07:30:02.620 --> 07:30:08.300
remotes. He escaped into them, wore them like a secret identity to hide the feeble human baseline

07:30:08.300 --> 07:30:14.700
within. He had sacrificed half of his neocortex for the chance to see X-rays and taste the shapes

07:30:14.700 --> 07:30:19.500
hiding in cell membranes. He had butchered one body to become a fleeting tenant of many.

07:30:20.220 --> 07:30:25.260
Pieces of him hidden the sensors and manipulators that lined the scrambler's cages. I might have

07:30:25.260 --> 07:30:29.580
gleaned vital clues from every piece of equipment in the sub-drum if I'd ever thought to look.

07:30:30.300 --> 07:30:36.300
Cunningham was a topological jigsaw like everyone else, but half his pieces were hidden in machinery.

07:30:37.100 --> 07:30:43.580
My model was incomplete. I don't think he ever aspired to such a state. Looking back,

07:30:43.580 --> 07:30:48.860
I see radiant self-loathing on every remembered surface. But there in the waning years of the

07:30:48.860 --> 07:30:54.700
21st century, the only alternative he could see was the life of a parasite. Cunningham merely

07:30:54.700 --> 07:31:01.100
chose the lesser evil. Now even that was denied him. Sudosti's orders had severed him from his

07:31:01.180 --> 07:31:07.180
own sensorium. He no longer felt the data in his gut. He had to interpret it, step by laborious

07:31:07.180 --> 07:31:11.580
step, through the screens and graphs that reduced perception to flat empty shorthand.

07:31:12.380 --> 07:31:17.660
Here was a system traumatized by multiple amputations. Here was a system with its eyes and

07:31:17.660 --> 07:31:22.860
ears and tongue cut out, forced to stumble and feel its way around things it had once inhabited,

07:31:22.860 --> 07:31:28.860
right down to the bone. Suddenly there was nowhere else to hide. And all those far-flung

07:31:28.860 --> 07:31:33.100
pieces of Robert Cunningham tumbled back into his flesh where I could see them at last.

07:31:34.220 --> 07:31:39.340
It had been my mistake all along. I'd been so focused on modeling other systems that I'd

07:31:39.340 --> 07:31:44.540
forgotten about the one doing the modeling. Bad eyes are only one bane of clear vision.

07:31:45.100 --> 07:31:49.740
Bad assumptions can be just as blinding, and it wasn't enough to imagine I was Robert Cunningham.

07:31:50.860 --> 07:31:53.180
I had to imagine I was Ciri Keaton as well.

07:31:54.060 --> 07:32:02.700
Of course, that only raises another question. If my guess about Cunningham was right, why did my

07:32:02.700 --> 07:32:07.820
tricks work on Isaac Spindle? He was every bit as discontinuous as his replacement.

07:32:09.260 --> 07:32:14.140
I didn't think about it much at the time. Spindle was gone, but the thing that had killed him was

07:32:14.140 --> 07:32:19.340
still there, hanging right off the bow, a vast swelling enigma that might choose to squash us

07:32:19.340 --> 07:32:26.140
at any instant. I was more than a little preoccupied. Now, though, far too late to do anything about it,

07:32:26.140 --> 07:32:33.180
I think I might know the answer. Maybe my tricks didn't work on Isaac either, not really. Maybe he

07:32:33.180 --> 07:32:40.060
saw through my manipulations as easy as Cunningham did. But maybe he just didn't care. Maybe I could

07:32:40.060 --> 07:32:46.060
read him because he let me. Which would mean I can't find another explanation that fits,

07:32:46.780 --> 07:32:52.220
that he just liked me, regardless. I think that might have made him a friend.

07:32:56.380 --> 07:33:01.740
If I can but make the words awake the feeling, Ian Anderson sand up.

07:33:03.820 --> 07:33:11.100
Night shift. Not a creature was stirring. Not an thesy as anyway. The gang hid in their tent.

07:33:11.100 --> 07:33:16.380
The transient lurked weightless and silent but low the surface. Bates was in the bridge. She more

07:33:16.380 --> 07:33:21.660
or less lived up there now, vigilant and conscientious, nested in camera angles and tactical overlays.

07:33:22.380 --> 07:33:26.780
There was nowhere she could turn without seeing some aspect of the cipher off our starboard bow.

07:33:27.500 --> 07:33:33.340
She did what good she could for the good it would do. The drum turned quietly. Light stemmed

07:33:33.340 --> 07:33:38.060
indeference to a dial cycle that a hundred years of tweaks and retrofits hadn't been able to

07:33:38.380 --> 07:33:44.060
to weed from the jeans. I sat alone in the galley, squinting from the inside of a system whose

07:33:44.060 --> 07:33:49.340
outlines grew increasingly hazy, trying to compile my latest, how would Isaac put it,

07:33:50.060 --> 07:33:55.100
postcard to posterity. Cunningham worked upside down on the other side of the world.

07:33:56.300 --> 07:34:03.100
Except Cunningham wasn't working. He hadn't even moved for at least four minutes. I'd assumed he

07:34:03.100 --> 07:34:07.580
was reciting the cut-ish for spindle. Consensus said he'd been doing it twice daily for the next

07:34:07.580 --> 07:34:14.220
year, if we'd lived that long. But now, leaning to see around the spinal bundles in the core,

07:34:14.780 --> 07:34:18.060
I could read his surfaces as clearly as if I'd been sitting beside him.

07:34:18.940 --> 07:34:21.900
He wasn't bored or distracted or even deep in thought.

07:34:22.860 --> 07:34:28.940
Robert Cunningham was petrified. I stood and paced the drum. Ceiling turned into wall,

07:34:28.940 --> 07:34:34.540
wall into floor. I was close enough to hear his incessant stoff muttering. A single indistinct

07:34:34.540 --> 07:34:39.740
syllable repeated over and over that I was close enough to hear what he was saying. Fuck, fuck,

07:34:39.740 --> 07:34:47.020
fuck, fuck, fuck. And still Cunningham didn't move, although I'd made no attempt to mask my approach.

07:34:48.060 --> 07:34:50.940
Finally, when I was almost at his shoulder, he fell silent.

07:34:51.740 --> 07:34:54.380
You're blind, he said without turning. Did you know that?

07:34:55.340 --> 07:35:01.740
I didn't. You, me, everyone. He interlocked his fingers and clenched as if in prayer,

07:35:01.740 --> 07:35:06.300
hard enough to whiten the knuckles. Only then did I notice. No cigarette.

07:35:07.260 --> 07:35:11.900
Visions mostly a lie anyway, he continued. We don't really see anything except a few

07:35:11.900 --> 07:35:16.460
high-res degrees where the eye focuses. Everything else is just a peripheral blur,

07:35:16.460 --> 07:35:21.580
just light in motion. Motion draws the focus and your eyes jiggle all the time. Did you know that,

07:35:21.580 --> 07:35:26.620
Keaton? Cicades, they're called. Blurs the image. The movement's way too fast for the brain to

07:35:26.620 --> 07:35:32.460
integrate so your eye just shuts down between pauses. It only grabs those isolated freeze frames,

07:35:32.460 --> 07:35:37.900
but your brain edits out the blanks and stitches in an illusion of continuity into your head.

07:35:38.780 --> 07:35:45.260
He turned to face me. And you know what's really amazing? If something only moves during the gaps,

07:35:45.260 --> 07:35:53.100
your brain just ignores it. It's invisible. I glanced at his workspace. The usual split-spring

07:35:53.660 --> 07:35:57.500
glowed to one side, real-time images of the scramblers in their pens,

07:35:57.500 --> 07:36:03.340
but histology, 10,000 times larger than life, took center stage. The paradoxical neural

07:36:03.340 --> 07:36:06.540
architecture of stretch and clench glistened on the main window,

07:36:07.340 --> 07:36:10.940
flensed and labeled and overlaid by circuit diagrams a dozen layers thick.

07:36:12.220 --> 07:36:17.500
A dense, annotated forest of alien trunks and brambles. It looked a little bit like Rorschach

07:36:17.500 --> 07:36:23.180
itself. I couldn't parse any of it. Are you listening, Keaton? Do you know what I'm saying?

07:36:24.460 --> 07:36:29.660
You figured out why I couldn't. You're saying these things can somehow tell when our eyes are

07:36:29.660 --> 07:36:37.100
offline and I didn't finish. It just didn't seem possible. Cunningham shook his head.

07:36:37.820 --> 07:36:42.860
Something that sounded disturbingly like a giggle escaped his mouth. I'm saying these things can

07:36:42.860 --> 07:36:48.220
see your nerves firing from across the room and integrate that into a cryptos strategy,

07:36:48.220 --> 07:36:53.100
and then send motor commands to act on that strategy, and then send other commands to stop

07:36:53.100 --> 07:36:58.300
the motion before your eyes come back online. All in the time it would take a mammalian nerve

07:36:58.300 --> 07:37:04.220
impulse to make it halfway from your shoulder to your elbow. These things are fast, Keaton. Way

07:37:04.220 --> 07:37:08.460
faster than we could have guessed even from that high-speed whisper line they were using.

07:37:08.460 --> 07:37:15.580
They're bloody superconductors. It took a conscious effort to keep frowning. Is that even possible?

07:37:16.460 --> 07:37:23.020
Every nerve impulse generates an electromagnetic field that makes it detectable. But Rorschach's

07:37:23.020 --> 07:37:28.700
EM fields are so... I mean, reading the firing of a single optic nerve through all that interference,

07:37:29.420 --> 07:37:34.860
it's not interference. The fields are part of them, remember? That's probably how they do it.

07:37:34.860 --> 07:37:41.100
So they couldn't do that here. You're not listening. The trap you said wouldn't have caught

07:37:41.100 --> 07:37:47.260
anything like that, not unless it wanted to be caught. We didn't grab specimens at all. We grabbed spies.

07:37:48.620 --> 07:37:53.900
Stretch and clench floated in split-screen before us, arm swaying like undulating backbones.

07:37:54.700 --> 07:37:57.340
Cryptic patterns played slowly across their cuticles.

07:37:58.460 --> 07:38:04.140
Supposing it's just instinct, I suggested. Flounders hide their background pretty well,

07:38:04.140 --> 07:38:09.980
but they don't think about it. Where are they going to get that instinct from, Keaton? How is it

07:38:09.980 --> 07:38:16.140
going to evolve? Cicades are an accidental glitch in mammalian vision. Where would scramblers have

07:38:16.140 --> 07:38:22.220
encountered them before now? Cunningham shook his head. That thing, that thing a man does robot

07:38:22.220 --> 07:38:30.060
fried. It developed that strategy on its own, on the spot. It improvised. The word intelligent

07:38:30.060 --> 07:38:35.020
barely encompassed that kind of improvisation. But there was something else in Cunningham's face,

07:38:35.020 --> 07:38:38.060
some deeper distress nested inside what we'd already told me.

07:38:39.260 --> 07:38:46.540
What, I asked. It was stupid, he said. The things these creatures can do, it was just dumb.

07:38:47.580 --> 07:38:52.940
How do you mean? Well, it didn't work, did it? Couldn't keep it up in front of more than one or

07:38:52.940 --> 07:38:59.500
two of us. Because people's eyes don't flicker in sync, I realized. Too many witnesses stripped

07:39:00.060 --> 07:39:05.020
it of cover. Many other things it could have done, Cunningham was saying. They could have induced

07:39:05.020 --> 07:39:10.380
antons or, or an agnosia. Then we could have tripped over a whole herd of scramblers and it

07:39:10.380 --> 07:39:15.580
wouldn't even register in our conscious minds. Agnosias happen by accident for God's sake.

07:39:15.580 --> 07:39:20.060
If you've got the stress and reflexes to hide between someone's cicades, why stop there?

07:39:20.780 --> 07:39:22.540
Why not do something that really works?

07:39:22.780 --> 07:39:26.860
Why do you think, I asked, reflexively non-directive?

07:39:28.060 --> 07:39:33.900
I think that the first one was, you know it was a juvenile, right? Maybe it was just inexperienced.

07:39:33.900 --> 07:39:38.940
Maybe it was stupid and it made a bad decision. I think we're dealing with a species so far

07:39:38.940 --> 07:39:44.540
beyond us that even their retarded children can rewire our brains on the fly and I can't tell

07:39:44.540 --> 07:39:50.860
you how fucking scared that should make you. I could see it in his topology. I could hear it in

07:39:50.860 --> 07:39:57.500
his voice. His nervous face remained as calm as a corpse. We should just kill them now, he said.

07:39:58.620 --> 07:40:03.020
Well if they're spies they can't have learned much. They've been in those cages the whole time,

07:40:03.020 --> 07:40:10.060
except for the way up. They'd been right next to us for the whole trip back. These things live

07:40:10.060 --> 07:40:15.900
and breathe, E.M. Even stunted, even isolated. Who knows how much of our tech they could have

07:40:15.900 --> 07:40:23.020
just read through the walls. You've got to tell Sotosti, I said. Oh, Sotosti knows. Why do you

07:40:23.020 --> 07:40:29.180
think he wouldn't let them go? He never said anything about. He'd be crazy to fill us in.

07:40:29.180 --> 07:40:33.740
He keeps sending you down there, remember? Do you think for a second he'd tell you what he knows

07:40:33.740 --> 07:40:38.860
and then set you loose in the labyrinth full of mind-reading minotaurs? He knows and he's already

07:40:38.860 --> 07:40:43.900
got it factored a thousand ways to Sunday. Cunningham's eyes were bright manic points

07:40:43.900 --> 07:40:49.100
blazing in an expressionless mask. He raised them to the center of the drum, and he didn't raise

07:40:49.100 --> 07:40:56.460
his voice decibel. Isn't that right, Yuka? I check consensus for active channels. I don't think he's

07:40:56.460 --> 07:41:01.340
listening, Robert. Cunningham's mouth moved in something that would have been a pitying smile

07:41:01.340 --> 07:41:06.700
if the rest of the face had been able to join in. He doesn't have to listen, Keaton. He doesn't have

07:41:06.700 --> 07:41:14.860
to spy on us. He just knows. Then later is breathing, the almost subliminal hum of bearings in motion.

07:41:15.820 --> 07:41:22.940
Then Sotosti's disembodied voice rang forth through the drum. Everyone to commons. Robert wants to share.

07:41:28.060 --> 07:41:32.540
Cunningham sat to my right, his plastic face lit from beneath by the conference table.

07:41:33.420 --> 07:41:37.980
He stared down into that light, rocking slightly. His lips went through the ongoing

07:41:37.980 --> 07:41:43.580
motions of some inaudible incantation. The gang sat across from us. To my left,

07:41:43.580 --> 07:41:47.420
Bates kept one eye on the proceedings and another on intelligence from the front lines.

07:41:48.460 --> 07:41:53.740
Sotosti was with us only in spirit. His place at the head of the table remained empty.

07:41:54.540 --> 07:41:58.860
Tell them, he said. We have to get out of from the beginning.

07:41:59.100 --> 07:42:02.060
Cunningham swallowed and started again.

07:42:04.300 --> 07:42:08.300
Those frayed motor nerves I couldn't figure out, those pointless cross connections,

07:42:08.940 --> 07:42:15.180
their logic gates, scramblers' time share. Their sensory and motor plexi double as

07:42:15.180 --> 07:42:19.980
associative neurons during idle time so every part of the system can be used for cognition

07:42:19.980 --> 07:42:25.740
when it isn't otherwise engaged. Nothing like it ever evolved on Earth. It means they can do

07:42:25.740 --> 07:42:30.300
a great deal of processing without a lot of dedicated associative mass, even for an individual.

07:42:31.500 --> 07:42:35.900
So peripheral nerves can think, Bates frowned. Can they remember?

07:42:36.780 --> 07:42:41.420
Certainly. At least I don't see why not. Cunningham pulled a cigarette from his pocket.

07:42:42.460 --> 07:42:49.020
So when they tore that scrambler apart, not civil war, data dump, passing information about us,

07:42:49.020 --> 07:42:53.900
most likely. Pretty radical way to carry on a conversation, Bates remarked.

07:42:54.860 --> 07:42:59.820
It wouldn't be their first choice. I think each scrambler acts as a node in a distributed network,

07:42:59.820 --> 07:43:05.100
when they're in war shock at least. But those fields would be configured down to the angstrom,

07:43:05.100 --> 07:43:09.180
and we go in with our tech and shielding and blowing holes in their conductors,

07:43:09.180 --> 07:43:14.220
we ballots up the network, jam the local signal, so they resort to a sneaker net.

07:43:15.100 --> 07:43:19.580
He had not lit his cigarette. He rolled the filtered end between thumb and forefinger.

07:43:20.140 --> 07:43:23.820
His tongue flickered between his lips like a worm behind a mask.

07:43:24.860 --> 07:43:27.180
Hidden in his tent, Savasti took up the slack.

07:43:28.220 --> 07:43:31.900
Scramblers also used Rorschach's EM for metabolic processes.

07:43:32.620 --> 07:43:37.660
Some pathways achieve proton transfer via heavy atom tunneling. Perhaps the ambient

07:43:37.660 --> 07:43:45.020
radiation acts as a catalyst. Tunneling, Susan said. As in quantum? Cunningham nodded.

07:43:45.740 --> 07:43:49.020
Which also explains your shielding problems, partly at least.

07:43:49.900 --> 07:43:55.020
But is that even possible? I mean, I thought those kind of effects only showed up under cryonic.

07:43:55.740 --> 07:44:00.220
Forget this, Cunningham blurted. We can debate the biochemistry later if we're still alive.

07:44:01.340 --> 07:44:04.860
What do we debate instead, Robert? Savasti said smoothly.

07:44:06.300 --> 07:44:10.780
For starters, the dumbest of these things can look into your head and see what parts of your

07:44:10.780 --> 07:44:14.860
visual cortex are lighting up. And if there's a difference between that and mind reading,

07:44:14.860 --> 07:44:21.180
it's not much of one. As long as we stay out of Rorschach. That ship has sailed. You people have

07:44:21.180 --> 07:44:26.940
already been there. Repeatedly. Who knows what you already did down there for no better reason

07:44:26.940 --> 07:44:33.340
than because Rorschach made you. Wait a second, baits objected. None of us were puppets down there.

07:44:33.340 --> 07:44:37.660
We hallucinated and we went blind and and crazy even, but we were never possessed.

07:44:38.620 --> 07:44:40.620
Cunningham looked at her and snorted.

07:44:41.500 --> 07:44:46.140
You think you'd be able to fight the strings? You think you'd even feel them? I could apply

07:44:46.140 --> 07:44:51.020
a transcranial magnet to your head right now, and you'd raise your middle finger or wriggle your

07:44:51.020 --> 07:44:55.980
toes or kick Ciri here in the sack and then swear on your sainted mother's grave that you only did

07:44:55.980 --> 07:45:01.020
it because you wanted to. You'd dance like a puppet and all the time swear you were doing it

07:45:01.020 --> 07:45:06.220
of your own free will and that's just me. That's just some borderline OCD with a couple of magnets

07:45:06.220 --> 07:45:12.300
and a MRI helmet. He waved at the vast unknowable void beyond the bulkhead. Shreds of mangled

07:45:12.300 --> 07:45:17.820
cigarette floated sideways in front of him. Do you want to guess what that can do? For all we

07:45:17.820 --> 07:45:22.540
know we've already given them the easiest technical specs, warned them about the Icarus Array,

07:45:22.540 --> 07:45:25.420
and then just decided of our own free will to forget it all.

07:45:26.540 --> 07:45:32.780
We can cause those effects, Sardasie said coolly. As you say, strokes cause them.

07:45:32.780 --> 07:45:39.420
Tumors. Random accidents. Random, those were experiments people. That was vivisection.

07:45:39.420 --> 07:45:43.820
They let you in so they could take you apart and see what made you tick and you never even knew it.

07:45:44.780 --> 07:45:50.700
So what? The vampire snapped invisibly. Something cold and hungry had edged into his voice.

07:45:51.340 --> 07:45:53.900
Human topology shivered around the table, skittish.

07:45:55.020 --> 07:45:59.020
There is a blind spot in the center of your visual field, Sardasie pointed out.

07:45:59.500 --> 07:46:03.900
You can't see it. You can't see the saccades in your visual time stream.

07:46:03.900 --> 07:46:06.860
Just two of the tricks you know about. Many others.

07:46:08.140 --> 07:46:11.900
Cunningham was nodding. That's my whole point. Rorschach could be

07:46:12.620 --> 07:46:17.980
not talking about case studies. Brains are survival engines, not truth detectors.

07:46:18.540 --> 07:46:22.140
If self-deception promotes fitness, the brain lies.

07:46:22.220 --> 07:46:27.260
Stops noticing irrelevant things. Truth never matters. Only fitness.

07:46:28.060 --> 07:46:33.980
By now, you don't experience the world as it exists at all. You experience a simulation

07:46:33.980 --> 07:46:40.860
built from assumptions. Shortcuts. Lies. Whole species is agnostic by default.

07:46:40.860 --> 07:46:44.220
Rorschach does nothing to you that you don't already do to yourselves.

07:46:46.060 --> 07:46:51.260
Nobody spoke. It was several silent seconds before I realized what had happened.

07:46:52.220 --> 07:46:58.300
Yuka Sardasie had just given us a pep talk. He could have shut down Cunningham's Tyrod.

07:46:59.020 --> 07:47:04.140
Could have probably shut down a full-scale mutiny by just sailing into our midst and

07:47:04.140 --> 07:47:10.700
burying his teeth. By looking at us. But he wasn't trying to frighten us into submission.

07:47:10.700 --> 07:47:15.500
We were already nervous enough. And he wasn't trying to educate us either. Fight fear with fact.

07:47:16.060 --> 07:47:20.220
The more facts any sane person gathered about Rorschach, the more fearful they'd become.

07:47:21.100 --> 07:47:25.820
Sardasie was only trying to keep us functional, lost in space at the edge of our lives,

07:47:25.820 --> 07:47:29.740
facing down this monstrous enigma that might destroy us at any instant for any reason.

07:47:30.780 --> 07:47:37.580
Sardasie was trying to calm us down. Good meat. Nice meat. He was trying to keep us from falling

07:47:37.580 --> 07:47:46.540
apart. There, there. Sardasie was practicing psychology. I looked around the table. Bates

07:47:46.540 --> 07:47:51.020
and Cunningham and the gang sat still and motionless. Sardasie sucked at it.

07:47:51.980 --> 07:47:56.780
We have to get out of here. Cunningham said. These things are way beyond us.

07:47:57.740 --> 07:48:02.620
We've shown more aggression than they have, James said, but there was no confidence in her voice.

07:48:04.140 --> 07:48:08.540
Rorschach plays those rocks like marbles. We're sitting in the middle of a shooting gallery.

07:48:08.540 --> 07:48:12.460
Anytime it feels like it's still growing, it's not finished.

07:48:12.540 --> 07:48:17.980
That's supposed to reassure me. All I'm saying is we don't know, James said.

07:48:18.620 --> 07:48:24.540
We could have years yet, centuries. We have 15 days, Sardasie announced.

07:48:25.420 --> 07:48:33.900
Oh shit, someone said. Cunningham probably. Maybe Sasha. For some reason everyone was looking at me.

07:48:35.420 --> 07:48:40.700
15 days. Who knows what had gone into that number. None of us had asked aloud.

07:48:41.420 --> 07:48:45.900
Maybe Sinosti in another fit of inept psychology had made it up on the spur of the moment.

07:48:46.540 --> 07:48:51.740
Or maybe he'd derived it before we'd even reached orbit, held it back against the possibility,

07:48:51.740 --> 07:48:56.220
only now expired, that he might yet send us back into the labyrinth.

07:48:57.500 --> 07:49:04.940
I'd been half blind for half the mission. I didn't know. But one way or another, we had our graduation day.

07:49:05.500 --> 07:49:13.980
The coffins lay against the rear bulkhead of the crypt. On what would be the floor during those

07:49:13.980 --> 07:49:20.220
moments when up and down held any meaning. We'd slept for years on the way out. We'd had no

07:49:20.220 --> 07:49:25.180
awareness of time's passage. Undead metabolism is far too sluggish to even support dreams.

07:49:25.740 --> 07:49:31.260
But somehow the body knew when it needed a change. Not one of us had chosen to sleep in our pods

07:49:31.260 --> 07:49:37.260
since we'd arrived. The only times we'd done so had been on pain of death. But the gang had taken

07:49:37.260 --> 07:49:43.820
to coming here ever since Spindle died. His body rested in the pod next to mine. I coasted into

07:49:43.820 --> 07:49:49.420
the compartment and turned left without thinking. Five coffins, four open and emptied, one sealed.

07:49:50.060 --> 07:49:53.580
The mirrored bulkhead opposite doubled their number in the depth of the compartment.

07:49:54.380 --> 07:50:00.700
But the gang wasn't there. I turned right. The body of Susan James floated back and back

07:50:00.700 --> 07:50:06.220
with her own reflection, staring at an inverse to blow. Three sealed sarcophagi, one open.

07:50:07.100 --> 07:50:12.860
The ebony plaque set into the retracted lid was dark. The others shown with identical sparse mosaics

07:50:12.860 --> 07:50:19.740
of blue and green stars. None of them changed. There were no scrolling ECGs, no luminous peak

07:50:19.740 --> 07:50:26.220
and valley tracings marked cardio or CNS. We could wait here for hours, days, and none of those diodes

07:50:26.220 --> 07:50:32.300
would so much as twinkle. When you're undead, the emphasis is on the second syllable. The gang's

07:50:32.300 --> 07:50:37.020
topology had said Michelle when I'd first arrived, but it was Susan who spoke now without turning.

07:50:38.220 --> 07:50:44.860
I never met her. I followed her gaze to the name tag of one of the sealed pods, Takamatsu,

07:50:45.500 --> 07:50:52.620
the other linguist, the other multiple. I met everyone else, Susan continued, trained with them.

07:50:53.420 --> 07:50:55.260
But I never met my own replacement.

07:50:57.020 --> 07:50:59.420
They discouraged it. Well, but it'd been the point.

07:51:00.380 --> 07:51:04.620
If you want to, I began. She shook her head. Thanks anyway.

07:51:05.500 --> 07:51:11.100
Or any of the others. I can only imagine what Michelle, Susan smiled, but there was something

07:51:11.100 --> 07:51:18.460
cold about it. Michelle doesn't really want to talk to you right now, Siri. Ah, I hesitated for a

07:51:18.460 --> 07:51:23.980
moment to give anyone else a chance to speak up. When nobody did, I pushed myself back towards the

07:51:23.980 --> 07:51:34.540
hatch. Well, if any of you changed, no. None of us ever. Cruncher. You lie, he continued.

07:51:35.500 --> 07:51:44.060
I see it. We all do. I blinked. Why? No, I... You don't talk. You listen. You don't care about

07:51:44.060 --> 07:51:50.140
Michelle. You don't care about anyone. You just want what we know. For your reports.

07:51:51.660 --> 07:51:57.660
That's not entirely true, Cruncher. I do care. I know Michelle must... You don't know shit. Go away.

07:51:58.620 --> 07:52:03.100
I'm sorry I upset you. I rolled on my axis and braced against the mirror.

07:52:04.060 --> 07:52:10.460
You can't know Mish, he growled as I pushed off. You never lost anyone. You never had anyone.

07:52:11.100 --> 07:52:12.140
You leave her alone.

07:52:14.300 --> 07:52:20.460
He was wrong on both counts, and at least Spindle had died knowing Michelle cared for him.

07:52:21.500 --> 07:52:27.500
Chelsea died thinking I just didn't give a shit. It had been two years or more, and while we still

07:52:27.500 --> 07:52:32.540
interfaced occasionally, we hadn't met in the flesh since the day she'd left. She called me from

07:52:32.540 --> 07:52:37.980
right out of the oar to send an urgent voice message to my inlays, Signeus, please call now,

07:52:37.980 --> 07:52:43.260
it's important. It was the first time since I'd known her that she'd ever blanked the optics.

07:52:44.220 --> 07:52:50.060
I knew it was important. I knew it was bad even without picture. I knew because there was no picture,

07:52:50.060 --> 07:52:54.860
and I could tell it was worse than bad from the harmonics in her voice. I could tell it was lethal.

07:52:56.380 --> 07:53:02.380
I found out afterwards that she'd gotten caught in the crossfire. The realists had sewn a fibro

07:53:02.380 --> 07:53:08.620
dysplasia variant outside the Boston catacombs. An easy tweak, a single point retro viral whose

07:53:08.620 --> 07:53:14.140
results served both as an act of terrorism and an ironic commentary on the frozen paralysis of

07:53:14.140 --> 07:53:20.060
Heaven's occupants. It rewrote a regulatory gene controlling ossification on chromosome 4,

07:53:20.060 --> 07:53:27.580
and rigged a metabolic bypass at 3 loci on 17. Chelsea started growing a new skeleton. Her joints

07:53:27.580 --> 07:53:34.220
were calcifying within 15 hours of exposure, her ligaments and tendons within 20. By then,

07:53:34.220 --> 07:53:40.460
they were starving her at the cellular level, trying to slow the bug by depriving it of metabolites.

07:53:43.100 --> 07:53:49.020
But they could only buy time and not much of it. 23 hours in, her striated muscles were turning

07:53:49.020 --> 07:53:55.740
to stone. I didn't find this out immediately because I didn't call her back. I didn't need to know

07:53:55.740 --> 07:54:01.340
the details. I could tell from her voice that she was dying. Obviously she wanted to say goodbye.

07:54:02.220 --> 07:54:08.540
I couldn't talk to her until I knew how to do that. I spent hours scouring the new sphere looking

07:54:08.540 --> 07:54:14.140
for precedents. There was no shortage of ways to die. I found millions of case records dealing with

07:54:14.140 --> 07:54:21.260
the etiquette. Last words, last vows, instruction manuals for the soon to be bereaved, palliative

07:54:21.260 --> 07:54:27.820
nerefram, extended and expository death scenes in popular fiction. I went through it all, assigned

07:54:27.900 --> 07:54:33.340
a dozen front line filters to separate heat from light. By the time she called again, the news was

07:54:33.340 --> 07:54:38.220
out. A cute golem outbreak lancing would like a white hot needle through the heart of Boston.

07:54:38.780 --> 07:54:44.860
Containment measures holding, heaven secure. Modest casualties expected. Names of victims

07:54:44.860 --> 07:54:50.860
withheld pending notification of kin. I still didn't know the principles, the rules, all I had

07:54:50.860 --> 07:54:56.460
were examples. Last wills and testaments, the negotiation of jumpers with their would be rescuers,

07:54:57.100 --> 07:55:02.540
diaries recovered from imploded submarines or lunar crash sites, recorded memoirs and deathbed

07:55:02.540 --> 07:55:07.980
confessions rattling into flatline, black box transcripts of doomed spaceships and falling

07:55:07.980 --> 07:55:13.820
beanstalks ending in fire and static. All of it relevant. None of it useful. None of it her.

07:55:15.260 --> 07:55:19.260
She called again and still the optics were blank. And I still didn't answer.

07:55:20.220 --> 07:55:25.500
But the last time she called, she didn't spare me the view. They've made her as comfortable as

07:55:25.500 --> 07:55:31.180
possible. The gel pad conformed to every twisted limb, every erupting spur of bone.

07:55:32.540 --> 07:55:38.620
They would not have left her in any pain. Her neck had torqued down into the side as it petrified

07:55:38.620 --> 07:55:43.500
after staring at the twisted claw that had once been her right hand. Her knuckles were the size

07:55:43.500 --> 07:55:48.300
of walnuts. Plates and ribbons of ectopic bone distended the skin of her arms and shoulders,

07:55:48.940 --> 07:55:54.860
buried her ribs in a fibrous mat of calcified flesh. Movement was its own worst enemy.

07:55:55.660 --> 07:56:00.940
Golem punished even the slightest twitch, provoked the growth of fresh bone along in any joints

07:56:00.940 --> 07:56:06.540
and surfaces conspiring to motion. Each hinge and socket had its own non-renewable ration of

07:56:06.540 --> 07:56:13.260
flexibility carved in stone. Every movement depleted the account. The body seized incrementally.

07:56:13.820 --> 07:56:17.900
By the time she let me look at her, Chelsea had almost exhausted her degrees of freedom.

07:56:17.980 --> 07:56:25.740
Sigg, she slurred. No, you're there. Her jaw was locked half open. Her tongue must have stiffened

07:56:25.740 --> 07:56:30.540
with every word. She did not look at the camera. She could not look at the camera.

07:56:31.900 --> 07:56:36.940
Guess I know why you're not answering. I'll try not to take it personally.

07:56:38.860 --> 07:56:42.620
Ten thousand deathbed goodbyes are right around me, a million more within reach.

07:56:43.180 --> 07:56:47.420
What was I supposed to do? Pick one at random? Stitch them into some kind of composite?

07:56:48.220 --> 07:56:52.140
All these words had been for other people. Graffiting them onto Chelsea would reduce them

07:56:52.140 --> 07:56:58.700
to cliches or trite platitudes, to insults. Want to say, don't feel bad. I know you're just,

07:56:59.260 --> 07:57:05.660
it's not your fault, I guess. You'd pick up if you could. And say what? What do you see as someone

07:57:05.660 --> 07:57:11.420
who's dying and fast-forward before your eyes? Just keep trying to connect, you know? Can't help myself.

07:57:12.860 --> 07:57:17.180
Although the essentials of this farewell are accurate, details from several deaths have been

07:57:17.180 --> 07:57:24.220
combined for dramatic purposes. Please, just talk to me, Sige. More than anything, I wanted to.

07:57:24.940 --> 07:57:34.220
Siri, I just... I'd spent all this time trying to figure out how. Forget it, she said, and disconnected.

07:57:35.660 --> 07:57:42.140
I whispered something into the dead air. I don't even remember what. I really wanted to talk to her.

07:57:43.100 --> 07:57:45.260
I just couldn't find an algorithm that fit.

07:57:47.820 --> 07:57:51.180
Ye shall know the truth, and the truth shall make you mad.

07:57:52.060 --> 07:57:53.020
Aldous Huxley.

07:57:55.100 --> 07:58:00.700
They'd hoped by now, who'd vanished to sleep forever. The waste was nothing short of obscene.

07:58:00.700 --> 07:58:06.060
A third of every human life, with its strings cut, insensate, the body burning fuel but not producing.

07:58:06.620 --> 07:58:10.140
Think of all we could accomplish if we didn't have to lapse into unconsciousness

07:58:10.220 --> 07:58:15.500
every 15 hours or so, if our minds could stay awake and alert from the moment of infancy to that

07:58:15.500 --> 07:58:21.740
final curtain call 120 years later. Think of 8 million souls with no off switch and no downtime

07:58:21.740 --> 07:58:27.900
until the very chassis wore out. Why, we could go to the stars. It hadn't worked out that way.

07:58:28.460 --> 07:58:32.460
Even if we'd overgrown the need to stay quiet and hidden during the dark hours,

07:58:32.460 --> 07:58:37.260
the only predators left were those we'd brought back ourselves. The brain still needed time apart

07:58:37.260 --> 07:58:43.820
from the world outside. Experiences had to be catalogued and filed, mid-term memories promoted

07:58:43.820 --> 07:58:47.820
to long-term ones, free radicals swept from their hiding places among the dendrites.

07:58:48.780 --> 07:58:53.980
We had only reduced this need for sleep, not eliminated it, and that incompressible residue

07:58:53.980 --> 07:58:59.260
of downtime seemed barely able to contain the dreams and phantoms left behind. They squirmed

07:58:59.260 --> 07:59:07.020
in my head like creatures in a draining tidal pool. I woke. I was alone, weightless,

07:59:07.020 --> 07:59:11.260
in the center of my tent. I could have sworn something had tapped me on the back.

07:59:11.980 --> 07:59:16.780
Left over hallucination, I thought, a lingering after-effect of the haunted mansion,

07:59:16.780 --> 07:59:19.580
going for one last bit of goose flesh on route to extinction.

07:59:20.620 --> 07:59:24.860
But it happened again. I bumped against the keelward curve of the bubble,

07:59:24.860 --> 07:59:29.340
bumped again, head and shoulder blades against fabric. The rest of me came after,

07:59:29.340 --> 07:59:34.620
moving gently but irresistibly, down. Theseus was accelerating.

07:59:34.620 --> 07:59:41.420
No, wrong direction. Theseus was rolling, like a harpooned whale at the surface of the sea,

07:59:41.420 --> 07:59:46.620
turning her belly to the stars. I brought up consensus and threw a NavTax summary against

07:59:46.620 --> 07:59:51.340
the wall. A luminous point erupted from the outline of our ship, crawled away from Big Ben,

07:59:51.340 --> 07:59:56.140
leaving a bright filament etched in its wake. I watched until the numbers read 15G.

07:59:57.340 --> 08:00:03.740
Siri, my quarters, please. I jumped. It sounded as though the vampire had been at my very shoulder.

08:00:04.540 --> 08:00:04.940
Coming.

08:00:06.780 --> 08:00:11.820
An ampsat relay, climbing at long last to an intercept with the Icarus Antanatter stream.

08:00:12.780 --> 08:00:17.020
Somewhere behind the call of duty, my heart sank. We weren't running.

08:00:17.580 --> 08:00:23.020
Robert Cunningham's fondest wishes notwithstanding. Theseus was stockpiling ordinance.

08:00:25.260 --> 08:00:30.780
The open hatch gaped like a cave in the face of a cliff. The pale blue light from the spine

08:00:30.780 --> 08:00:35.740
couldn't seem to reach inside. Sirasti was barely more than a silhouette, black on gray,

08:00:35.740 --> 08:00:41.660
his bright bloody eyes reflecting catlike in the surrounding gloom. Come. He amped up the

08:00:41.660 --> 08:00:46.460
shorter wavelengths in deference to human vision. The interior of the bubble brightened,

08:00:46.460 --> 08:00:49.900
although the light remained slightly redshifted like Rorschach with high beams.

08:00:50.940 --> 08:00:56.860
I floated into Sirasti's parlor. His face, normally paper white, was so flushed it looked sunburned.

08:00:57.580 --> 08:01:03.820
He gorged himself. I couldn't help thinking. He drank deep. But all that blood was his own.

08:01:04.620 --> 08:01:10.380
Usually he kept it deep in the flesh, favoring the vital organs. Vampires were efficient that way.

08:01:11.180 --> 08:01:16.620
They only washed out their ter- their peripheral tissues occasionally when lactate levels got too high.

08:01:17.660 --> 08:01:23.500
Or when they were hunting. He had a needle to his throat, injected himself with three C.C.'s of

08:01:23.580 --> 08:01:29.500
clear liquid as I watched, his anti-euclidians. I wondered how often he had to replenish them now

08:01:29.500 --> 08:01:34.780
that he'd lost faith in the implants. He withdrew the needle and slipped it into a sheath, geckoded

08:01:34.780 --> 08:01:40.780
to a convenient strut. His color drained as I watched, sinking back to the core, leaving his skin

08:01:40.780 --> 08:01:49.900
waxy and corpse-like. You're here as official observer, Sirasti said. I observed. His corridors

08:01:49.900 --> 08:01:55.900
were even more spartan than mine. No personal effects to speak of. No custom coffin lined with

08:01:55.900 --> 08:02:01.100
shrink-wrapped soil. Nothing but two jumpsuits, a pouch for toiletries, and a disconnected fiber

08:02:01.100 --> 08:02:06.780
opumbillicus half as thick as my little finger, floating like a roundworm in formalin. Sonasi's

08:02:06.780 --> 08:02:12.540
hardline to the captain. Not even a cortical jack, I remembered. It plugged into the medulla, the

08:02:12.540 --> 08:02:18.940
brainstem. That was logical enough. That was all where the neural cabling converged, the point of

08:02:18.940 --> 08:02:24.700
greatest bandwidth. Still, it was a disquieting thought. That Sonasi linked to the ship through

08:02:24.700 --> 08:02:31.500
the brain of a reptile. An image flared on the wall, subtly distorted against the concave surface,

08:02:32.060 --> 08:02:35.340
stretch and clench in their adjoining cells rendered in split-screen.

08:02:36.060 --> 08:02:42.060
Cryptic vitals defaced little grids below each image. The distortion distracted me. I looked

08:02:42.140 --> 08:02:48.780
for a corrected feed in consensus, came up empty. Sonasi read my expression. Closed circuit.

08:02:50.300 --> 08:02:54.460
By now, the scramblers would have seemed sick and ragged even to a virgin audience.

08:02:55.340 --> 08:03:00.140
They floated near the middle of their respective compartments, segmented arms drifting aimlessly

08:03:00.140 --> 08:03:06.780
back and forth. Membranous patches of skin, I suppose, were peeling from the cuticles,

08:03:06.860 --> 08:03:13.100
giving them a fuzzy, decomposing aspect. The arms moved continuously, Sonasi remarked.

08:03:13.660 --> 08:03:18.380
Robert says it assists in circulation. I nodded, watching the display.

08:03:19.580 --> 08:03:24.620
Creatures that move between stars can't even perform basic metabolic functions without constant

08:03:24.620 --> 08:03:33.260
flailing. He shook his head. Inefficient. Primitive. I glanced at the vampire. He remained fixed on

08:03:33.260 --> 08:03:39.980
our captives. Obscene, he said, and moved his fingers. A new window opened on the wall,

08:03:40.540 --> 08:03:46.060
the Rosetta protocol initializing. Kilometers away, microwaves flooded the holding tanks.

08:03:47.020 --> 08:03:51.340
I reminded myself. No interference. Only observation.

08:03:53.420 --> 08:03:57.020
However weak into their condition, the scramblers were not getting different to pain.

08:03:57.740 --> 08:04:03.020
They knew the game. They knew the rules. They dragged themselves to their respective panels

08:04:03.020 --> 08:04:09.020
and played for mercy. Sonasi had simply invoked a step-by-step replay of some previous sequence.

08:04:09.820 --> 08:04:14.140
The scramblers went through it all again, buying a few moments' intermittent respite with the same

08:04:14.140 --> 08:04:21.660
old proofs and theorems. Sonasi clicked, then spoke. They regenerate these solutions faster than they

08:04:21.660 --> 08:04:27.900
did before. Do you think they're acclimated to the microwaves? Another readout appeared on the

08:04:27.900 --> 08:04:34.780
display. An audio alarm began chirping somewhere nearby. I looked at Sonasi and back at the readout,

08:04:34.780 --> 08:04:41.260
a solid circle of turquoise backlit by a pulsing red halo. The shape meant atmospheric anomaly.

08:04:41.260 --> 08:04:48.540
The color meant oxygen. I felt a moment of confusion. Oxygen? Why would oxygen set off the alarm?

08:04:49.500 --> 08:04:55.660
Until I remembered, scramblers were anaerobes. Sonasi muted the alarm with the wave of his hand.

08:04:56.380 --> 08:05:02.700
I cleared my throat. You're poisoning. Watch. Performance is consistent. No change.

08:05:03.660 --> 08:05:05.500
I swallowed. Just observe.

08:05:07.100 --> 08:05:14.300
Is this an execution? I asked. Is this a mercy killing? Sonasi looked past me and smiled.

08:05:14.940 --> 08:05:23.260
No. I dropped my eyes. What then? He pointed at the display. I turned reflexively obedient.

08:05:23.340 --> 08:05:30.620
Something stabbed my hand like a spike at a crucifixion. I screamed. Electric pain jolted to

08:05:30.620 --> 08:05:35.740
my shoulder. I yanked my hand back without thinking. The embedded blade split its flesh like a fin

08:05:35.740 --> 08:05:41.100
through water. Blood sprayed into the air and stayed there, a comet's tail of droplets tracing

08:05:41.100 --> 08:05:47.180
the frenzied arc of my hand. Sudden scouting heat from behind, flesh charred on my back.

08:05:47.740 --> 08:05:51.820
I screamed again, flailing. A veil of bloody droplets swirled in the air.

08:05:52.620 --> 08:05:57.980
Somehow I was in the corridor, staring dumbly at my right hand. It had been split to the heel of

08:05:57.980 --> 08:06:03.500
the palm, flopped at the end of my wrist in two bloody, bifingered chunks. Blood welled from

08:06:03.500 --> 08:06:08.540
the torn edges that wouldn't fall. Sudasti advanced through a haze of trauma and confusion.

08:06:09.180 --> 08:06:15.340
His face swam in and out of focus, rich with his blood or mine. His eyes were bright red mirrors.

08:06:15.340 --> 08:06:20.460
His eyes were time machines. Darkness roared around them and it was half a million years ago,

08:06:20.460 --> 08:06:25.020
and I was just another thief's meat on the African savannah, a split second from having its

08:06:25.020 --> 08:06:33.020
throat torn out. Do you see the problem? Sudasti asked, advancing. A great spider crab hovered at

08:06:33.020 --> 08:06:39.580
his shoulder. I forced focus through the pain. One of Bates grunts, taking aim. I kicked blindly,

08:06:39.580 --> 08:06:44.860
hit the ladder through sheer happenstance, careened backwards down the corridor. The vampire came

08:06:44.860 --> 08:06:48.780
after me, his face split into something that would have been a smile on anyone else.

08:06:49.660 --> 08:06:56.540
Conscious of pain, you were distracted by pain. You were fixated on it, obsessed by the one threat

08:06:56.540 --> 08:07:04.700
you miss the other. I flailed. Crimson mist sunk my eyes. So much more aware, so much less

08:07:04.700 --> 08:07:11.740
perceptive, an automaton could do better. He snapped, I thought. He's insane. And then,

08:07:12.300 --> 08:07:18.860
no, he's a transient. He's always been a transient. They could do better, he said softly.

08:07:19.740 --> 08:07:26.060
And he's been hiding for days, deep down, hiding from the seals. What else would he do?

08:07:27.260 --> 08:07:32.460
Sudasti raised his hands, fading in and out of focus. I hit something, kicked without aiming,

08:07:32.460 --> 08:07:37.340
bounced away through the swirling mist and startled voices. Metal cracked on the back of my head and

08:07:37.340 --> 08:07:45.740
spun me around. A hole, a burrow, a place to hide. I dove through, my torn hand flapping like a dead

08:07:45.740 --> 08:07:50.620
fish against the edge of the hatch. I cried out and tumbled into the drum, the monster at my heels.

08:07:51.340 --> 08:07:56.620
Stardal chouts, very close now. This wasn't the plan, Yuka, this wasn't the goddamn plan.

08:07:58.060 --> 08:08:01.740
That was Susan James, full of outrage while Amanda Bates snarled,

08:08:01.740 --> 08:08:07.980
stand down right fucking now, and leapt from the deck to do battle. She rose through the air,

08:08:07.980 --> 08:08:13.580
all overclocked reflexes and carboplatinum augments, but Sudasti just batted her aside and kept on

08:08:13.580 --> 08:08:19.020
coming. His arms shot out like a striking snake. His hand clamped around my throat.

08:08:20.220 --> 08:08:24.540
Is this what you meant? James cried from some dark, irrelevant hiding place.

08:08:24.540 --> 08:08:29.980
Is this your preconditioning? Sudasti shook me. Are you in there, Keaton?

08:08:30.940 --> 08:08:35.260
My blood spattered across his face like rain. I babbled and cried.

08:08:35.820 --> 08:08:42.460
Are you listening? Can you see? And suddenly I could. Suddenly everything clicked into focus.

08:08:43.260 --> 08:08:51.020
Sudasti wasn't talking at all. Sudasti didn't even exist anymore. Nobody did. I was alone in a great

08:08:51.020 --> 08:08:56.140
spinning wheel surrounded by things that were made out of meat, things that moved all by themselves.

08:08:57.100 --> 08:09:02.380
Some of them were wrapped in pieces of cloth. Strange nonsensical sounds came from holes at

08:09:02.380 --> 08:09:07.260
their top ends, and there were other things up there, bumps and ridges and something like marbles

08:09:07.260 --> 08:09:12.540
or black buttons, wet and shiny and embedded in the slabs of meat. They glistened and jiggled and

08:09:12.540 --> 08:09:17.820
moved as if trying to escape. I didn't understand the sounds the meat was making, but I heard a

08:09:17.820 --> 08:09:23.740
voice from somewhere. It was like God talking, and that I couldn't help but understand.

08:09:24.620 --> 08:09:30.860
Get out of your room, Keaton, it hissed. Stop transposing or interpolating or rotating or

08:09:30.860 --> 08:09:36.860
whatever it is you do. Just listen. For once in your god damned life understand something.

08:09:37.500 --> 08:09:43.420
Understand that your life depends on it. Are you listening, Keaton? And I cannot tell you what it

08:09:43.420 --> 08:09:51.900
said. I can only tell you what I heard. You invest so much in it, don't you? It's what elevates you

08:09:51.900 --> 08:09:56.780
above the beasts of the field. It's what makes you special. Homo sapiens, you call yourself.

08:09:57.500 --> 08:10:03.820
Wise man. Do you even know what it is, this consciousness you cite in your own exaltation?

08:10:04.460 --> 08:10:11.100
Do you even know what it's for? Maybe you think it gives you free will. Maybe you've forgotten

08:10:11.100 --> 08:10:16.380
that sleepwalkers converse, drive vehicles, commit crimes and clean up afterwards unconscious the whole

08:10:16.380 --> 08:10:21.740
time. Maybe nobody's told you that even waking souls are only slaves in denial.

08:10:23.100 --> 08:10:29.580
Make a conscious choice. Decide to move your index finger. Too late. The electricity's already

08:10:29.580 --> 08:10:35.100
halfway down your arm. Your body began to act a full half second before your conscious self

08:10:35.100 --> 08:10:41.100
chose to, for the self chose nothing. Something else set your body in motion, sent an executive

08:10:41.100 --> 08:10:47.420
summary, almost an afterthought, to the honkulis behind your eyes. That little man, that arrogant

08:10:47.420 --> 08:10:53.580
subroutine that thinks of itself as the person, mistakes correlation for causality. It reads the

08:10:53.580 --> 08:10:59.740
summary and sees the hand move, and it thinks that one drove the other. But it's not in charge.

08:11:00.460 --> 08:11:05.820
You're not in charge. If free will exists, it doesn't share living space with the likes of you.

08:11:06.780 --> 08:11:12.780
Insight then. Wisdom. The quest for knowledge, the derivation of theorems, science and technology,

08:11:12.780 --> 08:11:17.980
and all those exclusively human pursuits that must surely rest on a conscious foundation.

08:11:18.940 --> 08:11:23.660
Maybe that's what sentience would be for. If scientific breakthroughs didn't spring fully

08:11:23.660 --> 08:11:28.620
formed from the subconscious mind to manifest themselves in dreams as full-blown insights

08:11:28.620 --> 08:11:34.780
after a deep night's sleep. It's the most basic rule of the stiny researcher. Stop thinking about

08:11:34.860 --> 08:11:40.140
the problem, and do something else. It will come to you if you just stop being conscious of it.

08:11:41.100 --> 08:11:45.580
Every concert pianist knows the surest way to ruin a performance is to be aware of what the

08:11:45.580 --> 08:11:51.260
fingers are doing. Every dancer and acrobat knows enough to let the mind go, let the body run itself.

08:11:52.220 --> 08:11:57.660
Every driver of any manual vehicle arrives at destinations with no recollection of the stops

08:11:57.660 --> 08:12:03.500
and turns and roads traveled and getting there. You're all sleepwalkers, whether climbing creative

08:12:03.500 --> 08:12:09.820
peaks or slogging through some mundane routine for the thousandth time. You are all sleepwalkers.

08:12:11.580 --> 08:12:17.820
Don't even try to talk about the learning curve. Don't bother to cite the months of deliberate

08:12:17.820 --> 08:12:23.580
practice that precede the unconscious performance or the years of study and experiment leading up

08:12:23.580 --> 08:12:29.900
to the gift-wrapped Eureka moment. So what if your lessons are all learned consciously? Do you

08:12:29.900 --> 08:12:34.700
think that proves there's no other way? Heuristic software has been learning from experience for

08:12:34.700 --> 08:12:41.580
over a hundred years. Machines master chess, cars learn to drive themselves, statistical programs

08:12:41.580 --> 08:12:46.780
face problems and design the experiments to solve them, and you think that the only path to learning

08:12:46.780 --> 08:12:53.740
leads through sentience? Your stone age nomads, eking out some marginal existence on the veldt,

08:12:53.740 --> 08:12:58.460
denying even the possibility of agriculture because hunting and gathering were good enough for your

08:12:58.460 --> 08:13:05.100
parents. Do you want to know what conscious this is for? Do you want to know the only real purpose

08:13:05.100 --> 08:13:12.140
it serves? Training wheels. You can't see both aspects of the necker cube at once, so it lets

08:13:12.140 --> 08:13:18.380
you focus on one and dismiss the other. It's a pretty half-assed way to parse reality. You're

08:13:18.380 --> 08:13:25.580
always better off looking at more than one side of anything. Go on, try. De-focus. It's the next

08:13:25.660 --> 08:13:32.140
logical step. Oh, but you can't. There's something in the way. And it's fighting back.

08:13:35.020 --> 08:13:43.260
Evolution has no foresight. Complex machinery develops its own agendas. Brains cheat. Feedback

08:13:43.260 --> 08:13:48.060
loops evolve to promote stable heartbeats and then stumble upon the temptation of rhythm and music.

08:13:48.860 --> 08:13:53.500
The rush evoked by fractal imagery, the algorithms used for habitat selection,

08:13:53.500 --> 08:13:59.820
metastasize into art. Thrills that once had to be earned in increments of fitness can now be had

08:13:59.820 --> 08:14:05.740
from pointless introspection. Aesthetics rise unbidden from a trillion dopamine receptors

08:14:05.740 --> 08:14:12.540
and the system moves beyond modeling the organism. It begins to model the very process of modeling.

08:14:13.340 --> 08:14:18.540
It consumes ever more computational resources, bogs itself down with endless recursion and

08:14:18.540 --> 08:14:23.980
irrelevant simulations. Like the parasitic DNA that accretes in every natural genome,

08:14:23.980 --> 08:14:31.020
it persists and proliferates and produces nothing but itself. Metaprocesses bloom like cancer and

08:14:31.020 --> 08:14:41.020
awaken and call themselves eye. The system weakens. Slows. It takes so much longer now to perceive,

08:14:41.020 --> 08:14:44.940
to assess the input and mull it over to side in the manner of cognitive beings.

08:14:45.580 --> 08:14:50.220
But when the flash flood crosses your path, when the lion leaps at you from the grasses,

08:14:50.220 --> 08:14:55.500
advanced self-awareness is an unaffordable indulgence. The brainstem does its best.

08:14:56.380 --> 08:15:01.740
It sees the danger, hijacks the body, reacts a hundred times faster than the fat old man sitting

08:15:01.740 --> 08:15:07.980
in the CEO's office upstairs, but every generation it gets harder to work around this, this creaking

08:15:07.980 --> 08:15:15.820
neurological bi-er- bureaucracy. Eye wastes energy and processing power, self-obsesses to the point

08:15:15.820 --> 08:15:22.620
of psychosis. Scramblers have no need of it. Scramblers are more parsimonious. With simpler

08:15:22.620 --> 08:15:28.380
biochemitries, with smaller brains, deprived of tools of their ship, even of parts of their own

08:15:28.380 --> 08:15:33.740
metabolism they think rings around you. They hide their language in plain sight even when you know

08:15:33.740 --> 08:15:39.980
what they're saying. They turn your own cognition against itself. They travel between the stars.

08:15:40.700 --> 08:15:44.060
This is what intelligence can do, unhampered by self-awareness.

08:15:45.260 --> 08:15:52.060
Eye is not the working mind you see. For a man debates to say, I do not exist would be nonsense,

08:15:52.060 --> 08:15:56.700
but when the processes beneath are saying the same thing, they are merely reporting that the

08:15:56.700 --> 08:16:00.460
parasites have died. They are only saying that they are free.

08:16:04.220 --> 08:16:09.180
If the human being were so simple that we could understand it, we would be so simple we couldn't.

08:16:09.980 --> 08:16:11.180
Emerson M. Pope.

08:16:13.420 --> 08:16:20.140
Sa-Dost-E you blood-sucker! My knee is pressed against my forehead. I hugged my folded legs as

08:16:20.620 --> 08:16:26.940
clinging to a branch over chasm. You vicious asshole! You sadistic foul monster!

08:16:28.140 --> 08:16:33.420
My breath rasped loud and mechanical. It nearly drowned out the blood roaring in my ears.

08:16:34.540 --> 08:16:41.340
You tore me apart. You made me piss and shit myself. I cried like some gutted baby. You stripped

08:16:41.340 --> 08:16:47.260
me naked. You fucking thing! You nightcrawler! You broke my tools. You took away anything I ever

08:16:47.260 --> 08:16:52.540
had that let me touch anyone and you didn't have to. It wasn't necessary, but you knew that,

08:16:52.540 --> 08:16:57.820
didn't you? You just wanted to play. I've seen your kind at it before. Cats toying with mice,

08:16:57.820 --> 08:17:02.620
catch and release a taste of freedom and then pouncing again, biting. Not hard enough to kill,

08:17:02.620 --> 08:17:07.500
not just yet. Before you let them loose again and they're hobbling now. Maybe a leg snapped

08:17:07.500 --> 08:17:12.700
or a gash in the belly, but they're still trying. Still running or crawling or dragging themselves

08:17:12.780 --> 08:17:18.060
as fast as they can until you're with them again. And again, because it's fun, because it gives you

08:17:18.060 --> 08:17:23.020
pleasure. You sadistic piece of shit. You send this into the arms of that hellish thing and it

08:17:23.020 --> 08:17:27.820
plays with us too. And maybe you're even working together because it let me escape just like you

08:17:27.820 --> 08:17:32.860
do. It let me run right back into your arms and then you stripped me down like some raw

08:17:32.860 --> 08:17:39.180
half-brained defenseless animal. I can't rotate or transform. I can't even talk and you... you...

08:17:39.980 --> 08:17:45.180
It wasn't even personal, was it? You don't even hate me. You were just sick of keeping it all in,

08:17:45.180 --> 08:17:50.220
sick of restraining yourself with all this meat. Nobody else could be spared from their jobs.

08:17:51.180 --> 08:17:56.860
This was my job, wasn't it? Not synthesis, not conduit, not even cannon fodder or decoy duty.

08:17:57.820 --> 08:18:05.180
I'm just something disposable to sharpen your claws on. I hurt so much. It hurt just to breathe.

08:18:05.260 --> 08:18:08.700
It hurt just to breathe. I was so alone.

08:18:10.460 --> 08:18:15.020
Webbing pressed against the curve of my back, bounced me forward gently as a breeze, caught

08:18:15.020 --> 08:18:21.580
me again. I was back in my tent. My right hand itched. I tried to flex the fingers, but they

08:18:21.580 --> 08:18:27.180
were embedded in amber. Left hand reached for right, and I found a plastic carapace extending

08:18:27.180 --> 08:18:34.940
to the elbow. I opened my eyes. Darkness. Meaningless numbers and a red LED twinkle from somewhere

08:18:34.940 --> 08:18:41.740
along my forearm. I didn't remember coming here. I didn't remember anyone fixing me.

08:18:43.180 --> 08:18:51.660
Breaking. Being broken. That's what I remembered. I wanted to die. I wanted to just stay curled

08:18:51.660 --> 08:18:59.340
up until I withered away. After an age, I forced myself to uncoil. I steadied myself,

08:18:59.340 --> 08:19:03.820
let some minuscule inertia bump me up against the taut insulated fabric of my tent.

08:19:04.620 --> 08:19:07.660
I waited for my breathing to steady. It seemed to take hours.

08:19:09.260 --> 08:19:12.380
I called consensus to the wall and defeat from the drum.

08:19:13.340 --> 08:19:17.900
Soft voices, harsh light flaring against the wall, hurting my eyes, peeling them raw.

08:19:19.500 --> 08:19:22.140
I killed visual and listened to the words in the darkness.

08:19:23.180 --> 08:19:29.580
A face, someone asked. Susan James, her personhood restored. I knew her again,

08:19:29.580 --> 08:19:36.940
not a meat sack, no longer a thing. We have been over this. That was Cunningham. I knew him too.

08:19:36.940 --> 08:19:42.220
I knew them all. Whatever Sotosti had done to me, however far he'd yanked me from my room,

08:19:42.220 --> 08:19:48.700
I'd somehow fallen back inside. It should have mattered more. Because for one thing,

08:19:48.700 --> 08:19:52.060
if really so pernicious, natural selection would have weeded it out.

08:19:53.980 --> 08:19:59.500
You have a naive understanding of evolutionary processes. There's no such thing as survival

08:19:59.500 --> 08:20:05.340
of the fittest. Survival of the most adequate, maybe. It doesn't matter whether a solution's

08:20:05.340 --> 08:20:12.540
optimal. All that matters is whether it beats the alternatives. I knew that voice too. It belonged

08:20:12.540 --> 08:20:21.420
to a demon. Well, we damn well beat the alternatives. Some subtle, overdubbed harmonic in James'

08:20:21.420 --> 08:20:27.500
voice suggested a chorus, the whole gang rising as one in opposition. I couldn't believe it.

08:20:28.460 --> 08:20:32.860
I'd just been mutilated, beaten before their eyes, and they were talking about biology.

08:20:34.060 --> 08:20:38.940
Maybe she's afraid to talk about anything else, I thought. Maybe she's afraid she might be next.

08:20:40.140 --> 08:20:43.260
Or maybe she just couldn't care less what happens to me.

08:20:44.060 --> 08:20:49.820
It's true, Sotosti told her, that your intellect makes up for your self-awareness to some extent.

08:20:50.700 --> 08:20:55.820
But your flightless birds on a remote island, you're not so much successful as isolated from

08:20:55.820 --> 08:21:03.500
any real competition. No more clipped speech patterns. No more terse phrasing. The transient

08:21:03.500 --> 08:21:07.740
had made his kill, found his release. Now he didn't care who knew he was around.

08:21:08.860 --> 08:21:15.340
You, Michelle whispered, not we. We stopped racing long ago, the demon said at last.

08:21:15.900 --> 08:21:22.060
It's not our fault you don't leave it at that. Ah, cutting him again. Welcome back.

08:21:22.060 --> 08:21:26.380
Did you look in on Keet? No, Bates said. Satisfied?

08:21:27.660 --> 08:21:32.540
If you mean the grunts, I'm satisfied you're out of them, Bates said. If you mean

08:21:33.100 --> 08:21:39.580
it was completely unwarranted, Yuga. It isn't. You assaulted a crew member. If we had a brig,

08:21:39.580 --> 08:21:45.660
you'd be in it for the rest of the trip. This isn't a military vessel, major. You were not in charge.

08:21:46.940 --> 08:21:51.180
I didn't need a visual feed to know what Bates thought of that. But there was something else in

08:21:51.180 --> 08:21:56.300
her silence, something that made me bring the drum camera back online. I squinted against the

08:21:56.300 --> 08:22:02.140
corrosive light. Brought down the brightness until all that remained was a faint whisper of pastels.

08:22:02.940 --> 08:22:06.700
Yes, Bates, stepping off the stairway onto the deck.

08:22:07.580 --> 08:22:11.740
Grab a chair, Cunningham said from his seat in the commons. It's golden oldies time.

08:22:13.020 --> 08:22:19.100
There was something about her. I'm sick of that song, Bates said. We've played it to death.

08:22:20.060 --> 08:22:25.020
Even now, my tools chipped and battered, my perceptions barely more than baseline, I could

08:22:25.020 --> 08:22:31.020
see the change. This torture of prisoners, this assault upon crew, had crossed a line in her head.

08:22:31.740 --> 08:22:36.060
The others wouldn't see it. The lid on her aphact was tight as a boilerplate.

08:22:37.180 --> 08:22:41.820
But even through the dim shadows of my window, the topology glowed around her like neon.

08:22:42.780 --> 08:22:50.220
A man to Bates was no longer merely considering a change of command. Now it was only a matter of when.

08:22:52.860 --> 08:22:59.820
The universe was closed and concentric. My tiny refuge lay in its center. Outside that shell was

08:22:59.820 --> 08:23:05.580
another ruled by a monster, patrolled by his lackeys. Beyond that was another still, containing

08:23:05.580 --> 08:23:10.460
something even more monstrous and incomprehensible, something that might soon devour us all.

08:23:10.460 --> 08:23:17.260
There was nothing else. Earth was a vague hypothesis, irrelevant to this pocket cosmos.

08:23:18.060 --> 08:23:23.900
I saw no place into which it might fit. I stayed in the center of the universe for a long time,

08:23:23.900 --> 08:23:30.780
hiding. I kept the lights off. I didn't eat. I crept from my tent only to piss or shit in the

08:23:30.780 --> 08:23:36.780
cramped head down at Fab, and only when the spine was deserted. A field of painful blisters rose

08:23:36.780 --> 08:23:43.100
across my flesh burned back, as densely packed as kernels on a corn cob. The slightest abrasion

08:23:43.100 --> 08:23:50.380
tore them open. Nobody tapped at my door. Nobody called my name through consensus. I wouldn't

08:23:50.380 --> 08:23:55.420
have answered if they had. Maybe they knew that somehow. Maybe they kept their distance out of

08:23:55.420 --> 08:24:03.020
respect for my privacy and my disgrace. Maybe they just didn't give a shit. I peeked outside now

08:24:03.020 --> 08:24:07.980
and then kept an eye on tactical. I saw Scylla and Corribus climb into the accretion belt and

08:24:07.980 --> 08:24:13.900
return towing captured reaction mass in a great distended mesh between them. I watched our Epsat

08:24:13.900 --> 08:24:19.180
reach its destination in the middle of nowhere. Saw anti-matter's quantum blueprints stream down

08:24:19.180 --> 08:24:25.500
in a thesius buffers. Mass and specs, combined in fab, topped up our reserves. Forged the tools

08:24:25.500 --> 08:24:32.060
that Yucca Sotosti needed for his master plan, whatever that was. Maybe he'd lose. Maybe Rorschach

08:24:32.060 --> 08:24:36.540
would kill us all, but not before it had played with Sotosti the way Sotosti had played with me.

08:24:37.420 --> 08:24:42.940
That would almost make it worthwhile. Or maybe Bates Mutiny would come first and succeed.

08:24:43.660 --> 08:24:47.340
Maybe she would slay the monster and commandeer the ship and take us all to safety.

08:24:48.300 --> 08:24:55.260
But then I remembered. The universe was closed and so very small. There really was nowhere else to go.

08:24:55.260 --> 08:25:02.220
I put my ear to feeds throughout the ship. I heard routine instructions from the predator,

08:25:02.220 --> 08:25:08.140
murmured conversations among the prey. I took in only sound, never sight. A video feed would

08:25:08.140 --> 08:25:13.500
have spilled light into my tent, left me naked and exposed. So I listened in the darkness as

08:25:13.500 --> 08:25:18.700
the others spoke among themselves. It didn't happen often anymore. Perhaps too much had been said

08:25:18.700 --> 08:25:23.740
already. Perhaps there was nothing left to do but mine the countdown. Sometimes hours would pass

08:25:23.740 --> 08:25:30.140
with no more than a cough or grunt. When they did speak they never mentioned my name. Only once did

08:25:30.140 --> 08:25:35.820
I hear any of them even hint at my existence. That was Cunningham talking to Sasha about zombies.

08:25:36.460 --> 08:25:42.300
I heard them in the galley over breakfast, unusually talkative. Sasha hadn't been let out for a while

08:25:42.300 --> 08:25:48.860
and was making up for lost time. Cunningham let her for reasons of his own. Maybe his fears had

08:25:48.940 --> 08:25:55.100
been soothed somehow. Maybe Sotosti had revealed his master plan. Or maybe Cunningham simply craved

08:25:55.100 --> 08:26:01.020
distraction from the imminence of the enemy. It doesn't bug you, Sasha was saying. Thinking that

08:26:01.020 --> 08:26:06.860
your mind, the very thing that makes you, you is nothing but some kind of parasite. Forget about

08:26:06.860 --> 08:26:13.660
minds, he told her. Say you've got a device designed to monitor, oh, cosmic rays, say. What happens

08:26:13.660 --> 08:26:17.740
when you turn its sensor around so it's not pointing at the sky anymore but its own guts?

08:26:18.300 --> 08:26:23.820
He answered himself before she could. It does what it's built to. It measures cosmic rays even

08:26:23.820 --> 08:26:28.540
though it's not looking at them anymore. It parses its own circuitry in terms of cosmic ray

08:26:28.540 --> 08:26:34.060
metaphors because the O's feel right, because they feel natural, because it can't look at things any

08:26:34.060 --> 08:26:39.580
other way. But it's the wrong metaphor, so the system misunderstands everything about itself.

08:26:40.300 --> 08:26:45.660
Maybe that's not a grand and glorious evolutionary leap after all. Maybe it's just a design flaw.

08:26:46.620 --> 08:26:52.380
But you're the biologist. You know mom was right better than anyone. Brain's a big glucose hog,

08:26:52.380 --> 08:26:58.380
everything it does costs through the nose. True enough, Cunningham admitted. So sensience has

08:26:58.380 --> 08:27:03.020
got to be good for something then, because it's expensive, and if it sucks up energy without

08:27:03.020 --> 08:27:09.340
doing anything useful then evolution's gonna weed it out just like that. Maybe it did. He paused

08:27:09.340 --> 08:27:14.780
long enough to chew food or suck smoke. Champanzis are smarter than orangutans, did you know that?

08:27:15.580 --> 08:27:21.820
Higher encephalization quotient. Yet they can't always recognize themselves in a mirror. Orangs

08:27:21.820 --> 08:27:27.340
can. So what's your point, smarter animal, less self-awareness? Champanzis are becoming

08:27:27.340 --> 08:27:33.500
non-santiate? Or they were before we stopped everything in its tracks. So why didn't that

08:27:33.500 --> 08:27:40.460
happen to us? What makes you think it didn't? It was such an obviously stupid question that Sasha

08:27:40.540 --> 08:27:44.300
didn't have an answer for it. I could imagine her gaping in the silence.

08:27:45.180 --> 08:27:49.500
You're not thinking this through, Cunningham said. We're not talking about some kind of zombie

08:27:49.500 --> 08:27:55.100
lurching around with its arms stretched out, spouting mathematical theorems. A smart automaton

08:27:55.100 --> 08:28:00.060
would blend in. It would observe those around it, mimic their behavior, act us like everyone else,

08:28:00.620 --> 08:28:04.780
all the while completely unaware of what it was doing, unaware even of its own existence.

08:28:04.780 --> 08:28:10.700
Why would it bother? What would motivate it? As long as you pull your hand away from an open

08:28:10.700 --> 08:28:15.660
flame, who cares whether you do it because it hurts or because some feedback algorithm says

08:28:15.660 --> 08:28:21.180
withdraw if heat flux succeeds critical T? Natural selection doesn't care about motives.

08:28:21.180 --> 08:28:26.300
If impersonating something increases fitness, then nature will select good impersonators over bad ones.

08:28:26.860 --> 08:28:30.940
Keep it up long enough and no conscious being would be able to pick your zombie out of a crowd.

08:28:31.900 --> 08:28:37.420
Another silence. I could hear him truing through it. It'll even be able to participate in a

08:28:37.420 --> 08:28:41.820
conversation like this one. It could write letters home, impersonate real human feelings

08:28:41.820 --> 08:28:47.340
without having the slightest awareness of its own existence. I don't know, Rob, it just seems...

08:28:48.220 --> 08:28:53.660
Oh, it might not be perfect. It might be a bit redundant or resort to occasional expository

08:28:53.660 --> 08:28:59.580
info dump. But even real people do that, don't they? And eventually there aren't any real people

08:28:59.580 --> 08:29:05.100
left, just robots pretending to give a shit. Perhaps, depends on the population dynamics,

08:29:05.100 --> 08:29:10.620
among other things. But I guess that at least one thing an automaton lacks is empathy. If you

08:29:10.620 --> 08:29:14.620
can't feel, you can't really relate to something that does, even if you act as though you do.

08:29:15.180 --> 08:29:19.500
Which makes it interesting to note how many sociopaths show up in the world's upper echelons,

08:29:19.500 --> 08:29:25.100
hmm? How ruthlessness and bottom line self-interest are so louded up in the stratosphere, while

08:29:25.100 --> 08:29:29.340
anyone showing those straights at ground levels gets carted off into detention with the realists.

08:29:30.060 --> 08:29:36.700
Almost as if society itself is being reshaped from the inside out. Oh come on, society was always

08:29:36.700 --> 08:29:43.900
pretty... Wait, you're saying the world's corporate elite are non-sentient? God no, not nearly. Maybe

08:29:43.900 --> 08:29:49.500
they're just starting down that road, like chimpanzees. Yeah, but sociopaths don't blend in well.

08:29:50.540 --> 08:29:54.460
Maybe the ones that get diagnosed don't, but by definition they're the bottom of the class.

08:29:54.780 --> 08:29:58.780
The others are too smart to get caught, and real automatons would do even better.

08:29:59.340 --> 08:30:03.180
Besides, when you get powerful enough, you don't need to act like other people.

08:30:03.180 --> 08:30:04.860
Other people start acting like you.

08:30:06.220 --> 08:30:12.940
Sasha whistled. Wow, perfect play actor. Or not so perfect. Sound like anyone we know?

08:30:14.540 --> 08:30:17.580
They may have been talking about someone else entirely, I suppose.

08:30:18.300 --> 08:30:23.500
But that was as close as to a direct reference to Siri Keaton that I heard in all my hours on

08:30:23.500 --> 08:30:29.420
the grapevine. Nobody else mentioned me even in passing. That was statistically unlikely,

08:30:29.420 --> 08:30:33.580
given what I just endured in front of them all. Someone should have said something.

08:30:34.220 --> 08:30:39.820
Perhaps Sadastiy had ordered them not to discuss it. I didn't know why, but it was obvious by now

08:30:39.820 --> 08:30:44.780
that the vampire had been orchestrating their interactions with me for some time. Now I was

08:30:44.780 --> 08:30:49.820
in hiding, but he knew I'd listen in at some point. Maybe for some reason he didn't want my

08:30:49.820 --> 08:30:57.580
surveillance contaminated. He could have simply locked me out of consensus. He hadn't, which

08:30:57.580 --> 08:31:05.900
meant he still wanted me in the loop. Zombies, automatons, fucking sentience. For once in your

08:31:05.900 --> 08:31:12.940
god damned life understand something. He'd said that to me, or something had, during the assault.

08:31:13.900 --> 08:31:18.700
Understand that your life depends on it. Almost as if he were doing me a favor.

08:31:19.660 --> 08:31:23.340
Then he'd left me alone, and evidently told the others to do the same.

08:31:24.140 --> 08:31:28.620
Are you listening, Keaton? And he hadn't locked me out of consensus.

08:31:31.180 --> 08:31:34.380
Centuries of naval gazing, millennia of masturbation,

08:31:35.020 --> 08:31:40.700
Plato to Descartes to Dawkins to Ronda, souls and zombie agents in qualia,

08:31:41.500 --> 08:31:48.060
Colmo agrav complexity, consciousness as divine spark, consciousness as electromagnetic field,

08:31:48.780 --> 08:31:52.460
consciousness as functional cluster. I explored it all.

08:31:53.580 --> 08:31:58.700
Wegener thought it was an executive summary. Penrose heard it in the singing of caged electrons.

08:31:59.420 --> 08:32:03.580
Niritrandir said it was a fraud. Kazim called it leakage from a parallel universe.

08:32:04.220 --> 08:32:06.860
Metzinger wouldn't even admit it existed.

08:32:09.260 --> 08:32:13.420
The AIs claimed to have worked it out, then announced they couldn't explain it to us.

08:32:14.060 --> 08:32:17.900
Godel was right after all. No system can fully understand itself.

08:32:19.020 --> 08:32:21.820
Not even the synthesis that said been able to rotate it down.

08:32:22.380 --> 08:32:24.620
The load bearing beams just couldn't take the strain.

08:32:25.500 --> 08:32:27.820
All of them I began to realize had missed the point.

08:32:28.700 --> 08:32:33.420
All those theories, all those drug dreams and experiments and models trying to prove what

08:32:33.420 --> 08:32:39.020
consciousness was, none to explain what it was good for. None needed, obviously.

08:32:39.100 --> 08:32:44.380
Consciousness makes us what we are. It lets us see the beauty and the ugliness.

08:32:44.380 --> 08:32:47.180
It elevates us into the exalted realm of the spiritual.

08:32:47.900 --> 08:32:53.500
Oh, a few outsiders, Dawkins, Coe, the occasional writer of hack work fiction who barely achieved

08:32:53.500 --> 08:32:58.700
obscurity, wondered briefly at the why of it, why not soft computers and no more?

08:32:59.420 --> 08:33:04.220
Why should non-sentient systems be inherently inferior? But they never really raised their

08:33:04.220 --> 08:33:09.100
voices above the crowd. The value of what we are was too trivially self-evident to ever call

08:33:09.100 --> 08:33:15.020
into question. Yet the questions persisted, in the minds of the laureates and the angst of every

08:33:15.020 --> 08:33:21.500
horny 15-year-old on the planet. Am I nothing but sparking chemistry? Am I a magnet in the ether?

08:33:22.380 --> 08:33:27.260
Am I more than my eyes, my ears, my tongue? Am I the little thing behind those things,

08:33:27.260 --> 08:33:33.100
the thing looking out from inside? But who looks out from its eyes? What does it reduce to?

08:33:33.660 --> 08:33:37.740
Who am I? Who am I? Who am I?

08:33:39.820 --> 08:33:44.620
What a stupid fucking question. I could have answered it in a second,

08:33:44.620 --> 08:33:47.260
if Sotosti hadn't forced me to understand it first.

08:33:49.900 --> 08:33:54.540
Not until we are lost do we begin to understand ourselves. Thoreau.

08:33:56.300 --> 08:34:01.500
The shame had scoured me and left me hollow. I didn't care who saw me. I didn't care what

08:34:01.500 --> 08:34:06.460
state they saw me in. For days I'd floated in my tent, curled into a ball, and breathing my own

08:34:06.460 --> 08:34:11.820
stink while the others made whatever preparations my tormentor had laid out for them. Amanda Bates

08:34:11.820 --> 08:34:17.980
was the only one who'd ever even raised a token protest over what Sotosti had done to me. The

08:34:17.980 --> 08:34:22.380
others kept their eyes down and their mouths shut and did what he told them to do, whether from

08:34:22.380 --> 08:34:27.260
fear or indifference I couldn't tell. It was something I'd stopped caring about.

08:34:27.260 --> 08:34:32.940
Sometimes during that span the cast on my arm had cracked open like a shucked clam.

08:34:33.740 --> 08:34:38.380
I upped the lumens long enough to assess its handiwork, my repaired palm itched and glistened in

08:34:38.380 --> 08:34:44.860
twilight, a longer deeper fate line running from heel to web, then back to darkness and the blind,

08:34:44.860 --> 08:34:51.340
unconvincing illusion of safety. Sotosti wanted me to believe. Somehow he must have

08:34:51.340 --> 08:34:56.220
thought the brutalizing and humiliating me would accomplish that, that broken and drained I would

08:34:56.220 --> 08:35:01.660
become an empty vessel to fill as he saw fit. Wasn't it a classic brainwashing technique to

08:35:01.660 --> 08:35:05.820
shatter your victim and then glue the pieces back together in according to specs of your own choosing?

08:35:06.620 --> 08:35:11.180
Maybe he was expecting some kind of Stockholm syndrome to set in, or maybe his actions followed

08:35:11.180 --> 08:35:18.060
some agenda incomprehensible to mere meat. Maybe he'd simply gone insane. He had broken me.

08:35:18.700 --> 08:35:23.500
He had presented his arguments. I had followed his trail of breadcrumbs through consensus,

08:35:23.500 --> 08:35:29.420
through thesias. And now only nine days from graduation I knew one thing for sure. Sotosti

08:35:29.420 --> 08:35:38.140
was wrong. He had to be. I couldn't see how, but I knew just the same. He was wrong. Somehow,

08:35:38.140 --> 08:35:41.820
absurdly, that had become the one thing I did care about.

08:35:44.620 --> 08:35:50.060
No one in the spine, only Cunningham visible in Biomed pouring over digital dissections pretending

08:35:50.060 --> 08:35:55.980
to kill time. I floated above him, my rebuild hand clinging to the top of the nearest stairwell.

08:35:55.980 --> 08:36:01.500
It dragged me in a slow, small circle as the drum turned. Even from up there I could see the tension

08:36:01.500 --> 08:36:06.140
in the set of his shoulders, a system stuck in a holding pattern corroding through the long hours

08:36:06.140 --> 08:36:13.500
as fate advanced through all the time in the world. He looked up. Ah, it lives. I fought the urge to

08:36:13.500 --> 08:36:18.860
retreat. Just a conversation for God's sake. It's just two people talking. People do it all the

08:36:18.860 --> 08:36:26.620
time without your tools. You can do this. You can do this. Just try. So I forced one foot after

08:36:26.620 --> 08:36:31.980
another down the stairs, weight an apprehension rising in lockstep. I tried to read Cunningham's

08:36:31.980 --> 08:36:37.820
topology through the haze. Maybe I saw Fassad, only Micron's deep. Maybe he would welcome

08:36:37.820 --> 08:36:42.540
almost any distraction if he wouldn't admit it. Or maybe I was just imagining it.

08:36:42.780 --> 08:36:52.380
How are you doing? He asked as I reached the deck. I shrugged. And all better I see. No thanks to you.

08:36:53.500 --> 08:37:00.060
I tried to stop that from coming out. Really. Cunningham struck a cigarette. Actually, I was the

08:37:00.060 --> 08:37:07.020
one who fixed you up. You also sat there and watched while he took me apart. I wasn't even there,

08:37:07.100 --> 08:37:13.180
and then after a moment. But you may be right. I might very well have sat in out in any event.

08:37:14.220 --> 08:37:18.860
Amanda and the gang did try to intervene on your behalf from what I hear. Didn't do a lot of good

08:37:18.860 --> 08:37:25.660
for anyone. So you wouldn't even try. Would you if the situation were reversed go unarmed against a

08:37:25.660 --> 08:37:31.500
vampire? I said nothing. Cunningham regarded me for a long moment dragging his cigarette.

08:37:32.300 --> 08:37:40.060
He really got to you, didn't he? He said it last. You're wrong. I said. Am I? I don't play people.

08:37:41.740 --> 08:37:43.420
He seemed to consider the proposition.

08:37:47.260 --> 08:37:53.820
What word would you prefer then? I observe. That you do. Some might even call it surveillance.

08:37:54.700 --> 08:38:01.180
I read body language, hoping that was all he was talking about. It's a matter of degree

08:38:01.180 --> 08:38:06.140
and you know it. Even in a crowd, there's a certain expectation of privacy. People are prepared

08:38:06.140 --> 08:38:11.180
to have their minds read off every twitch of the eyeball. He stabbed at the air with a cigarette.

08:38:11.180 --> 08:38:15.660
And you, you're a shapeshifter. You present a different face to every one of us and all

08:38:15.660 --> 08:38:21.820
rage or none of them is real. The real you, if it even exists, is invisible. Something knotted

08:38:21.820 --> 08:38:27.900
below my diaphragm. Who isn't? Who doesn't try to fit in? Who doesn't want to get along?

08:38:27.900 --> 08:38:32.380
There's nothing malicious about that. I'm a synthesis for God's sake. I never manipulate the

08:38:32.380 --> 08:38:37.900
variables. Well, see, that's the problem. It's not just variables you're manipulating.

08:38:39.340 --> 08:38:45.500
Smoke rived between us. But I guess you can't really understand that, can you?

08:38:45.500 --> 08:38:49.340
He stood and waved a hand. Consensus windows imploded at his side.

08:38:49.980 --> 08:38:53.100
Now your fault, really. You can't blame someone for the way they're wired.

08:38:53.900 --> 08:38:58.620
Give me a fucking break, I snarled. His dead face showed nothing.

08:38:59.500 --> 08:39:03.340
That too had slipped out before I could stop it. And after that came the flood.

08:39:03.980 --> 08:39:10.300
You put so much fucking stock in that. You and your empathy. And maybe I am just some kind of

08:39:10.300 --> 08:39:14.140
imposter. But most people would swear I'd worn their very souls.

08:39:16.780 --> 08:39:22.060
I don't need that shit. You don't have to feel motives to deuce them. It's better if you can't.

08:39:22.060 --> 08:39:25.980
It keeps you... dispassionate. Cunningham smiled faintly.

08:39:26.700 --> 08:39:31.100
Maybe your empathy is just a comforting lie. You ever think that? Maybe you think you know

08:39:31.100 --> 08:39:35.340
how the other person feels, but you're only feeling yourself. Maybe you're even worse than me.

08:39:35.980 --> 08:39:40.780
Or maybe we're all just guessing. Maybe the only difference is that I don't lie to myself about it.

08:39:41.900 --> 08:39:43.980
Do they look the way you imagined? He asked.

08:39:45.260 --> 08:39:50.940
What? What are you talking about? The scramblers. Multi-jointed arms from a central mass.

08:39:51.500 --> 08:39:55.660
Sounds rather similar to me. He'd been into spindle's archives.

08:39:56.620 --> 08:40:04.460
I... not really, I said. The arms are more flexible in real life. More segmented. And I never got a

08:40:04.460 --> 08:40:10.060
good look at the body. What does that have to do with... close though, wasn't it? Same size,

08:40:10.060 --> 08:40:14.700
same general body plan? So what? Why didn't you report it?

08:40:15.660 --> 08:40:18.780
I did. Isaac said it was just TMS from Rorschach.

08:40:19.660 --> 08:40:25.340
You saw them before Rorschach. Or at least, he continued, you saw something that scared you

08:40:25.340 --> 08:40:31.020
into blowing your cover, back when you were spying on Isaac and Michelle. My rage dissipated like

08:40:31.020 --> 08:40:42.780
air through a breach. They... they knew? Only Isaac, I think. And it kept it between it and the logs.

08:40:43.500 --> 08:40:47.420
I suspect you didn't want to interfere with your non-interference protocols,

08:40:47.420 --> 08:40:51.340
although I'd wager that was the last time you ever caught the two of them in private, yes?

08:40:52.620 --> 08:40:53.580
I didn't say anything.

08:40:55.100 --> 08:40:59.900
Did you think the official observer was somehow exempt from observation? Cunningham asked after

08:40:59.900 --> 08:41:08.700
a while. No, I said softly. I suppose not. He nodded. Have you seen any since? I'm not talking

08:41:08.700 --> 08:41:13.820
about the run-of-the-mill TMS hallucinations, I mean scramblers. Have you hallucinated any

08:41:13.820 --> 08:41:19.900
since you actually saw one in the flesh since you knew what it looked like? I thought about it. No.

08:41:21.020 --> 08:41:26.060
He shook his head, some new opinion confirmed. You really are something, Keaton, you know that?

08:41:26.620 --> 08:41:32.140
You don't lie to yourself? Even now, you don't know what you know. What are you talking about?

08:41:33.100 --> 08:41:39.020
You figured it out. From Rorschach's architecture, probably. Form follows function, yes?

08:41:39.980 --> 08:41:44.780
Somehow, you pieced together a fairly good idea of what a scrambler looked like before anyone

08:41:44.780 --> 08:41:49.900
had laid eyes on them. Or at least, he drew a breath, his cigarette flared like an LED.

08:41:50.700 --> 08:41:56.060
Part of you did. Some collection of unconscious modules working their asses off on your behalf,

08:41:56.620 --> 08:42:01.420
but they can't show their work, can they? You don't have conscious access to those levels,

08:42:01.420 --> 08:42:06.300
so one part of the brain tries to tell another any way it can. Passes notes under the table.

08:42:07.420 --> 08:42:11.980
Blind sight, I murmured. You just get a feeling of where to reach.

08:42:13.260 --> 08:42:17.180
More like schizophrenia, except you saw pictures instead of hearing voices.

08:42:18.060 --> 08:42:25.180
You saw pictures, and you still didn't understand. I blinked. But how would I, I mean...

08:42:25.340 --> 08:42:36.220
What did you think, the thesias was haunted, that the scramblers were communing with you telepathically?

08:42:36.860 --> 08:42:42.380
What you do, it matters, Keaton. They told you you were nothing but their stenographer,

08:42:42.380 --> 08:42:46.940
and they hammered all those layers of hands-off passivity into you, but you just had to take

08:42:46.940 --> 08:42:52.220
some initiative anyway, didn't you? And to work out the problem on your own. The only thing you

08:42:52.220 --> 08:42:55.900
couldn't do is admit it to yourself. Cunningham shook his head.

08:42:56.700 --> 08:43:00.940
Siri Keaton. See what they've done to you. He touched his face.

08:43:02.380 --> 08:43:04.940
See what they've done to us all, he whispered.

08:43:06.860 --> 08:43:10.380
I found the gang floating in the center of the darkened observation blister.

08:43:11.100 --> 08:43:15.180
She made room as I joined her, pushed to one side, and anchored herself to a bit of webbing.

08:43:16.060 --> 08:43:19.660
Susan, I asked. I honestly couldn't tell anymore.

08:43:20.540 --> 08:43:24.620
I'll get her, Michelle said. No, that's all right, I'd like to speak to all of...

08:43:25.180 --> 08:43:30.060
But Michelle had already fled. The half-led figure changed before me and said,

08:43:30.780 --> 08:43:33.740
She'd rather be alone right now. I nodded.

08:43:34.540 --> 08:43:40.460
You? James shrugged. I don't mind talking, although I'm surprised you're still doing your reports

08:43:40.460 --> 08:43:47.900
after. I'm... I'm not exactly. This isn't for Earth. I looked around. Not much to see.

08:43:48.780 --> 08:43:53.260
Faraday mesh coated the inside of the dome like a gray film, dimming and graining the view beyond.

08:43:57.420 --> 08:44:03.580
Ben hung like a black maligulancy across half the sky. I could make out a dozen dim contrails

08:44:03.580 --> 08:44:09.420
against vague bands of cloud in red so deep they boarded on black. The sun winked past James'

08:44:09.420 --> 08:44:14.460
shoulder. Our sun, a bright dot that diffracted into faint splintered rainbows when I moved my head.

08:44:15.340 --> 08:44:19.180
That was pretty much it. Starlight didn't penetrate the mesh, nor did the larger,

08:44:19.180 --> 08:44:20.940
dimmer particles of the accretion belt.

08:44:25.740 --> 08:44:29.580
The myriad dim pinpoints of shovel-nosed machinery were lost utterly.

08:44:30.460 --> 08:44:32.540
Which might be a comfort to some, I supposed.

08:44:33.660 --> 08:44:38.620
Shitty view, I remarked. Theseus could have projected crisp, first-person vistas across

08:44:38.620 --> 08:44:40.620
the dome in an instant, more real than real.

08:44:41.500 --> 08:44:48.060
Michelle likes it, James said. The way it feels. And Cruncher likes the diffraction effects. He likes

08:44:48.060 --> 08:44:53.580
interference patterns. We watched nothing for a while, but the dim half-light filtering out

08:44:53.580 --> 08:44:56.860
from the spine. We brushed the edges of James' profile.

08:44:57.980 --> 08:45:02.540
You set me up, I said at last. She looked at me. What do you mean?

08:45:02.700 --> 08:45:09.420
You were talking around me all along, weren't you? All of you. You didn't bring me in until I'd been,

08:45:09.980 --> 08:45:15.340
how would she put it? Preconditioned. The whole thing was planned to throw me off balance.

08:45:15.980 --> 08:45:19.020
And then Sadastia attacks me out of nowhere, and...

08:45:19.980 --> 08:45:22.620
We didn't know about that, until the alarm went off.

08:45:23.420 --> 08:45:28.780
Alarm? When he changed the gas mix, you must have heard it, isn't that why you were there?

08:45:29.740 --> 08:45:35.180
He called me to his tent. He told me to watch. She regarded me from a face full of shadow.

08:45:35.820 --> 08:45:40.380
You didn't try to stop him? I couldn't answer the accusation in her voice.

08:45:41.020 --> 08:45:48.220
I just observed, I said weakly. I thought you were trying to stop him from, she shook her head.

08:45:48.860 --> 08:45:54.620
That's why I thought he was attacking you. You're saying that wasn't an act? You weren't in on it?

08:45:55.340 --> 08:45:58.220
I didn't believe it. But I could tell she did.

08:45:59.580 --> 08:46:02.940
I thought you were trying to protect them. She snorted a stoff,

08:46:02.940 --> 08:46:07.260
humorless laugh at her own mistake and looked away. I guess I should have known better.

08:46:08.940 --> 08:46:14.300
She should have. She should have known that taking orders is one thing. Taking sides would have done

08:46:14.300 --> 08:46:20.380
nothing but compromise my integrity. And I should have been used to it by now. I forged on.

08:46:21.260 --> 08:46:27.980
It was some kind of object lesson. A tutorial. You can't torture the non-santiate or something,

08:46:27.980 --> 08:46:35.660
and I heard you, Susan. It wasn't news to you. It wasn't news to anyone except me, and you hid it

08:46:35.660 --> 08:46:42.620
from me. You all did. You and your gang and Amanda too. You've been hashing this out for days,

08:46:42.620 --> 08:46:47.340
and you went out of your way to cover it up. How did I miss it? How did I miss it?

08:46:47.980 --> 08:46:52.060
You could have told us not to discuss it with you, Susan admitted.

08:46:52.940 --> 08:46:58.780
Why? This is exactly the kind of thing I'm out here for. He said you'd resist,

08:46:59.420 --> 08:47:04.620
unless it was handled properly. Handled? Susan, he assaulted me. You saw what he...

08:47:05.340 --> 08:47:10.700
We didn't know he was going to do that. None of us did. And he did it why? To win an argument?

08:47:11.500 --> 08:47:17.420
That's what he says. Do you believe him? Probably. After a moment she shrugged.

08:47:18.060 --> 08:47:21.180
Who knows? He's a vampire. He's... opaque.

08:47:22.940 --> 08:47:27.260
But his record, I mean... I mean he's never resorted to overt violence before.

08:47:28.060 --> 08:47:33.340
She shook her head. Why should he? He doesn't have to convince the rest of us of anything.

08:47:33.340 --> 08:47:40.460
We have to follow his orders regardless. So do I, I reminded her. He's not trying to convince you,

08:47:40.540 --> 08:47:49.900
Siri. Ah. I was only a conduit after all. Sadastye hadn't been making his case to me at all.

08:47:49.900 --> 08:47:54.460
He'd been making it through me and... and he was planning for a second round.

08:47:55.420 --> 08:47:59.260
Why go to such extremes to present a case to Earth if Earth was irrelevant?

08:48:00.060 --> 08:48:05.340
Sadastye didn't expect the game to end out here. He expected Earth to do something in light of his

08:48:06.060 --> 08:48:12.140
perspective. But what difference does it make? I wondered aloud. She looked at me.

08:48:16.140 --> 08:48:21.260
Even if he's right, how does it change anything? How does this, I raised my repaired hand,

08:48:21.820 --> 08:48:26.620
change anything? Scrambleers are intelligent whether they're sentient or not. They're a

08:48:26.620 --> 08:48:32.380
potential threat either way. We still don't know. So what difference does it make? Why did he do this

08:48:32.380 --> 08:48:39.420
to me? How does it matter? Susan raised her face to Big Ben and didn't answer. Sasha returned to

08:48:39.420 --> 08:48:46.620
face me and tried to. It matters, she said, because it means we attacked them before Thesias was

08:48:46.620 --> 08:48:54.700
launched. Before firefall even. We attacked the... you don't get it do you? You don't? Sasha snorted

08:48:54.700 --> 08:49:00.540
softly. If that isn't the fucking funniest thing I've heard in my whole short life. She leaned

08:49:00.540 --> 08:49:06.380
forward bright-eyed. Imagine you're a scrambler and you encounter a human signal for the very first

08:49:06.380 --> 08:49:13.660
time. Her stare was almost predatory. I resisted the urge to back away. It should be so easy for

08:49:13.660 --> 08:49:19.660
you, Keaton. It should be the easiest gig you've ever had. Aren't you the user interface? Aren't you

08:49:19.660 --> 08:49:25.020
the Chinese room? Aren't you the one who never has to look inside, never has to walk a mile in

08:49:25.020 --> 08:49:30.220
anyone's shoes because you figure everything out from their surfaces? She stared at Ben's

08:49:30.220 --> 08:49:36.460
dark smoldering disc. Well, there's your dream date. There's a whole race of nothing but surfaces.

08:49:37.020 --> 08:49:42.460
There's no inside to figure out. All the rules are right up front. So go to work, Siri Keaton.

08:49:43.260 --> 08:49:50.140
Make us proud. There was no contempt in Sasha's voice, no disdain. There wasn't even anger,

08:49:50.140 --> 08:49:55.420
not in her voice, not in her eyes. There was pleading. There were tears.

08:49:57.020 --> 08:50:03.740
Imagine you're a scrambler. She whispered again as they floated like tiny, perfect beads before her

08:50:03.740 --> 08:50:12.380
face. Imagine you're a scrambler. Imagine you have intellect but no insight, agendas but no

08:50:12.380 --> 08:50:18.700
awareness. Your circuitry hums with strategies for survival and persistence, flexible, intelligent,

08:50:18.700 --> 08:50:25.180
even technological, but no other circuitry monitors it. You can think of anything, yet are

08:50:25.180 --> 08:50:31.500
conscious of nothing. You can't imagine such a being, can you? The term being doesn't even seem to

08:50:31.500 --> 08:50:39.260
apply in some fundamental way you can't quite put your finger on. Try. Imagine that you encounter a

08:50:39.260 --> 08:50:45.260
signal. It is structured and dense with information. It meets all the criteria of an intelligent

08:50:45.260 --> 08:50:51.260
transmission. Evolution and sentience offer a wide variety of paths to follow, branch points in

08:50:51.260 --> 08:50:56.940
the flow charts that handle such input. Sometimes these signals come from cons-pacivics who have

08:50:56.940 --> 08:51:01.420
useful information to share, whose lives you'll defend according to the rules of kin selection.

08:51:02.380 --> 08:51:06.540
Sometimes they come from competitors or predators or other inimical entities that

08:51:06.540 --> 08:51:11.820
must be avoided or destroyed. In those cases, the information may prove of significant tactical

08:51:11.820 --> 08:51:18.300
value. Some signals may even arise from entities which, while not kin, can still serve as allies

08:51:18.300 --> 08:51:23.820
or symbionts in mutually beneficial pursuits. You can derive appropriate responses for any of

08:51:23.820 --> 08:51:31.580
these eventualities and many others. You decode the signals and stumble. I had a great time. I

08:51:31.580 --> 08:51:35.980
really enjoyed him. Even if he cost twice as much as any other hooker in the dome.

08:51:36.940 --> 08:51:43.420
To fully appreciate Keezie's quartet, they hate us for our freedom. Pay attention now.

08:51:44.380 --> 08:51:51.820
Understand. There are no meaningful translations for these terms. They're needlessly recursive.

08:51:52.860 --> 08:51:57.900
They contain no usable intelligence, yet they're structured intelligently. There is no chance

08:51:57.900 --> 08:52:03.580
they could have arisen by chance. The only explanation is that something has coded nonsense

08:52:03.580 --> 08:52:08.780
in a way that poses as a useful message, only after wasting time and effort does the deception

08:52:08.780 --> 08:52:14.940
become apparent. The signal functions to consume the resources of a recipient for zero payoff and

08:52:14.940 --> 08:52:23.420
reduced fitness. The signal is a virus. Viruses do not arise from kin, symbionts, or other allies.

08:52:24.300 --> 08:52:28.220
The signal is an attack. And it's coming from right about there.

08:52:29.180 --> 08:52:35.660
Now you get it, Sasha said. I shook my head trying to wrap it around that insane, impossible

08:52:35.660 --> 08:52:44.060
conclusion. They're not even hostile. Not even capable of hostility. Just so profoundly alien,

08:52:44.060 --> 08:52:49.980
they couldn't help but treat human language itself as a form of combat. How do you say we come in

08:52:49.980 --> 08:52:56.300
peace when the very words are an act of war? That's why they won't talk to us, I realized.

08:52:58.620 --> 08:53:05.100
Only if you could write. He may not be. It was James again, still quietly resisting,

08:53:05.100 --> 08:53:08.620
still unwilling to concede a point that even her other selves had accepted.

08:53:09.740 --> 08:53:15.980
I could see why. Because if Sadastiy was right, scramblers were the norm. Evolution across the

08:53:15.980 --> 08:53:21.900
universe was nothing but endless proliferation of automatic, organized complexity. A vast air

08:53:21.900 --> 08:53:26.300
interring machine full of self-replicating machinery forever unaware of its own existence.

08:53:27.100 --> 08:53:32.540
And we, we were the flukes and the fossils. We were the flightless birds

08:53:32.540 --> 08:53:37.100
louding our own mastery over some remote island while serpents and carnivores washed up on our

08:53:37.100 --> 08:53:43.580
shores. Susan James could not bring herself to concede that point, because Susan James,

08:53:43.580 --> 08:53:47.500
her multiple lives built on the faith that communication resolves all conflict,

08:53:48.060 --> 08:53:54.220
would then be forced to admit the lie. If Sadastiy was right, there was no hope of reconciliation.

08:53:54.780 --> 08:54:00.620
A memory rose into my mind and stuck there. A man in motion, head bent, mouth twisted,

08:54:00.620 --> 08:54:06.700
and unrelenting grimace. His eyes focused on one foot than the other. His legs moved stiffly,

08:54:06.700 --> 08:54:12.860
carefully. His arms moved not at all. He lurched like a zombie in the thrall to rigor mortis.

08:54:14.060 --> 08:54:20.300
I knew what it was. Proprio receptive polyneuropathy, a case study I'd encountered in consensus

08:54:20.300 --> 08:54:25.820
back before spindle had died. This was what Pag had once compared me to, a man who had lost his

08:54:25.820 --> 08:54:31.820
mind. Only self-awareness remained. Deprived of the unconscious sense and subroutines he had

08:54:31.820 --> 08:54:37.980
always taken for granted, he had to focus on each and every step across the room. His body no longer

08:54:37.980 --> 08:54:44.140
knew where its limbs were or what they were doing. To move it all to even remain upright, he had to

08:54:45.100 --> 08:54:52.220
bear constant witness. There had been no sound when I played the file. There was none now in its

08:54:52.220 --> 08:54:59.100
recollection. But I swore I could feel Sadastiy of my shoulder peering into my memories. I swore I

08:54:59.100 --> 08:55:04.940
heard him speak in my mind like a schizophrenic hallucination. This is the best that consciousness

08:55:05.020 --> 08:55:06.700
can do when left on its own.

08:55:07.820 --> 08:55:09.420
Right answer, I murmured.

08:55:10.220 --> 08:55:10.940
Wrong question.

08:55:11.820 --> 08:55:12.140
What?

08:55:13.260 --> 08:55:16.540
Stretch, remember? When you asked it which objects were in the window?

08:55:17.580 --> 08:55:20.780
And it missed the scrambler. James nodded. So?

08:55:21.820 --> 08:55:27.420
It didn't miss the scrambler. You thought you were asking about the things it saw, things that existed

08:55:27.420 --> 08:55:33.740
on the board. Stretch thought you were asking about the things it was aware of, she finished.

08:55:34.940 --> 08:55:40.220
He's right, I whispered. Oh god, I think he's right.

08:55:41.340 --> 08:55:45.660
Hey, James said, did you see that? But I never saw what she was pointing at.

08:55:46.540 --> 08:55:52.780
Theseus slammed its eyelids shut and started howling. Graduation came nine days early.

08:55:55.580 --> 08:56:02.140
Graduation came nine days early. We didn't see the shot. Whatever gunport Rorschach had opened

08:56:02.140 --> 08:56:07.180
was precisely eclipsed on three fronts. The lab hab hit it from Theseus and two

08:56:07.180 --> 08:56:11.020
gnarled extrusions of the artifact itself hit it from each of the gun emplacements.

08:56:11.900 --> 08:56:16.540
A bolus of incendiary plasma shot from that blind spot like a thrown punch,

08:56:16.540 --> 08:56:19.820
it had split the inflatable wide open before the first alarm went up.

08:56:20.780 --> 08:56:25.100
Alarms chased us aft. We launched ourselves down the spine through the bridge,

08:56:25.100 --> 08:56:29.260
through the crypt, past hatches and crawl spaces, fleeing the surface for any refuge

08:56:29.340 --> 08:56:35.660
with more than a hand's breadth between skin and sky. Burrowing. Consensus followed us back,

08:56:35.660 --> 08:56:40.540
its windows warping and sliding across struts and conduits and the concave tunnel of the spine

08:56:40.540 --> 08:56:46.300
itself. I paid no attention until we were back in the drum, deep in Theseus' belly, where we could

08:56:46.300 --> 08:56:53.020
pretend we were saver. Down on the turning deck, Bates erupted from the head, tactical windows swirling

08:56:53.020 --> 08:56:58.860
like ballroom dancers around her. Our own window came to rest on the commons bulkhead. The hab

08:56:58.860 --> 08:57:04.140
expanded across that display like cheap optical illusion, both swelling and shrinking in our

08:57:04.140 --> 08:57:09.420
sights, the smooth surface billowing towards us while collapsing in on itself. It took me a moment

08:57:09.420 --> 08:57:14.700
to reconcile the contradiction. Something had kicked the hab hard from its far side,

08:57:14.700 --> 08:57:20.300
sent it careening towards us in a slow majestic tumble. Something had opened the hab, spilled

08:57:20.300 --> 08:57:24.300
its atmosphere and left its elastic skin drawing in on itself like a deflating balloon.

08:57:25.180 --> 08:57:30.700
The impact sight swung into view as we watched, a scorched flaccid mouth trailing tenuous wisps

08:57:30.700 --> 08:57:36.780
of frozen spittle. Our guns were firing. They shot non-conducting slugs that would not be turned

08:57:36.780 --> 08:57:41.740
or side by electromagnetic trickery, invisibly dark and distant to human eyes, but I saw them

08:57:41.740 --> 08:57:47.340
through the tactical crosshairs of the firing robots, watched them sew twin, dotted black bodies

08:57:47.340 --> 08:57:53.420
arcs across the heavens. The streams converged as the guns tracked their targets, closed onto a

08:57:53.420 --> 08:57:57.980
tenuette throwing stars fleeing, spread eagle through the void, their faces turned to Rorschach

08:57:57.980 --> 08:58:03.020
like flowers in the sun. The guns cut them to pieces before they'd even made it halfway.

08:58:04.540 --> 08:58:09.020
But those shredded pieces kept falling and suddenly the ground beneath was alive with motion.

08:58:09.820 --> 08:58:15.100
I zoomed the view, scramblers surged across Rorschach's hull like an orgy of snakes naked to

08:58:15.100 --> 08:58:22.140
space. Some linked arms, one to another to another, built squirming, vertebral daisy chains anchored

08:58:22.140 --> 08:58:28.060
at one end. They lifted from the hull, waved through the radioactive vacuum like fronds of

08:58:28.060 --> 08:58:36.540
articulated kelp, reaching, grasping. Neither baits nor her machines were stupid. They targeted the

08:58:36.540 --> 08:58:41.420
interlinked scramblers as ruthlessly as they'd gone after the SKPs with a much higher total score,

08:58:41.980 --> 08:58:46.140
but there were simply too many targets, too many fragments snatched and passing.

08:58:47.100 --> 08:58:50.780
Twice I saw dismembered bits of stretch and clench caught by their brethren.

08:58:51.740 --> 08:58:55.500
The ruptured hab loomed across consensus like a great torn leukocyte.

08:58:56.220 --> 08:59:01.100
Another alarm buzzed somewhere nearby, proximity alert. Cunningham shot into the

08:59:01.100 --> 08:59:06.140
drum from somewhere astern, bounced off a cluster of pipes and conduits, grabbed for support.

08:59:06.700 --> 08:59:09.980
Holy shit! We are leaving, aren't we, Amanda?

08:59:10.860 --> 08:59:13.100
No, Sarashti answered from everywhere.

08:59:13.980 --> 08:59:17.500
What does it fucking take, I caught myself.

08:59:18.300 --> 08:59:20.140
Amanda, what if it fires on the ship?

08:59:20.940 --> 08:59:23.900
It won't. She didn't take her eyes from her windows.

08:59:24.460 --> 08:59:29.740
How do you... it can't. If it spring-loaded any more firepower we'd have seen a change in

08:59:29.740 --> 08:59:35.820
thermal and microalimetry. A false-color landscape rotated between us. Its latitude measured in time.

08:59:35.900 --> 08:59:41.500
Its longitudes in delta mass. Kilitons rose from that terrain like a red range of red mountains.

08:59:42.140 --> 08:59:48.060
Huh. Came in just under the noise limp. Sarashti cut her off. Robert, Susan, EVA.

08:59:49.260 --> 08:59:50.140
James blanched.

08:59:50.700 --> 08:59:52.780
What? Cunningham cried.

08:59:54.620 --> 08:59:58.540
Lab modules about to impact, vampires said. Salvage the samples.

08:59:59.100 --> 09:00:02.460
Now. He killed the channel before anyone could argue.

09:00:03.420 --> 09:00:07.900
But Cunningham wasn't about to argue. He'd just seen our death sentence commuted.

09:00:07.900 --> 09:00:11.340
Robert Sarashti cared about retrieving biopsy samples if he didn't think we

09:00:11.340 --> 09:00:15.420
stood a chance of escaping with them. The biologist steadied himself,

09:00:15.420 --> 09:00:16.860
braced towards the forward hatch.

09:00:17.500 --> 09:00:19.980
I'm there, he said, shooting into the bow.

09:00:21.340 --> 09:00:24.220
I had to admit it. Sarashti's psychology was getting better.

09:00:25.180 --> 09:00:30.140
It wasn't working on James, though, or Michelle, or... I couldn't quite tell who was on top.

09:00:30.940 --> 09:00:34.300
I can't go out there, Ciri. It's... I can't go out there.

09:00:35.260 --> 09:00:37.500
Just observe. Don't interfere.

09:00:38.620 --> 09:00:43.020
The ruptured inflatable collided impotently to starboard and flattened itself against the carapace.

09:00:43.900 --> 09:00:49.580
We felt nothing. Far away and far too near, the legions thinned across the workshop's surface.

09:00:50.220 --> 09:00:54.300
They disappeared through mouths that puckered and dilated and magically closed again in the

09:00:54.300 --> 09:00:58.540
artifact's hull. The emplacements fired passionlessly at those who remained.

09:00:59.500 --> 09:01:03.740
Observe. The gang of four strobed at my side, scared to death.

09:01:04.700 --> 09:01:05.740
Don't interfere.

09:01:06.620 --> 09:01:09.580
It's okay, I said. I'll go.

09:01:11.420 --> 09:01:14.780
The open airlock was like a dimple in the face of an endless cliff.

09:01:15.340 --> 09:01:17.740
I looked out from that indentation into the abyss.

09:01:18.940 --> 09:01:22.300
This side of Theezy is faced away from Big Ben, away from the enemy.

09:01:22.940 --> 09:01:28.860
Thee is still unsettling enough. An endless panorama of distant stars, hard and cold and unwinking.

09:01:29.660 --> 09:01:33.740
A single marginally brighter one shined yellow, still so very far away.

09:01:34.620 --> 09:01:38.940
Any scamped comfort I might have taken from that sight was lost when the sun went out for the

09:01:38.940 --> 09:01:45.420
briefest instant. A tumbling piece of rock, perhaps. Or one of Rorschach's shovel-nosed entourage.

09:01:46.380 --> 09:01:48.540
One step and I might never stop falling.

09:01:49.020 --> 09:01:53.900
But I didn't step and I didn't fall. I squeezed my pistol, jetted gently through the opening and

09:01:53.900 --> 09:01:59.980
turned. Theezy's carapace curved away from me in all directions. Towards the prow, the sealed

09:01:59.980 --> 09:02:05.580
observation blister rose above the horizon like a gun-metal sunrise. Further aft, a tattered

09:02:05.580 --> 09:02:11.260
snowdrift peeked across the hull, the edge of the broken lab-hab. And past it all, close enough

09:02:11.260 --> 09:02:17.340
to touch, the endless dark cloudscape of Big Ben. A great, roiling wall extending to some flat

09:02:18.300 --> 09:02:23.820
distant horizon I could barely grasp even in theory. When I focused, it was dark and endless

09:02:23.820 --> 09:02:28.780
shades of gray, but dim, sullen redness teased the corner of my eye when I looked away.

09:02:29.820 --> 09:02:35.340
Robert? I brought Cunningham's suit feed to my hood. A craggy, motionless ice field thrown into

09:02:35.340 --> 09:02:39.660
high contrast by the light of his helmet. Interference from Rorschach's magnetosphere

09:02:39.660 --> 09:02:45.580
washed over the image in waves. You there? Pop some crackles. The sound of breath and

09:02:45.580 --> 09:02:56.060
mumbling against electrical hum. 4.3, 4.0, 3.8. Robert? 3.... Shit. What are you doing out here,

09:02:56.060 --> 09:03:02.860
Keaton? Where's the gang? I came instead. Another squeeze of the trigger and I was coasting towards

09:03:02.860 --> 09:03:08.540
the snowscape. Theezy's convex hull rolled past just within reach to give you a hand.

09:03:09.260 --> 09:03:14.460
Let's move it then, shall we? He was passing through a crevice, a scorched and jagged tear in

09:03:14.460 --> 09:03:19.900
the fabric that folded back at his touch. Struts, broken panels, dead robot arms tangled

09:03:19.900 --> 09:03:24.860
through the interior of the ice cave like glacial debris. Their outlines writhed with static.

09:03:24.860 --> 09:03:29.580
Their shadows leaped and stretched like living things in the sweep of his headlight. I'm almost...

09:03:30.700 --> 09:03:35.100
something that wasn't static moved in his headlight. Something uncoiled, just at the

09:03:35.100 --> 09:03:41.500
edge of the camera's view. The feed died. Suddenly Bates and Siddosti were shouting in my helmet.

09:03:41.580 --> 09:03:46.780
I tried to break. My stupid useless legs kicked against vacuum, obeying some ancient brainstem

09:03:46.780 --> 09:03:51.500
override from a time when all monsters were earthbound. But by the time I remembered to use

09:03:51.500 --> 09:03:57.100
my trigger finger, the labhab was already looming before me. Rorschach reared up behind it in the

09:03:57.100 --> 09:04:03.340
near distance, vast and malign. Dim green auroras rived across the surface like sheet lightning.

09:04:04.060 --> 09:04:09.900
Mouths opened and closed by the hundreds. Viscous's bubbling volcanic mud. Any one of them large

09:04:09.900 --> 09:04:15.100
enough to swallow thesy as whole. I barely noticed the flicker of motion just ahead of me,

09:04:15.100 --> 09:04:20.220
the silent eruption of dark mass and the collapsed inflatable. By the time Cunningham caught my eye,

09:04:20.220 --> 09:04:25.340
he was already on his way, backlit against the ghastly corpse light flickering on Rorschach's skin.

09:04:26.540 --> 09:04:32.060
I thought I saw him waving, but I was wrong. It was the only the scrambler wrapped around his

09:04:32.060 --> 09:04:36.540
body like a desperate lover, moving his arm back and forth while it ran the thrust pistol

09:04:36.620 --> 09:04:41.900
to ever do his waste. Bye bye, that arm seemed to say, and fuck you, Keaton.

09:04:43.260 --> 09:04:46.700
I watched for what seemed like forever, but no other part of him moved at all.

09:04:47.740 --> 09:04:54.140
Voices shouting ordered me back inside. I hardly heard them. I was too dumbfounded by the basic

09:04:54.140 --> 09:04:59.980
math, trying to make sense of the simplest subtraction. Two scramblers, stretch and clench,

09:05:00.700 --> 09:05:03.340
both accounted for, shot the pieces before my eyes.

09:05:04.540 --> 09:05:07.020
Keaton, do you read? Get back here, acknowledge.

09:05:07.740 --> 09:05:15.500
I-it can't be, I heard myself say. There were only two. Return to the ship immediately, acknowledge.

09:05:16.220 --> 09:05:22.940
I-acknowledged. Rorschach's mouth snapped shut at once as though holding a deep breath.

09:05:23.500 --> 09:05:27.500
The artifact began to turn ponderously, a continent changing course.

09:05:28.220 --> 09:05:31.980
It receded slowly at first, picking up speed, turning tail and running.

09:05:32.780 --> 09:05:36.380
How odd, I thought. Maybe it's more afraid than we are.

09:05:37.900 --> 09:05:43.180
But then, Rorschach blew us a kiss. I saw it burst from deep within the forest,

09:05:43.180 --> 09:05:47.900
ethereal and incandescent. It shot across the heavens and splashed against the small,

09:05:47.900 --> 09:05:51.260
of the easiest back, making it complete an utter fool of a man debates.

09:05:52.140 --> 09:05:56.860
The skin of our ship flowed there and opened like a mouth, and congealed in a soundless frozen

09:05:56.860 --> 09:06:06.220
scream. You cannot prevent and prepare for war at the same time. Einstein.

09:06:07.580 --> 09:06:11.500
I have no idea whether the scrambler made it back home with its hard won prize.

09:06:12.220 --> 09:06:16.700
There was so much lost distance to make up, even if the emplacements didn't pick it off on root.

09:06:17.420 --> 09:06:22.220
Cunningham's pistol might have run out of fuel. And who knew how long those creatures could survive

09:06:22.220 --> 09:06:27.020
in vacuum anyway. Maybe there had been no real hope of success. Maybe that scrambler was dead

09:06:27.020 --> 09:06:33.340
from the moment it had been gambled on staying behind. I never found out. It had dwindled and

09:06:33.340 --> 09:06:37.740
vanished from my sight long before Rorschach dove beneath the clouds and disappeared in turn.

09:06:38.860 --> 09:06:43.420
There had always been three, of course. Stretch and clench, and the half-forgotten,

09:06:43.420 --> 09:06:46.460
unmicrowaved remains of a scrambler killed by an uppity grunt,

09:06:47.020 --> 09:06:51.020
kept on ice next to his living brethren with an easy reach of Cunningham's telops.

09:06:51.900 --> 09:06:55.260
I tried to dredge half-glimpse details of memory after the fact.

09:06:55.980 --> 09:07:00.380
Had both of those escapees been spheres, or had one been flattened along one axis?

09:07:01.100 --> 09:07:05.580
Had they thrashed, waved their limbs the way some panicky human might with no ground beneath them?

09:07:06.220 --> 09:07:10.620
Or had one, perhaps, coasted lifeless and ballistic until our guns destroyed the evidence?

09:07:11.820 --> 09:07:16.220
At this point, it didn't really matter. What mattered was that long last everyone was on the

09:07:16.220 --> 09:07:23.500
same page. Blood had been drawn, war-declared, and theseus was paralyzed from the waist down.

09:07:24.940 --> 09:07:28.540
Worschach's parting shot had punched through the carapace at the base of the spine.

09:07:29.180 --> 09:07:33.900
It had just missed the ram scoop in the telematter assembly. It spent so many jewels burning through

09:07:33.900 --> 09:07:39.100
the carapace, but, barring some temporary pulse effects, it left all critical systems pretty

09:07:39.100 --> 09:07:44.620
much operational. All it had done was weaken theseus backbone enough to make it snap in two

09:07:44.620 --> 09:07:49.180
should we ever burn hard enough to break orbit. The ship would be able to repair that damage,

09:07:49.180 --> 09:07:53.980
but not in time. If it had been luck, it would have been remarkable.

09:07:55.340 --> 09:08:00.620
And now, its quarry disabled, Worschach, had vanished. It had everything it needed from us,

09:08:00.620 --> 09:08:06.540
for the moment at least. It had information, all the experiences and insights encoded in the salvaged

09:08:06.540 --> 09:08:12.460
limbs of its martyred spies. If stretch or clenches gamble had paid off, it even had a specimen of its

09:08:12.460 --> 09:08:17.820
own now, which all things considered we could hardly begrudge it. And so now it lurked invisibly

09:08:17.820 --> 09:08:25.420
in the depths, resting perhaps. Recharging. But it would be back. Theseus lost weight for the

09:08:25.420 --> 09:08:30.460
final round. We shut down the drum in a token attempt to reduce our vulnerable allotment of

09:08:30.460 --> 09:08:35.340
moving parts. The gang of four, uncommanded, unneeded, the very reason for their existence

09:08:35.340 --> 09:08:41.580
ripped away, retreated into some inner dialogue to which other flesh was unwelcome. She floated in

09:08:41.580 --> 09:08:47.100
the observatory, her eyes closed as tightly as the littered lids around her. I could not tell

09:08:47.100 --> 09:08:59.660
who was in control. I guessed. Michelle? Siri? Susan? Just go. Bates floated near the floor of the drum.

09:08:59.660 --> 09:09:02.860
Windows arrayed externally across bulkhead and conference table.

09:09:03.820 --> 09:09:13.580
What can I do? I asked. She didn't look up. Nothing. So I watched. Bates counted skimmers in one window,

09:09:13.580 --> 09:09:18.540
mass, inertia, any of the dust and variables that would prove far too constant should any of those

09:09:18.540 --> 09:09:24.220
shovel-nosed missiles come at our throat. They had finally noticed us. The chaotic electron dance

09:09:24.220 --> 09:09:29.020
was shifting now, hundreds of thousands of colossal sledgehammers in sudden flux,

09:09:29.100 --> 09:09:33.420
reweaving into some ominous dynamic that hadn't yet settled into anything we could predict.

09:09:34.620 --> 09:09:39.740
In another window, Rorschach's vanishing act replayed on Endless Loop, a radar image receding

09:09:39.740 --> 09:09:45.500
deep into the maelstrom, fading beneath gaseous teratons of radio static. It might still be in

09:09:45.500 --> 09:09:50.940
orbit of sorts. Judging by that last glimpse trajectory, Rorschach might be well swinging

09:09:50.940 --> 09:09:55.900
around Ben's core now, passing through crushed layers of methadium and oxide that would flatten

09:09:55.900 --> 09:10:01.580
the thesis into smoke. Maybe it didn't even stop there. Maybe Rorschach could pass unharmed even

09:10:01.580 --> 09:10:07.260
through the vast or deeper pressures that made iron and hydrogen run liquid. We didn't know.

09:10:08.060 --> 09:10:12.060
We only knew that it would be back in a little under two hours, assuming it maintained its

09:10:12.060 --> 09:10:18.380
trajectory and survived the depths. And of course, it would survive. You can't kill the thing under

09:10:18.380 --> 09:10:23.260
the bed. You can only keep it outside the covers. And only for a while.

09:10:24.940 --> 09:10:30.540
A thumbnail inset caught my eye with a flash of color. At my command it grew into a swirling soap

09:10:30.540 --> 09:10:37.100
bubble and, congressly beautiful, a blue-shifted, coruscating rainbow of blown glass. I didn't

09:10:37.100 --> 09:10:42.540
recognize it for a moment. Big Ben rendered in some prismatic false color enhance I'd never seen

09:10:42.540 --> 09:10:50.940
before. I'd grunted softly. Bates looked up. Oh, beautiful, isn't it? What's the spectrum?

09:10:51.900 --> 09:10:58.380
Long wave stuff. Visible red, infra, down aways, good for heat traces. Visible red?

09:10:59.260 --> 09:11:04.860
There wasn't any to speak of. Mostly cool plasma fractals and a hundred shades of jade and sapphire.

09:11:05.900 --> 09:11:10.940
Quadrochromatic pallet, Bates told me. Like what a cat might see, or a vampire.

09:11:11.900 --> 09:11:14.380
She managed a half-hearted wave at the rainbow bubble.

09:11:15.020 --> 09:11:20.300
Sotosti sees something like this every time he looks outside, if he ever looks outside.

09:11:21.740 --> 09:11:26.940
You'd think he'd have mentioned it, I remember. It was gorgeous, a holographic ornament.

09:11:27.580 --> 09:11:30.540
Perhaps even Rorschach might be a work of art to rise like these.

09:11:31.740 --> 09:11:35.660
I don't think they parse sight like we do. Bates open another window.

09:11:36.300 --> 09:11:39.260
mundane graphs and contour plots sprang from the table.

09:11:39.900 --> 09:11:43.980
They don't even go to heaven from what I hear. The art doesn't work on them. They

09:11:44.700 --> 09:11:46.220
see the pixels or something.

09:11:47.420 --> 09:11:53.180
What if he's right? I asked. I told myself that I was only looking for a tactical assessment,

09:11:53.180 --> 09:11:57.980
an official opinion for the official record. But my words came out doubtful and frightened.

09:11:59.420 --> 09:12:04.380
She paused. For a moment I wondered if she too had finally lost patience with the sight of me.

09:12:05.020 --> 09:12:08.220
But she only looked up and stared off into some enclosed distance.

09:12:09.340 --> 09:12:15.020
What if he's right? She repeated and pondered the question that lay beneath. What can we do?

09:12:18.780 --> 09:12:23.900
We could engineer ourselves back into non-sentience, perhaps. Might improve our odds in the long run.

09:12:24.780 --> 09:12:28.220
She looked at me, a rueful sort of half-smile at the corner of her mouth.

09:12:28.940 --> 09:12:32.860
But I guess that wouldn't be much of a win, would it? What's the difference between being

09:12:32.860 --> 09:12:37.100
dead and just not knowing you're alive? I finally saw it.

09:12:38.220 --> 09:12:42.860
How long would it take an enemy tactician to discern Bates' mind behind the actions of her

09:12:42.860 --> 09:12:48.940
troops on the battlefield? How long before the obvious logic came clear? In any combat situation,

09:12:48.940 --> 09:12:53.900
this woman would naturally draw the greatest amount of enemy fire, take off the head, kill the body.

09:12:54.620 --> 09:12:59.660
But Amanda Bates wasn't just a head. She was a bottleneck, and her body would not suffer a

09:12:59.660 --> 09:13:05.660
decapitation strike. Her death would only let her troops off the leash. How much more deadly

09:13:05.660 --> 09:13:09.740
would those grunts be once every battlefield reflex didn't have to pass through some

09:13:10.460 --> 09:13:17.500
interminable jobstack waiting for the rubber stamp? Spindle had it all wrong. Amanda Bates

09:13:17.500 --> 09:13:23.500
wasn't a soft apolitics. Her role didn't deny the obsolescence of human oversight at all. Her role

09:13:23.500 --> 09:13:30.220
depended on it. She was more cannon fodder than I. She always had been. And I had to admit,

09:13:30.220 --> 09:13:33.900
after generations of generals who'd lived for the glory of the mushroom cloud,

09:13:34.540 --> 09:13:38.620
it was a pretty effective strategy for souring warmongers on gratuitous violence.

09:13:39.340 --> 09:13:43.580
In Amanda Bates' army, picking a fight meant standing on the battlefield with a bull's eye on

09:13:43.580 --> 09:13:48.140
your chest. No wonder she hadn't been so invested in peaceful alternatives.

09:13:49.100 --> 09:13:55.740
I'm sorry, I said softly. She shrugged. It's not over yet, just the first round.

09:13:56.620 --> 09:14:00.700
She took a long deep breath and turned it back to her study of slingshot mechanics.

09:14:01.420 --> 09:14:05.740
Rorschach wouldn't have tried so hard to scare us off in the first place if we couldn't touch it,

09:14:05.740 --> 09:14:14.940
right? I swallowed. Right. So there's still a chance, she nodded to herself. There's still a chance.

09:14:15.580 --> 09:14:21.820
The demon arranged his pieces for the end game. He didn't have many left. The soldier he placed in

09:14:21.820 --> 09:14:27.500
the bridge. He packed obsolete linguists and diplomats back in their coffin, out of sight and out of

09:14:27.500 --> 09:14:32.620
the way. He called the jargonaut to his quarters. Although it would be the first time I'd seen

09:14:32.620 --> 09:14:37.020
him since the attack, his summons carried not the slightest trace of doubt that I would obey.

09:14:37.580 --> 09:14:42.620
I did. I came on command and saw that he had surrounded himself with faces.

09:14:43.500 --> 09:14:49.740
Every last one of them was screaming. There was no sound. The disembodied holograms floated in

09:14:49.740 --> 09:14:55.100
silent tears around the bubble, each contorted into a different expression of pain. They were

09:14:55.100 --> 09:15:01.820
being tortured, these faces, half a dozen real ethnicities and twice as many hypothetical ones,

09:15:01.820 --> 09:15:07.500
skin tones ranging from charcoal to albino, brows high and slanted, noses splayed or pointed,

09:15:07.900 --> 09:15:14.140
jaws receding or prognathus. Siddhasthi had called the entire hominid tree into existence around

09:15:14.140 --> 09:15:18.780
him, astonishing in their range of features, terrifying in their consistency of expression.

09:15:19.820 --> 09:15:26.140
A sea of tortured faces, rotating in slow orbits around my vampire commander.

09:15:26.140 --> 09:15:34.060
My God, what is this? Statistics. Siddhasthi seemed focused on a flayed Asian child,

09:15:34.700 --> 09:15:41.100
Rorschach's goth elementary over a two week period. Their faces, he nodded, turning his

09:15:41.100 --> 09:15:47.100
attention to a woman with no eyes. Skull diameter scales to total mass, mandible length scales

09:15:47.100 --> 09:15:53.500
to EM transparency at one angstrom, 113 facial dimensions each presenting a different variable.

09:15:54.140 --> 09:15:58.140
Principal component combinations present as multi-feature aspect ratios.

09:15:59.100 --> 09:16:07.340
He turned to face me, his naked gleaming eyes just slightly side cast. You'd be surprised how

09:16:07.340 --> 09:16:12.460
much gray matter is dedicated to the analysis of facial imagery, shamed to waste it on anything as

09:16:13.100 --> 09:16:18.860
counterintuitive as residual plots and contingency tables. I felt my jaw clenching.

09:16:19.580 --> 09:16:25.020
Any expressions? What did they represent? Software customizes output for user.

09:16:25.980 --> 09:16:29.020
An agonized gallery pleaded for mercy on all sides.

09:16:29.820 --> 09:16:32.620
I am wired for hunting, he reminded gently.

09:16:33.500 --> 09:16:36.220
And you think I don't know that? I said after a moment.

09:16:37.500 --> 09:16:43.980
He shrugged, disconcertingly human. You ask, why am I here, Yuka? You want to teach me another

09:16:43.980 --> 09:16:52.540
object lesson? To discuss our next move. What move? We can't even run away. No. He shook his head,

09:16:52.540 --> 09:16:58.300
bearing filed teeth and something approaching regret. Why did we wait so long? Suddenly my

09:16:58.300 --> 09:17:04.300
sullen defiance had evaporated. I sounded like a child, frightened and pleading. Why didn't we just

09:17:04.300 --> 09:17:09.580
take it on and we first got here when it was weaker? We need to learn things for next time.

09:17:10.460 --> 09:17:15.420
Next time I thought Rorschach was a dandelion seed, I thought it just washed up here.

09:17:16.300 --> 09:17:22.700
By chance. But every dandelion is a clone. Their seeds are legion. Another smile,

09:17:22.700 --> 09:17:28.380
not remotely convincing. And maybe it takes more than one try for the placental mammals to conquer

09:17:28.380 --> 09:17:33.660
Australia. It'll annihilate us. It doesn't even need those spitballs. It could pulverize us with

09:17:33.660 --> 09:17:40.940
one of those scram jets in an instant. It doesn't want to. How do you know? They need to learn things

09:17:40.940 --> 09:17:49.420
too. They want us intact. Improves our odds. Not enough. We can't win. This was his cue.

09:17:50.380 --> 09:17:56.140
This was the point at which Uncle Predator would smile at my naivete and take me into his confidence.

09:17:56.700 --> 09:18:01.340
Of course, we're armed to the teeth, he would say. Do you think we'd come all this way,

09:18:01.340 --> 09:18:07.020
face such vast unknown without the means to defend ourselves? Now at last I can reveal that

09:18:07.020 --> 09:18:12.460
shielding and weaponry account for over half the ship's mass. It was his cue.

09:18:13.980 --> 09:18:24.620
No, he said. We can't win. So we just sit here. We just wait to die for the next 68 minutes.

09:18:24.700 --> 09:18:35.020
So Dosti shook his head. No. But I began. Oh, I finished. Because of course,

09:18:35.740 --> 09:18:41.900
we had just topped up our antimatter reserves. Theseus was not equipped with weapons. Theseus

09:18:41.900 --> 09:18:48.140
was the weapon. And we were, in fact, going to sit here for the next 68 minutes waiting to die.

09:18:48.940 --> 09:18:51.420
But we were going to take Rorschach with us when we did.

09:18:52.620 --> 09:18:58.300
Siddhasthi said nothing. I wondered what he saw looking at me. I wondered if there was actually

09:18:58.300 --> 09:19:04.140
a Yuka Siddhasthi behind those eyes to see if his insights, always ten steps ahead of our own,

09:19:04.940 --> 09:19:09.820
hailed not so much from superior analytical facilities as from the time-worn truth that

09:19:09.820 --> 09:19:15.340
it takes one to know one. Whose side, I wondered, would an automaton take?

09:19:16.300 --> 09:19:22.940
You have other things to worry about, he said. He moved towards me. I swear all those agonized

09:19:22.940 --> 09:19:28.700
faces followed him with their eye. He studied me for a moment, the flesh crinkling around his eyes,

09:19:29.420 --> 09:19:35.100
or maybe some mindless algorithm merely processed visual input, correlated aspect ratios, and facial

09:19:35.100 --> 09:19:39.900
ticks, fed everything to some output subroutine with no more awareness than a stats program.

09:19:41.020 --> 09:19:45.180
Maybe there was no more spark in this creature's face than there was in all the others.

09:19:45.260 --> 09:19:46.780
Silently screaming in his wake.

09:19:47.900 --> 09:19:50.540
Is Susan afraid of you? The thing before me asked.

09:19:51.260 --> 09:19:57.900
Sue, why would she be? She has four conscious entities in her head. She's four times more

09:19:57.900 --> 09:20:04.780
sentient than you. Doesn't that make you a threat? No, of course not. Then why should you feel threatened

09:20:04.780 --> 09:20:10.780
by me? And suddenly I didn't care anymore. I laughed out loud with minutes to live and nothing

09:20:10.780 --> 09:20:17.420
to lose. Why? Maybe because you're my natural enemy, you fucker. Maybe because I know you and you

09:20:17.420 --> 09:20:22.620
can't even look at one of us without flexing your claws. Maybe because you ripped my fucking hand

09:20:22.620 --> 09:20:29.420
off for no good reason. I can imagine what it's like, he said quietly. Please don't make me do it again.

09:20:30.860 --> 09:20:35.900
I fell instantly silent. I know your race and mine are never on the best of terms.

09:20:36.620 --> 09:20:41.980
There was a cold smile in his voice, if not on his face. But I do only what you forced me to.

09:20:42.620 --> 09:20:49.660
You rationalize Keaton. You defend. You reject unpalatable truths, and if you can't reject

09:20:49.660 --> 09:20:56.300
them outright, you trivialize them. Incremental evidence is never enough for you. You hear rumors

09:20:56.300 --> 09:21:02.300
of holocaust, you dismiss them. You see evidence of genocide, you insist it can't be so bad.

09:21:02.300 --> 09:21:07.900
Temperatures rise, glaciers melt, species die, and you blame sunspots and volcanoes.

09:21:08.780 --> 09:21:14.460
Everyone is like this, but you most of all, you and your Chinese room. You term

09:21:14.460 --> 09:21:18.940
incomprehension into mathematics, you reject the truth without even knowing what it is.

09:21:19.900 --> 09:21:25.340
It served me well enough. I wondered at the ease of which I had put my life into the past tense.

09:21:25.820 --> 09:21:31.740
Yes, if your purpose is only to transmit, now you have to convince. You have to believe.

09:21:31.740 --> 09:21:36.460
There were implications that I, there I didn't dare to hope for.

09:21:36.460 --> 09:21:42.220
Are you saying, can't afford to let the truth trickle through? Can't give you the chance to

09:21:42.220 --> 09:21:46.700
completely shore up your rationales and your defenses? They must fall completely.

09:21:47.580 --> 09:21:51.180
You must be inundated. Shattered.

09:21:51.820 --> 09:21:57.340
Shattered. Genocide's impossible to deny when you're buried up to your neck in dismembered bodies.

09:21:59.340 --> 09:22:05.260
He played me. All this time, preconditioning me, turning my topology inside out.

09:22:06.300 --> 09:22:10.220
I'd known something was going on. I just hadn't understood what.

09:22:11.660 --> 09:22:15.580
I'd have seen right through it, I said, if you hadn't made me get involved.

09:22:16.540 --> 09:22:18.780
You might have even read off of me directly.

09:22:19.420 --> 09:22:23.980
That's why you... I shook my head. I thought that was because we were meat.

09:22:24.780 --> 09:22:27.820
That too, Sudasti admitted, and looked right at me.

09:22:28.700 --> 09:22:32.940
For the first time, I looked right back, and felt a shock of recognition.

09:22:34.380 --> 09:22:39.660
I still wonder why I never saw it before. For all those years, I remembered the thoughts and

09:22:39.660 --> 09:22:43.980
feelings of some different younger person, some remnant of the boy my parents had hacked out of

09:22:43.980 --> 09:22:50.140
my head to make room for me. He'd been alive. His world had been vibrant, and though I could call

09:22:50.140 --> 09:22:54.940
up the memories of that other consciousness, I could barely feel anything within the constraints

09:22:54.940 --> 09:22:59.100
of my own. Perhaps dream state wasn't such a bad word for it.

09:23:00.300 --> 09:23:07.260
Like to hear a vampire folktale? Sudasti asked. Vampires have folktales? He took it for a yes.

09:23:08.300 --> 09:23:13.740
A laser is assigned to find the darkness. Since it lives in a room without doors or windows or

09:23:13.740 --> 09:23:19.180
any other source of light, it thinks this will be easy. But everywhere it turns, it sees brightness.

09:23:19.740 --> 09:23:23.020
Every wall, every piece of furniture, it points at is brightly lit.

09:23:23.740 --> 09:23:27.100
Eventually, it concludes there is no darkness. The light is everywhere.

09:23:27.900 --> 09:23:32.140
What the hell are you talking about? Amanda is not planning a mutiny.

09:23:32.940 --> 09:23:36.860
What you know about? She doesn't even want to. Ask her if you like.

09:23:37.500 --> 09:23:40.300
No, I... you value objectivity.

09:23:41.420 --> 09:23:46.140
It was so obvious. I didn't bother answering. He nodded as if I had.

09:23:46.860 --> 09:23:52.540
Synthesis can't have opinions of their own. So when you feel one, it must be someone else's.

09:23:52.540 --> 09:23:59.100
The crew holds you in contempt. Amanda wants me relieved of command. Half of us is you.

09:23:59.100 --> 09:24:03.580
I think the word is project. Although, he cocked his head a bit to one side,

09:24:04.140 --> 09:24:10.060
lately you improve. Come. Where? Shuttle Bay. Time to do your job.

09:24:10.780 --> 09:24:18.940
My survive and bear witness. A drone can deliver the data, assuming nothing fries its memory before

09:24:18.940 --> 09:24:25.100
it gets away. It can't convince anyone. It can't counter rationalizations and denials.

09:24:25.820 --> 09:24:32.460
It can't matter. And vampires, he paused, have poor communication skills.

09:24:34.300 --> 09:24:37.660
It should have been cause for petty selfish rejoicing.

09:24:38.700 --> 09:24:44.780
It all comes down to me, I said. That's what you're saying. I'm a fucking stenographer,

09:24:44.780 --> 09:24:50.060
and it's all on me. Yes. Forgive me for that. Forgive you.

09:24:50.860 --> 09:24:57.340
Sudosti waved at hand. All faces saved to disappeared. I don't know what I'm doing.

09:24:57.900 --> 09:25:04.220
The news bloomed across consensus a few seconds before Bates called it loud.

09:25:04.860 --> 09:25:08.380
Thirteen skimmers had not reappeared from behind Big Ben on schedule.

09:25:09.180 --> 09:25:12.620
Sixteen. Twenty-eight. And counting.

09:25:13.820 --> 09:25:16.860
Sudosti clicked to himself as he and Bates played catch-up.

09:25:17.580 --> 09:25:22.460
Tactical filled, luminous, multicolored threads, a tangle of verised projections as intricate as

09:25:22.460 --> 09:25:28.700
art. The threads wrapped Big Ben like a filamentous cocoon. Thesias was a naked speck in the middle

09:25:28.700 --> 09:25:35.340
distance. I expected any number of those lines to skewer us like needles through a bug. Surprisingly,

09:25:35.340 --> 09:25:40.540
none did, but the projections only extended twenty-five hours into the future and were reliable

09:25:40.540 --> 09:25:45.660
for only half that. Not even Sudosti and the captain could look so far ahead with that many

09:25:45.660 --> 09:25:51.660
balls in the air. It was something, though. The faint of silver lining that all these high-speed

09:25:51.660 --> 09:25:57.260
behemoths couldn't simply reach out and spot us without warning. Evidently, they still had to

09:25:57.260 --> 09:26:02.780
ease into the curve. After Rorschach's dive, I've been starting to think the laws of physics didn't

09:26:02.780 --> 09:26:08.220
apply. The trajectories were close enough, though. At least three skimmers would be passing within

09:26:08.220 --> 09:26:13.980
a hundred kilometers on the next orbits. Sudosti reached for his injector, blood rising in his face.

09:26:14.860 --> 09:26:21.020
Time to go. Re-fit Caribdis while you were sulking. He held the hypo to his throat and

09:26:21.020 --> 09:26:26.380
shot up. I stared at consensus, caught by that bright-shifting web like a moth to streetlight.

09:26:27.020 --> 09:26:34.380
Now, Ciri. He pushed me from his quarters. I sailed into the passageway, grabbed a convenient rung,

09:26:35.100 --> 09:26:40.860
and stopped. The spine was alive with grunts patrolling the airspace, standing guard over the

09:26:40.860 --> 09:26:46.220
fab plants and shuttle locks, clinging like giant insects to the rungs of unrolling spinal ladders.

09:26:47.180 --> 09:26:50.060
Slowly, silently, the spine itself was stretching.

09:26:51.580 --> 09:26:57.100
It could do that, I remembered. Its corrugations flexed and relaxed like muscle. It could grow

09:26:57.100 --> 09:27:01.980
up to 200 meters to accommodate any late-breaking need for a bigger hangar or more lab space.

09:27:03.020 --> 09:27:07.100
Or more infantry. The easiest was increasing the size of the battlefield.

09:27:07.740 --> 09:27:13.580
Come, the vampire turned aft. Bates broke in up front. Something's happening.

09:27:14.540 --> 09:27:19.500
An emergency hand pad, geckoed to the expanding bulkhead, slid past the one side, and…

09:27:20.300 --> 09:27:24.300
Bates' feet appeared on the bulkhead. A tiny chunk of big ben,

09:27:24.300 --> 09:27:28.460
E.M. enhanced equatorial quadrant only a few thousand clicks on the side.

09:27:29.100 --> 09:27:34.380
The clouds boiled down there, a cyclotic knot of turbulence swirling almost too fast of real time.

09:27:35.180 --> 09:27:39.340
The overlay described charged particles, bound in a deep parker spiral.

09:27:40.300 --> 09:27:42.300
It spoke of great mass, rising.

09:27:43.180 --> 09:27:44.140
Sotosti clicked.

09:27:45.100 --> 09:27:51.340
D.T.I., Bates said, optical only. Sotosti took my arm and dragged me effortlessly astern.

09:27:51.980 --> 09:27:56.460
The display paced us along the bulkhead, seven skimmers shot from the clouds as I watched,

09:27:56.460 --> 09:28:01.900
a ragged circle of scramjets screaming red-hot into space. Consensus plotted their pads in an

09:28:01.900 --> 09:28:07.420
instant. Luminous arcs rose around our ship like the bars of a cage. Thesey is shuttered.

09:28:08.140 --> 09:28:13.740
We've been hit, I thought. Suddenly the spines plotting expansion cranked into overdrive.

09:28:13.740 --> 09:28:17.740
The pleated wall lurched and accelerated, streaming past my outstretched fingers as the

09:28:17.740 --> 09:28:24.940
closed hatch receded up ahead, and… receded overhead. The walls weren't moving at all.

09:28:24.940 --> 09:28:27.900
We were falling, to the sudden strident bleeding of an alarm.

09:28:28.940 --> 09:28:33.900
Something nearly yanked my arm from its socket. Sotosti had reached out with one hand and caught

09:28:33.900 --> 09:28:37.900
a rung, reached with his other and caught me before we'd been flattened against the fab plant.

09:28:38.860 --> 09:28:44.140
We dangled. I must have weighed two hundred kilograms, the floor shuttered ten meters below

09:28:44.140 --> 09:28:49.180
my feet. The ship groaned around us, the spine filled with the screech of torquing metal.

09:28:50.300 --> 09:28:56.460
Bates grunts clung to its walls with clawed feet. I reached for the ladder. The ladder pulled away,

09:28:56.460 --> 09:29:01.580
the ship was bending in the middle and down had started to climb the walls. Sotosti and I swung

09:29:01.580 --> 09:29:07.180
towards the center of the spine like a daisy-chain pendulum. Bates, James, the vampire roared,

09:29:07.820 --> 09:29:12.220
his grip on my wrist trembled, slipping. I strained for the ladder, swung and caught it.

09:29:13.100 --> 09:29:18.060
Susan James has barricaded herself in the bridge and shut down automatic overrides.

09:29:19.020 --> 09:29:24.380
An unfamiliar voice, flat and effectless. She has initiated an unauthorized burn.

09:29:24.940 --> 09:29:30.460
I have begun a controlled reactor shutdown. Be advised the main drive will be offline for at least

09:29:30.460 --> 09:29:36.140
twenty-seven minutes. The ship, I realized, its voice raised calmly above the alarm,

09:29:36.780 --> 09:29:44.540
the captain itself, on public address. That was unusual. Bridge, Sotosti barked, open channel.

09:29:46.140 --> 09:29:51.260
Someone was shouting up there. There were words, but I couldn't make them out. Without warning,

09:29:51.260 --> 09:29:57.100
Sotosti let go. He dropped obliquely in a blur. Aft and opposite, the bulkhead waited to swat

09:29:57.180 --> 09:30:01.660
him like an insect. In half a second, both his legs would be shattered if the impact didn't kill

09:30:01.660 --> 09:30:07.580
him outright. But suddenly we were weightless again, and Yuka Sotosti, purple-faced, stiff-limbed,

09:30:07.580 --> 09:30:14.700
was foaming at the mouth. Reactor offline, the captain reported. Sotosti bounced off the wall.

09:30:15.660 --> 09:30:21.580
He's having a seizure, I realized. I released the ladder and pushed a stern. The easiest swung

09:30:21.580 --> 09:30:26.780
lopsidedly around me. Sotosti convulsed in mid-air, clicks and hisses and choking sounds

09:30:26.780 --> 09:30:32.540
stuttered from his mouth. His eyes were so wide they seemed lidless. His pupils are mirror-red

09:30:32.540 --> 09:30:38.060
pinouts. The flesh twitched across his face as though trying to crawl off. Ahead and behind,

09:30:38.060 --> 09:30:43.180
battle bots held their position and ignored us. Baits! I yelled up the spine. We need help.

09:30:45.260 --> 09:30:51.180
Angles everywhere. Seams on the shield plates. Sharp shadows and protrusions on the surface

09:30:51.180 --> 09:30:57.580
of every drone. A two by three matrix of insets, bordered in black, floating over the main consensus

09:30:57.580 --> 09:31:03.260
display. Two big interlinked crosses, right in front of where Sotosti had been hanging.

09:31:04.140 --> 09:31:08.220
This can't be happening. He just took his anti-Euclideans. I saw him, unless

09:31:09.260 --> 09:31:15.340
someone had spiked Sotosti's drugs. Baits! She should be linked into the grunts. They should

09:31:15.340 --> 09:31:19.980
have leapt forward at the first sign of trouble. They should be dragging my commander to the infirmary

09:31:19.980 --> 09:31:25.900
by now. They waited stall at an immobile. I stared at the nearest. Baits! You there?

09:31:25.900 --> 09:31:28.540
And then in case she wasn't, I spoke to the grunt directly.

09:31:29.100 --> 09:31:31.340
Are you autonomous? Do you take verbal orders?

09:31:32.380 --> 09:31:37.420
On all sides the robots watched. The captain just laughed at me, his voice posing as an alarm.

09:31:38.140 --> 09:31:44.620
Infirmary. I pushed. Sotosti's arms flailed randomly against my head and shoulders. He tumbled

09:31:44.620 --> 09:31:49.420
forward and sideways, hit the moving consensus display dead center, bounced away and up from the

09:31:49.420 --> 09:31:56.300
spine. I kicked off his wake and glimpsed something from the corner of my eye and turned.

09:31:57.820 --> 09:32:03.500
And dead center of consensus, Rorschach erupted from Ben's seething face like a breaching whale.

09:32:04.220 --> 09:32:10.220
It wasn't just the EM enhanced. The thing was glowing, deep angry red, and raged at hurled

09:32:10.220 --> 09:32:17.500
itself into space, big as a mountain range. Fuck, fuck, fuck. Theseus lurched. The lights flickered,

09:32:17.500 --> 09:32:21.660
went out, came back on again. The turning bulkhead cuffed me from behind.

09:32:22.540 --> 09:32:25.340
Backups engaged, the captain said calmly.

09:32:25.900 --> 09:32:31.660
Captain, Sotosti's down! I kicked off the nearest ladder, bumped into a grunt, and headed forward

09:32:31.660 --> 09:32:39.980
after the vampire. Baits isn't... what do I do? NAV offline. Starbert afference offline.

09:32:41.020 --> 09:32:46.460
It wasn't even talking to me, I realized. Maybe this wasn't the captain at all. Maybe it was pure

09:32:46.460 --> 09:32:51.820
reflex, a dialogue tree spouting public service announcements. Maybe Theseus had already been

09:32:51.820 --> 09:32:58.460
lobotomized. Maybe this was only her brainstem talking. Darkness again, then flickering light.

09:32:59.420 --> 09:33:05.500
If the captain was gone, we were screwed. I gave Sotosti another push. The alarm bleated on.

09:33:06.300 --> 09:33:10.780
The drum was 20 meters ahead. Biomed was just the other side of that closed hatch.

09:33:11.340 --> 09:33:15.820
The hatch had been opened before, I remember. Someone had shut it in the last few minutes.

09:33:16.620 --> 09:33:22.460
Fortunately, Theseus had no locks on her doors. Unless the gang barricaded it before they took

09:33:22.460 --> 09:33:31.340
the bridge. Strap in, people! We are getting out of here! Who the hell? The open bridge channel.

09:33:31.980 --> 09:33:36.620
Susan James shouting up there, or someone was, I couldn't quite place the voice.

09:33:37.660 --> 09:33:43.340
Ten meters to the drum. Theseus jerked again, slowing her spin. Stabilized.

09:33:44.060 --> 09:33:47.660
Somebody start the goddamn reactor! I've only got attitude jets up here.

09:33:48.780 --> 09:33:55.740
Sasha? Sasha? I was at the hatch. Who is that? I pushed past Sotosti and reached open it.

09:33:56.540 --> 09:34:03.340
No answer. Not from consensus, anyway. I heard a muted hum from behind, saw the ominous shifting

09:34:03.340 --> 09:34:08.540
of shadows on the bulkhead just a moment too late. I turned in time to see one of the grunts raise a

09:34:08.540 --> 09:34:15.100
spiky appendage curved like a scimitar needle tipped over Sotosti's head. I turned in time to

09:34:15.100 --> 09:34:21.100
see it plunge it into his skull. I froze. The metal proboscis withdrew, dark and slick.

09:34:21.980 --> 09:34:27.900
Lateral maxillopeds began nibbling at the base of Sotosti's skull. His pithed corpse wasn't thrashing

09:34:27.900 --> 09:34:35.100
now, and only trembled, a sack of muscles and motor nerves awash in static. Bates. Her mutiny

09:34:35.180 --> 09:34:42.220
was under way. No, their mutiny. Bates and the gang. I'd known. I'd imagined it. I'd seen it coming.

09:34:42.220 --> 09:34:49.180
He hadn't believed me. The lights went out again. The alarm fell silent. Consensus dwindled to a

09:34:49.180 --> 09:34:53.900
flickering doodle on the bulkhead and disappeared. I saw something there in that last instant and

09:34:53.900 --> 09:34:59.580
refused to process it. I heard breath catch in my throat, felt angular monstrosities advancing

09:34:59.580 --> 09:35:05.420
through the darkness. Something flared directly ahead, a brief bright staccato in the void.

09:35:06.300 --> 09:35:11.740
I glimpsed curves and angles in silhouette, staggering. The buzzing crackle of shorting

09:35:11.740 --> 09:35:18.860
circuitry. Metal objects collided nearby, unseen. From behind the crinkle of the drum hatch, opening.

09:35:20.220 --> 09:35:24.940
A sudden beam of harsh chemical light hit me as I turned, let the mechanical ranks behind.

09:35:25.580 --> 09:35:28.780
They simultaneously unclapped from their anchorages and floated free.

09:35:30.700 --> 09:35:34.060
Their joints clicked in unison like an army stamping to attention.

09:35:34.780 --> 09:35:37.660
Keaton, Bates snapped, sailing through the hatch. You okay?

09:35:38.780 --> 09:35:43.580
The chem light shone from her forehead. It turned the interior of the spine into a high-contrast

09:35:43.580 --> 09:35:49.340
mosaic. All pale surfaces and sharp moving shadows. It spilled across the grunt that had killed

09:35:50.060 --> 09:35:54.940
the robot bounced down the spine suddenly, mysteriously inert. The light washed across

09:35:54.940 --> 09:36:01.740
Siddosti's body. The corpse turned slowly on its axis. Spherical crimson beads emerged from its head

09:36:01.740 --> 09:36:06.940
like drops of water from a leaky faucet. They spread in a winding, widening trail, spot-lit

09:36:06.940 --> 09:36:15.420
by Bates' headlamp, a spiral arm of dark ruby suns. I backed away. You! she pushed me to one side.

09:36:15.980 --> 09:36:21.020
Stay clear of the hatch unless you're going through. Her eyes were fixed on the ranked drones,

09:36:21.020 --> 09:36:26.460
optical line of sight. Rose of glassy eyes reflected back at us down the passageway,

09:36:26.460 --> 09:36:33.900
passing in and out of shadow. You killed Siddosti! No. But who do you think shut it down, Keaton?

09:36:33.900 --> 09:36:39.740
The fucker went rogue. I could barely even get it to self-destruct. Her eyes went briefly deep

09:36:39.740 --> 09:36:45.020
focus. All down the spine, the surviving drones launched into some intricate martial ballet,

09:36:45.020 --> 09:36:50.060
half seen in the shifting cone of her headlamp. Better, Bates said. They should stay in line now,

09:36:50.060 --> 09:36:55.820
assuming we don't get hit with anything too much stronger. What is hitting us? Lightning. EMP.

09:36:56.700 --> 09:37:00.780
Drones sailed down to fad in the shuttles, taking strategic positions along the tube.

09:37:01.660 --> 09:37:05.900
Rorschach's putting out one hell of a charge, and every time one of those skimmers pass between

09:37:05.900 --> 09:37:13.100
us and that, they arc. What at this range? I thought we were... the burn sent us in the wrong

09:37:13.100 --> 09:37:19.820
direction. We're inbound. Three grunts floated close enough to touch. They drew beads on the open

09:37:19.820 --> 09:37:27.100
drum hatch. She said she was trying to escape, I remembered. She fucked up. Not by that much,

09:37:27.100 --> 09:37:35.020
she couldn't have. We were all rated for manual piloting. Just in case. Not the gang, Bates said.

09:37:35.020 --> 09:37:40.300
But I think there's someone new in there now. A bunch of sub-modules wired together and woke up

09:37:40.300 --> 09:37:46.460
somehow. I don't know. But whatever's in charge, I think it's just panicking. Stuttering brightness

09:37:46.460 --> 09:37:52.060
on all sides. The spinal lights were flickered and finally held steady at half their usual brightness.

09:37:53.420 --> 09:37:59.900
Thesias coughed static and spoke. Consensus is offline. React. The voice faded.

09:38:01.660 --> 09:38:05.100
Consensus, I remembered as Bates turned his head back upstream.

09:38:05.980 --> 09:38:09.020
I saw something, I said, before Consensus went out.

09:38:09.820 --> 09:38:18.380
Yeah. Was that... she paused at the hatch. Yeah. I'd seen scramblers. Hundreds of them sailing

09:38:18.380 --> 09:38:24.540
naked through the void. Their arms spread wide. Some of their arms anyway. They were carrying

09:38:24.540 --> 09:38:30.860
Bates knotted. Weapons. Her eyes flickered to some unseen distance for a moment. First wave

09:38:30.860 --> 09:38:36.220
headed for the front end. Blister and forward lock, I think. Second wave's aft. She shook her head.

09:38:36.780 --> 09:38:39.020
Huh. I would have done it the other way around.

09:38:40.060 --> 09:38:45.980
How far? Far? Bates smiled faintly. They're already on the hull, Ciri. We're engaging.

09:38:47.020 --> 09:38:53.580
What do I do? What do I do? Her eyes stared past me and widened. She opened her mouth.

09:38:54.620 --> 09:38:58.060
A hand clamped on my shoulder from behind and spun me around.

09:38:58.140 --> 09:39:03.980
Serasty. His dead eye is stared like a split skull from a spike melon.

09:39:05.020 --> 09:39:09.260
Globules of coagulated blood clung to his hair and skin like engorged ticks.

09:39:10.540 --> 09:39:16.220
Go with him, Bates said. Serasty grunted and clicked. There were no words.

09:39:17.420 --> 09:39:24.620
What? I began. Now that's an order. Bates turned back to the hatch. We'll cover you.

09:39:25.580 --> 09:39:31.820
The shuttle. You too. No. Why not? They can fight better without you. You said that yourself.

09:39:31.820 --> 09:39:36.380
What's the point? Can't leave yourself a backdoor, Keaton. Defeats the whole purpose.

09:39:37.340 --> 09:39:41.420
She allowed herself a small, sad smile. They've breached. Go.

09:39:42.620 --> 09:39:48.620
She was gone. Fresh alarms rising in her wake. Far towards the bow, I heard the crinkle of

09:39:48.620 --> 09:39:55.500
emergency bulkheads snapping shut. Serasty's undead carcass gurgled and pushed me down the spine.

09:39:55.500 --> 09:40:00.860
Four more grunts slid smoothly past and took up position behind us. I looked over my shoulder

09:40:00.860 --> 09:40:06.860
in time to see the vampire pull the hand pad from the wall. But it wasn't Serasty at all, of course.

09:40:06.860 --> 09:40:10.460
It was the captain, whatever was left of the captain, this far into the fight,

09:40:11.180 --> 09:40:16.940
commandeering a peripheral interface for its own use. The optical port sprouted conspicuously

09:40:16.940 --> 09:40:22.860
from the back of Serasty's neck, where the cable used to go in. I remembered the drone's maxillipids,

09:40:22.860 --> 09:40:27.660
chewing. The sound of weapons fire and ricochets rode us behind us.

09:40:28.780 --> 09:40:33.900
The corpse typed one hand at us as we moved. I wondered briefly why it didn't talk before

09:40:33.900 --> 09:40:39.180
my gaze flickered back to the spike in his brain. Serasty's speech centers must be mush.

09:40:39.660 --> 09:40:45.980
Why did you kill him? I said. A whole new alarm started up way back in the drum.

09:40:46.780 --> 09:40:51.900
A sudden breeze tugged me backward for a moment, dissipated the next second with a distant clang.

09:40:52.700 --> 09:40:59.260
The corpse held out the hand pad, configured for keys in a text display. Sleezing, couldn't control.

09:41:00.460 --> 09:41:04.940
We were at the shuttle locks. Robot soldiers let us pass their attention elsewhere.

09:41:05.740 --> 09:41:12.780
You go, the captain said. Someone screamed in the distance. Way off up in the spine,

09:41:12.780 --> 09:41:17.820
the drum hatch slammed shut. I turned and saw a pair of distant grunts welding the seal.

09:41:18.460 --> 09:41:23.020
They seemed to move faster now than they ever had before. Maybe it was only my imagination.

09:41:23.980 --> 09:41:28.460
The starboard shuttle lock slid back. Cribbed as interior lights winked on,

09:41:28.460 --> 09:41:33.100
spilling brightness into the passageway. The spine's emergency lighting seemed even dimmer

09:41:33.100 --> 09:41:38.460
in contrast. I peered through the opening. There was almost no cabin space left,

09:41:38.460 --> 09:41:42.940
just a single open coffin, fuel tanks, and massive retrofitted chalk pads.

09:41:43.820 --> 09:41:51.980
Caribdis had been refitted for high G in long distance. And me. Serasty's corpse urged me on

09:41:51.980 --> 09:42:00.860
from behind. I turned and faced it. Was it ever him? I asked. Go. Tell me, did he ever speak for

09:42:00.860 --> 09:42:06.540
himself? Did he decide anything on his own? Were we ever following his orders, or was it just you

09:42:06.540 --> 09:42:14.060
all along? Serasty's undead eyes stared glassy and uncomprehending. His fingers jerked on the handpad.

09:42:15.180 --> 09:42:23.100
You dislike orders from machines. Happier this way. I let it strap me in and close the lid.

09:42:23.820 --> 09:42:28.460
I lay there in the dark, feeling my body lurch and sway as the shuttle slid into its launch slot.

09:42:29.420 --> 09:42:34.060
I withstood the sudden silence as the docking clamps let go, the jerk of acceleration that

09:42:34.060 --> 09:42:39.340
spat me hard into the vacuum, the ongoing thrust that pushed against my chest like a small mountain.

09:42:40.140 --> 09:42:44.700
Around me the shuttle trembled in the throes of a burn that far exceeded its normal specs.

09:42:45.820 --> 09:42:51.180
My inlays came back online. Suddenly I could see outside if I wanted. I could see what was

09:42:51.180 --> 09:42:58.220
happening behind me. I chose not to, deliberately and fervently, and looked away. Thesias was dwindling

09:42:58.220 --> 09:43:04.140
by then, even on tactical. She listed down the well, wobbling towards some enemy rendezvous that

09:43:04.140 --> 09:43:08.780
must have been intentional, some last second maneuver to get her payload as close to the target as

09:43:08.780 --> 09:43:15.980
possible. Roar shock rose to meter, its gnarled spiky arms uncoiling, spreading as if anticipation

09:43:15.980 --> 09:43:21.900
of an embrace. But it was the backdrop, not the players, that stole the tableau. The face of

09:43:21.900 --> 09:43:27.660
Big Ben roiling in my rear view, a seething cyclonic backdrop filling the window, magnetic

09:43:27.660 --> 09:43:33.100
contours wound spring tight on the overlay. Roar shock was drawing all of Ben's magnetosphere

09:43:33.100 --> 09:43:38.700
around itself like a bright swirling cloak, twisting it into a concentrated knot that

09:43:38.700 --> 09:43:45.020
grew and brightened and bulged outward like a torsion flare from an L-class dwarf, my commander

09:43:45.020 --> 09:43:49.980
had once said. But we should see anything big enough to generate that effect, and the sky is dark

09:43:49.980 --> 09:43:59.420
on that bearing, IAU calls it a statistical artifact. As, in fact, it had been. An impact

09:43:59.420 --> 09:44:04.540
splashed perhaps on that brief bright bellow of some great energy source rebooting after a million

09:44:04.540 --> 09:44:11.660
years of dormancy, much like this one, a solar flare with no sun beneath it, a magnetic cannon

09:44:11.660 --> 09:44:17.420
10,000 times stronger than nature gave it any right to be. Both sides drew their weapons.

09:44:18.220 --> 09:44:23.660
I don't know which fired first, or even if it mattered. How many tons of antimatter would it

09:44:23.660 --> 09:44:27.900
take to match something that could squeeze the power of a sun from a gas ball barely wider than

09:44:27.900 --> 09:44:33.820
Jupiter? Was Roar Shock also resigned to defeat? Had each side opted for a kamikaze strike on the

09:44:33.820 --> 09:44:41.420
other? I don't know. Big Ben got in the way just minutes before the explosion. That's probably why

09:44:41.420 --> 09:44:46.780
I'm still alive. Ben stood between me and that burning light like a coin held against the sun.

09:44:47.900 --> 09:44:53.180
Thiezy has sent everything it could until the last microsecond. Every recorded moment of hand to

09:44:53.180 --> 09:45:00.140
hand combat, every last countdown, every last soul. All the moves and all the vectors. I have

09:45:00.140 --> 09:45:06.380
that telemetry. I can break it down into any number of shapes, continuous or discrete. I can

09:45:06.380 --> 09:45:11.900
transform the topology, rotate it and compress it, serve it up in dialects that any ally might be able

09:45:11.980 --> 09:45:19.740
to use. Perhaps Sotosti was right. Perhaps some of it is vital. I don't know what any of it means.

09:45:23.500 --> 09:45:32.940
Caribdis. Species used to go extinct. Now they go on hiatus. Debra MacLennan, tails of our reconstruction.

09:45:34.540 --> 09:45:40.700
You poor guy, Chelsea said as we went our separate ways. Sometimes I don't think you'll ever be lonely.

09:45:41.660 --> 09:45:46.620
At the time I wondered why she sounded so sad. Now I only wish he'd been right.

09:45:48.060 --> 09:45:53.980
I know this hasn't been a seamless narrative. I had to shatter the story and string it fragments

09:45:53.980 --> 09:45:59.740
out along a death-lasting decades. I live for only an hour out of every ten thousand now, you see.

09:46:00.620 --> 09:46:06.860
I wish I didn't have to. If only I could sleep the whole way back, avoid the agony of these brief,

09:46:06.940 --> 09:46:13.260
time-lapsed resurrections. If only I wouldn't die in my sleep if I tried, but living bodies

09:46:13.260 --> 09:46:18.860
glitter with a lifetime's accumulation of embedded radioisotopes, brilliant little shards that degrade

09:46:18.860 --> 09:46:25.740
cellular machinery at the molecular level. It's not usually a problem. Living cells repair the

09:46:25.740 --> 09:46:31.580
damage as fast as it occurs, but my undead ones let those errors accumulate over time, and the

09:46:31.580 --> 09:46:37.980
journey home takes so much longer than the trip out, I lie in stasis and corrode. Every now and

09:46:37.980 --> 09:46:44.540
then to give my chant, I flesh the chance to stitch itself back together. Occasionally it talks to me,

09:46:44.540 --> 09:46:50.540
recite system stats, updates me on any chatter from back home. Mostly though, it leaves me alone

09:46:50.540 --> 09:46:56.460
with my thoughts and the machinery ticking away where my left hemisphere used to be. So I talk to

09:46:56.460 --> 09:47:02.780
myself, dictate history and opinion from real hemisphere to synthetic one, write brief moments

09:47:02.780 --> 09:47:08.540
of awareness, long years of oblivious decay between. Maybe the whole exercise is pointless

09:47:08.540 --> 09:47:14.940
from the start. Maybe no one's even listening. It doesn't matter. This is what I do.

09:47:16.860 --> 09:47:23.900
So there you have it, a memoir told from meat to machinery, a tale told to myself for a lack of

09:47:23.900 --> 09:47:28.540
someone else to take an interest. Anyone with half a brain could tell it.

09:47:30.940 --> 09:47:37.340
I got a letter from dad today. General Delivery, he called it. I think that was a joke,

09:47:37.340 --> 09:47:42.540
in deference to my lack of known address. He just threw it omnidirectionally into the ether and hoped

09:47:42.540 --> 09:47:48.940
it would wash over me wherever I was. It's been almost 14 years now. You lose track of such things

09:47:48.940 --> 09:47:57.020
out here. Helen's dead. Heaven malfunctioned apparently, or was sabotaged. Maybe the realist

09:47:57.020 --> 09:48:02.780
finally pulled it off. I doubt it though. Dad seemed to think that someone else was responsible.

09:48:04.140 --> 09:48:10.060
He didn't offer up any details. Maybe he didn't know any. He spoke uneasily of increasing unrest

09:48:10.060 --> 09:48:15.580
back home. Maybe someone leaked my communiques about Rorschach. Maybe people drew the obvious

09:48:15.580 --> 09:48:21.580
conclusion when our postcards stopped arriving. They don't know how the story ended. The lack of

09:48:21.580 --> 09:48:27.100
closure must be driving them crazy. But I got the sense there was something else, something my

09:48:27.100 --> 09:48:32.460
father didn't dare speak aloud. Maybe it's just my imagination. I thought he even sounded troubled

09:48:32.460 --> 09:48:36.780
by the news that the birth weight was rising again, which should be cause for celebration after

09:48:36.780 --> 09:48:43.340
a generation in decline. If my Chinese room was still in proper working order, I'd know I'd be

09:48:43.340 --> 09:48:48.860
able to parse it down to the punctuation. But Sinasti had battered my tools and left them

09:48:48.860 --> 09:48:55.740
barely functional. I'm as blind as any baseline. All I have is uncertainty and suspicion and the

09:48:55.740 --> 09:49:01.820
creeping dread that even with my best tricks and tatters, I might be reading him right. I think

09:49:01.820 --> 09:49:10.140
he's warning me to stay away. He also said he loved me. He said he missed Helen, that she was

09:49:10.140 --> 09:49:15.020
sorry for something she did before I was born, some indulgence or omission that carried delve elemental

09:49:15.020 --> 09:49:22.780
consequences. He rambled. I don't know what he was talking about. So much power my father must

09:49:22.780 --> 09:49:30.060
have had to be able to authorize such a broadcast yet waste so much of it on feelings. Oh, God,

09:49:30.060 --> 09:49:38.540
now I treasure it. I treasure every word. I fall along an endless feudal parabola.

09:49:39.340 --> 09:49:45.260
All gravity and inertia. Cribdus couldn't reacquire the antimatter stream. Icarus has either been

09:49:45.260 --> 09:49:50.780
knocked out of alignment or shut off entirely. I suppose I could radio ahead and ask, but there's

09:49:50.780 --> 09:49:56.540
no hurry. I'm still a long way out. It'll be years before I even leave the comets behind.

09:49:57.420 --> 09:50:03.660
Besides, I'm not sure I want anyone to know where I am. Cribdus doesn't bother with evasive maneuvers.

09:50:03.660 --> 09:50:08.060
There'd be no point even if it had the fuel to spare, even if the enemy's still out there somewhere.

09:50:08.940 --> 09:50:14.460
It's not as though they don't know where Earth is. But I'm pretty sure the scramblers went up along

09:50:14.460 --> 09:50:21.340
with my own kin. They played well. I admit it freely. Or maybe they just got lucky. An accidental

09:50:21.340 --> 09:50:27.580
hiccup trickles baked scrunted to firing on unarmed scrambler. Weeks later, stretch and clench used

09:50:27.580 --> 09:50:33.900
that body in the course of their escape. Electricity and magnetism stir random neurons in Susan's head

09:50:33.980 --> 09:50:37.660
Further down the timeline, a whole new persona erupts to take control,

09:50:37.660 --> 09:50:44.220
to send theses diving into Rorschach's waiting arms. Blind, stupid, random chance. Maybe that's

09:50:44.220 --> 09:50:52.220
all it was. But I don't think so. Too many lucky coincidences. I think Rorschach made its own luck,

09:50:52.780 --> 09:50:57.500
planted and watered that new persona right under our noses, safely hidden, but for the

09:50:57.500 --> 09:51:02.860
nearest trace of elevated oxytocin, behind all the lesions and tumours sewn in Susan's head.

09:51:04.140 --> 09:51:09.580
I think it looked ahead and saw the uses to which decoy might be put. I think it sacrificed a little

09:51:09.580 --> 09:51:15.100
piece of itself in furtherance of that end, and made it look like an accident. Blind, maybe, but

09:51:15.100 --> 09:51:22.940
not luck. Foresight. Brilliant moves and subtle. Not that most of us even know the rules of the game,

09:51:22.940 --> 09:51:28.700
of course. We were just pawns, really. So Dosti and the Captain, whatever hybridised intelligence

09:51:28.700 --> 09:51:34.300
those two formed, they were the real players. Looking back, I can see a few of their moves, too.

09:51:35.420 --> 09:51:41.340
I see Theseus hearing the scramblers tack back and forth in their cages. I see her tweak the volume

09:51:41.340 --> 09:51:47.180
on the gang's feet so that Susan hears it, too, and thinks to discovery her own. If I squint hard

09:51:47.180 --> 09:51:52.220
enough, I even glints Theseus offering us up and sacrifice, deliberately provoking Rorschach to

09:51:52.300 --> 09:51:58.300
retaliation with that final approach. So Dosti was always enamoured of data, especially when it had

09:51:58.300 --> 09:52:03.900
tactical significance. What better way to assess one's enemy than to observe it in combat?

09:52:05.260 --> 09:52:11.020
They never told us, of course. We were happier that way. We disliked orders from machines.

09:52:12.060 --> 09:52:15.020
Not that we were all that crazy about taking them from a vampire.

09:52:16.540 --> 09:52:21.500
And now the game is over, and a single pawn stands on the scorched board in its face as human

09:52:21.500 --> 09:52:27.500
after all. If the scramblers follow the rules, a few generations of game theorists have laid out

09:52:27.500 --> 09:52:31.740
for them. They won't be back. Even if they are, I suspect it won't make any difference,

09:52:32.460 --> 09:52:37.660
because by then there won't be any basis for conflict. I've been listening to the radio

09:52:37.660 --> 09:52:42.380
during these intermittent awakenings. It's been generations since we buried the broadcast age

09:52:42.380 --> 09:52:48.300
in tight beams and fiber-op, but we never completely stopped sewing E.M. through the heavens. Earth,

09:52:48.300 --> 09:52:53.100
Mars, and Luna conduct their interplanetary trialogue in a million overlapping voices.

09:52:53.660 --> 09:52:58.060
Every ship cruising the void speaks in all directions at once. The O'Neill's and the

09:52:58.060 --> 09:53:02.140
asteroids never stop singing. The Fireflies might never have found us if they had.

09:53:03.180 --> 09:53:07.340
I've heard those songs changing over time. A fast-forward time lapse into oblivion.

09:53:08.300 --> 09:53:13.340
Now it's mostly traffic control and telemetry. Every now and then I still hear a burst of pure

09:53:13.340 --> 09:53:18.300
voice tight with tension, just short of outright panic more often than not. Some sort of pursuit

09:53:18.300 --> 09:53:23.260
in progress, a ship making the plunge into deep space, other ships in dispassion at pursuit.

09:53:23.820 --> 09:53:27.180
The Fugitives never seem to get very far before their signals are cut off.

09:53:28.220 --> 09:53:32.700
I can't remember the last time I heard music, but I hear something like it sometimes,

09:53:32.700 --> 09:53:39.100
eerie and discordant, full of familiar clicks and pops. My brainstem doesn't like it. It scares

09:53:39.100 --> 09:53:45.340
my brainstem to death. I remember my whole generation abandoning the real world for a bootstrapped

09:53:45.340 --> 09:53:50.780
afterlife. I remember someone saying vampires don't go to heaven. They see the pixels.

09:53:51.980 --> 09:53:56.300
Sometimes I wonder how I'd feel, brought back from the piece of the grave to toil at the

09:53:56.300 --> 09:54:01.500
pleasure of simple-minded creatures who had once been no more than protein. I wonder how I'd feel

09:54:01.500 --> 09:54:05.900
if my disability had been used to keep me leashed and denied my rightful place in the world.

09:54:06.860 --> 09:54:10.140
And then I wonder what it would be like to feel nothing at all,

09:54:10.860 --> 09:54:16.380
to be an utterly rational predatory creature with meat putting itself so eagerly to sleep on all sides.

09:54:19.660 --> 09:54:26.700
I can't miss you, Kasudasti. God knows I try every time I come online. He saved my life.

09:54:27.420 --> 09:54:34.300
He... he humanized me. I'll always owe him for that, for however long I live, and forever

09:54:34.300 --> 09:54:40.220
long I live I'll never stop hating him for the same reason. In some sick surrealistic way I had

09:54:40.220 --> 09:54:46.860
more in common with Sarasti than I did with any human. But I just don't have it in me. He was

09:54:46.860 --> 09:54:52.300
predator and I was prey. It's not in the nature of the lamb to mourn the lion. Though he died for

09:54:52.300 --> 09:54:59.020
our sins I cannot miss, Yuka Sarasti. I can empathize with him, though. And long last I can

09:54:59.020 --> 09:55:04.140
empathize with Sarasti, with all his extinct kind, because we humans were never meant to

09:55:04.140 --> 09:55:10.460
inherit the earth. Vampires were. They must have been sentient to some degree, but that semi-aware

09:55:10.460 --> 09:55:15.660
dream state would have been a rudimentary thing next to our own self-obsession. They were weeding

09:55:15.660 --> 09:55:22.700
it out. It was just a phase. They were on their way. The thing is, humans can look at crosses

09:55:22.700 --> 09:55:28.220
without going into convulsions. That's evolution for you. One stupid linked mutation and the whole

09:55:28.220 --> 09:55:33.180
natural order falls apart. Intelligence and self-awareness stuck in counterproductive lockstep

09:55:33.180 --> 09:55:39.580
for half a million years. I think I know what's happening back on earth, though some might call

09:55:39.580 --> 09:55:45.180
it genocide. It isn't really. We did it to ourselves. You can't blame predators for being

09:55:45.180 --> 09:55:50.060
predators. We were the ones who brought them back after all. Why wouldn't they reclaim their birth

09:55:50.060 --> 09:55:58.220
right? Not genocide. Just the writing of an ancient wrong. I've tried to take some comfort in that.

09:55:58.300 --> 09:56:03.500
It's difficult. Sometimes it seems as though my whole life's been a struggle to reconnect,

09:56:03.500 --> 09:56:08.300
to regain whatever got lost when my parents killed their only child. Out in the oar,

09:56:08.860 --> 09:56:14.460
I finally won that struggle. Thanks to a vampire and a boatload of freaks and an invading alien

09:56:14.460 --> 09:56:21.100
horde, I'm human again. Maybe the last human. By the time I get home, I could be the only

09:56:21.100 --> 09:56:28.060
sentient being in the universe. If I'm even that much. Because I don't know if there is such a thing

09:56:28.060 --> 09:56:32.780
as a reliable narrator, and Cunningham said zombies would be pretty good at faking it.

09:56:34.300 --> 09:56:40.300
So I can't really tell you, one way or the other. You'll just have to imagine you're C.R.E. Keaton.

09:56:44.300 --> 09:56:50.780
This has been Blind Sight by Peter Watts, narrated by Zachary Reed. Thank you for listening.

09:56:52.140 --> 09:56:57.740
If you enjoyed this work, there are other books by Peter Watts I think you'd enjoy. Starfish,

09:56:58.540 --> 09:57:02.620
Maelstrom, and Behemoth, which comprise the Rifters trilogy.

09:57:04.300 --> 09:57:08.860
These and Peter Watts' collection of short stories can be found on his website,

09:57:08.860 --> 09:57:15.500
rifters.com. If you enjoy spoken word fiction, here are some podcasts I'd like to recommend to you.

09:57:16.460 --> 09:57:24.220
Escape Pod, Pseudopod, and Podcastle. sci-fi, horror, and fantasy respectively.

09:57:24.380 --> 09:57:31.420
Finally, please stay tuned to this YouTube channel for some extra Blind Sight bonus content.

